WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.100 --> 00:00:02.260
- [Narrator] In the year 1492,

00:00:02.260 --> 00:00:05.260
Christopher Columbus discovered the Americas.

00:00:05.260 --> 00:00:09.160
Millions died in pursuit of conquering this unknown land.

00:00:09.160 --> 00:00:12.640
The European powers of the time took part in colonization

00:00:12.640 --> 00:00:15.790
and the centuries after witnessed remarkable wars

00:00:15.790 --> 00:00:17.830
and a new age of influence.

00:00:17.830 --> 00:00:19.420
These events led to the birth

00:00:19.420 --> 00:00:24.040
of a new nation on July 4th, 1776,

00:00:24.040 --> 00:00:26.440
the United States of America.

00:00:26.440 --> 00:00:28.900
Since, the USA has conquered the world

00:00:28.900 --> 00:00:30.850
in every aspect possible.

00:00:30.850 --> 00:00:33.400
From developing the most powerful military

00:00:33.400 --> 00:00:34.660
in modern history,

00:00:34.660 --> 00:00:37.750
two countless astonishing human accomplishments,

00:00:37.750 --> 00:00:41.770
the country has earned the name the modern Roman Empire.

00:00:41.770 --> 00:00:44.770
But can this giant continue its dominance?

00:00:44.770 --> 00:00:47.830
To understand the story of this fascinating land,

00:00:47.830 --> 00:00:50.473
we must start from the very beginning.

00:00:52.433 --> 00:00:54.933
(tense music)

00:01:01.404 --> 00:01:04.720
(upbeat music)

00:01:04.720 --> 00:01:07.150
Long before European colonization,

00:01:07.150 --> 00:01:10.330
the Native peoples of North America had developed complex

00:01:10.330 --> 00:01:13.750
and sophisticated systems of society and government.

00:01:13.750 --> 00:01:16.750
Hundreds of thousands warred, made peace,

00:01:16.750 --> 00:01:18.970
and governed over specific regions

00:01:18.970 --> 00:01:21.460
and had done so for thousands of years.

00:01:21.460 --> 00:01:23.950
By the time the first European explorers began

00:01:23.950 --> 00:01:26.200
to arrive on the North American continent

00:01:26.200 --> 00:01:27.850
in the 15th century,

00:01:27.850 --> 00:01:31.180
the Native Americans had already established themselves

00:01:31.180 --> 00:01:33.910
and their communities for thousands of years.

00:01:33.910 --> 00:01:35.620
The North American continent-

00:01:35.620 --> 00:01:38.350
vast and rich with natural resources-

00:01:38.350 --> 00:01:41.080
would beckon all who came to know of its shores.

00:01:41.080 --> 00:01:44.740
And so when a Norse navigator named Leif Erikson learned

00:01:44.740 --> 00:01:46.000
that there was a land west

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:49.210
of Greenland from fellow explorer, Bjarni Herjolfsson,

00:01:49.210 --> 00:01:51.580
he made preparations to set sail.

00:01:51.580 --> 00:01:53.620
Herjolfsson, who had been blown off-course

00:01:53.620 --> 00:01:56.140
while sailing had accidentally discovered

00:01:56.140 --> 00:01:58.930
what would one day be called Newfoundland.

00:01:58.930 --> 00:02:00.910
And although he did not land,

00:02:00.910 --> 00:02:03.850
his story gave Erikson the information he needed

00:02:03.850 --> 00:02:06.850
to successfully sail across the Labrador Sea

00:02:06.850 --> 00:02:09.340
and make landfall in North America.

00:02:09.340 --> 00:02:12.550
Erikson and the Norseman would establish a small settlement

00:02:12.550 --> 00:02:17.260
in Labrador called L'Anse aux Meadow or Meadows Cove.

00:02:17.260 --> 00:02:20.890
This settlement and numerous small outposts built nearby it

00:02:20.890 --> 00:02:24.280
would be abandoned over the course of about 20 years.

00:02:24.280 --> 00:02:27.940
Afterward, it would be nearly another 500 years

00:02:27.940 --> 00:02:31.585
before Europeans set foot on the shores of North America.

00:02:31.585 --> 00:02:34.213
(tense music)

00:02:34.213 --> 00:02:37.840
(ominous music) (tense music)

00:02:37.840 --> 00:02:40.900
Searching for a more direct and faster route to India,

00:02:40.900 --> 00:02:44.110
the great European powers of the age sent dozens

00:02:44.110 --> 00:02:46.060
of expeditions around the globe.

00:02:46.060 --> 00:02:49.480
In October, 1492, the Genovese explorer,

00:02:49.480 --> 00:02:52.060
Christopher Columbus, employed by the king

00:02:52.060 --> 00:02:55.390
and queen of Spain, discovered the West Indies,

00:02:55.390 --> 00:02:59.620
and inadvertently opened a new frontier of exploration/

00:02:59.620 --> 00:03:01.600
Popularized as the New World

00:03:01.600 --> 00:03:04.870
by Florentine Explorer Amerigo Vespucci,

00:03:04.870 --> 00:03:08.800
it was open season for European explorers, traders,

00:03:08.800 --> 00:03:10.690
and businessmen alike.

00:03:10.690 --> 00:03:14.230
European powers began claiming sections of this New World

00:03:14.230 --> 00:03:17.890
as their own with every major exploratory mission.

00:03:17.890 --> 00:03:20.170
Vespucci, who created and sold maps

00:03:20.170 --> 00:03:22.270
of his own discoveries in the New World,

00:03:22.270 --> 00:03:24.160
gained the notable distinction

00:03:24.160 --> 00:03:29.020
of having the entire hemisphere named for him, America.

00:03:29.020 --> 00:03:30.820
While much of the early exploration

00:03:30.820 --> 00:03:33.220
of the New World focused on what would become known

00:03:33.220 --> 00:03:35.560
as the Caribbean and South America,

00:03:35.560 --> 00:03:36.880
it did not take long

00:03:36.880 --> 00:03:39.430
before explorers turned their attention north

00:03:39.430 --> 00:03:43.900
to the enormous landmass above Columbus's Hispaniola.

00:03:43.900 --> 00:03:47.470
At the dawn of the 16th century, the Spanish, English,

00:03:47.470 --> 00:03:49.690
Portuguese, Swedish, Dutch,

00:03:49.690 --> 00:03:52.450
and French all entered a race to explore

00:03:52.450 --> 00:03:55.630
and map the entire east coast of North America.

00:03:55.630 --> 00:03:59.560
In 1497, Italian explorer, Giovanni Caboto,

00:03:59.560 --> 00:04:02.800
known as John Cabot by his English employers,

00:04:02.800 --> 00:04:05.290
discovered the same region of Newfoundland

00:04:05.290 --> 00:04:07.030
that Leif Erikson and the Vikings

00:04:07.030 --> 00:04:10.330
had settled nearly 500 years earlier.

00:04:10.330 --> 00:04:13.180
Cabot's discoveries credited him as the discoverer

00:04:13.180 --> 00:04:15.160
of the North American continent,

00:04:15.160 --> 00:04:17.320
as no record of Erikson's expedition

00:04:17.320 --> 00:04:19.900
or settlement had yet been discovered.

00:04:19.900 --> 00:04:23.140
To the South, expeditions by Juan Ponce de Leon,

00:04:23.140 --> 00:04:25.540
Alvar Nunez Cabeza de Vaca,

00:04:25.540 --> 00:04:28.180
and Hernando de Soto would map Florida

00:04:28.180 --> 00:04:30.100
and the American Southeast,

00:04:30.100 --> 00:04:33.010
as Spain prepared to establish permanent colonies

00:04:33.010 --> 00:04:34.210
in the New World.

00:04:34.210 --> 00:04:37.150
Likewise, to the North, Jacques Cartier explored

00:04:37.150 --> 00:04:38.560
the Saint Lawrence River

00:04:38.560 --> 00:04:41.380
while Giovanni da Verrazzano mapped much

00:04:41.380 --> 00:04:43.660
of the East Coast for France.

00:04:43.660 --> 00:04:46.210
All along the coast, the Europeans encountered

00:04:46.210 --> 00:04:49.090
the numerous tribes of Native Americans.

00:04:49.090 --> 00:04:52.420
Early interactions ranged from welcoming to violent,

00:04:52.420 --> 00:04:54.880
as cultures from separate hemispheres met

00:04:54.880 --> 00:04:56.590
for the first time.

00:04:56.590 --> 00:04:59.290
As it had in the Caribbean and South America,

00:04:59.290 --> 00:05:02.140
first contact introduced these cultures to each other

00:05:02.140 --> 00:05:05.260
with the sharing of gifts and trading of information.

00:05:05.260 --> 00:05:08.050
Naturally, these meetings exposed Native Americans

00:05:08.050 --> 00:05:09.670
to European diseases

00:05:09.670 --> 00:05:12.700
and caused widespread illness and death.

00:05:12.700 --> 00:05:14.890
The first attempts to make permanent settlements

00:05:14.890 --> 00:05:18.010
in the New World began in the mid 16th century

00:05:18.010 --> 00:05:20.320
with varying degrees of success.

00:05:20.320 --> 00:05:23.560
Surviving in the New World was not an easy task

00:05:23.560 --> 00:05:25.990
and establishing a permanent settlement proved

00:05:25.990 --> 00:05:28.210
to be exceptionally challenging.

00:05:28.210 --> 00:05:30.640
In 1585, the English attempted

00:05:30.640 --> 00:05:32.590
to establish a permanent colony

00:05:32.590 --> 00:05:34.360
on Roanoke Island off the coast

00:05:34.360 --> 00:05:36.700
of what is today North Carolina.

00:05:36.700 --> 00:05:39.490
The journey across the Atlantic was brutal

00:05:39.490 --> 00:05:42.550
and left the colonists with few supplies when they arrived,

00:05:42.550 --> 00:05:43.630
making contact with

00:05:43.630 --> 00:05:47.260
the local Aquascogoc, Pamala, and Sakonnet tribes,

00:05:47.260 --> 00:05:50.470
the colonists, many of whom were military personnel,

00:05:50.470 --> 00:05:53.890
became embroiled in an argument with the Aquascogoc

00:05:53.890 --> 00:05:56.260
and burned their village to the ground.

00:05:56.260 --> 00:05:59.230
Meetings with the Sakonnet went considerably better,

00:05:59.230 --> 00:06:01.180
outfitting the colonists with enough food

00:06:01.180 --> 00:06:03.760
to survive a miserable winter.

00:06:03.760 --> 00:06:06.310
Smallpox and influenza epidemics ran

00:06:06.310 --> 00:06:09.850
through every native village who encountered the colonists.

00:06:09.850 --> 00:06:11.650
Communication broke down

00:06:11.650 --> 00:06:15.220
and violence finally convinced the colonists to move on,

00:06:15.220 --> 00:06:16.750
abandoning the colony.

00:06:16.750 --> 00:06:18.820
Arriving in 1587,

00:06:18.820 --> 00:06:21.880
a year after the first attempt to settle Roanoke failed,

00:06:21.880 --> 00:06:25.180
colonists, largely made up of middle-class Londoners

00:06:25.180 --> 00:06:27.220
with no military experience,

00:06:27.220 --> 00:06:29.290
landed on Croatoan Island

00:06:29.290 --> 00:06:32.740
and began to establish a settlement some 40 miles south

00:06:32.740 --> 00:06:34.810
of the first failed settlement.

00:06:34.810 --> 00:06:37.900
The colony suffered great difficulty surviving.

00:06:37.900 --> 00:06:41.410
In 1588, a relief mission to the colony was looted

00:06:41.410 --> 00:06:44.860
by Spanish Naval vessels operating off the coast,

00:06:44.860 --> 00:06:48.670
leaving its new location unknown to English authorities.

00:06:48.670 --> 00:06:52.630
That same year, Spanish vessels sailed near Croatoan Island

00:06:52.630 --> 00:06:54.910
and found that it appeared abandoned.

00:06:54.910 --> 00:06:57.820
The next relief mission to the colony finally arrived

00:06:57.820 --> 00:07:02.680
in 1590 and found smoke rising from both Croatoan Island

00:07:02.680 --> 00:07:04.360
and Roanoke Island.

00:07:04.360 --> 00:07:05.830
A landing party discovered

00:07:05.830 --> 00:07:08.590
both settlements abandoned and sacked.

00:07:08.590 --> 00:07:13.120
The only clues were the letters CRO carved into a tree

00:07:13.120 --> 00:07:16.300
and the word Croatoan carved into one of the posts

00:07:16.300 --> 00:07:20.380
of a palisade allegedly built by the settlers of the colony.

00:07:20.380 --> 00:07:22.090
Known one as the Lost Colony,

00:07:22.090 --> 00:07:24.850
the settlers of Roanoke were never discovered.

00:07:24.850 --> 00:07:27.880
The colony deemed lost by the English government.

00:07:27.880 --> 00:07:32.290
In 1564, a group of French Huguenots settlers attempted

00:07:32.290 --> 00:07:33.123
to start a colony

00:07:33.123 --> 00:07:36.010
in what would become St. Augustine, Florida,

00:07:36.010 --> 00:07:37.990
only to have the colony sacked,

00:07:37.990 --> 00:07:42.100
and all of its male citizens killed by rival Spanish forces.

00:07:42.100 --> 00:07:44.560
The settlement established by the Spanish colonists

00:07:44.560 --> 00:07:45.880
at St. Augustine

00:07:45.880 --> 00:07:49.240
is considered the first permanent European settlement

00:07:49.240 --> 00:07:50.563
in North America.

00:07:51.653 --> 00:07:55.030
(uplifting music)

00:07:55.030 --> 00:07:57.970
In 1607, the English attempted again

00:07:57.970 --> 00:08:01.150
to establish a permanent colony in the New World.

00:08:01.150 --> 00:08:02.860
Led by the London company,

00:08:02.860 --> 00:08:06.010
the settlement aimed to establish a colony in Virginia

00:08:06.010 --> 00:08:09.310
and selected a marshy region on the James River,

00:08:09.310 --> 00:08:11.650
which they christened Jamestown.

00:08:11.650 --> 00:08:13.510
The colony did well initially,

00:08:13.510 --> 00:08:14.890
quickly constructing living

00:08:14.890 --> 00:08:17.980
and meeting space as well as a palisade fort.

00:08:17.980 --> 00:08:20.860
Relations with the local Powhatan tribes began

00:08:20.860 --> 00:08:24.190
with hostilities, but gradually cooled over time

00:08:24.190 --> 00:08:26.020
as the settlers and Native peoples

00:08:26.020 --> 00:08:28.180
of the region learned to cohabitate.

00:08:28.180 --> 00:08:29.830
The Powhatan offered food

00:08:29.830 --> 00:08:32.950
and friendship to the colonists who took the opportunity

00:08:32.950 --> 00:08:35.170
to search the surrounding region for gold

00:08:35.170 --> 00:08:37.090
and other precious metals.

00:08:37.090 --> 00:08:39.490
Instead they found that the swampy region

00:08:39.490 --> 00:08:43.150
that they had inhabited held no riches, but disease.

00:08:43.150 --> 00:08:46.780
The people of Jamestown suffered from lack of coordination,

00:08:46.780 --> 00:08:50.380
disease and the harshness of the environment around them,

00:08:50.380 --> 00:08:53.080
despite the aid of the Powhatan people.

00:08:53.080 --> 00:08:55.590
It was only when Captain John Smith took command

00:08:55.590 --> 00:08:58.720
of the colony and in near dictatorial fashion,

00:08:58.720 --> 00:09:01.450
reorganized their efforts to establish trade

00:09:01.450 --> 00:09:04.180
with the Natives and plant crops of their own in

00:09:04.180 --> 00:09:05.590
and around the colony.

00:09:05.590 --> 00:09:07.600
Smith returned home to England not long

00:09:07.600 --> 00:09:09.970
after his term as leader of the colony,

00:09:09.970 --> 00:09:13.390
but he had established a path for the colonist to follow

00:09:13.390 --> 00:09:16.600
that allowed Jamestown to endure difficult years

00:09:16.600 --> 00:09:18.190
of famine and struggle.

00:09:18.190 --> 00:09:22.870
Jamestown survived and by the mid 17th century was thriving

00:09:22.870 --> 00:09:25.570
as more settlements began to grow around her.

00:09:25.570 --> 00:09:27.280
Jamestown has the distinction

00:09:27.280 --> 00:09:29.320
of being the first English settlement

00:09:29.320 --> 00:09:31.450
to survive in the New World.

00:09:31.450 --> 00:09:35.200
In 1619, 12 years after the colony's founding,

00:09:35.200 --> 00:09:38.440
Jamestown became the site of yet another first

00:09:38.440 --> 00:09:41.660
when the first African slaves arrived in Virginia.

00:09:41.660 --> 00:09:45.160
20 to 30 enslaved Africans who had been captured

00:09:45.160 --> 00:09:48.760
by English privateers from a Spanish slave ship were brought

00:09:48.760 --> 00:09:50.860
to Point Comfort, Virginia.

00:09:50.860 --> 00:09:52.510
From there, a number were sold

00:09:52.510 --> 00:09:54.730
or traded to the settlement at Jamestown.

00:09:54.730 --> 00:09:57.160
Slavery had existed in the New World since

00:09:57.160 --> 00:09:58.990
the mid 16th century,

00:09:58.990 --> 00:10:01.210
but this moment marked the beginning of two

00:10:01.210 --> 00:10:03.370
and a half centuries of slavery

00:10:03.370 --> 00:10:06.160
in what would become the United States.

00:10:06.160 --> 00:10:08.530
The English continued their colonial settlement

00:10:08.530 --> 00:10:10.660
in 1620 with the establishing

00:10:10.660 --> 00:10:14.200
of the Puritan colony at Plymouth, Massachusetts.

00:10:14.200 --> 00:10:17.080
Unlike the financially motivated London Company

00:10:17.080 --> 00:10:20.560
at Jamestown, the Puritan colonists at Plymouth,

00:10:20.560 --> 00:10:23.560
known as Pilgrims, had come to America in search

00:10:23.560 --> 00:10:25.120
of religious freedom.

00:10:25.120 --> 00:10:28.300
They voyaged across the Atlantic in the Mayflower,

00:10:28.300 --> 00:10:31.630
suffering months of terrible weather at sea.

00:10:31.630 --> 00:10:33.370
When they arrived in the New World,

00:10:33.370 --> 00:10:34.450
they first landed near

00:10:34.450 --> 00:10:37.120
what would become known as Provincetown.

00:10:37.120 --> 00:10:40.300
There the colonists, concerned over their rights to the land

00:10:40.300 --> 00:10:42.700
and their legal right to establish a colony,

00:10:42.700 --> 00:10:45.760
drafted and signed the Mayflower Compact,

00:10:45.760 --> 00:10:47.020
establishing their right

00:10:47.020 --> 00:10:49.630
to self-govern while still holding allegiance

00:10:49.630 --> 00:10:51.070
to the English crown.

00:10:51.070 --> 00:10:53.530
However, without finding a reasonable place

00:10:53.530 --> 00:10:56.590
to begin building their settlement and after a brief

00:10:56.590 --> 00:10:59.080
but violent encounter with a local tribe,

00:10:59.080 --> 00:11:01.750
the Puritans found Provincetown unfit

00:11:01.750 --> 00:11:04.150
and sailed up the coast for better ground.

00:11:04.150 --> 00:11:07.030
At last, they decided on Plymouth Harbor,

00:11:07.030 --> 00:11:10.600
building upon an abandoned Patuxet settlement as a base

00:11:10.600 --> 00:11:11.770
for their new home.

00:11:11.770 --> 00:11:13.300
Settled between two hills

00:11:13.300 --> 00:11:15.760
on which the colonists built two forts,

00:11:15.760 --> 00:11:18.220
the colony at Plymouth initially struggled

00:11:18.220 --> 00:11:21.640
through difficult winter, living aboard the Mayflower

00:11:21.640 --> 00:11:23.830
and building their settlement by day.

00:11:23.830 --> 00:11:27.100
In March, 1621, they made first contact

00:11:27.100 --> 00:11:28.450
with the Wampanoag.

00:11:28.450 --> 00:11:31.450
The Wampanoag Chief Massasoit was hesitant

00:11:31.450 --> 00:11:33.160
to trust the Pilgrims.

00:11:33.160 --> 00:11:36.040
Also uncertain of the Puritans was Squanto,

00:11:36.040 --> 00:11:40.253
a Patuxet Native who had been taken in by the Wampanoag.

00:11:40.253 --> 00:11:43.390
Squanto or Tisquantum spoke English

00:11:43.390 --> 00:11:44.890
and had spent time in Europe

00:11:44.890 --> 00:11:49.540
after he'd been kidnapped by an English explorer in 1614.

00:11:49.540 --> 00:11:50.920
He had returned to America

00:11:50.920 --> 00:11:53.800
with another explorer whose party was ambushed

00:11:53.800 --> 00:11:56.950
and massacred by Massasoit and his tribe.

00:11:56.950 --> 00:11:58.420
Working as an interpreter,

00:11:58.420 --> 00:12:01.240
Squanto helped the Puritans in the Wampanoag reach

00:12:01.240 --> 00:12:03.100
an agreement of non-aggression.

00:12:03.100 --> 00:12:06.460
In the fall of 1621, the Pilgrims celebrated

00:12:06.460 --> 00:12:09.670
what has become known as the first Thanksgiving,

00:12:09.670 --> 00:12:13.060
along with Chief Massasoit and several of his men.

00:12:13.060 --> 00:12:15.850
The celebration lasted for three days

00:12:15.850 --> 00:12:17.500
and both parties procured

00:12:17.500 --> 00:12:20.410
and presented various dishes of local game.

00:12:20.410 --> 00:12:22.900
Like Jamestown, Plymouth was well run

00:12:22.900 --> 00:12:24.880
and its early success was built upon

00:12:24.880 --> 00:12:28.630
by enterprising companies and individuals in England.

00:12:28.630 --> 00:12:31.750
More and more companies began crossing the Atlantic

00:12:31.750 --> 00:12:33.970
and established new settlements.

00:12:33.970 --> 00:12:35.950
Throughout the 17th century,

00:12:35.950 --> 00:12:37.360
the English began spreading

00:12:37.360 --> 00:12:39.160
as more colonies were formed

00:12:39.160 --> 00:12:42.310
and amalgamated with their fellow English neighbors.

00:12:42.310 --> 00:12:45.070
The Massachusetts Bay Colony, for example,

00:12:45.070 --> 00:12:46.810
would absorb the Plymouth colony

00:12:46.810 --> 00:12:49.030
and others as it grew in size.

00:12:49.030 --> 00:12:51.640
As these settlements became more established,

00:12:51.640 --> 00:12:54.520
trade opened with Europe and goods, money,

00:12:54.520 --> 00:12:57.670
and more colonists poured into the New World.

00:12:57.670 --> 00:13:00.850
Not to be outdone, other European powers attempted

00:13:00.850 --> 00:13:03.160
to create their own permanent settlements

00:13:03.160 --> 00:13:04.330
as they grabbed more

00:13:04.330 --> 00:13:07.090
and more of the coastal region for themselves.

00:13:07.090 --> 00:13:10.990
What started as small settlements along coastal waters soon

00:13:10.990 --> 00:13:14.050
became large swaths of territory,

00:13:14.050 --> 00:13:16.600
claimed in the name of kings and queens

00:13:16.600 --> 00:13:19.390
from far-off European nations.

00:13:19.390 --> 00:13:23.050
In 1614, the Dutch West India company began

00:13:23.050 --> 00:13:26.410
to establish permanent settlements in the Northeast around

00:13:26.410 --> 00:13:29.530
what would one day become New York and New Jersey.

00:13:29.530 --> 00:13:32.110
Small settlements and fur trading outposts

00:13:32.110 --> 00:13:33.310
on Governors Island

00:13:33.310 --> 00:13:35.650
and along the Hudson and East Rivers marked

00:13:35.650 --> 00:13:38.020
what was called New Netherlands.

00:13:38.020 --> 00:13:41.560
In 1624, fearing military incursions

00:13:41.560 --> 00:13:43.330
from other European powers,

00:13:43.330 --> 00:13:44.530
they purchased the island

00:13:44.530 --> 00:13:49.240
of Manhattan from the Munsee Lenape tribe for $24

00:13:49.240 --> 00:13:51.280
and constructed Fort Amsterdam

00:13:51.280 --> 00:13:53.080
at the southern tip of the island.

00:13:53.080 --> 00:13:54.850
The settlement which grew within

00:13:54.850 --> 00:13:58.030
and alongside the fort was called New Amsterdam.

00:13:58.030 --> 00:14:00.520
The settlement utilized its unique environment

00:14:00.520 --> 00:14:04.600
to expand trade and use hydropower to enhance its growth.

00:14:04.600 --> 00:14:06.910
New Amsterdam was a city of trade

00:14:06.910 --> 00:14:10.900
and commerce in its earliest form, and always would be.

00:14:10.900 --> 00:14:14.590
It was a tempting target for the English who wanted control

00:14:14.590 --> 00:14:16.420
of the Hudson for themselves.

00:14:16.420 --> 00:14:20.680
In 1664, four English frigates sailed into the harbor

00:14:20.680 --> 00:14:22.000
of New Amsterdam

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:24.820
and ordered the Dutch to surrender the city.

00:14:24.820 --> 00:14:26.590
They did so bloodlessly,

00:14:26.590 --> 00:14:30.700
although the event did spark the Second Anglo-Dutch War.

00:14:30.700 --> 00:14:32.800
In June, 1665,

00:14:32.800 --> 00:14:35.950
New Amsterdam was reincorporated under English law

00:14:35.950 --> 00:14:38.080
and renamed New York City.

00:14:38.080 --> 00:14:39.970
Spain, whose early discovery

00:14:39.970 --> 00:14:41.890
of the New World gave them an advantage

00:14:41.890 --> 00:14:45.790
in colonizing South America and the Caribbean began settling

00:14:45.790 --> 00:14:49.000
in what would become the American Southeast.

00:14:49.000 --> 00:14:51.880
From their earliest settlement in St. Augustine,

00:14:51.880 --> 00:14:53.500
the Spanish traveled inward

00:14:53.500 --> 00:14:56.680
toward their territorial conquests in Mexico

00:14:56.680 --> 00:14:58.540
and upward toward Canada,

00:14:58.540 --> 00:15:00.340
carving a path through the center

00:15:00.340 --> 00:15:02.380
of the North American continent.

00:15:02.380 --> 00:15:04.540
By the end of the 17th century,

00:15:04.540 --> 00:15:07.330
Spain's North American empire would cover much

00:15:07.330 --> 00:15:09.520
of the Deep South, Midwest,

00:15:09.520 --> 00:15:11.890
and Western portions of the continent.

00:15:11.890 --> 00:15:14.140
France, England's longtime rival

00:15:14.140 --> 00:15:16.240
and chief competitor in North America,

00:15:16.240 --> 00:15:18.520
set their sights for permanent settlement along

00:15:18.520 --> 00:15:20.200
the Saint Lawrence River.

00:15:20.200 --> 00:15:22.930
Still hoping for an easy path to the Pacific,

00:15:22.930 --> 00:15:26.440
the settlements, Tadoussac, Quebec, Trois-Rivieres,

00:15:26.440 --> 00:15:30.040
and Montreal followed the winding Saint Lawrence further

00:15:30.040 --> 00:15:31.480
and further inland.

00:15:31.480 --> 00:15:33.460
France established firm control

00:15:33.460 --> 00:15:35.200
of the fur trade in the region.

00:15:35.200 --> 00:15:37.630
Then began to extend its influence further

00:15:37.630 --> 00:15:39.340
down the Mississippi River.

00:15:39.340 --> 00:15:41.230
In the Gulf, the French established

00:15:41.230 --> 00:15:42.370
a settlement along the bank

00:15:42.370 --> 00:15:47.370
of the Mississippi called Nouvelle-Orleans or New Orleans.

00:15:47.590 --> 00:15:50.920
New Orleans was established in 1718

00:15:50.920 --> 00:15:53.320
and was the gateway to the Mississippi,

00:15:53.320 --> 00:15:56.863
a crown jewel in France's North American empire.

00:15:57.728 --> 00:15:59.470
(tense music)

00:15:59.470 --> 00:16:01.510
As the 18th century began,

00:16:01.510 --> 00:16:03.790
the numerous settlements continued to grow

00:16:03.790 --> 00:16:05.890
as Europe carved up great swaths

00:16:05.890 --> 00:16:07.690
of North America for their own.

00:16:07.690 --> 00:16:11.530
These colonial territories were defined by various treaties

00:16:11.530 --> 00:16:14.410
and agreements between the colonizing nations,

00:16:14.410 --> 00:16:18.130
often ignoring the already existing Native population,

00:16:18.130 --> 00:16:19.990
and the complex relationships

00:16:19.990 --> 00:16:23.260
which already existed in North America.

00:16:23.260 --> 00:16:25.630
Many Native Americans fought back.

00:16:25.630 --> 00:16:27.250
Acting as opportunists,

00:16:27.250 --> 00:16:30.820
tribes worked with and against European settlers,

00:16:30.820 --> 00:16:32.680
often sparking conflict.

00:16:32.680 --> 00:16:35.110
Raids on settlements were not uncommon

00:16:35.110 --> 00:16:37.150
and the colonists could not always rely

00:16:37.150 --> 00:16:39.670
on their far-flung colonial protectors

00:16:39.670 --> 00:16:42.970
if these actions required a serious defense.

00:16:42.970 --> 00:16:45.100
One of the largest and most violent

00:16:45.100 --> 00:16:47.650
of these was King Philip's War.

00:16:47.650 --> 00:16:50.920
In 1675 in the colony of New England,

00:16:50.920 --> 00:16:53.590
war broke out after a significant failure

00:16:53.590 --> 00:16:55.930
of diplomacy between the colonists

00:16:55.930 --> 00:16:58.810
and the Wampanoag tribe and their allies.

00:16:58.810 --> 00:17:00.820
Metacomet, son of Massasoit,

00:17:00.820 --> 00:17:03.250
who had aided the Pilgrims at Plymouth Colony,

00:17:03.250 --> 00:17:06.880
had become the grand sachem of the Wampanoag Confederacy

00:17:06.880 --> 00:17:09.490
and did not have the same tolerance for the settlers

00:17:09.490 --> 00:17:10.900
as his father had.

00:17:10.900 --> 00:17:14.560
Disagreements over livestock, intrusion on Wampanoag land,

00:17:14.560 --> 00:17:17.410
and the presence of colonial missionaries attempting

00:17:17.410 --> 00:17:20.770
to convert Natives to Christianity was the last straw

00:17:20.770 --> 00:17:23.350
for Metacomet who, unlike his father,

00:17:23.350 --> 00:17:25.600
saw only danger in the existence

00:17:25.600 --> 00:17:27.370
of these settlers on their land.

00:17:27.370 --> 00:17:29.800
An alliance of Algonquians tribes led

00:17:29.800 --> 00:17:31.420
by Metacomet struck at,

00:17:31.420 --> 00:17:35.410
not only New England's far-flung countryside settlements,

00:17:35.410 --> 00:17:38.500
but the larger, more established towns as well.

00:17:38.500 --> 00:17:41.470
With no English soldiers stationed in the colonies,

00:17:41.470 --> 00:17:45.070
the New England Militia mobilized to defend their homes.

00:17:45.070 --> 00:17:47.920
The militia targeted native villages knowing

00:17:47.920 --> 00:17:50.530
that it would enrage and damage the Indian's ability

00:17:50.530 --> 00:17:51.880
to wage war.

00:17:51.880 --> 00:17:55.210
Metacomet was killed in 1676,

00:17:55.210 --> 00:17:56.950
just a year into the war.

00:17:56.950 --> 00:17:59.830
His death spelled doom for the Wampanoag

00:17:59.830 --> 00:18:02.170
and their Narraganset allies

00:18:02.170 --> 00:18:04.300
with no one guiding the conflict,

00:18:04.300 --> 00:18:05.980
things quickly turned in the favor

00:18:05.980 --> 00:18:08.350
of the New England Militia who all

00:18:08.350 --> 00:18:10.630
but destroyed the Wampanoag people

00:18:10.630 --> 00:18:14.170
and forced their allies out of the New England territory.

00:18:14.170 --> 00:18:17.620
It was the bloodiest conflict in North America to date.

00:18:17.620 --> 00:18:19.660
In the wake of King Philip's war,

00:18:19.660 --> 00:18:22.510
tension between the English colonists and their French

00:18:22.510 --> 00:18:24.340
and Dutch neighbors grew high.

00:18:24.340 --> 00:18:25.390
In the Northeast,

00:18:25.390 --> 00:18:27.400
five native tribes located north

00:18:27.400 --> 00:18:31.480
of the New England colony formed the Wabanaki Confederation

00:18:31.480 --> 00:18:32.950
after witnessing the demise

00:18:32.950 --> 00:18:36.910
of their Southern Wampanoag neighbors in King Philip's War,

00:18:36.910 --> 00:18:39.850
increasing tensions with the English colonists.

00:18:39.850 --> 00:18:44.320
In 1689, just two years after King Philip's War had ended,

00:18:44.320 --> 00:18:46.630
the colonists were at war again,

00:18:46.630 --> 00:18:49.480
this time at the behest of their mother countries.

00:18:49.480 --> 00:18:52.960
Fighting broke out as the English-backed Iroquois tribes

00:18:52.960 --> 00:18:54.550
attacked French settlements

00:18:54.550 --> 00:18:58.090
and the French-backed Wabanaki attacked English ones.

00:18:58.090 --> 00:19:00.400
As French and English soldiers made their way

00:19:00.400 --> 00:19:03.220
to the New World, the colonists of New England

00:19:03.220 --> 00:19:06.040
and New France prepared to fight each other.

00:19:06.040 --> 00:19:07.930
Known as King William's War,

00:19:07.930 --> 00:19:10.810
the conflict dragged on for nearly a decade

00:19:10.810 --> 00:19:13.780
and saw French successes in the colony of New York

00:19:13.780 --> 00:19:16.240
and English successes in Acadia,

00:19:16.240 --> 00:19:18.160
later known as Nova Scotia,

00:19:18.160 --> 00:19:20.200
and along the Saint Lawrence River.

00:19:20.200 --> 00:19:22.930
Neither side was able to take their main goal.

00:19:22.930 --> 00:19:24.700
For the French, Boston,

00:19:24.700 --> 00:19:29.680
for the English, Quebec, and the war concluded in 1697.

00:19:29.680 --> 00:19:32.410
But King William's War was only the beginning.

00:19:32.410 --> 00:19:34.960
It was the first of four major conflicts

00:19:34.960 --> 00:19:36.550
between France and England,

00:19:36.550 --> 00:19:38.710
which pitted their various Native allies

00:19:38.710 --> 00:19:42.460
against one another, and peace was not kept for long.

00:19:42.460 --> 00:19:45.580
In 1701, King Charles II,

00:19:45.580 --> 00:19:49.360
the last Habsburg king of Spain died with no direct heir

00:19:49.360 --> 00:19:52.810
and a confusing web of potential replacements bound

00:19:52.810 --> 00:19:53.980
by secret treaties

00:19:53.980 --> 00:19:55.540
and backroom agreements.

00:19:55.540 --> 00:19:59.155
English, Austrian, Prussian and Dutch powers scrambled

00:19:59.155 --> 00:20:01.210
to stop the French from taking control

00:20:01.210 --> 00:20:02.620
of the Spanish throne.

00:20:02.620 --> 00:20:05.140
Known as the War of Spanish Succession

00:20:05.140 --> 00:20:07.900
or Queen Anne's war in North America,

00:20:07.900 --> 00:20:10.060
the conflict originated in Europe,

00:20:10.060 --> 00:20:12.370
and did not take long for the fighting to come

00:20:12.370 --> 00:20:14.260
to the shores of North America.

00:20:14.260 --> 00:20:16.090
In the South, Spanish Florida

00:20:16.090 --> 00:20:18.790
and French colonists in Louisiana were engaged

00:20:18.790 --> 00:20:22.210
by English colonists from the province of Carolina.

00:20:22.210 --> 00:20:25.870
The fighting decimated the Native populations of the region

00:20:25.870 --> 00:20:28.870
and helped secure English control of Georgia.

00:20:28.870 --> 00:20:32.500
In New England, the Wabanaki again sided with the French

00:20:32.500 --> 00:20:35.470
and continuous raids on New English settlements plagued

00:20:35.470 --> 00:20:37.390
the Massachusetts Bay Colony.

00:20:37.390 --> 00:20:38.860
Concerted efforts made

00:20:38.860 --> 00:20:41.620
by the English military once again failed

00:20:41.620 --> 00:20:43.270
to capture Quebec City,

00:20:43.270 --> 00:20:46.180
but made considerable gains in Acadia.

00:20:46.180 --> 00:20:48.790
The fighting in North America had little effect

00:20:48.790 --> 00:20:51.250
on the war's ultimate outcome in Europe,

00:20:51.250 --> 00:20:53.260
but more than 13 years

00:20:53.260 --> 00:20:55.660
of continuous fighting wreaked havoc

00:20:55.660 --> 00:20:57.280
throughout North America,

00:20:57.280 --> 00:20:58.990
permanently damaging Native

00:20:58.990 --> 00:21:01.090
and colonial communities alike.

00:21:01.090 --> 00:21:04.090
In the end, the French would give away vital territory

00:21:04.090 --> 00:21:07.360
to the English, including the Hudson River Valley,

00:21:07.360 --> 00:21:09.520
Acadia, and Newfoundland.

00:21:09.520 --> 00:21:11.470
These concessions did not include

00:21:11.470 --> 00:21:14.980
the various Native tribes engaged on either side of the war

00:21:14.980 --> 00:21:17.830
and set the stage for future conflicts.

00:21:17.830 --> 00:21:19.420
For nearly three decades,

00:21:19.420 --> 00:21:20.680
there was relative peace

00:21:20.680 --> 00:21:23.890
between the major European powers in North America.

00:21:23.890 --> 00:21:26.050
In this time, the colonies grew larger

00:21:26.050 --> 00:21:29.710
and more complex, forming their own colonial governments,

00:21:29.710 --> 00:21:30.970
and expanding a new

00:21:30.970 --> 00:21:34.210
and thriving North American economy of agriculture,

00:21:34.210 --> 00:21:37.300
textile production, and maritime trade.

00:21:37.300 --> 00:21:40.300
As the value of the North American colonies grew,

00:21:40.300 --> 00:21:42.460
it did alongside her South American

00:21:42.460 --> 00:21:44.140
and Caribbean neighbors.

00:21:44.140 --> 00:21:47.860
Valuable gold and silver had been found in South America

00:21:47.860 --> 00:21:50.410
and the Caribbean produced commodities which were

00:21:50.410 --> 00:21:52.267
by now a necessity in Europe

00:21:52.267 --> 00:21:56.920
and North America, namely molasses and other sugar products.

00:21:56.920 --> 00:21:59.440
The production of these commodities, of course,

00:21:59.440 --> 00:22:02.380
was powered by the sweat of slave labor.

00:22:02.380 --> 00:22:05.230
By now, the American colonies were all engaged

00:22:05.230 --> 00:22:08.050
in what was known as the triangle trade.

00:22:08.050 --> 00:22:10.930
Slaves from Africa were brought to the Americas

00:22:10.930 --> 00:22:13.510
where these slave ships would deposit African slaves

00:22:13.510 --> 00:22:17.710
for sale and take on cargo of sugar bound for New England.

00:22:17.710 --> 00:22:20.680
These ships would then sell the sugar and slaves

00:22:20.680 --> 00:22:24.340
and take on rum, tobacco, cotton and other goods

00:22:24.340 --> 00:22:27.490
and return to Africa to trade them for slaves.

00:22:27.490 --> 00:22:29.170
On and on it went,

00:22:29.170 --> 00:22:33.520
an evermore valuable and grotesque sale of human lives.

00:22:33.520 --> 00:22:37.330
Slavery was rampant in the Caribbean and South America

00:22:37.330 --> 00:22:40.660
and grew rapidly in North American colonies as well.

00:22:40.660 --> 00:22:41.890
From the first years

00:22:41.890 --> 00:22:45.510
of North American colonization in the early 1600s

00:22:45.510 --> 00:22:47.800
to the mid 18th century,

00:22:47.800 --> 00:22:49.540
the number of slaves imported

00:22:49.540 --> 00:22:52.467
to the Americas had increased from roughly 300,000

00:22:53.470 --> 00:22:58.000
from 1600 to 1625 to more than 2 million

00:22:58.000 --> 00:23:01.870
from 1751 to 1775.

00:23:01.870 --> 00:23:02.980
The increased value

00:23:02.980 --> 00:23:05.740
of the Americas led directly to the third

00:23:05.740 --> 00:23:07.390
of the Indian wars.

00:23:07.390 --> 00:23:09.190
Like Queen Anne's War before it,

00:23:09.190 --> 00:23:12.520
the conflict began well outside of North America.

00:23:12.520 --> 00:23:14.500
Distrustful of the Spanish control

00:23:14.500 --> 00:23:16.000
of the South American market,

00:23:16.000 --> 00:23:17.470
the British were displeased

00:23:17.470 --> 00:23:20.890
by the mercantile stranglehold Spain had over trade

00:23:20.890 --> 00:23:23.170
to South America and the Caribbean.

00:23:23.170 --> 00:23:25.300
Likewise, the Spanish were displeased

00:23:25.300 --> 00:23:27.880
with British encroachment in North America on

00:23:27.880 --> 00:23:30.970
what they believed was their territory north of Florida.

00:23:30.970 --> 00:23:35.050
After the 1721 founding of the Colony of Georgia,

00:23:35.050 --> 00:23:36.820
following Queen Anne's War,

00:23:36.820 --> 00:23:38.350
the Spanish were convinced

00:23:38.350 --> 00:23:41.770
that the British had designs on removing them from Florida.

00:23:41.770 --> 00:23:45.190
Spanish vessels began boarding British trading ships,

00:23:45.190 --> 00:23:46.990
searching for contraband.

00:23:46.990 --> 00:23:50.290
While this action was legal due to past treaties,

00:23:50.290 --> 00:23:52.540
the boardings resulted in increased tensions

00:23:52.540 --> 00:23:54.040
between the two powers.

00:23:54.040 --> 00:23:57.280
In 1731, the British brig, Rebecca,

00:23:57.280 --> 00:23:58.480
was stopped off the coast

00:23:58.480 --> 00:24:02.530
of Cuba and boarded for inspection of contraband cargo.

00:24:02.530 --> 00:24:04.780
Onboard, the Spanish officials found

00:24:04.780 --> 00:24:06.760
an illegal cargo of sugar.

00:24:06.760 --> 00:24:10.150
Rebecca's captain, a man named Robert Jenkins,

00:24:10.150 --> 00:24:12.040
alleged that during the search,

00:24:12.040 --> 00:24:14.950
he had been tortured by the Spanish officials

00:24:14.950 --> 00:24:17.770
and had had his ear partially cut off.

00:24:17.770 --> 00:24:20.890
While the Royal Navy would admit that Jenkins was at fault

00:24:20.890 --> 00:24:23.050
for carrying illegal cargo,

00:24:23.050 --> 00:24:26.620
his story, told before the Houses of Parliament in England,

00:24:26.620 --> 00:24:27.910
struck a nerve.

00:24:27.910 --> 00:24:32.230
In 1739, the British found that, among other reasons,

00:24:32.230 --> 00:24:33.460
the Spanish were guilty

00:24:33.460 --> 00:24:36.850
of depredations upon British subjects

00:24:36.850 --> 00:24:40.630
and commenced war against the Spanish in the Americas,

00:24:40.630 --> 00:24:43.630
known as the War of Jenkins' Ear.

00:24:43.630 --> 00:24:46.990
The conflict saw little action on North American shores

00:24:46.990 --> 00:24:49.840
with the bulk of the fighting occurring in South America

00:24:49.840 --> 00:24:53.170
and the Caribbean as the British Navy attempted to capture

00:24:53.170 --> 00:24:56.830
and claim multiple Spanish forts and port towns.

00:24:56.830 --> 00:24:58.630
Fighting between the British colonists

00:24:58.630 --> 00:25:00.490
in the Carolinas and Georgia

00:25:00.490 --> 00:25:03.850
and the Spanish colonists in Florida came too little fruit

00:25:03.850 --> 00:25:05.830
for either side and again,

00:25:05.830 --> 00:25:07.660
only appeared to do the worst harm

00:25:07.660 --> 00:25:09.430
to the local Indian tribes

00:25:09.430 --> 00:25:11.050
who fought on either side.

00:25:11.050 --> 00:25:14.920
In 1742, another war broke out in Europe.

00:25:14.920 --> 00:25:16.420
This time between Prussia

00:25:16.420 --> 00:25:19.150
and Austria over control of Silesia.

00:25:19.150 --> 00:25:21.130
Once again, a question of the right

00:25:21.130 --> 00:25:25.060
of succession brought all of Europe's great powers into war.

00:25:25.060 --> 00:25:28.180
The death of Emperor Charles VI of Austria

00:25:28.180 --> 00:25:30.670
had left a power vacuum in central Europe

00:25:30.670 --> 00:25:33.640
with Great Britain, the Dutch Republic, Hanover,

00:25:33.640 --> 00:25:36.310
and Russia supporting Charles VI's daughter,

00:25:36.310 --> 00:25:40.690
Maria Theresa as is heir, and France, Spain, Prussia,

00:25:40.690 --> 00:25:43.900
and Sweden supporting Charles Albert of Bavaria

00:25:43.900 --> 00:25:46.660
who believed he had the right of inheritance.

00:25:46.660 --> 00:25:49.960
This war, known as King George's War in North America,

00:25:49.960 --> 00:25:52.690
and the War of Austrian Succession in Europe,

00:25:52.690 --> 00:25:55.210
swallowed everything in its wake,

00:25:55.210 --> 00:25:57.670
including the War of Jenkins' Ear.

00:25:57.670 --> 00:26:01.570
As war raged in Europe, France and England once again turned

00:26:01.570 --> 00:26:04.750
their attention toward their North American territories.

00:26:04.750 --> 00:26:07.510
As before, the Wabanaki Confederacy

00:26:07.510 --> 00:26:10.300
and the Iroquois Confederacy allied themselves

00:26:10.300 --> 00:26:11.950
with the French and British,

00:26:11.950 --> 00:26:14.110
hoping to affect some great change

00:26:14.110 --> 00:26:16.450
for their rapidly shrinking continent.

00:26:16.450 --> 00:26:18.670
Fighting focused once again over control

00:26:18.670 --> 00:26:21.250
of Acadia and the Saint Lawrence River.

00:26:21.250 --> 00:26:24.340
In 1745, the British colonists achieved

00:26:24.340 --> 00:26:27.490
the first substantial gain in the last 50 years

00:26:27.490 --> 00:26:29.080
of colonial warfare

00:26:29.080 --> 00:26:31.390
with the capture of Fortress Louisbourg

00:26:31.390 --> 00:26:33.700
at the mouth of the Saint Lawrence River.

00:26:33.700 --> 00:26:34.960
Fighting stretched down

00:26:34.960 --> 00:26:37.990
into the Colony of New York as well as New England.

00:26:37.990 --> 00:26:41.290
The war took an awful toll on the British colonists,

00:26:41.290 --> 00:26:43.900
particularly in the final years of fighting.

00:26:43.900 --> 00:26:47.560
When the war at last came to an end in 1748,

00:26:47.560 --> 00:26:50.400
the British colonists were forced to return Louisbourg

00:26:50.400 --> 00:26:53.290
to the French, infuriating the colonists

00:26:53.290 --> 00:26:56.350
who had won it at an excessive cost of life.

00:26:56.350 --> 00:26:59.020
Once again, after years of violence,

00:26:59.020 --> 00:27:02.020
the borders were returned to their pre-war status

00:27:02.020 --> 00:27:04.030
with nothing having been gained.

00:27:04.030 --> 00:27:07.900
Territorial disputes went unsettled, grudges continued,

00:27:07.900 --> 00:27:10.900
and the situation in the North American back country

00:27:10.900 --> 00:27:14.740
was still violent as English colonists, French colonists,

00:27:14.740 --> 00:27:18.010
and Native American tribes all vied for control

00:27:18.010 --> 00:27:19.210
of the wilderness.

00:27:19.210 --> 00:27:21.430
The undefined borders between British

00:27:21.430 --> 00:27:23.470
and French colonies had long been

00:27:23.470 --> 00:27:25.750
an issue between the two nations.

00:27:25.750 --> 00:27:28.270
Yet despite multiple conflicts,

00:27:28.270 --> 00:27:30.160
no formal agreement had been reached

00:27:30.160 --> 00:27:33.520
as far as definitively laying out who owned what.

00:27:33.520 --> 00:27:37.393
It was only a matter of time before war broke out again.

00:27:39.260 --> 00:27:42.670
(uplifting music)

00:27:42.670 --> 00:27:45.790
In late 1753, the lieutenant governor

00:27:45.790 --> 00:27:48.550
of the Virginia Colony, Robert Dinwitty,

00:27:48.550 --> 00:27:52.510
ordered a young Virginia major named George Washington

00:27:52.510 --> 00:27:55.210
to remove French colonial troops from forts

00:27:55.210 --> 00:27:57.160
in the Ohio River Valley.

00:27:57.160 --> 00:28:00.550
The Colony of Virginia claimed this territory as its own

00:28:00.550 --> 00:28:02.200
and felt that it was within their right

00:28:02.200 --> 00:28:04.360
to vacate the French from the forts,

00:28:04.360 --> 00:28:05.890
which still dotted the region

00:28:05.890 --> 00:28:08.290
from the last century of fighting.

00:28:08.290 --> 00:28:11.050
The expedition resulted in a French rejection

00:28:11.050 --> 00:28:12.610
of Virginia's demands.

00:28:12.610 --> 00:28:15.580
And Washington, who was promoted to lieutenant colonel

00:28:15.580 --> 00:28:18.400
upon his return, was once again sent into

00:28:18.400 --> 00:28:20.020
the Ohio River Valley

00:28:20.020 --> 00:28:22.390
to remove the French from their forts.

00:28:22.390 --> 00:28:24.430
By force, if necessary.

00:28:24.430 --> 00:28:26.500
In April 1754,

00:28:26.500 --> 00:28:28.810
French troops learned from their Native allies,

00:28:28.810 --> 00:28:32.020
the Mingos that a small British fort had been built

00:28:32.020 --> 00:28:35.530
by colonial militia at the forts of the Ohio River.

00:28:35.530 --> 00:28:38.200
French troops marched to the fort and captured it.

00:28:38.200 --> 00:28:41.320
They built in its place a much later fortification,

00:28:41.320 --> 00:28:43.420
which they named Fort Duquesne.

00:28:43.420 --> 00:28:45.670
Meanwhile, further south in the valley,

00:28:45.670 --> 00:28:49.060
Colonel Washington and his small force of colonial militia

00:28:49.060 --> 00:28:51.490
and Natives, allied to the English,

00:28:51.490 --> 00:28:53.680
came upon and engaged an encampment

00:28:53.680 --> 00:28:55.990
of unsuspecting French troops.

00:28:55.990 --> 00:28:58.300
The French were quickly overwhelmed

00:28:58.300 --> 00:29:00.010
and later explained that they had been sent

00:29:00.010 --> 00:29:02.230
to intercept Washington peacefully

00:29:02.230 --> 00:29:04.690
and to warn him of his apparent incursion in

00:29:04.690 --> 00:29:07.030
what they believed was French territory.

00:29:07.030 --> 00:29:08.710
To Washington's surprise,

00:29:08.710 --> 00:29:11.530
the leader of the Native forces accompanying him,

00:29:11.530 --> 00:29:13.630
Tanaghrisson, attacked and killed

00:29:13.630 --> 00:29:15.370
the wounded French commander,

00:29:15.370 --> 00:29:18.700
likely due to a longstanding hatred of the French.

00:29:18.700 --> 00:29:21.040
Washington feared the French would attack

00:29:21.040 --> 00:29:25.030
and constructed a small fort, which he named Fort Necessity.

00:29:25.030 --> 00:29:27.880
Necessity was, as Washington predicted,

00:29:27.880 --> 00:29:30.940
quickly surrounded by French troops from Duquesne

00:29:30.940 --> 00:29:32.620
and forced to surrender.

00:29:32.620 --> 00:29:35.800
This small skirmish set the world on fire.

00:29:35.800 --> 00:29:37.600
Lieutenant Governor Dinwitty called

00:29:37.600 --> 00:29:39.610
for aid from his fellow colonies

00:29:39.610 --> 00:29:42.100
and from the British government back in England.

00:29:42.100 --> 00:29:43.360
Fearing that the incursion

00:29:43.360 --> 00:29:45.700
would strengthen French claims to the region,

00:29:45.700 --> 00:29:48.010
the British Government immediately sent troops

00:29:48.010 --> 00:29:50.980
to strike at the various French forts still in

00:29:50.980 --> 00:29:52.900
and around the Saint Lawrence River

00:29:52.900 --> 00:29:54.790
and the Ohio River Valley.

00:29:54.790 --> 00:29:57.700
The French sent additional forces to North America

00:29:57.700 --> 00:30:00.460
to hold off the inevitable British invasion.

00:30:00.460 --> 00:30:04.720
Quite suddenly, France and England were once again at war.

00:30:04.720 --> 00:30:08.200
Multiple early British forays into the Ohio River Valley

00:30:08.200 --> 00:30:10.810
and Canada failed spectacularly.

00:30:10.810 --> 00:30:11.920
Early into the war,

00:30:11.920 --> 00:30:13.900
it seemed as though the French would be able

00:30:13.900 --> 00:30:16.360
to secure their holdings in North America

00:30:16.360 --> 00:30:19.090
and even found success in capturing a number

00:30:19.090 --> 00:30:22.660
of critical British forts in the colony of New York,

00:30:22.660 --> 00:30:26.530
including Fort Ticonderoga and Fort William Henry.

00:30:26.530 --> 00:30:30.250
In 1758, fortunes changed for the English

00:30:30.250 --> 00:30:33.730
as the complicated system of entangled alliances produced

00:30:33.730 --> 00:30:36.730
by the past century of war finally ignited

00:30:36.730 --> 00:30:38.560
the Seven Years' War.

00:30:38.560 --> 00:30:40.720
The fighting in the Ohio River Valley,

00:30:40.720 --> 00:30:43.450
known as the French and Indian War in America,

00:30:43.450 --> 00:30:47.050
had launched the largest European land war to date

00:30:47.050 --> 00:30:49.390
with every major European power

00:30:49.390 --> 00:30:51.190
of the era engaged.

00:30:51.190 --> 00:30:52.540
Millions of soldiers

00:30:52.540 --> 00:30:56.170
and thousands of naval vessels were activated for duty.

00:30:56.170 --> 00:30:59.320
Fighting stretched not only across North American

00:30:59.320 --> 00:31:02.950
but to Europe, the Caribbean, India, and Asia.

00:31:02.950 --> 00:31:05.260
As the French were forced to direct their attention

00:31:05.260 --> 00:31:09.040
to Europe and to other more valuable parts of their empire,

00:31:09.040 --> 00:31:10.150
the British were able

00:31:10.150 --> 00:31:12.970
to take advantage on the North American front.

00:31:12.970 --> 00:31:15.580
With the British Navy actively keeping the French

00:31:15.580 --> 00:31:17.410
from not being able to resupply

00:31:17.410 --> 00:31:19.210
along the Saint Lawrence River,

00:31:19.210 --> 00:31:22.180
British and American colonial forces successfully

00:31:22.180 --> 00:31:25.270
captured Fort Niagara, Fortress Louisbourg,

00:31:25.270 --> 00:31:26.980
and the City of Quebec.

00:31:26.980 --> 00:31:28.630
As the French lost more

00:31:28.630 --> 00:31:31.600
and more ground, it became clear that the fight

00:31:31.600 --> 00:31:33.880
for North America was over.

00:31:33.880 --> 00:31:37.570
In 1760, British General Jeffrey Amherst managed

00:31:37.570 --> 00:31:39.460
to secure a formal surrender

00:31:39.460 --> 00:31:41.320
from the Governor of New France,

00:31:41.320 --> 00:31:45.880
Pierre Francois de Rigaud Marquis de Vaudreuil-Cavagnal,

00:31:45.880 --> 00:31:49.180
and largely ended the hostilities in North America.

00:31:49.180 --> 00:31:52.210
Meanwhile, the Seven Years' War continued abroad

00:31:52.210 --> 00:31:54.130
and continued to carve pieces

00:31:54.130 --> 00:31:56.890
from the Kingdom of France and her allies.

00:31:56.890 --> 00:32:01.450
In 1763, the Seven Years' War officially came to an end,

00:32:01.450 --> 00:32:03.790
and the French and Indian War with it.

00:32:03.790 --> 00:32:07.000
Casualties were astronomical for the period

00:32:07.000 --> 00:32:10.630
with some estimates reaching as high as 1.4 million.

00:32:10.630 --> 00:32:11.530
Of that number,

00:32:11.530 --> 00:32:13.450
the French and Indian War accounted

00:32:13.450 --> 00:32:17.770
for roughly 23,000 killed, wounded, or captured.

00:32:17.770 --> 00:32:20.950
Just under 2% of the total casualties

00:32:20.950 --> 00:32:22.570
of the global conflict.

00:32:22.570 --> 00:32:26.020
For nearly a century, England had beaten back the French,

00:32:26.020 --> 00:32:29.470
Dutch and Spanish Empires gradually cementing

00:32:29.470 --> 00:32:31.180
its claim to the New World.

00:32:31.180 --> 00:32:33.400
Over the course of the 18th century,

00:32:33.400 --> 00:32:35.410
the successes of the British Empire

00:32:35.410 --> 00:32:38.860
during these conflicts had created the ideal conditions

00:32:38.860 --> 00:32:40.840
for their colonies in North America

00:32:40.840 --> 00:32:44.380
to experience an incredible population boom

00:32:44.380 --> 00:32:47.880
from roughly 250,000 in 1700

00:32:47.880 --> 00:32:52.210
to more than 1.25 million in 1750.

00:32:52.210 --> 00:32:55.270
The raw materials produced by the American colonies,

00:32:55.270 --> 00:32:56.740
including hemp, copper,

00:32:56.740 --> 00:32:59.800
and tar were necessary for the British Army

00:32:59.800 --> 00:33:04.300
and Navy to wage war and protect the vastly growing empire.

00:33:04.300 --> 00:33:06.730
While it was in the interest of the British Empire

00:33:06.730 --> 00:33:08.020
to defeat the French

00:33:08.020 --> 00:33:10.450
and secure their North American holdings,

00:33:10.450 --> 00:33:13.300
it had also been in the colonists' interests.

00:33:13.300 --> 00:33:16.690
The English colonists had no great love for the French

00:33:16.690 --> 00:33:19.480
and anti-Catholic sentiment was a regular part

00:33:19.480 --> 00:33:23.200
of colonial life, especially in places like New England,

00:33:23.200 --> 00:33:25.090
which had been staunchly Protestant

00:33:25.090 --> 00:33:28.090
for the first two centuries of its settlement.

00:33:28.090 --> 00:33:30.580
That the American colonies were made up chiefly

00:33:30.580 --> 00:33:32.590
of individuals of the Protestant faith

00:33:32.590 --> 00:33:35.740
was naturally no coincidence.

00:33:35.740 --> 00:33:37.930
Many Protestant organizations had funded

00:33:37.930 --> 00:33:41.770
the various colonization efforts through the 17th century

00:33:41.770 --> 00:33:44.080
and had maintained a lasting impact

00:33:44.080 --> 00:33:46.720
in presence into the 1700s.

00:33:46.720 --> 00:33:48.820
However, the strongest impact

00:33:48.820 --> 00:33:51.610
of Protestantism in the American colonies came

00:33:51.610 --> 00:33:53.440
during the colonial wars,

00:33:53.440 --> 00:33:56.890
which dominated the early and mid 18th century.

00:33:56.890 --> 00:33:59.500
A global religious phenomenon occurred,

00:33:59.500 --> 00:34:02.500
known as the Great Awakening gripped both Europe

00:34:02.500 --> 00:34:04.000
and North America

00:34:04.000 --> 00:34:07.063
and brought the Protestant faith to new heights.

00:34:07.904 --> 00:34:10.240
(suspenseful music)

00:34:10.240 --> 00:34:13.600
The Great Awakening was a major evangelical revival

00:34:13.600 --> 00:34:16.480
which expanded the Protestant faith throughout Europe

00:34:16.480 --> 00:34:18.520
and Colonial North America.

00:34:18.520 --> 00:34:21.340
The revival brought about new religious theories

00:34:21.340 --> 00:34:25.270
and dogma as concepts such as the nature of salvation

00:34:25.270 --> 00:34:29.020
and the idea of rebirth were spread by itinerant preachers

00:34:29.020 --> 00:34:31.480
who traveled the countryside giving sermons

00:34:31.480 --> 00:34:33.490
and lectures as they saw fit.

00:34:33.490 --> 00:34:36.220
These preachers were tremendous orators

00:34:36.220 --> 00:34:39.370
and captured captive audiences wherever they went.

00:34:39.370 --> 00:34:41.620
George Whitfield, a major player

00:34:41.620 --> 00:34:43.420
in this evangelical movement,

00:34:43.420 --> 00:34:46.900
traveled across the colonies and preached in major cities

00:34:46.900 --> 00:34:49.990
and small towns, wherever he could gather a crowd.

00:34:49.990 --> 00:34:51.760
And gather them he did.

00:34:51.760 --> 00:34:56.140
In October, 1740, while preaching in Boston, Massachusetts,

00:34:56.140 --> 00:34:58.030
Whitfield allegedly drew a crowd

00:34:58.030 --> 00:35:02.260
of more than 30,000 people from around New England.

00:35:02.260 --> 00:35:03.820
To put that in perspective,

00:35:03.820 --> 00:35:06.040
Boston was the highest populated city

00:35:06.040 --> 00:35:09.310
in Colonial North America in 1740,

00:35:09.310 --> 00:35:12.970
coming in at roughly 17,000 people living in

00:35:12.970 --> 00:35:14.470
and around the city.

00:35:14.470 --> 00:35:17.830
Nearly double the city's population was present

00:35:17.830 --> 00:35:19.780
to hear Whitfield speak.

00:35:19.780 --> 00:35:21.670
The movement revived the religious spirit

00:35:21.670 --> 00:35:22.960
of Christian peoples

00:35:22.960 --> 00:35:25.330
and reaffirmed their faith through periods

00:35:25.330 --> 00:35:28.540
of intense conflict and uncertain survival.

00:35:28.540 --> 00:35:31.090
While the revival did not change governments

00:35:31.090 --> 00:35:32.680
or raise great armies

00:35:32.680 --> 00:35:35.860
as religious revivals had done in the past in Europe,

00:35:35.860 --> 00:35:37.990
the Great Awakening was formative

00:35:37.990 --> 00:35:41.410
for many individuals in colonial North America,

00:35:41.410 --> 00:35:44.470
many of whom would go on to be the founding fathers

00:35:44.470 --> 00:35:46.992
and mothers of the nation.

00:35:46.992 --> 00:35:50.260
(uplifting music)

00:35:50.260 --> 00:35:53.080
The 1763 Treaty of Paris

00:35:53.080 --> 00:35:56.410
saw enormous territorial gains for Great Britain.

00:35:56.410 --> 00:36:00.040
Vast swaths of formerly French-occupied land

00:36:00.040 --> 00:36:03.370
were now British colonies, including Canada,

00:36:03.370 --> 00:36:06.820
all of the Louisiana Territory east of the Mississippi,

00:36:06.820 --> 00:36:09.010
and many Caribbean islands.

00:36:09.010 --> 00:36:12.490
The British colonists in North America were ecstatic

00:36:12.490 --> 00:36:14.770
as the land of the West would soon be open

00:36:14.770 --> 00:36:16.810
for settlement and development.

00:36:16.810 --> 00:36:20.140
The land, however, was already occupied,

00:36:20.140 --> 00:36:23.650
namely by the many Iroquois and other Native tribes

00:36:23.650 --> 00:36:26.770
who had fought alongside the British during the war.

00:36:26.770 --> 00:36:28.390
To avoid any incidents,

00:36:28.390 --> 00:36:33.190
King George III issued the Royal Proclamation of 1763,

00:36:33.190 --> 00:36:35.290
which forbade any settlement west

00:36:35.290 --> 00:36:38.380
of a line drawn along the Appalachian Mountains,

00:36:38.380 --> 00:36:40.660
known as the Proclamation Line.

00:36:40.660 --> 00:36:43.870
Effectively, the British had created an Indian reserve

00:36:43.870 --> 00:36:47.740
to the West of the Appalachians and east of the Mississippi.

00:36:47.740 --> 00:36:50.680
This did not sit well with American colonists

00:36:50.680 --> 00:36:52.300
who felt that they had fought the French

00:36:52.300 --> 00:36:55.420
and Indian War to gain access to this land.

00:36:55.420 --> 00:36:57.820
Naturally, many ignored the proclamation

00:36:57.820 --> 00:37:01.180
and settled West, increasing tension between themselves

00:37:01.180 --> 00:37:03.460
and the Natives, much to the dismay

00:37:03.460 --> 00:37:05.620
of British colonial authorities.

00:37:05.620 --> 00:37:07.720
Relations between the British government

00:37:07.720 --> 00:37:10.840
and the American colonists became increasingly strained

00:37:10.840 --> 00:37:12.760
through the 1760s.

00:37:12.760 --> 00:37:15.220
As Great Britain attempted to regain control

00:37:15.220 --> 00:37:16.270
of their economy,

00:37:16.270 --> 00:37:19.900
the Seven Years' War had grown from a territorial dispute

00:37:19.900 --> 00:37:22.660
into a full-fledged global conflict

00:37:22.660 --> 00:37:24.310
with a cost to go with it.

00:37:24.310 --> 00:37:25.750
To pay off the war debt,

00:37:25.750 --> 00:37:28.420
the British Parliament levied a series of acts

00:37:28.420 --> 00:37:30.310
and taxes against the colonies

00:37:30.310 --> 00:37:33.760
in order to try and regain their lost financial footing.

00:37:33.760 --> 00:37:37.060
The colonists, who viewed themselves as loyal subjects

00:37:37.060 --> 00:37:40.660
to the British crown, became increasingly agitated.

00:37:40.660 --> 00:37:43.750
It was not that the taxes were exorbitantly high.

00:37:43.750 --> 00:37:45.790
In fact, they were quite low,

00:37:45.790 --> 00:37:47.440
and often the measures taken

00:37:47.440 --> 00:37:50.200
by the British Government were taken to lower the cost

00:37:50.200 --> 00:37:51.430
of British goods

00:37:51.430 --> 00:37:54.460
and raise the costs of those being sold by their French

00:37:54.460 --> 00:37:55.990
or Dutch competitors.

00:37:55.990 --> 00:37:59.830
For the colonists, the heart of the issue was not the cost,

00:37:59.830 --> 00:38:03.130
but rather the lack of consultation before levying

00:38:03.130 --> 00:38:04.810
the acts and taxes.

00:38:04.810 --> 00:38:06.280
As British subjects,

00:38:06.280 --> 00:38:08.590
the colonists believed they had all of the rights

00:38:08.590 --> 00:38:11.050
and liberties of any British citizen,

00:38:11.050 --> 00:38:13.600
which included representation.

00:38:13.600 --> 00:38:15.130
The British Government argued

00:38:15.130 --> 00:38:18.160
that the colonists were represented virtually

00:38:18.160 --> 00:38:21.700
and that the Parliament acted in their best interests.

00:38:21.700 --> 00:38:25.900
Many Americans did not agree and resentment began to grow.

00:38:25.900 --> 00:38:30.700
The rallying cry became, no taxation without representation,

00:38:30.700 --> 00:38:34.750
as more and more colonists began to view King George III

00:38:34.750 --> 00:38:37.240
as a tyrant and the British Parliament

00:38:37.240 --> 00:38:39.160
as an aggressor toward them.

00:38:39.160 --> 00:38:41.920
Great Britain had always regulated the economies

00:38:41.920 --> 00:38:43.720
of its respective colonies

00:38:43.720 --> 00:38:46.240
through acts and laws passed by parliament.

00:38:46.240 --> 00:38:47.560
Through the last century,

00:38:47.560 --> 00:38:50.020
these laws had only been loosely enforced

00:38:50.020 --> 00:38:51.400
as the economic gains

00:38:51.400 --> 00:38:54.580
of the American colonies also benefit Great Britain.

00:38:54.580 --> 00:38:57.580
As the 1760s began, however,

00:38:57.580 --> 00:38:59.440
Britain needed to regain control

00:38:59.440 --> 00:39:01.270
of the financial situation,

00:39:01.270 --> 00:39:03.727
sparking animosity from the colonists

00:39:03.727 --> 00:39:07.570
who had long appreciated their free economic relationship

00:39:07.570 --> 00:39:10.630
and raising questions on the constitutional rights

00:39:10.630 --> 00:39:12.520
of the American colonists.

00:39:12.520 --> 00:39:16.960
In 1764, the Sugar Act was imposed to regulate the amount

00:39:16.960 --> 00:39:18.490
of French and Dutch sugar

00:39:18.490 --> 00:39:21.460
and molasses being imported to the colonies

00:39:21.460 --> 00:39:24.100
in favor of sugar and molasses being sold

00:39:24.100 --> 00:39:26.320
by the British East India Company.

00:39:26.320 --> 00:39:27.610
While it lowered the cost

00:39:27.610 --> 00:39:29.830
of sugar from the East India Company,

00:39:29.830 --> 00:39:32.260
colonists saw the act as a violation

00:39:32.260 --> 00:39:35.020
of their rights to trade and conduct business.

00:39:35.020 --> 00:39:37.120
Colonists protested the Sugar Act

00:39:37.120 --> 00:39:40.570
by boycotting British goods affected by the act.

00:39:40.570 --> 00:39:43.600
While this form of protest was not widely successful

00:39:43.600 --> 00:39:47.140
from an economic standpoint- the East India Company had one

00:39:47.140 --> 00:39:50.080
of its best years in 1774-

00:39:50.080 --> 00:39:53.080
the protest was noted by British Parliament

00:39:53.080 --> 00:39:56.020
and many Whigs within the British government warned

00:39:56.020 --> 00:39:58.240
that relations could worsen if some sort

00:39:58.240 --> 00:40:00.310
of agreement could not be met.

00:40:00.310 --> 00:40:03.430
The following year in 1765,

00:40:03.430 --> 00:40:05.800
the Parliament passed the Stamp Act.

00:40:05.800 --> 00:40:07.090
It was the first act

00:40:07.090 --> 00:40:10.720
of Parliament ever directed specifically at the colonies,

00:40:10.720 --> 00:40:13.000
as opposed to across the empire.

00:40:13.000 --> 00:40:16.090
The Stamp Act would require any form of official paper

00:40:16.090 --> 00:40:17.980
to need an official stamp.

00:40:17.980 --> 00:40:20.650
The act affected newspapers, almanacs,

00:40:20.650 --> 00:40:25.240
and official documents such as licenses, deeds, and wills.

00:40:25.240 --> 00:40:27.880
It even meant that playing cards required

00:40:27.880 --> 00:40:29.380
the official stamp.

00:40:29.380 --> 00:40:32.110
Such a direct tax had never been levied

00:40:32.110 --> 00:40:35.020
against the colonists, and many saw it as an attack

00:40:35.020 --> 00:40:36.700
by the Parliament in response

00:40:36.700 --> 00:40:38.680
to the boycotts the year before.

00:40:38.680 --> 00:40:40.420
Secret organizations known

00:40:40.420 --> 00:40:42.970
as the Sons of Liberty began to appear

00:40:42.970 --> 00:40:44.260
throughout the colonies

00:40:44.260 --> 00:40:47.860
and threatened violence on anyone who sold the stamps.

00:40:47.860 --> 00:40:51.430
Indeed, violence began to break out across the region

00:40:51.430 --> 00:40:54.430
as the Sons of Liberty targeted British officials

00:40:54.430 --> 00:40:55.690
who enforced the act.

00:40:55.690 --> 00:40:58.450
In one such case, the home of Lieutenant Governor

00:40:58.450 --> 00:41:00.820
of the province of Massachusetts Bay

00:41:00.820 --> 00:41:04.480
and Chief Justice Thomas Hutchinson was ransacked

00:41:04.480 --> 00:41:08.080
by an angry mob led by the Sons of Liberty.

00:41:08.080 --> 00:41:10.990
While Hutchinson and his family escaped the violence,

00:41:10.990 --> 00:41:12.790
their home was destroyed.

00:41:12.790 --> 00:41:15.940
Some colonists, however, did not act out in violence

00:41:15.940 --> 00:41:19.480
but relied instead on a united political action.

00:41:19.480 --> 00:41:21.550
Nine colonies sent representatives

00:41:21.550 --> 00:41:24.490
to the Stamp Act Congress in New York City

00:41:24.490 --> 00:41:27.160
and compiled a declaration of rights

00:41:27.160 --> 00:41:29.590
and grievances for the British Parliament.

00:41:29.590 --> 00:41:31.990
The declaration stated the position of many

00:41:31.990 --> 00:41:33.670
of the American colonists,

00:41:33.670 --> 00:41:37.270
stating that the British taxes levied without representation

00:41:37.270 --> 00:41:40.750
violated their rights as not only British subjects,

00:41:40.750 --> 00:41:41.920
but as men.

00:41:41.920 --> 00:41:46.000
Again, the Americans engaged in protest by boycott.

00:41:46.000 --> 00:41:48.460
This time with significant results.

00:41:48.460 --> 00:41:49.870
The income from imports

00:41:49.870 --> 00:41:54.730
to the American colonies fell from 2,250,000 pounds

00:41:54.730 --> 00:41:58.463
in 1764 to 1,944,000 in 1765.

00:42:01.870 --> 00:42:05.470
In England, American Statesman Benjamin Franklin argued

00:42:05.470 --> 00:42:07.990
the case of the American colonies to parliament

00:42:07.990 --> 00:42:11.260
and warned that continued abuse of the colonists could

00:42:11.260 --> 00:42:13.660
and would result in rebellion.

00:42:13.660 --> 00:42:15.370
Fortunately for the colonies,

00:42:15.370 --> 00:42:17.980
the Parliament experienced a shift in government,

00:42:17.980 --> 00:42:20.650
which had sympathy for Whig politics,

00:42:20.650 --> 00:42:23.980
which resulted in the repeal of the Stamp Act.

00:42:23.980 --> 00:42:28.270
The Parliament passed the Declaratory Act in 1766,

00:42:28.270 --> 00:42:30.040
reversing the Stamp Act,

00:42:30.040 --> 00:42:32.950
but at the same time, insisting that the Parliament,

00:42:32.950 --> 00:42:36.760
as a legislative body, had the right in power to make laws

00:42:36.760 --> 00:42:40.420
for the colonies in all cases whatsoever.

00:42:40.420 --> 00:42:43.750
Both sides viewed the result as a political victory,

00:42:43.750 --> 00:42:45.910
believing that their interpretation of the rights

00:42:45.910 --> 00:42:48.880
of the colonists had been heard and secured.

00:42:48.880 --> 00:42:51.310
The Parliament believed it had exerted its will

00:42:51.310 --> 00:42:54.190
as the governing body of the colonies and once

00:42:54.190 --> 00:42:56.080
and for all had established their right

00:42:56.080 --> 00:42:57.520
to levy laws on them,

00:42:57.520 --> 00:43:00.220
and the Americans believed that the British Parliament

00:43:00.220 --> 00:43:03.040
would not ever directly tax them again

00:43:03.040 --> 00:43:05.800
without some form of representation.

00:43:05.800 --> 00:43:07.840
A door had been left open

00:43:07.840 --> 00:43:10.480
and if the British Government was not careful,

00:43:10.480 --> 00:43:12.610
it might be able to close again.

00:43:12.610 --> 00:43:17.110
In 1767, things were still not going well economically

00:43:17.110 --> 00:43:18.130
for the British.

00:43:18.130 --> 00:43:19.450
The Rockingham Government,

00:43:19.450 --> 00:43:21.490
which had helped repeal the Stamp Act,

00:43:21.490 --> 00:43:24.340
was suffering at the hands of their Tory opponents,

00:43:24.340 --> 00:43:26.020
who criticized them harshly

00:43:26.020 --> 00:43:27.490
and felt that they had been played

00:43:27.490 --> 00:43:29.350
by the American colonists.

00:43:29.350 --> 00:43:32.140
Charles Townsend, who served as the chancellor

00:43:32.140 --> 00:43:34.000
of the Exchequer to the ministry

00:43:34.000 --> 00:43:35.650
of William Pitt the Elder,

00:43:35.650 --> 00:43:38.380
found himself in control of the administration

00:43:38.380 --> 00:43:42.070
when Pitt suddenly passed away in 1766.

00:43:42.070 --> 00:43:44.500
Townsend himself died a year later,

00:43:44.500 --> 00:43:47.920
but before he did, urged by the financial crisis

00:43:47.920 --> 00:43:51.160
and the insistence of the Tory factions within Parliament,

00:43:51.160 --> 00:43:52.300
passed a series

00:43:52.300 --> 00:43:55.930
of five acts which would collectively bear his name,

00:43:55.930 --> 00:43:57.730
The Townsend Acts.

00:43:57.730 --> 00:44:00.220
The first act known as the Revenue Act

00:44:00.220 --> 00:44:04.660
imposed direct taxation on lead, glass, paper, paint,

00:44:04.660 --> 00:44:06.700
and, notably, tea.

00:44:06.700 --> 00:44:09.280
The second created a new customs board

00:44:09.280 --> 00:44:11.860
for the North American colonies in Boston

00:44:11.860 --> 00:44:15.280
and allowed customs officials unprecedented control

00:44:15.280 --> 00:44:18.940
over vessels coming in and out of colonial ports.

00:44:18.940 --> 00:44:21.700
The third suspended the New York Assembly

00:44:21.700 --> 00:44:24.190
from conducting business until it had complied

00:44:24.190 --> 00:44:26.920
with the requirements of the Quartering Act passed

00:44:26.920 --> 00:44:30.070
in 1765 alongside the Stamp Act.

00:44:30.070 --> 00:44:32.800
The fourth act, known as the Indemnity Act,

00:44:32.800 --> 00:44:35.320
colloquially known as the Tea Act,

00:44:35.320 --> 00:44:38.080
lowered the commercial duties on tea imported

00:44:38.080 --> 00:44:39.940
by the East India Company,

00:44:39.940 --> 00:44:41.770
hoping to combat the smuggling

00:44:41.770 --> 00:44:44.920
of Dutch East India tea into English ports.

00:44:44.920 --> 00:44:47.830
The final act, known as the Colonial Trade Act,

00:44:47.830 --> 00:44:51.190
passed after Townsend's death in 1767,

00:44:51.190 --> 00:44:53.350
also aimed to target smuggling,

00:44:53.350 --> 00:44:55.780
and granted admiralty courts jurisdiction

00:44:55.780 --> 00:44:58.900
over all matters concerning customs violations,

00:44:58.900 --> 00:45:02.170
taking away the authority of local colonial courts.

00:45:02.170 --> 00:45:04.960
Before his death, Townsend feared that it would provoke

00:45:04.960 --> 00:45:08.170
a rebellious response from the American colonists.

00:45:08.170 --> 00:45:11.050
Townsend could not have been more correct.

00:45:11.050 --> 00:45:14.740
A flurry of activity gripped the American colonies.

00:45:14.740 --> 00:45:17.920
Pamphlets and letters flew from the pens of lawyers

00:45:17.920 --> 00:45:21.040
and farmers alike, as they published their grievances

00:45:21.040 --> 00:45:24.250
in papers and broadsides across the colonies.

00:45:24.250 --> 00:45:27.700
Committees of correspondence were formed and shared ideas

00:45:27.700 --> 00:45:28.930
and debated the political

00:45:28.930 --> 00:45:31.870
and economic situation in the colonies.

00:45:31.870 --> 00:45:34.990
Once again, the Sons of Liberty were active,

00:45:34.990 --> 00:45:38.800
implementing the boycott of British goods and inciting riots

00:45:38.800 --> 00:45:40.540
where the opportunity was ripe.

00:45:40.540 --> 00:45:44.170
Particularly in Boston, unrest began to foment

00:45:44.170 --> 00:45:45.003
in such a way

00:45:45.003 --> 00:45:48.370
that the customs officials were obliged to leave town.

00:45:48.370 --> 00:45:51.670
This prompted British authorities to send for British troops

00:45:51.670 --> 00:45:54.610
to occupy Boston to quell the mob.

00:45:54.610 --> 00:45:56.650
On March 5th, 1770,

00:45:56.650 --> 00:45:58.690
the consequences became quite clear

00:45:58.690 --> 00:46:00.880
when a young British sentry guarding

00:46:00.880 --> 00:46:03.070
the Boston Customs House was set upon

00:46:03.070 --> 00:46:05.410
by an angry mob of colonists.

00:46:05.410 --> 00:46:07.870
Accounts of the event state that the incident began

00:46:07.870 --> 00:46:09.580
as an argument between the private

00:46:09.580 --> 00:46:11.740
and a young wig maker's apprentice,

00:46:11.740 --> 00:46:14.260
who upon insulting the private and his officer

00:46:14.260 --> 00:46:16.150
was warned away from the post.

00:46:16.150 --> 00:46:19.270
Refusing to go and further insulting the officer,

00:46:19.270 --> 00:46:22.060
he was struck in the head by the private's musket.

00:46:22.060 --> 00:46:25.540
A crowd began to gather as the altercation grew louder

00:46:25.540 --> 00:46:28.450
and bells rang out indicating a fire,

00:46:28.450 --> 00:46:31.780
drawing yet more Bostonians toward the lone sentry.

00:46:31.780 --> 00:46:33.820
The sentry sent a runner to get help

00:46:33.820 --> 00:46:35.890
as the crowd became more violent,

00:46:35.890 --> 00:46:38.470
throwing ice and oyster shells at the century

00:46:38.470 --> 00:46:40.780
and calling for him to fire his weapon.

00:46:40.780 --> 00:46:42.220
Captain Thomas Preston

00:46:42.220 --> 00:46:44.560
and a handful of men from the Grenadier Company

00:46:44.560 --> 00:46:47.680
of the 29th Regiment, afoot, arrived at the scene

00:46:47.680 --> 00:46:50.890
and deployed around the sentry with bayonets fixed.

00:46:50.890 --> 00:46:55.000
The crowd, now grown to 300 or 400 by some estimates,

00:46:55.000 --> 00:46:57.250
pressed in around the British troops,

00:46:57.250 --> 00:47:00.310
still throwing objects and shouting for them to fire.

00:47:00.310 --> 00:47:02.620
Preston shouted for the crowd to disperse

00:47:02.620 --> 00:47:05.290
and ordered his men to load their muskets.

00:47:05.290 --> 00:47:07.180
As the crowd pressed in on Preston

00:47:07.180 --> 00:47:11.110
and his men, they shouted, "Fire, damn you, fire."

00:47:11.110 --> 00:47:12.940
A young private was struck in the head

00:47:12.940 --> 00:47:16.540
by a flying object, causing him to drop his musket.

00:47:16.540 --> 00:47:18.460
He bent to retrieve it and stood up

00:47:18.460 --> 00:47:22.270
and unintentionally fired into the crowd without orders.

00:47:22.270 --> 00:47:24.640
In a panic, the rest of the soldiers fired

00:47:24.640 --> 00:47:27.100
into the crowd in a ragged volley.

00:47:27.100 --> 00:47:28.900
As the crowd broke in horror

00:47:28.900 --> 00:47:33.160
and the smoke cleared, it revealed three dead colonists:

00:47:33.160 --> 00:47:35.650
Samuel Gray, James Caldwell,

00:47:35.650 --> 00:47:37.390
and Crispus Attucks,

00:47:37.390 --> 00:47:40.360
a mixed race former slave, Samuel Maverick,

00:47:40.360 --> 00:47:43.930
and Patrick Carr were wounded and would die shortly after.

00:47:43.930 --> 00:47:46.030
Five colonists had been killed in

00:47:46.030 --> 00:47:49.240
what would be known as the Boston Massacre.

00:47:49.240 --> 00:47:51.070
The city was put on high alert

00:47:51.070 --> 00:47:53.800
and British troops mustered in full force,

00:47:53.800 --> 00:47:56.590
preparing to defend against further riots.

00:47:56.590 --> 00:47:59.590
The trial which followed was a media circus

00:47:59.590 --> 00:48:01.780
as the Sons of Liberty latched onto those

00:48:01.780 --> 00:48:04.690
who had died as patriots and martyrs.

00:48:04.690 --> 00:48:07.810
Attorney John Adams defended the British soldiers,

00:48:07.810 --> 00:48:09.850
despite his own personal feelings toward

00:48:09.850 --> 00:48:12.640
the British abuse of the American colonies

00:48:12.640 --> 00:48:15.700
and his relationship to his cousin, Samuel Adams,

00:48:15.700 --> 00:48:18.700
who was one of the founding members of the Sons of Liberty.

00:48:18.700 --> 00:48:21.670
Adams, whose devout loyalty to the law led him to believe

00:48:21.670 --> 00:48:24.550
that all men were entitled to a trial no matter

00:48:24.550 --> 00:48:26.650
who they were or what they had done,

00:48:26.650 --> 00:48:29.890
successfully argued the men were not guilty of murder

00:48:29.890 --> 00:48:32.230
and had six of these soldiers acquitted

00:48:32.230 --> 00:48:35.410
and two others found guilty only of manslaughter.

00:48:35.410 --> 00:48:38.560
Adam's experience in the aftermath of the trial did little

00:48:38.560 --> 00:48:41.620
to move him closer to his cousin's patriot leanings,

00:48:41.620 --> 00:48:44.350
but did affirm his belief in the legitimacy

00:48:44.350 --> 00:48:46.240
of a government of laws.

00:48:46.240 --> 00:48:48.220
Tensions remained high in Boston,

00:48:48.220 --> 00:48:50.890
but gradually began to recede elsewhere.

00:48:50.890 --> 00:48:54.760
In 1773, amidst one of the worst banking crisis

00:48:54.760 --> 00:48:56.500
of the 18th century,

00:48:56.500 --> 00:48:58.870
the British Parliament again made an attempt

00:48:58.870 --> 00:49:02.200
to ensure the survival of the British East India Company

00:49:02.200 --> 00:49:05.530
by undercutting the illegal importation of Dutch tea

00:49:05.530 --> 00:49:07.150
to the American colonies,

00:49:07.150 --> 00:49:09.820
while lowering the cost of EIC Tea

00:49:09.820 --> 00:49:12.070
to the lowest possible amount.

00:49:12.070 --> 00:49:14.977
Known as the Tea Act of 1773,

00:49:14.977 --> 00:49:17.830
the act allowed the EIC to unload its cargo

00:49:17.830 --> 00:49:19.420
in the American colonies

00:49:19.420 --> 00:49:21.760
without paying any duties on it,

00:49:21.760 --> 00:49:25.150
while charging an exorbitant amount on Dutch tea.

00:49:25.150 --> 00:49:27.400
The act prompted the Sons of Liberty

00:49:27.400 --> 00:49:30.580
to organize a raid on three merchant ships docked

00:49:30.580 --> 00:49:34.510
in Boston Harbor, carrying loads of East India Company Tea,

00:49:34.510 --> 00:49:36.460
which had yet to be offloaded.

00:49:36.460 --> 00:49:38.740
Known as the Boston Tea Party,

00:49:38.740 --> 00:49:40.960
the Sons of Liberty boarded the ships

00:49:40.960 --> 00:49:45.580
and dumped 342 crates of tea into the harbor.

00:49:45.580 --> 00:49:47.020
The loss of tea amounted

00:49:47.020 --> 00:49:50.890
to approximately 9,659 pounds

00:49:50.890 --> 00:49:55.890
in 1773, the equivalent of 1.7 million US dollars today.

00:49:56.680 --> 00:49:58.150
Parliament was outraged

00:49:58.150 --> 00:50:00.490
and responded by passing a series of acts known

00:50:00.490 --> 00:50:03.700
as the Intolerable Acts in 1774.

00:50:03.700 --> 00:50:06.550
The first three acts, the Boston Port Act,

00:50:06.550 --> 00:50:08.500
the Massachusetts Government Act,

00:50:08.500 --> 00:50:10.990
and the Administration of Justice Act,

00:50:10.990 --> 00:50:13.390
all targeted Massachusetts alone

00:50:13.390 --> 00:50:15.400
and punished the City of Boston

00:50:15.400 --> 00:50:17.290
and the Massachusetts Bay Colony

00:50:17.290 --> 00:50:19.390
for its role in the Tea Party.

00:50:19.390 --> 00:50:21.820
The Boston Port Act closed the port of Boston

00:50:21.820 --> 00:50:24.670
until the colonists paid for the destroyed tea.

00:50:24.670 --> 00:50:27.100
The act angered citizens in Boston

00:50:27.100 --> 00:50:30.370
who had not even participated in the Tea Party

00:50:30.370 --> 00:50:32.740
and they felt they were being punished unjustly

00:50:32.740 --> 00:50:35.740
without being able to testify in their own defense.

00:50:35.740 --> 00:50:37.480
The Massachusetts Government Act

00:50:37.480 --> 00:50:39.460
revoked Massachusetts Charter

00:50:39.460 --> 00:50:42.520
and brought the colony under direct British control.

00:50:42.520 --> 00:50:43.990
Town meetings were limited

00:50:43.990 --> 00:50:45.670
and all appointments had to be appointed

00:50:45.670 --> 00:50:47.260
by the Royal governor.

00:50:47.260 --> 00:50:50.500
The Administration of Justice Act allowed the Royal governor

00:50:50.500 --> 00:50:52.990
of Massachusetts to order the trial

00:50:52.990 --> 00:50:55.900
or retrial of any royal official

00:50:55.900 --> 00:50:59.200
to take place in Great Britain if the accused could not get

00:50:59.200 --> 00:51:01.570
a fair trial in Massachusetts.

00:51:01.570 --> 00:51:04.300
The final act, which affected all of the colonies,

00:51:04.300 --> 00:51:07.420
was the Quartering Act of 1774,

00:51:07.420 --> 00:51:09.910
which allowed royal governors to house soldiers

00:51:09.910 --> 00:51:11.620
and buildings if suitable quarters

00:51:11.620 --> 00:51:13.990
were not provided by the colonies.

00:51:13.990 --> 00:51:17.710
These acts were the last straw for many colonists.

00:51:17.710 --> 00:51:21.130
The perceived violation of what they viewed as their natural

00:51:21.130 --> 00:51:24.490
and constitutional rights as British subjects threatened

00:51:24.490 --> 00:51:27.160
to turn resentment of their British mother country

00:51:27.160 --> 00:51:30.550
to hatred and send the colonists into rebellion.

00:51:30.550 --> 00:51:33.670
Parliament hoped that the intolerable acts would isolate

00:51:33.670 --> 00:51:34.960
the problem which seemed to be

00:51:34.960 --> 00:51:37.360
the strongest in Massachusetts.

00:51:37.360 --> 00:51:40.000
Meanwhile, the colonists began taking steps

00:51:40.000 --> 00:51:42.940
beyond simple committees of correspondence.

00:51:42.940 --> 00:51:45.730
The formation of the first Continental Congress

00:51:45.730 --> 00:51:50.620
in the fall of 1774 worked to redress the intolerable acts

00:51:50.620 --> 00:51:53.170
and petitioned the British Government for a repeal,

00:51:53.170 --> 00:51:56.830
as they had in 1765 with the Stamp Act.

00:51:56.830 --> 00:52:00.460
The petition to the king never received a formal reply.

00:52:00.460 --> 00:52:02.650
With no reply from the British Government.

00:52:02.650 --> 00:52:06.700
In May, 1775, the colonies convened again.

00:52:06.700 --> 00:52:09.490
The Second Continental Congress found itself

00:52:09.490 --> 00:52:11.470
again attempting to organize

00:52:11.470 --> 00:52:13.870
a general boycott of British goods

00:52:13.870 --> 00:52:15.190
and achieve some kind

00:52:15.190 --> 00:52:17.290
of formal response from the Parliament

00:52:17.290 --> 00:52:20.230
when the tension which had gripped the American colonies

00:52:20.230 --> 00:52:23.710
since the end of the French and Indian War finally reached

00:52:23.710 --> 00:52:27.430
a breaking point in a small village outside of Boston

00:52:27.430 --> 00:52:31.873
on a mild mid-April morning in 1775.

00:52:32.726 --> 00:52:36.580
(suspenseful music)

00:52:36.580 --> 00:52:39.910
On the evening of April 18th, 1775,

00:52:39.910 --> 00:52:42.670
with tensions running high between the people of Boston

00:52:42.670 --> 00:52:44.680
and the British troops garrisoned

00:52:44.680 --> 00:52:47.890
in and around the city, the Sons of Liberty discovered

00:52:47.890 --> 00:52:51.430
that General Thomas Gage planned to march British troops

00:52:51.430 --> 00:52:52.900
to a cache of weapons

00:52:52.900 --> 00:52:57.160
and powder hidden in Concord, just a few miles from Boston,

00:52:57.160 --> 00:52:59.050
and destroy the supply.

00:52:59.050 --> 00:53:02.200
Patriots Paul Revere and William Dawes rode

00:53:02.200 --> 00:53:03.790
through the Boston countryside

00:53:03.790 --> 00:53:07.840
and warned the population that the regulars are turning out,

00:53:07.840 --> 00:53:10.420
or as it's more popularly remembered,

00:53:10.420 --> 00:53:11.920
the British are coming.

00:53:11.920 --> 00:53:14.710
Colonial militia men rose from their slumber,

00:53:14.710 --> 00:53:16.570
gathered their muskets and rushed

00:53:16.570 --> 00:53:19.870
to stop the British troops from making it to Concord.

00:53:19.870 --> 00:53:22.960
On the morning of April 19th, 1775,

00:53:22.960 --> 00:53:26.770
Massachusetts militia men faced off against British regulars

00:53:26.770 --> 00:53:29.020
on the Lexington Town Green.

00:53:29.020 --> 00:53:30.760
When ordered to lay down their arms

00:53:30.760 --> 00:53:32.110
and return to their homes,

00:53:32.110 --> 00:53:34.660
the militia refused and stood their ground.

00:53:34.660 --> 00:53:37.510
Captain John Parker, commanding the group of 70

00:53:37.510 --> 00:53:40.540
or so Massachusetts militia ordered them not

00:53:40.540 --> 00:53:43.330
to fire unless fired upon first.

00:53:43.330 --> 00:53:46.660
British officers ordered their men to level their muskets,

00:53:46.660 --> 00:53:48.820
but cautioned them not to fire.

00:53:48.820 --> 00:53:51.400
Suddenly, a shot rang out.

00:53:51.400 --> 00:53:54.040
No one knows where the shot came from.

00:53:54.040 --> 00:53:55.720
Neither side laid claim,

00:53:55.720 --> 00:53:57.220
both blaming the other.

00:53:57.220 --> 00:54:01.180
With this moment, known as the shot heard around the world,

00:54:01.180 --> 00:54:04.300
the resentment and anger boiled over at last

00:54:04.300 --> 00:54:06.280
and the war began.

00:54:06.280 --> 00:54:08.440
When the American Revolution began,

00:54:08.440 --> 00:54:10.600
it did not start as a revolution.

00:54:10.600 --> 00:54:14.320
While certainly the ideas it generated were revolutionary,

00:54:14.320 --> 00:54:17.230
the actions of the first Continental Congress were those

00:54:17.230 --> 00:54:19.720
of a legislative body hoping to attain

00:54:19.720 --> 00:54:22.840
a form of reconciliation with the mother country.

00:54:22.840 --> 00:54:25.120
Better characterized as a rebellion,

00:54:25.120 --> 00:54:28.300
the earliest stages of the war were fought by the colonists

00:54:28.300 --> 00:54:31.660
to reclaim what they saw as their natural-born rights

00:54:31.660 --> 00:54:34.420
as British subjects and citizens.

00:54:34.420 --> 00:54:35.530
On the home front,

00:54:35.530 --> 00:54:37.990
early victories for the militias kept the spark

00:54:37.990 --> 00:54:39.250
of rebellion lit.

00:54:39.250 --> 00:54:40.900
However, it was not long

00:54:40.900 --> 00:54:42.910
before the British put a concerted effort

00:54:42.910 --> 00:54:44.980
into putting down the uprising.

00:54:44.980 --> 00:54:48.520
At the Battle of Bunker Hill in June, 1775,

00:54:48.520 --> 00:54:50.830
British troops stormed earthworks held

00:54:50.830 --> 00:54:55.030
by the colonial militia near Boston in a costly victory.

00:54:55.030 --> 00:54:56.710
It was becoming clear to many

00:54:56.710 --> 00:54:59.230
that if the colonies did not unify,

00:54:59.230 --> 00:55:01.960
they would be crushed one by one.

00:55:01.960 --> 00:55:05.050
While some representatives in the Continental Congress,

00:55:05.050 --> 00:55:06.580
now in its second session,

00:55:06.580 --> 00:55:08.800
still erred on the side of caution,

00:55:08.800 --> 00:55:11.830
believing that a reconciliation could still be made,

00:55:11.830 --> 00:55:15.880
the Congress made the decision to form a single unified army

00:55:15.880 --> 00:55:19.030
to prevent their forces from being wiped out piecemeal.

00:55:19.030 --> 00:55:21.850
At the head of this new Continental Army would be

00:55:21.850 --> 00:55:23.320
a colonel from the colony

00:55:23.320 --> 00:55:26.500
of Virginia named George Washington.

00:55:26.500 --> 00:55:29.680
Washington, born from one of the most prominent families

00:55:29.680 --> 00:55:31.240
in colonial Virginia,

00:55:31.240 --> 00:55:34.060
had had aspirations to be a naval officer

00:55:34.060 --> 00:55:36.520
in the English Navy when he was a young man.

00:55:36.520 --> 00:55:39.820
His mother, Mary Ball Washington, was wary.

00:55:39.820 --> 00:55:42.550
She knew that a life at sea was a difficult one

00:55:42.550 --> 00:55:45.220
and could lead to an early death or maiming.

00:55:45.220 --> 00:55:48.340
She implored her son not to enlist in the Navy

00:55:48.340 --> 00:55:51.100
and to pursue a career in the Army instead.

00:55:51.100 --> 00:55:53.440
Washington obeyed and would spend much

00:55:53.440 --> 00:55:54.970
of his young adult life attempting

00:55:54.970 --> 00:55:57.220
to gain a commission in the British Army.

00:55:57.220 --> 00:55:58.630
He worked as a surveyor

00:55:58.630 --> 00:56:01.870
and endeared himself to the royal governor of Virginia,

00:56:01.870 --> 00:56:03.940
hoping to obtain that commission.

00:56:03.940 --> 00:56:05.260
It never came.

00:56:05.260 --> 00:56:07.060
Instead, Washington served

00:56:07.060 --> 00:56:09.340
as a colonel in the Virginia Militia

00:56:09.340 --> 00:56:12.640
and implemented his own particular style of leadership,

00:56:12.640 --> 00:56:14.290
modeled after the British.

00:56:14.290 --> 00:56:15.910
Serving in this capacity,

00:56:15.910 --> 00:56:18.370
a young George Washington found himself

00:56:18.370 --> 00:56:21.520
at the center of some of the most important moments

00:56:21.520 --> 00:56:23.680
of the French and Indian War.

00:56:23.680 --> 00:56:24.910
At Fort Necessity

00:56:24.910 --> 00:56:26.800
and the Battle of Monongahela,

00:56:26.800 --> 00:56:29.380
Washington served alongside British soldiers

00:56:29.380 --> 00:56:31.270
as a colonial officer.

00:56:31.270 --> 00:56:34.450
And despite surviving numerous close calls with death

00:56:34.450 --> 00:56:36.640
and leading his troops valiantly,

00:56:36.640 --> 00:56:38.800
he was never made an official offer

00:56:38.800 --> 00:56:41.140
for a commission in the British Army.

00:56:41.140 --> 00:56:42.760
More than a decade after the end

00:56:42.760 --> 00:56:44.530
of the French and Indian War,

00:56:44.530 --> 00:56:46.720
Washington was serving as a representative

00:56:46.720 --> 00:56:49.870
of Virginia at the Second Continental Congress.

00:56:49.870 --> 00:56:52.150
When it came time for the Congress to decide

00:56:52.150 --> 00:56:54.520
who would lead this new United Army,

00:56:54.520 --> 00:56:56.710
Washington was a natural choice.

00:56:56.710 --> 00:56:58.720
While his track record on the battlefield

00:56:58.720 --> 00:57:02.620
was less than stellar, his experience was unquestioned,

00:57:02.620 --> 00:57:05.110
and the fact that he was a Virginian pleased many

00:57:05.110 --> 00:57:07.270
of the Southern delegates of the Congress,

00:57:07.270 --> 00:57:09.730
as the war thus far had been fought by,

00:57:09.730 --> 00:57:14.020
and almost entirely took place in the Northern colonies.

00:57:14.020 --> 00:57:18.160
In June, 1775, after receiving a unanimous vote

00:57:18.160 --> 00:57:19.930
of approval from the Congress,

00:57:19.930 --> 00:57:22.300
Washington rode north for Boston,

00:57:22.300 --> 00:57:25.660
and began to construct the necessary administration

00:57:25.660 --> 00:57:27.820
for the new Continental Army.

00:57:27.820 --> 00:57:30.940
The Continental Army struggled with many issues.

00:57:30.940 --> 00:57:33.850
Supply was always a chief concern.

00:57:33.850 --> 00:57:36.730
Lack of food and a reliable supply chain meant

00:57:36.730 --> 00:57:40.150
that the army needed to constantly forage for sustenance.

00:57:40.150 --> 00:57:43.690
This meant a tense and sometimes violent relationship

00:57:43.690 --> 00:57:45.880
with the civilian populations near

00:57:45.880 --> 00:57:47.560
where the armies had camped.

00:57:47.560 --> 00:57:50.170
Command differences plagued the army as well.

00:57:50.170 --> 00:57:52.750
Beyond disgruntled and entitled officers,

00:57:52.750 --> 00:57:54.160
this army consisted

00:57:54.160 --> 00:57:58.300
of troops from nearly every once colony on the East Coast.

00:57:58.300 --> 00:58:00.820
These soldiers were as different from each other

00:58:00.820 --> 00:58:03.340
as if they had come from another country.

00:58:03.340 --> 00:58:06.940
In one early instance, General Washington literally had

00:58:06.940 --> 00:58:09.490
to pull soldiers off of each other during

00:58:09.490 --> 00:58:11.980
a snowball fight outside of Boston,

00:58:11.980 --> 00:58:14.320
which had turned into an outright brawl

00:58:14.320 --> 00:58:17.680
between soldiers from Massachusetts and Virginia.

00:58:17.680 --> 00:58:20.320
Uniting these men into a fighting force

00:58:20.320 --> 00:58:22.758
was a war unto itself.

00:58:22.758 --> 00:58:24.340
(uplifting music)

00:58:24.340 --> 00:58:27.700
Through the winter of 1775 to '76,

00:58:27.700 --> 00:58:31.750
the Continental Army diverted its efforts in two directions.

00:58:31.750 --> 00:58:34.120
To the North, the Congress ordered an invasion

00:58:34.120 --> 00:58:37.570
of Quebec under the command of Generals Benedict Arnold

00:58:37.570 --> 00:58:40.990
and Richard Montgomery, hoping to rally the Canadians

00:58:40.990 --> 00:58:45.280
to form a 14th colony, and rise against the British as well.

00:58:45.280 --> 00:58:47.260
It did not go as planned.

00:58:47.260 --> 00:58:50.470
And while successes were made in Upstate New York,

00:58:50.470 --> 00:58:54.430
the invasion ultimately ended in a dismal failure.

00:58:54.430 --> 00:58:55.930
Montgomery was killed

00:58:55.930 --> 00:58:59.170
and the majority of continental force was either captured

00:58:59.170 --> 00:59:01.090
or succumbed to smallpox.

00:59:01.090 --> 00:59:04.420
Meanwhile, Washington stayed with the army around Boston

00:59:04.420 --> 00:59:06.010
and managed the siege.

00:59:06.010 --> 00:59:09.430
With 11,000 British troops trapped in the city,

00:59:09.430 --> 00:59:12.490
Washington hoped the winter would force them to surrender,

00:59:12.490 --> 00:59:16.360
but he lacked the artillery to mount a full-scale siege.

00:59:16.360 --> 00:59:19.900
He sent the young Colonel Henry Knox to acquire artillery

00:59:19.900 --> 00:59:22.990
from the recently captured Fort Ticonderoga

00:59:22.990 --> 00:59:25.360
and in March, 1776,

00:59:25.360 --> 00:59:28.870
Knox returned to Boston having successfully gotten the guns

00:59:28.870 --> 00:59:31.360
over the Berkshire Mountains through the winter.

00:59:31.360 --> 00:59:34.660
With Knox's guns looking down from Dorchester Heights,

00:59:34.660 --> 00:59:37.240
the British decided to evacuate the city.

00:59:37.240 --> 00:59:39.910
On March 17th, 1776,

00:59:39.910 --> 00:59:42.730
the Continental Army reoccupied Boston,

00:59:42.730 --> 00:59:45.820
much to the joy of the civilian population.

00:59:45.820 --> 00:59:48.340
In the spring of 1776,

00:59:48.340 --> 00:59:49.870
the war was beginning to spread

00:59:49.870 --> 00:59:52.540
to other parts of the 13 colonies.

00:59:52.540 --> 00:59:55.060
Fighting had broken out in the Carolinas

00:59:55.060 --> 00:59:57.610
and a British siege of Charleston was thwarted

00:59:57.610 --> 01:00:00.670
by a daring defense of Sullivan's Island.

01:00:00.670 --> 01:00:01.870
In upstate New York,

01:00:01.870 --> 01:00:04.720
the survivors of the Canada Expedition fought

01:00:04.720 --> 01:00:07.900
to hold onto the gains they had made at Fort Ticonderoga

01:00:07.900 --> 01:00:10.540
and other key locations on Lake Champlain.

01:00:10.540 --> 01:00:13.210
Washington's forces in Boston moved south

01:00:13.210 --> 01:00:14.950
to occupy New York City.

01:00:14.950 --> 01:00:17.140
The Continental Congress ordered Washington

01:00:17.140 --> 01:00:18.850
to defend the island city,

01:00:18.850 --> 01:00:21.460
despite the lack of a meaningful navy.

01:00:21.460 --> 01:00:23.980
Washington was uncertain his army,

01:00:23.980 --> 01:00:27.400
many of whom were untrained and undisciplined militia,

01:00:27.400 --> 01:00:29.500
was going to be capable of standing up

01:00:29.500 --> 01:00:31.870
to a British assault on the city.

01:00:31.870 --> 01:00:34.960
In Philadelphia, now the American capital,

01:00:34.960 --> 01:00:37.420
the Second Continental Congress had shifted from

01:00:37.420 --> 01:00:40.450
a government body imploring the British Government

01:00:40.450 --> 01:00:44.530
for a redress of grievances to a government body responsible

01:00:44.530 --> 01:00:46.630
for the management of a war.

01:00:46.630 --> 01:00:48.670
The Olive Branch Petition sent

01:00:48.670 --> 01:00:52.810
to England in July, 1775 had been the last attempt

01:00:52.810 --> 01:00:55.720
of the Congress to make peace with the mother country.

01:00:55.720 --> 01:00:59.380
It had been met with the naming of the Congress as traitors

01:00:59.380 --> 01:01:01.750
and the revolution as illegal.

01:01:01.750 --> 01:01:05.200
After the action in Boston, it had become clear to a faction

01:01:05.200 --> 01:01:08.830
of the Congress, led by John Adams, Benjamin Franklin,

01:01:08.830 --> 01:01:10.990
Thomas Jefferson, and others,

01:01:10.990 --> 01:01:14.410
that a return to the pre-war status the American colonies

01:01:14.410 --> 01:01:17.890
in Great Britain had shared, was no longer a possibility.

01:01:17.890 --> 01:01:19.660
The necessity for self-rule

01:01:19.660 --> 01:01:23.350
had surpassed any possible reconciliation with England.

01:01:23.350 --> 01:01:25.840
Many of the representatives also realized

01:01:25.840 --> 01:01:29.140
that victory in this conflict could only be achieved

01:01:29.140 --> 01:01:33.640
with the assistance of a foreign power, namely France.

01:01:33.640 --> 01:01:36.100
They knew France would not intervene on behalf

01:01:36.100 --> 01:01:40.450
of rebel colonists, but they might for a sovereign nation.

01:01:40.450 --> 01:01:43.900
Consequently, by early summer 1776,

01:01:43.900 --> 01:01:47.080
the majority of the provincial congresses were prepared

01:01:47.080 --> 01:01:49.360
for a complete separation.

01:01:49.360 --> 01:01:52.000
On June 11th, the Congress formed a committee

01:01:52.000 --> 01:01:54.790
to draft a document stating the justification

01:01:54.790 --> 01:01:56.890
on their separation from Britain.

01:01:56.890 --> 01:02:00.160
The Declaration of Independence was written largely

01:02:00.160 --> 01:02:02.710
by Thomas Jefferson of Virginia.

01:02:02.710 --> 01:02:04.840
It laid out in plain words the reason

01:02:04.840 --> 01:02:07.660
for the former colonies', now state's,

01:02:07.660 --> 01:02:09.610
desire for separation

01:02:09.610 --> 01:02:13.030
and affirm the assertion that they had every right as men

01:02:13.030 --> 01:02:14.890
to make the separation.

01:02:14.890 --> 01:02:16.750
After considerable revisions

01:02:16.750 --> 01:02:18.340
to the original drafts,

01:02:18.340 --> 01:02:20.740
including the removal of a section condemning

01:02:20.740 --> 01:02:22.420
the British slave trade,

01:02:22.420 --> 01:02:26.377
the declaration was adopted by Congress on July 2nd, 1776,

01:02:27.850 --> 01:02:29.140
and its final wording,

01:02:29.140 --> 01:02:33.340
formally ratified on July 4th, 1776.

01:02:33.340 --> 01:02:35.507
Its most prolific line read,

01:02:35.507 --> 01:02:38.380
"We hold these truths to be self-evident,

01:02:38.380 --> 01:02:40.750
that all men are created equal,

01:02:40.750 --> 01:02:41.860
that they are endowed

01:02:41.860 --> 01:02:45.430
by their creator with certain unalienable rights,

01:02:45.430 --> 01:02:47.950
that among these are life, liberty,

01:02:47.950 --> 01:02:50.230
and the pursuit of happiness."

01:02:50.230 --> 01:02:52.180
The Declaration changed the shape

01:02:52.180 --> 01:02:56.500
of the war from a rebellion to a full-fledged revolution.

01:02:56.500 --> 01:02:59.110
The new colonies began operating as separate

01:02:59.110 --> 01:03:01.480
and autonomous states bound loosely

01:03:01.480 --> 01:03:03.400
by their unified Congress.

01:03:03.400 --> 01:03:05.410
Washington had the declaration read

01:03:05.410 --> 01:03:08.830
to his soldiers in New York City, spirit soared.

01:03:08.830 --> 01:03:12.250
At last, the soldiers of the Continental Army felt

01:03:12.250 --> 01:03:16.510
they had something to band together for, independence.

01:03:16.510 --> 01:03:20.050
The British struck back in August, 1776,

01:03:20.050 --> 01:03:22.840
launching a series of devastating attacks in

01:03:22.840 --> 01:03:24.730
and around New York City.

01:03:24.730 --> 01:03:27.790
As Washington had feared, his army was not prepared

01:03:27.790 --> 01:03:31.150
for the professional and well-disciplined British troops,

01:03:31.150 --> 01:03:32.410
and without a navy,

01:03:32.410 --> 01:03:35.290
he had no hope of defending the Island of Manhattan.

01:03:35.290 --> 01:03:37.750
After five consecutive defeats,

01:03:37.750 --> 01:03:40.540
Washington was forced to abandon New York City

01:03:40.540 --> 01:03:41.710
to the British

01:03:41.710 --> 01:03:45.340
and began a prolonged and bloody retreat into New Jersey

01:03:45.340 --> 01:03:48.040
and across the Delaware River into Pennsylvania

01:03:48.040 --> 01:03:50.980
in late November 1776.

01:03:50.980 --> 01:03:52.300
Lord William Howe,

01:03:52.300 --> 01:03:55.060
the commander of the British troops in North America,

01:03:55.060 --> 01:03:57.370
pursued Washington into New Jersey

01:03:57.370 --> 01:03:59.560
and established a series of garrisons,

01:03:59.560 --> 01:04:01.090
which stretched from New York

01:04:01.090 --> 01:04:03.010
as far south as Mount Holly.

01:04:03.010 --> 01:04:05.860
Washington knew that if he did not act quickly,

01:04:05.860 --> 01:04:07.270
the war would be over.

01:04:07.270 --> 01:04:08.290
He devised a plan

01:04:08.290 --> 01:04:12.670
to cross the Delaware on December 25th, 1776,

01:04:12.670 --> 01:04:15.850
and attack an exposed garrison in Trenton, New Jersey,

01:04:15.850 --> 01:04:19.780
occupied by a brigade of German troops hired by the British,

01:04:19.780 --> 01:04:21.550
known as Hessians.

01:04:21.550 --> 01:04:23.200
Washington crossed the Delaware

01:04:23.200 --> 01:04:26.200
on Christmas night through a blinding nor'easter

01:04:26.200 --> 01:04:29.830
and marched his tired and beleaguered army south to Trenton.

01:04:29.830 --> 01:04:31.990
The Hessians were surprised by the arrival

01:04:31.990 --> 01:04:34.120
of the Continental Army as fighting

01:04:34.120 --> 01:04:36.010
and maneuvering troops through the winter

01:04:36.010 --> 01:04:39.190
was generally viewed as difficult and dangerous

01:04:39.190 --> 01:04:41.320
for 18th century armies.

01:04:41.320 --> 01:04:44.020
He achieved a swift victory fighting through the streets

01:04:44.020 --> 01:04:47.470
of Trenton and won his first battle as commander

01:04:47.470 --> 01:04:49.090
of the Continental Army.

01:04:49.090 --> 01:04:50.230
Nine days later,

01:04:50.230 --> 01:04:53.020
after a tactically brilliant running engagement

01:04:53.020 --> 01:04:54.490
on January 2nd,

01:04:54.490 --> 01:04:57.130
the Continental Army again achieved victory

01:04:57.130 --> 01:05:00.790
on the morning of January 3rd in Princeton, New Jersey.

01:05:00.790 --> 01:05:04.090
The three battles fought kept the revolution alive

01:05:04.090 --> 01:05:05.710
in its darkest hour.

01:05:05.710 --> 01:05:09.760
In 1777, the British were desperate to regain control

01:05:09.760 --> 01:05:13.570
of the situation and launched two separate offensives.

01:05:13.570 --> 01:05:15.940
The British, led by Sir William Howe,

01:05:15.940 --> 01:05:18.820
captured the American capital of Philadelphia

01:05:18.820 --> 01:05:21.280
after defeating Washington at Brandywine

01:05:21.280 --> 01:05:24.700
and Germantown in the fall of 1777.

01:05:24.700 --> 01:05:27.550
While the loss of the capital was a blow to the morale

01:05:27.550 --> 01:05:31.300
of the Continental Army, the army had not fallen apart,

01:05:31.300 --> 01:05:33.250
as Howe had expected,

01:05:33.250 --> 01:05:34.930
and Washington took his forces

01:05:34.930 --> 01:05:37.300
to winter at Valley Forge,

01:05:37.300 --> 01:05:39.760
just a few miles west of Philadelphia.

01:05:39.760 --> 01:05:41.050
In upstate New York,

01:05:41.050 --> 01:05:43.900
British General John Burgoyne pushed his army south

01:05:43.900 --> 01:05:46.720
from Canada, capturing Fort Ticonderoga

01:05:46.720 --> 01:05:49.270
and hoping to sever New England from the rest

01:05:49.270 --> 01:05:51.010
of the United States in order

01:05:51.010 --> 01:05:53.140
to bring about a swift end to the war.

01:05:53.140 --> 01:05:55.150
Instead, Burgoyne faced off

01:05:55.150 --> 01:05:58.030
against Continental General's Benedict Arnold

01:05:58.030 --> 01:06:00.880
and Horatio Gates, fighting a series

01:06:00.880 --> 01:06:03.340
of battles near Saratoga, New York.

01:06:03.340 --> 01:06:05.860
Thanks to impressive leadership by Arnold

01:06:05.860 --> 01:06:07.900
and sound strategy by Gates,

01:06:07.900 --> 01:06:09.700
Burgoyne's army was defeated

01:06:09.700 --> 01:06:13.930
and ultimately forced to surrender in October, 1777.

01:06:13.930 --> 01:06:17.290
It was the largest British army to ever surrender

01:06:17.290 --> 01:06:21.970
to an enemy force to date, nearly 7,000 men.

01:06:21.970 --> 01:06:24.280
The British surrender at Saratoga paired

01:06:24.280 --> 01:06:25.390
with the twin victories

01:06:25.390 --> 01:06:28.600
of Trenton in Princeton from the previous winter campaign,

01:06:28.600 --> 01:06:31.120
convinced the French that this new country,

01:06:31.120 --> 01:06:34.420
these United States, did indeed have a chance

01:06:34.420 --> 01:06:35.620
of winning the war.

01:06:35.620 --> 01:06:38.200
Eager to get revenge after a century of losing

01:06:38.200 --> 01:06:39.130
to the British,

01:06:39.130 --> 01:06:41.710
the French declared a formal military alliance

01:06:41.710 --> 01:06:45.190
with the United States, declaring war on Great Britain

01:06:45.190 --> 01:06:48.190
and legitimizing the Declaration of Independence

01:06:48.190 --> 01:06:50.140
in one fell swoop.

01:06:50.140 --> 01:06:52.780
Great Britain was about to become embroiled

01:06:52.780 --> 01:06:55.660
in a global conflict again.

01:06:55.660 --> 01:06:59.292
Meanwhile, Washington spent the winter of 1777

01:06:59.292 --> 01:07:01.690
to '78 training the Continental Army

01:07:01.690 --> 01:07:04.300
to fight the way European armies did.

01:07:04.300 --> 01:07:06.670
He was aided by the help from foreign officers

01:07:06.670 --> 01:07:09.040
like the Marquis de Lafayette of France

01:07:09.040 --> 01:07:11.680
and the Baron von Steuben from Prussia.

01:07:11.680 --> 01:07:14.200
Steuben in particular instilled a sense

01:07:14.200 --> 01:07:17.470
of pride in the soldiers and trained them well.

01:07:17.470 --> 01:07:21.760
In 1778, when word came of the formal alliance with France,

01:07:21.760 --> 01:07:23.950
the British abandoned Philadelphia

01:07:23.950 --> 01:07:25.900
and rushed back toward New York.

01:07:25.900 --> 01:07:28.300
Their new commander, Sir Henry Clinton,

01:07:28.300 --> 01:07:31.150
did not have a high opinion of the Continental Army,

01:07:31.150 --> 01:07:33.940
but did have a healthy respect for the French,

01:07:33.940 --> 01:07:35.920
and feared their presence would trap

01:07:35.920 --> 01:07:37.660
the English in Philadelphia.

01:07:37.660 --> 01:07:40.090
Washington pounced as the British withdrew

01:07:40.090 --> 01:07:41.260
through New Jersey.

01:07:41.260 --> 01:07:44.410
His a newly-trained fighting force struck Clinton

01:07:44.410 --> 01:07:48.970
at Monmouth, New Jersey on June 28th, 1778,

01:07:48.970 --> 01:07:51.190
and fought the British to a standstill.

01:07:51.190 --> 01:07:53.710
While the Battle of Monmouth was a stalemate,

01:07:53.710 --> 01:07:55.840
Washington's forces had fought well

01:07:55.840 --> 01:07:59.470
and withstood the British in an open field engagement.

01:07:59.470 --> 01:08:00.700
The British withdrew back

01:08:00.700 --> 01:08:03.310
to New York and would not venture into New Jersey

01:08:03.310 --> 01:08:05.350
in a meaningful way again.

01:08:05.350 --> 01:08:09.220
In 1779, the British began to feel the pressure

01:08:09.220 --> 01:08:11.110
of a global conflict.

01:08:11.110 --> 01:08:14.200
Realizing that the war could not be won in the North,

01:08:14.200 --> 01:08:16.750
the British turned their attention to the South,

01:08:16.750 --> 01:08:19.300
hoping to find more loyalist support.

01:08:19.300 --> 01:08:21.250
British forces captured Savannah

01:08:21.250 --> 01:08:24.310
and Charleston in the fall of 1779

01:08:24.310 --> 01:08:27.280
and soundly defeated General Horatio Gates

01:08:27.280 --> 01:08:29.770
at the Battle of Camden in South Carolina.

01:08:29.770 --> 01:08:31.840
Gates was removed from command

01:08:31.840 --> 01:08:34.330
and one of Washington's trusted lieutenants,

01:08:34.330 --> 01:08:36.010
General Nathaniel Greene,

01:08:36.010 --> 01:08:38.770
was placed in command of the Southern Department.

01:08:38.770 --> 01:08:42.250
Greene knew that the local population was not nearly

01:08:42.250 --> 01:08:44.740
as loyalist as the British expected

01:08:44.740 --> 01:08:48.520
and relied on the local militias and partisans to harass

01:08:48.520 --> 01:08:51.070
and harry the British supply lines.

01:08:51.070 --> 01:08:53.740
In 1780 and 1781,

01:08:53.740 --> 01:08:56.530
Greene and his other field officers lured the British away

01:08:56.530 --> 01:08:59.920
from the coast and into the Carolina Backcountry

01:08:59.920 --> 01:09:01.300
where they were soundly defeated

01:09:01.300 --> 01:09:04.270
at the Battle of King's Mountain and Cowpens.

01:09:04.270 --> 01:09:07.240
As the British were lured further away from the Carolinas

01:09:07.240 --> 01:09:12.070
and into Virginia, the Carolinas exploded into a civil war

01:09:12.070 --> 01:09:15.760
as patriots fought Loyalists for control of the states.

01:09:15.760 --> 01:09:19.420
Greene moved back into the Carolinas to recapture the states

01:09:19.420 --> 01:09:22.120
fighting the British in a series of engagements

01:09:22.120 --> 01:09:23.200
and forcing them back

01:09:23.200 --> 01:09:25.720
to the coastal cities where they started.

01:09:25.720 --> 01:09:27.790
In the summer of 1781,

01:09:27.790 --> 01:09:31.360
Greene's army was exhausted from the near constant fighting,

01:09:31.360 --> 01:09:32.860
as was the British army

01:09:32.860 --> 01:09:35.260
under the command of Charles Cornwallis.

01:09:35.260 --> 01:09:38.860
Cornwallis knew he could not stay in the South any longer

01:09:38.860 --> 01:09:41.980
and marched his army north toward Yorktown, Virginia.

01:09:41.980 --> 01:09:43.960
In the North, the combined American

01:09:43.960 --> 01:09:45.700
and French forces marched south

01:09:45.700 --> 01:09:48.280
to intercept Cornwallis at Yorktown.

01:09:48.280 --> 01:09:51.670
Cornwallis found himself surrounded with his back to the sea

01:09:51.670 --> 01:09:53.260
and no hope for rescue.

01:09:53.260 --> 01:09:57.310
After a month-long siege, he was forced to surrender.

01:09:57.310 --> 01:10:01.150
The surrender at Yorktown was the last major military action

01:10:01.150 --> 01:10:02.830
of the American Revolution.

01:10:02.830 --> 01:10:05.110
Peace Talks opened after the surrender

01:10:05.110 --> 01:10:08.320
and took nearly two full years to finalize.

01:10:08.320 --> 01:10:11.590
In the end, the Treaty of Paris officially recognized

01:10:11.590 --> 01:10:14.080
the United States as a sovereign nation

01:10:14.080 --> 01:10:17.653
and was made independent and free from Great Britain.

01:10:18.650 --> 01:10:21.880
(uplifting music)

01:10:21.880 --> 01:10:24.310
As the American Revolution raged on,

01:10:24.310 --> 01:10:27.730
the Continental Congress, having declared independence,

01:10:27.730 --> 01:10:30.520
found themselves not only with the necessity

01:10:30.520 --> 01:10:32.920
to conduct a war as a sovereign body,

01:10:32.920 --> 01:10:35.860
but to unite the now independent states in

01:10:35.860 --> 01:10:38.350
a loose confederation government.

01:10:38.350 --> 01:10:42.340
On November 15th, 1777, the Congress adopted

01:10:42.340 --> 01:10:44.440
the Articles of Confederation,

01:10:44.440 --> 01:10:46.870
creating a weak central government

01:10:46.870 --> 01:10:49.450
which bound the states together only in times

01:10:49.450 --> 01:10:53.170
of great conflict, such as the ongoing revolution.

01:10:53.170 --> 01:10:55.060
The articles worked through the war

01:10:55.060 --> 01:10:57.910
as they granted the Congress the power to conduct the war

01:10:57.910 --> 01:11:01.990
as a united body and deal with foreign nations as such.

01:11:01.990 --> 01:11:03.610
After the war, however,

01:11:03.610 --> 01:11:05.710
it became apparent that the loose system

01:11:05.710 --> 01:11:08.170
of central government was not going to work.

01:11:08.170 --> 01:11:09.220
Under the articles,

01:11:09.220 --> 01:11:11.470
the state governments had direct control

01:11:11.470 --> 01:11:14.950
over their own commerce, economy and loss.

01:11:14.950 --> 01:11:16.870
And while many of these overlapped,

01:11:16.870 --> 01:11:20.470
not all did, creating chaos and confusion.

01:11:20.470 --> 01:11:23.080
The central government could not mediate the issues

01:11:23.080 --> 01:11:26.470
between states and disputes over state boundaries,

01:11:26.470 --> 01:11:29.740
taxation and international trade began

01:11:29.740 --> 01:11:31.690
to push the government to its limit.

01:11:31.690 --> 01:11:34.330
The United States was less than a decade old

01:11:34.330 --> 01:11:38.800
and was already facing an economic and political disaster.

01:11:38.800 --> 01:11:40.990
One of the major indicators that change needed

01:11:40.990 --> 01:11:43.870
to be made occurred in fall 1786

01:11:43.870 --> 01:11:46.180
when the economic situation began leading

01:11:46.180 --> 01:11:49.120
to mass foreclosures and bankruptcies.

01:11:49.120 --> 01:11:52.120
In Massachusetts, revolutionary war veteran,

01:11:52.120 --> 01:11:56.410
Daniel Shays led a rebellion of some 1,200 other veterans

01:11:56.410 --> 01:11:58.600
who had not been paid for their service,

01:11:58.600 --> 01:12:00.430
nor had received a pension,

01:12:00.430 --> 01:12:04.540
and occupied the Massachusetts Supreme Court in Springfield,

01:12:04.540 --> 01:12:07.810
thereby denying the Massachusetts Government the ability

01:12:07.810 --> 01:12:10.090
to foreclose on any property.

01:12:10.090 --> 01:12:13.360
They attacked the new federal arsenal at Springfield

01:12:13.360 --> 01:12:16.900
but were unsuccessful in taking possession of the grounds.

01:12:16.900 --> 01:12:19.540
Fighting began to occur all over the state

01:12:19.540 --> 01:12:21.280
as the rebellion spread.

01:12:21.280 --> 01:12:24.820
Fortunately, the Massachusetts militia defeated the rebels,

01:12:24.820 --> 01:12:27.940
scattering them, and putting an end to the fighting.

01:12:27.940 --> 01:12:31.210
It was clear the Articles of Confederation limited

01:12:31.210 --> 01:12:32.860
the federal government's ability

01:12:32.860 --> 01:12:37.330
to handle domestic issues as well as foreign policy issues.

01:12:37.330 --> 01:12:40.240
The Treaty of Paris, which had ended the revolution,

01:12:40.240 --> 01:12:43.150
made stipulations that debts owed by Americans

01:12:43.150 --> 01:12:46.360
to British subjects would still need to be honored

01:12:46.360 --> 01:12:49.360
and that loyalists would still be able to bring suits

01:12:49.360 --> 01:12:51.640
to United States courts for the return

01:12:51.640 --> 01:12:53.590
of their confiscated property.

01:12:53.590 --> 01:12:57.130
As each state was liable for ensuring these terms were met,

01:12:57.130 --> 01:12:59.800
there were discrepancies across the country,

01:12:59.800 --> 01:13:02.890
as some enforced these terms better than others.

01:13:02.890 --> 01:13:06.130
The result was British troops still occupying forts

01:13:06.130 --> 01:13:08.860
and territory, which now technically belonged

01:13:08.860 --> 01:13:10.270
to the United States,

01:13:10.270 --> 01:13:12.910
as the terms of the Treaty had not been met.

01:13:12.910 --> 01:13:14.620
With no authority to mediate

01:13:14.620 --> 01:13:17.170
or command the states to adhere to the treaty,

01:13:17.170 --> 01:13:19.630
the federal government could do nothing.

01:13:19.630 --> 01:13:23.110
With few options, a convention was called by several states

01:13:23.110 --> 01:13:25.660
in order to make amendments to the articles.

01:13:25.660 --> 01:13:27.520
In May, 1787,

01:13:27.520 --> 01:13:30.910
the constitutional convention convened in Philadelphia

01:13:30.910 --> 01:13:34.090
and began debating the Articles of Confederation

01:13:34.090 --> 01:13:36.550
and what would be required to alter them.

01:13:36.550 --> 01:13:40.480
It was immediately clear that the articles did not work,

01:13:40.480 --> 01:13:42.730
but what form of government would?

01:13:42.730 --> 01:13:44.770
A fundamentally new design

01:13:44.770 --> 01:13:47.110
was proposed and hotly debated.

01:13:47.110 --> 01:13:50.110
As would become the hallmark of American politics,

01:13:50.110 --> 01:13:51.850
several compromises were met

01:13:51.850 --> 01:13:54.130
to achieve the balance the states required

01:13:54.130 --> 01:13:57.010
to ratify this new form of government.

01:13:57.010 --> 01:14:00.130
This new constitution would form a government of checks

01:14:00.130 --> 01:14:03.670
and balances with three distinct branches dividing

01:14:03.670 --> 01:14:05.740
the federal authority between them.

01:14:05.740 --> 01:14:07.210
The legislative branch

01:14:07.210 --> 01:14:10.900
or the Congress would be divided into two houses,

01:14:10.900 --> 01:14:12.430
the House of Representatives,

01:14:12.430 --> 01:14:14.950
composed of state representatives comparable

01:14:14.950 --> 01:14:18.070
to the population of each state, and the Senate,

01:14:18.070 --> 01:14:21.370
composed of two representatives from each state.

01:14:21.370 --> 01:14:23.740
This branch has the power to create

01:14:23.740 --> 01:14:27.610
and vote on laws, enact taxes, declare war,

01:14:27.610 --> 01:14:31.630
override presidential vetoes, create federal courts,

01:14:31.630 --> 01:14:33.460
except for the Supreme Court,

01:14:33.460 --> 01:14:36.790
and sets the number of justices on the Supreme Court.

01:14:36.790 --> 01:14:38.980
Independently, the Senate has the power

01:14:38.980 --> 01:14:42.340
to confirm presidential appointments to the judiciary,

01:14:42.340 --> 01:14:45.550
heads of departments and other federal offices,

01:14:45.550 --> 01:14:48.100
ratify treaties with foreign powers,

01:14:48.100 --> 01:14:50.710
remove impeached officials from office.

01:14:50.710 --> 01:14:52.780
The House of Representatives has the power

01:14:52.780 --> 01:14:57.370
to impeach federal officials, including the president.

01:14:57.370 --> 01:15:00.700
The executive branch would be led by a president elected

01:15:00.700 --> 01:15:04.000
by an electoral college who would be vested with the power

01:15:04.000 --> 01:15:08.200
to execute, enforce or veto federal laws,

01:15:08.200 --> 01:15:10.000
appoint federal officers,

01:15:10.000 --> 01:15:12.970
grant pardons, and act as the primary role

01:15:12.970 --> 01:15:15.610
in all matters relating to foreign policy.

01:15:15.610 --> 01:15:17.050
As the commander in chief,

01:15:17.050 --> 01:15:18.880
it was also the role of the president

01:15:18.880 --> 01:15:19.977
to lead the military forces

01:15:19.977 --> 01:15:23.500
of the United States at the direction of Congress.

01:15:23.500 --> 01:15:26.020
The third branch, the judicial branch,

01:15:26.020 --> 01:15:28.270
would consist of a Supreme Court,

01:15:28.270 --> 01:15:29.860
appointed by the president

01:15:29.860 --> 01:15:31.960
and approved by the Congress.

01:15:31.960 --> 01:15:35.050
The Supreme Court is responsible for the interpretation

01:15:35.050 --> 01:15:37.120
of the laws passed by Congress

01:15:37.120 --> 01:15:40.810
and acts as the final ruling on matters of legality.

01:15:40.810 --> 01:15:42.790
In a later Supreme Court case,

01:15:42.790 --> 01:15:45.400
Marbury v. Madison, 1803,

01:15:45.400 --> 01:15:47.470
the Supreme Court added the determination

01:15:47.470 --> 01:15:51.040
of which laws of Congress are unconstitutional.

01:15:51.040 --> 01:15:54.190
While this check was not in the original constitution,

01:15:54.190 --> 01:15:57.400
it is an essential part of the function of the court,

01:15:57.400 --> 01:16:00.580
a government by the people for the people.

01:16:00.580 --> 01:16:03.670
It was the first time any nation's constitution

01:16:03.670 --> 01:16:08.020
had included the people as instrumental in the establishment

01:16:08.020 --> 01:16:10.000
and validity of the government.

01:16:10.000 --> 01:16:14.170
The Constitution was drafted in September, 1787,

01:16:14.170 --> 01:16:17.140
and distributed to the Congress of the Confederation.

01:16:17.140 --> 01:16:20.230
Instead of the amendments to the articles they had expected,

01:16:20.230 --> 01:16:24.130
the Constitution offered an entirely new form of government.

01:16:24.130 --> 01:16:27.490
Immediate debate began as the Constitution needed

01:16:27.490 --> 01:16:30.790
to be ratified and not unanimously by each state

01:16:30.790 --> 01:16:33.370
as under the Articles of Confederation,

01:16:33.370 --> 01:16:36.250
but rather by a 2/3 majority.

01:16:36.250 --> 01:16:38.410
In October, 1787,

01:16:38.410 --> 01:16:41.320
the first of 85 pamphlets championing

01:16:41.320 --> 01:16:44.680
the Constitution were published and widely distributed.

01:16:44.680 --> 01:16:46.870
Known as the Federalist papers,

01:16:46.870 --> 01:16:49.510
they were published anonymously at the time.

01:16:49.510 --> 01:16:50.710
Although we know now

01:16:50.710 --> 01:16:53.260
that its authors were Alexander Hamilton,

01:16:53.260 --> 01:16:55.930
James Madison and John Jay.

01:16:55.930 --> 01:16:58.750
Quickly, two factions began to form.

01:16:58.750 --> 01:17:00.760
On one side were the Federalists,

01:17:00.760 --> 01:17:02.227
who supported the Constitution

01:17:02.227 --> 01:17:04.480
and a powerful central government.

01:17:04.480 --> 01:17:07.240
On the other were the anti-Federalists,

01:17:07.240 --> 01:17:10.090
who saw the Constitution as too powerful

01:17:10.090 --> 01:17:13.120
and detracted from the power of state governments.

01:17:13.120 --> 01:17:17.290
One by one, however, the states ratified the Constitution.

01:17:17.290 --> 01:17:20.890
The need for a change in government had become too dire

01:17:20.890 --> 01:17:22.240
and most states realized

01:17:22.240 --> 01:17:25.510
that this constitution would be the best way forward.

01:17:25.510 --> 01:17:27.880
The Constitution was officially ratified

01:17:27.880 --> 01:17:32.200
by the states over the course of 1787 to '88.

01:17:32.200 --> 01:17:35.170
And on June 21st, 1788,

01:17:35.170 --> 01:17:38.620
the ninth State, New Hampshire, voted in favor,

01:17:38.620 --> 01:17:42.433
making the Constitution the new law of the land.

01:17:43.767 --> 01:17:46.510
(suspenseful music)

01:17:46.510 --> 01:17:49.810
George Washington, hero of the American Revolution

01:17:49.810 --> 01:17:52.270
was elected in early 1789

01:17:52.270 --> 01:17:55.300
to be the first president of the United States.

01:17:55.300 --> 01:17:58.090
John Adams, having received the second most votes,

01:17:58.090 --> 01:18:00.160
was elected his vice president.

01:18:00.160 --> 01:18:02.260
While Washington did not ally himself

01:18:02.260 --> 01:18:03.700
with either the Federalist

01:18:03.700 --> 01:18:06.760
or anti-Federalists factions which had taken root,

01:18:06.760 --> 01:18:09.520
he did favor Federalist policies in order

01:18:09.520 --> 01:18:11.740
to strengthen the fledgling government.

01:18:11.740 --> 01:18:13.330
He wisely filled his cabinet

01:18:13.330 --> 01:18:16.120
with the brightest political minds of the age,

01:18:16.120 --> 01:18:17.380
from both Federalist

01:18:17.380 --> 01:18:21.430
and anti-Federalists factions, including Thomas Jefferson,

01:18:21.430 --> 01:18:25.420
Alexander Hamilton, Henry Knox, and Edmund Randolph.

01:18:25.420 --> 01:18:27.820
During his presidency, Washington attempted

01:18:27.820 --> 01:18:31.540
to focus on the myriad domestic issues facing the country.

01:18:31.540 --> 01:18:32.650
He pushed the Congress

01:18:32.650 --> 01:18:35.500
to pass tariffs on imported goods in an effort

01:18:35.500 --> 01:18:37.750
to raise revenue for the federal government

01:18:37.750 --> 01:18:40.600
and worked closely with his secretary of treasury,

01:18:40.600 --> 01:18:44.650
Alexander Hamilton, to pass a series of economic programs

01:18:44.650 --> 01:18:47.440
and laws which would create a national bank,

01:18:47.440 --> 01:18:50.440
and establish a national debt for the government.

01:18:50.440 --> 01:18:53.560
He selected the permanent location for the future capital

01:18:53.560 --> 01:18:55.120
of the United States

01:18:55.120 --> 01:18:58.900
and would bear the name Washington, District of Columbia,

01:18:58.900 --> 01:19:01.000
in honor of the first president.

01:19:01.000 --> 01:19:03.730
In times of crisis, Washington took his role

01:19:03.730 --> 01:19:05.710
as commander in chief literally.

01:19:05.710 --> 01:19:10.000
In 1790, in response to the Distilled Spirits Duties Act

01:19:10.000 --> 01:19:14.800
or Whiskey Act, which taxed domestically distilled spirits,

01:19:14.800 --> 01:19:18.640
farmers in Western Pennsylvania began an armed insurrection.

01:19:18.640 --> 01:19:20.320
They attacked tax collectors

01:19:20.320 --> 01:19:22.420
and clashed with federal forces,

01:19:22.420 --> 01:19:25.090
prompting Washington to summon the Pennsylvania

01:19:25.090 --> 01:19:27.700
and Virginia militias to active duty.

01:19:27.700 --> 01:19:30.850
He personally led the troops into Western Pennsylvania

01:19:30.850 --> 01:19:32.860
and with a little show of force,

01:19:32.860 --> 01:19:34.150
his commissioners were able

01:19:34.150 --> 01:19:36.310
to broker the end of what became known

01:19:36.310 --> 01:19:38.050
as the Whiskey Rebellion.

01:19:38.050 --> 01:19:39.370
In foreign affairs,

01:19:39.370 --> 01:19:42.250
Washington suffered from attacks on all sides.

01:19:42.250 --> 01:19:46.060
In France, their one-time ally, King Louis Louis XVI,

01:19:46.060 --> 01:19:49.120
had lost control of his government and his people,

01:19:49.120 --> 01:19:52.540
resulting in an increasingly violent revolution.

01:19:52.540 --> 01:19:54.040
Trouble with barbery pirates

01:19:54.040 --> 01:19:56.170
in the Mediterranean threatened to disrupt

01:19:56.170 --> 01:19:59.080
a fragile American maritime trade.

01:19:59.080 --> 01:20:01.750
England had begun the practice of impressment

01:20:01.750 --> 01:20:05.290
or the stealing of sailors and ships from other nations,

01:20:05.290 --> 01:20:08.410
forcing Washington to demand satisfaction.

01:20:08.410 --> 01:20:09.460
Sending his friend

01:20:09.460 --> 01:20:12.490
and political confidant, John Jay, to England,

01:20:12.490 --> 01:20:15.610
Washington hoped to achieve an amicable trade agreement

01:20:15.610 --> 01:20:18.190
and cessation of American impressment.

01:20:18.190 --> 01:20:20.320
Jay returned with a treaty in hand

01:20:20.320 --> 01:20:22.660
and represented the American Government well

01:20:22.660 --> 01:20:25.270
in Washington's eyes, bringing Great Britain

01:20:25.270 --> 01:20:27.610
and the United States closer together.

01:20:27.610 --> 01:20:31.390
Conversely, the Jay Treaty angered pro-French factions

01:20:31.390 --> 01:20:34.450
in his administration and around the country.

01:20:34.450 --> 01:20:38.320
Washington was elected for a second term in 1792,

01:20:38.320 --> 01:20:40.720
again with Adams as his vice president.

01:20:40.720 --> 01:20:43.810
He continued to struggle with the new French Republic,

01:20:43.810 --> 01:20:48.280
as in 1793, they executed King Louis XVI

01:20:48.280 --> 01:20:51.880
and were engulfed in a series of revolutionary wars.

01:20:51.880 --> 01:20:54.190
Washington leaned hard into his desire

01:20:54.190 --> 01:20:56.560
for American isolation from Europe,

01:20:56.560 --> 01:20:59.230
much to the frustration of the pro-French members

01:20:59.230 --> 01:21:01.750
of his cabinet, like Thomas Jefferson.

01:21:01.750 --> 01:21:04.570
In 1793, during his second term,

01:21:04.570 --> 01:21:06.700
Washington was forced to remove himself

01:21:06.700 --> 01:21:09.010
and the government from their temporary capital

01:21:09.010 --> 01:21:12.370
in Philadelphia due to an outbreak of yellow fever.

01:21:12.370 --> 01:21:14.710
The government moved to Trenton, New Jersey

01:21:14.710 --> 01:21:19.390
where the Continental Congress had once briefly met in 1784.

01:21:19.390 --> 01:21:21.760
Washington struggled with the growing rift

01:21:21.760 --> 01:21:23.440
within his administration.

01:21:23.440 --> 01:21:27.340
The anti-Federalists, now the Democratic-Republicans,

01:21:27.340 --> 01:21:30.280
had grown further and further apart ideologically

01:21:30.280 --> 01:21:31.840
from the Federalists.

01:21:31.840 --> 01:21:35.290
Washington feared the creation of two political parties

01:21:35.290 --> 01:21:37.930
and warned repeatedly that their existence could lead

01:21:37.930 --> 01:21:40.540
to a serious fracture within the government.

01:21:40.540 --> 01:21:43.300
The Washington Administration set many precedents

01:21:43.300 --> 01:21:44.830
for the United States Government

01:21:44.830 --> 01:21:46.720
and the Office of the President.

01:21:46.720 --> 01:21:50.410
From pushing domestic policies to foreign intervention

01:21:50.410 --> 01:21:55.060
or lack thereof, Washington set the tone for his successors.

01:21:55.060 --> 01:21:58.180
His final act as president was to step down.

01:21:58.180 --> 01:22:01.030
While Congress had not yet placed any term restrictions

01:22:01.030 --> 01:22:04.300
on the Office of the President, it was widely expected

01:22:04.300 --> 01:22:06.760
that Washington might just remain president

01:22:06.760 --> 01:22:10.690
or establish a kind of dynasty, not unlike a king.

01:22:10.690 --> 01:22:13.120
Instead, after two terms served,

01:22:13.120 --> 01:22:14.740
Washington stepped down

01:22:14.740 --> 01:22:17.797
and did not run for office for a third term.

01:22:17.797 --> 01:22:19.360
(ominous music)

01:22:19.360 --> 01:22:23.770
His successor, elected by a narrow margin in 1797,

01:22:23.770 --> 01:22:27.490
was John Adams whose foreign affairs struggles were equal

01:22:27.490 --> 01:22:29.620
or worse to Washington's.

01:22:29.620 --> 01:22:31.840
The situation in France devolved further

01:22:31.840 --> 01:22:34.780
into a period known as the Reign of Terror.

01:22:34.780 --> 01:22:38.050
Adams continued Washington's policy of isolation

01:22:38.050 --> 01:22:41.140
and further pushed the United States away from France.

01:22:41.140 --> 01:22:43.810
In response, the new revolutionary government

01:22:43.810 --> 01:22:47.560
of France began an unofficial war against the United States

01:22:47.560 --> 01:22:49.180
or quasi-war.

01:22:49.180 --> 01:22:51.550
The fighting was kept primarily at sea

01:22:51.550 --> 01:22:53.590
and involved a number of naval battles

01:22:53.590 --> 01:22:55.780
with America's fledgling Navy.

01:22:55.780 --> 01:22:58.990
At home, Adams became increasingly unpopular

01:22:58.990 --> 01:23:00.940
with the Democratic-Republicans

01:23:00.940 --> 01:23:04.150
as he passed the Alien and Sedition Acts,

01:23:04.150 --> 01:23:05.920
allowing the government to arrest

01:23:05.920 --> 01:23:07.510
or silence any critics

01:23:07.510 --> 01:23:09.790
of the Adams Administration's actions

01:23:09.790 --> 01:23:11.440
in regards to France.

01:23:11.440 --> 01:23:13.600
Bedeviled by members of his own party

01:23:13.600 --> 01:23:15.490
and members of the opposition,

01:23:15.490 --> 01:23:17.950
Adams took it upon himself to broker an agreement

01:23:17.950 --> 01:23:21.790
with France and and end his administration in peace.

01:23:21.790 --> 01:23:23.560
In his final year in office,

01:23:23.560 --> 01:23:25.060
Adams and his wife Abigail

01:23:25.060 --> 01:23:26.980
were the first presidential family

01:23:26.980 --> 01:23:29.800
to move into the White House in the new capital

01:23:29.800 --> 01:23:31.570
in Washington, DC.

01:23:31.570 --> 01:23:33.370
They lived and worked out of the building

01:23:33.370 --> 01:23:35.560
as it was put together around them.

01:23:35.560 --> 01:23:37.960
Adams ran again, hoping that his peace

01:23:37.960 --> 01:23:39.850
with France would regain favor,

01:23:39.850 --> 01:23:42.520
but lost out to Thomas Jefferson early

01:23:42.520 --> 01:23:44.609
in the electoral process.

01:23:44.609 --> 01:23:46.870
(ominous music)

01:23:46.870 --> 01:23:51.010
The presidency of Thomas Jefferson ushered in 25 years

01:23:51.010 --> 01:23:54.760
of Democratic-Republican control of the executive branch.

01:23:54.760 --> 01:23:57.190
Jefferson's administration rapidly worked

01:23:57.190 --> 01:23:59.500
to undo the damage they felt Washington

01:23:59.500 --> 01:24:01.870
and Adams' administrations had done.

01:24:01.870 --> 01:24:04.510
Jefferson worked to reduce the accumulated debt,

01:24:04.510 --> 01:24:07.270
cutting the budget as low as he possibly could.

01:24:07.270 --> 01:24:10.690
He reduced the Army and Navy and removed the whiskey tax

01:24:10.690 --> 01:24:13.330
which had plagued Washington's presidency.

01:24:13.330 --> 01:24:15.490
Like Washington and Adams,

01:24:15.490 --> 01:24:19.030
Jefferson had to contend with piracy in the Mediterranean.

01:24:19.030 --> 01:24:21.400
He employed an American naval squadron

01:24:21.400 --> 01:24:23.830
to soundly defeat the barbery pirates

01:24:23.830 --> 01:24:25.960
and forced them to capitulate.

01:24:25.960 --> 01:24:28.633
Unlike his predecessors, Jefferson actively worked

01:24:28.633 --> 01:24:30.730
with the new French government,

01:24:30.730 --> 01:24:33.850
now under the control of Napoleon Bonaparte.

01:24:33.850 --> 01:24:35.980
Bonaparte, looking to make quick cash

01:24:35.980 --> 01:24:38.590
and to offload some old colonial holdings,

01:24:38.590 --> 01:24:40.600
sold the Louisiana territory

01:24:40.600 --> 01:24:43.990
to Jefferson's administration in 1803,

01:24:43.990 --> 01:24:47.980
opening an entirely new frontier for Americans.

01:24:47.980 --> 01:24:49.120
The following year,

01:24:49.120 --> 01:24:51.820
Jefferson employed the Corps of Discovery,

01:24:51.820 --> 01:24:53.920
led by Captain Merriweather Lewis

01:24:53.920 --> 01:24:55.600
and Lieutenant William Clark

01:24:55.600 --> 01:24:58.210
to mount an expedition up the Missouri River

01:24:58.210 --> 01:25:00.460
and over the continental divide.

01:25:00.460 --> 01:25:02.770
Their goals were to map the new territory

01:25:02.770 --> 01:25:05.470
to find a practical route across the western half

01:25:05.470 --> 01:25:06.730
of the continent and

01:25:06.730 --> 01:25:09.460
to establish an American presence in the West

01:25:09.460 --> 01:25:12.670
before Europeans got the chance to claim territory.

01:25:12.670 --> 01:25:16.090
Aided by a Shoshone woman named Sacagawea who served

01:25:16.090 --> 01:25:18.430
as an interpreter, the party made contact

01:25:18.430 --> 01:25:20.920
with over 70 Indian tribes,

01:25:20.920 --> 01:25:25.920
produced 140 maps and documented more than 200 new plant

01:25:25.990 --> 01:25:27.850
and animal species.

01:25:27.850 --> 01:25:30.070
Jefferson's second term was marred

01:25:30.070 --> 01:25:32.620
by the Napoleonic Wars raging in Europe.

01:25:32.620 --> 01:25:34.270
Both British and French Navies

01:25:34.270 --> 01:25:37.750
now actively attacked American ships and sailors,

01:25:37.750 --> 01:25:39.160
resulting in violations

01:25:39.160 --> 01:25:41.680
of America's neutral shipping rights.

01:25:41.680 --> 01:25:44.440
In response, Jefferson employed an embargo

01:25:44.440 --> 01:25:45.820
on American shipping.

01:25:45.820 --> 01:25:48.070
It was wildly unpopular

01:25:48.070 --> 01:25:50.590
and even more wildly unsuccessful,

01:25:50.590 --> 01:25:53.530
damaging Jefferson's attempts to balance the budget

01:25:53.530 --> 01:25:56.002
before his second term was up.

01:25:56.002 --> 01:25:58.750
(inspirational music)

01:25:58.750 --> 01:26:02.320
Despite the unpopularity the Democratic-Republicans faced

01:26:02.320 --> 01:26:05.860
at the end of Jefferson's administration, his protege,

01:26:05.860 --> 01:26:07.600
James Madison was elected

01:26:07.600 --> 01:26:10.510
as the fourth president of the United States.

01:26:10.510 --> 01:26:12.850
Madison, who had been instrumental

01:26:12.850 --> 01:26:15.220
during the Constitutional Convention,

01:26:15.220 --> 01:26:18.400
inherited a complicated and messy relationship

01:26:18.400 --> 01:26:19.840
with England and France,

01:26:19.840 --> 01:26:22.870
and mounting tension within the United States.

01:26:22.870 --> 01:26:25.210
Madison continued Jefferson's embargo

01:26:25.210 --> 01:26:27.580
for the first two years of his presidency,

01:26:27.580 --> 01:26:30.400
realizing that trade was necessary for the betterment

01:26:30.400 --> 01:26:33.550
of the United States, and at the behest of Congress,

01:26:33.550 --> 01:26:37.030
Madison reopened American shipping to France and England,

01:26:37.030 --> 01:26:40.420
asking them once again to honor America's neutrality.

01:26:40.420 --> 01:26:42.430
Naturally, the capturing of ships

01:26:42.430 --> 01:26:44.950
and impressment of sailors began again,

01:26:44.950 --> 01:26:48.520
almost immediately, a group of young congressmen,

01:26:48.520 --> 01:26:50.830
namely two gentlemen named Henry Clay

01:26:50.830 --> 01:26:53.590
and John C. Calhoun, hounded the president

01:26:53.590 --> 01:26:55.900
for a stronger show of force.

01:26:55.900 --> 01:26:57.730
Known as War Hawks,

01:26:57.730 --> 01:27:01.090
Clay, Calhoun, and their faction demanded Madison

01:27:01.090 --> 01:27:04.750
to take a more militant stance toward Britain and France.

01:27:04.750 --> 01:27:07.540
Increased tension on the American interior added

01:27:07.540 --> 01:27:08.530
to the fire.

01:27:08.530 --> 01:27:10.900
British agents had been suspected of arming

01:27:10.900 --> 01:27:14.020
and supplying a native uprising on the frontier

01:27:14.020 --> 01:27:16.090
and British troops still held forts

01:27:16.090 --> 01:27:18.190
which belonged to the United States.

01:27:18.190 --> 01:27:21.310
After British ships blatantly attacked American sailors

01:27:21.310 --> 01:27:23.740
immediately off of the American coast,

01:27:23.740 --> 01:27:25.780
Madison gave in to the War Hawks

01:27:25.780 --> 01:27:30.637
and asked the Congress to declare war on June 1st, 1812.

01:27:30.637 --> 01:27:32.590
The American people may have been ready

01:27:32.590 --> 01:27:33.880
for war with Britain,

01:27:33.880 --> 01:27:35.830
but its army and navy were not.

01:27:35.830 --> 01:27:38.200
In three separate invasions of Canada,

01:27:38.200 --> 01:27:39.730
the United States was defeated

01:27:39.730 --> 01:27:41.380
and beaten back with two out

01:27:41.380 --> 01:27:43.450
of three armies forced to surrender.

01:27:43.450 --> 01:27:45.790
Although not without some success.

01:27:45.790 --> 01:27:48.220
One of the invasions had resulted in the burning

01:27:48.220 --> 01:27:51.910
of the City of York, the provincial capital in Canada.

01:27:51.910 --> 01:27:53.980
Naval battles fared much better.

01:27:53.980 --> 01:27:56.950
In one instance, the USS Constitution

01:27:56.950 --> 01:27:59.320
and the HMS Guerriere faced off

01:27:59.320 --> 01:28:02.560
in a swift naval engagement lasting less than an hour.

01:28:02.560 --> 01:28:04.270
The British were horrified to find

01:28:04.270 --> 01:28:06.610
that their cannon balls bounced harmlessly off

01:28:06.610 --> 01:28:09.700
of the Constitution's 22-inch hole.

01:28:09.700 --> 01:28:12.970
The USS Constitution would go on to wreak havoc

01:28:12.970 --> 01:28:15.760
among the British Navy throughout the war.

01:28:15.760 --> 01:28:18.790
Many native tribes a banded together under the leadership

01:28:18.790 --> 01:28:22.587
of the Shawnee Chief Tecumseh and his brother Tenskwatawa

01:28:22.587 --> 01:28:25.900
or Lalawethika, known as the Prophet.

01:28:25.900 --> 01:28:28.240
Tecumseh's confederacy of tribes sided

01:28:28.240 --> 01:28:30.910
with the British in the last desperate gamble

01:28:30.910 --> 01:28:32.170
to establish control

01:28:32.170 --> 01:28:35.020
over the continued American expansion west.

01:28:35.020 --> 01:28:37.360
The British and Tecumseh's confederacy kept

01:28:37.360 --> 01:28:39.970
the American military at bay in Canada

01:28:39.970 --> 01:28:41.980
where Tecumseh was ultimately killed

01:28:41.980 --> 01:28:44.710
at the Battle of the Thames in 1813.

01:28:44.710 --> 01:28:48.400
Tecumseh's death fractured the confederacy of tribes

01:28:48.400 --> 01:28:51.070
and ultimately drew them out of the war.

01:28:51.070 --> 01:28:53.950
The British on the other hand turned on the offensive

01:28:53.950 --> 01:28:57.130
and attacked American positions along the Chesapeake,

01:28:57.130 --> 01:29:01.240
aiming to capture the United States capital, Washington DC.

01:29:01.240 --> 01:29:03.070
In August, 1814,

01:29:03.070 --> 01:29:06.130
the British successfully sailed up the Patuxent River,

01:29:06.130 --> 01:29:07.690
south of Washington,

01:29:07.690 --> 01:29:11.470
and landed troops who marched toward the US Capital City.

01:29:11.470 --> 01:29:12.970
A disastrous defense

01:29:12.970 --> 01:29:16.480
of the city at Bladensburg left Washington, DC open

01:29:16.480 --> 01:29:18.910
to attack and occupation.

01:29:18.910 --> 01:29:21.730
In the White House, Madison was forced to evacuate

01:29:21.730 --> 01:29:23.950
and watched the disaster from afar.

01:29:23.950 --> 01:29:25.450
His wife, Dolly Madison,

01:29:25.450 --> 01:29:28.120
realized that if the British captured the city,

01:29:28.120 --> 01:29:29.440
they would wreak havoc

01:29:29.440 --> 01:29:33.070
and likely set fire to the various government buildings.

01:29:33.070 --> 01:29:35.500
Mrs. Madison had her enslaved servant,

01:29:35.500 --> 01:29:39.310
Paul Jennings, take down and secure the famous copy

01:29:39.310 --> 01:29:42.370
of the Landsdowne portrait of George Washington,

01:29:42.370 --> 01:29:45.040
which hung prominently in the White House.

01:29:45.040 --> 01:29:47.620
Dolly's precaution proved prophetic,

01:29:47.620 --> 01:29:50.440
as when the British troops occupied Washington,

01:29:50.440 --> 01:29:53.980
they did indeed set numerous government buildings ablaze,

01:29:53.980 --> 01:29:57.370
including the still under construction US Capitol,

01:29:57.370 --> 01:30:01.240
the Treasury, the Department of War, and White House.

01:30:01.240 --> 01:30:04.270
As the city burned, a well-timed hurricane,

01:30:04.270 --> 01:30:06.820
rushed up the coast, putting out the fires,

01:30:06.820 --> 01:30:08.710
and in one recorded case,

01:30:08.710 --> 01:30:12.430
picked up two cannons and threw them several yards away,

01:30:12.430 --> 01:30:16.450
killing both British soldiers and American civilians.

01:30:16.450 --> 01:30:18.400
While the British had successfully taken

01:30:18.400 --> 01:30:20.200
and burned the US Capitol,

01:30:20.200 --> 01:30:22.330
they were forced to abandon the city,

01:30:22.330 --> 01:30:24.400
as controlling it would not be possible

01:30:24.400 --> 01:30:26.380
without additional reinforcement,

01:30:26.380 --> 01:30:28.900
and the hurricane had severely damaged their fleet

01:30:28.900 --> 01:30:30.310
on the Patuxent River.

01:30:30.310 --> 01:30:32.620
Madison returned to the ruined Capitol

01:30:32.620 --> 01:30:34.870
and continued to prosecute the war.

01:30:34.870 --> 01:30:37.000
The following month, British Naval efforts

01:30:37.000 --> 01:30:39.990
to capture the City of Baltimore were thwarted at the siege

01:30:39.990 --> 01:30:43.330
of Fort McHenry where British vessels bombarded the fort

01:30:43.330 --> 01:30:46.420
through a vicious battle which lasted into the night.

01:30:46.420 --> 01:30:48.220
In the morning at reve,

01:30:48.220 --> 01:30:52.660
Fort McHenry ran up its oversized Star-Spangled Banner flag

01:30:52.660 --> 01:30:55.390
as it prepared for another day of fighting.

01:30:55.390 --> 01:30:58.450
Instead, the British fleet sailed back out to sea,

01:30:58.450 --> 01:31:01.240
unwilling to engage more American positions,

01:31:01.240 --> 01:31:03.220
and began diverting the resources

01:31:03.220 --> 01:31:06.100
for an attack on New Orleans in Louisiana.

01:31:06.100 --> 01:31:08.470
The siege of Fort McHenry and the site

01:31:08.470 --> 01:31:10.450
of the oversized American flag

01:31:10.450 --> 01:31:13.870
on the morning of September 14th, 1814

01:31:13.870 --> 01:31:17.470
inspired American lawyer, Francis Scott Key to pen

01:31:17.470 --> 01:31:20.800
a poem titled "The Defense of Fort McHenry."

01:31:20.800 --> 01:31:22.120
The words of the poem,

01:31:22.120 --> 01:31:25.270
set to the tune of an old British drinking song,

01:31:25.270 --> 01:31:28.000
would go on to become the national anthem

01:31:28.000 --> 01:31:31.780
of the United States, "The Star-Spangled Banner."

01:31:31.780 --> 01:31:33.730
The British made one last attempt

01:31:33.730 --> 01:31:36.760
to make an offensive effort into the American mainland near

01:31:36.760 --> 01:31:39.250
the city of New Orleans in Louisiana.

01:31:39.250 --> 01:31:41.770
Hoping to get control of the Mississippi River,

01:31:41.770 --> 01:31:44.830
British forces landed several miles south of New Orleans

01:31:44.830 --> 01:31:46.810
and attempted to march on the city.

01:31:46.810 --> 01:31:48.730
The defense of the city was organized

01:31:48.730 --> 01:31:52.000
by a fiery commander named Andrew Jackson,

01:31:52.000 --> 01:31:53.500
whose hodgepodge assembly

01:31:53.500 --> 01:31:56.230
of defenders included pirates, militia,

01:31:56.230 --> 01:31:58.540
free Blacks and regulars.

01:31:58.540 --> 01:32:01.957
In January, 1815, unaware that the United States

01:32:01.957 --> 01:32:05.350
and England had concluded negotiations for a peace treaty

01:32:05.350 --> 01:32:09.970
in December, 1814, British forces marched on New Orleans

01:32:09.970 --> 01:32:12.460
and engaged in one last battle.

01:32:12.460 --> 01:32:15.580
Jackson's ragtag defenders held off several waves

01:32:15.580 --> 01:32:18.640
of British troops and won an incredible-

01:32:18.640 --> 01:32:22.540
if somewhat belated- victory for the United States.

01:32:22.540 --> 01:32:25.720
Although the war of 1812 is little known today,

01:32:25.720 --> 01:32:29.410
it had many lasting impacts across for the United States

01:32:29.410 --> 01:32:31.300
and the people of North America.

01:32:31.300 --> 01:32:34.030
Without question, the greatest effect on the war

01:32:34.030 --> 01:32:36.340
was not any territory gained,

01:32:36.340 --> 01:32:39.160
but rather the definitive end of any hope

01:32:39.160 --> 01:32:41.860
for the Native Americans to establish any kind

01:32:41.860 --> 01:32:44.080
of sovereignty over their land.

01:32:44.080 --> 01:32:45.340
As part of the treaty,

01:32:45.340 --> 01:32:47.170
the British had pushed for the establishment

01:32:47.170 --> 01:32:49.990
of an Indian state in the Great Lakes region,

01:32:49.990 --> 01:32:52.900
but the United States had outright rejected the plan.

01:32:52.900 --> 01:32:56.290
The dam was about to burst for Western expansion

01:32:56.290 --> 01:32:58.870
and there was nothing and no one left

01:32:58.870 --> 01:33:00.610
to stop the tide from sweeping away

01:33:00.610 --> 01:33:03.190
the Native tribes still standing.

01:33:03.190 --> 01:33:05.830
On a global scale, most of the European powers

01:33:05.830 --> 01:33:08.890
had assumed the United States would not be able to last.

01:33:08.890 --> 01:33:11.020
The great experiment would've run its course

01:33:11.020 --> 01:33:14.470
in these backwards farmers and high-hatted intellectuals

01:33:14.470 --> 01:33:16.390
would've torn the country apart.

01:33:16.390 --> 01:33:19.300
Instead, on a very public world stage,

01:33:19.300 --> 01:33:21.640
the United States had again declared war

01:33:21.640 --> 01:33:24.730
on the most powerful empire in the world

01:33:24.730 --> 01:33:26.950
and fought them to a standstill.

01:33:26.950 --> 01:33:29.260
While there was very little territory gained

01:33:29.260 --> 01:33:30.610
by the Treaty of Ghent,

01:33:30.610 --> 01:33:33.790
the statement was clear, the United States was here

01:33:33.790 --> 01:33:35.620
and they were here to stay,

01:33:35.620 --> 01:33:38.743
at least as long as it could stay together.

01:33:39.781 --> 01:33:43.270
(uplifting music)

01:33:43.270 --> 01:33:45.310
As the 19th century progressed,

01:33:45.310 --> 01:33:48.070
many Americans became enamored with the concept

01:33:48.070 --> 01:33:51.220
of continentalism, a belief that the United States

01:33:51.220 --> 01:33:53.110
would one day stretch from sea

01:33:53.110 --> 01:33:57.100
to shining sea and cover the North American continent.

01:33:57.100 --> 01:33:59.020
The Treaty of Ghent did very little

01:33:59.020 --> 01:34:00.820
to enhance the territory owned

01:34:00.820 --> 01:34:04.810
by the United States in the aftermath of the war of 1812,

01:34:04.810 --> 01:34:07.060
although Jefferson's Louisiana Purchase

01:34:07.060 --> 01:34:10.000
had increased the territory owned by the United States,

01:34:10.000 --> 01:34:12.340
all the way to the Rocky Mountains.

01:34:12.340 --> 01:34:13.870
Political treaties with Spain

01:34:13.870 --> 01:34:15.670
and Great Britain helped to expand

01:34:15.670 --> 01:34:18.610
and clarify these borders through the 1820s

01:34:18.610 --> 01:34:21.340
and Americans became increasingly ravenous

01:34:21.340 --> 01:34:23.650
to fulfill this continental dream.

01:34:23.650 --> 01:34:27.670
At the same time, President James Monroe's 1823

01:34:27.670 --> 01:34:30.610
warned European powers that the Western Hemisphere

01:34:30.610 --> 01:34:32.770
was no longer theirs to play with

01:34:32.770 --> 01:34:35.380
and that the United States would exert its influence

01:34:35.380 --> 01:34:37.570
as the major power in the region

01:34:37.570 --> 01:34:40.270
if they attempted to colonize here again.

01:34:40.270 --> 01:34:41.740
The message was clear

01:34:41.740 --> 01:34:44.290
and an idea began to take shape in the minds

01:34:44.290 --> 01:34:45.760
of the American people:

01:34:45.760 --> 01:34:49.510
this land is not for the Europeans and it never was.

01:34:49.510 --> 01:34:53.110
It is destined for the people of the United States.

01:34:53.110 --> 01:34:57.010
The term manifest destiny first appeared during the 1840s

01:34:57.010 --> 01:34:59.110
during growing conflict over control

01:34:59.110 --> 01:35:00.790
of the Oregon territory,

01:35:00.790 --> 01:35:03.310
but has come to encompass the entire era

01:35:03.310 --> 01:35:05.980
of westward expansion for the United States,

01:35:05.980 --> 01:35:08.770
believing that the were unquestionably destined

01:35:08.770 --> 01:35:10.900
to inhabit the entire continent

01:35:10.900 --> 01:35:13.540
and looking for a chance to redeem what some believed

01:35:13.540 --> 01:35:15.790
was ungodly and sinful.

01:35:15.790 --> 01:35:18.880
West, Americans looked to spread their values

01:35:18.880 --> 01:35:21.970
and their economy beyond the Mississippi River

01:35:21.970 --> 01:35:25.150
and reform the West into an evangelical version

01:35:25.150 --> 01:35:26.950
of the agrarian East.

01:35:26.950 --> 01:35:29.080
In their way stood the proud remnants

01:35:29.080 --> 01:35:31.480
of Native American tribes of the East

01:35:31.480 --> 01:35:34.060
and the tribes of the West now unwilling

01:35:34.060 --> 01:35:36.460
to give any more ground without a fight.

01:35:36.460 --> 01:35:39.520
Additionally, the few European colonies still standing

01:35:39.520 --> 01:35:42.520
in North America, namely Great Britain and Spain,

01:35:42.520 --> 01:35:45.160
as well as by 1824,

01:35:45.160 --> 01:35:49.540
a newly independent Mexico would not simply roll over

01:35:49.540 --> 01:35:52.840
and allow the United States to expand unchecked.

01:35:52.840 --> 01:35:55.390
When he purchased the Louisiana Territory,

01:35:55.390 --> 01:35:56.620
President Jefferson wanted

01:35:56.620 --> 01:35:59.680
to establish lasting diplomatic relationships

01:35:59.680 --> 01:36:02.050
with the myriad of tribes in the West,

01:36:02.050 --> 01:36:05.230
and as became the custom through the 19th century,

01:36:05.230 --> 01:36:08.680
hoped to civilize and assimilate the tribes

01:36:08.680 --> 01:36:10.630
into American society.

01:36:10.630 --> 01:36:12.280
It did not take long, however,

01:36:12.280 --> 01:36:15.700
for plans to assimilate the Native Americans becoming plans

01:36:15.700 --> 01:36:17.770
to remove and relocate them,

01:36:17.770 --> 01:36:21.490
especially in the aftermath of the war of 1812.

01:36:21.490 --> 01:36:25.780
As early as 1824, under the presidency of James Monroe,

01:36:25.780 --> 01:36:29.920
plans were drafted for the creation of Indian territories,

01:36:29.920 --> 01:36:31.960
which would force the Cherokee Indians

01:36:31.960 --> 01:36:34.030
to abandon their ancestral land east

01:36:34.030 --> 01:36:36.790
of the Mississippi River and move west.

01:36:36.790 --> 01:36:40.090
In 1829, President Andrew Jackson,

01:36:40.090 --> 01:36:42.790
the hero of the war of 1812,

01:36:42.790 --> 01:36:44.830
made those plans a reality,

01:36:44.830 --> 01:36:46.060
convincing the Congress

01:36:46.060 --> 01:36:49.177
to pass the Indian Removal Act In 1830.

01:36:49.177 --> 01:36:52.570
The act forced the five civilized tribes,

01:36:52.570 --> 01:36:55.720
the Chickasaw, Choctaw, Creek, Seminole,

01:36:55.720 --> 01:36:59.140
and Cherokee to abandon their lands and move west.

01:36:59.140 --> 01:37:01.360
It was an act of forced displacement

01:37:01.360 --> 01:37:04.780
with more than 60,000 people removed from their homes

01:37:04.780 --> 01:37:07.420
and relocated beyond the Mississippi River.

01:37:07.420 --> 01:37:10.120
The removal saw a few minor conflicts,

01:37:10.120 --> 01:37:13.030
but ultimately the tribes were coerced into leaving.

01:37:13.030 --> 01:37:15.100
Known one as the Trail of Tears,

01:37:15.100 --> 01:37:17.770
the routes taken by these tribes were difficult

01:37:17.770 --> 01:37:22.061
and resulted in the deaths of around 15,000 Natives.

01:37:22.061 --> 01:37:24.100
(suspenseful music)

01:37:24.100 --> 01:37:28.000
Pioneers made the journey westward to farm, mine and ranch,

01:37:28.000 --> 01:37:31.240
often finding the land inhospitable and dangerous.

01:37:31.240 --> 01:37:33.520
During their journeys, they faced skirmishes

01:37:33.520 --> 01:37:36.730
with Native Americans, diseases such as cholera

01:37:36.730 --> 01:37:40.150
and typhoid fever, punishing winters without food

01:37:40.150 --> 01:37:41.710
and other hardships.

01:37:41.710 --> 01:37:43.450
About 70,000 members

01:37:43.450 --> 01:37:46.120
of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints

01:37:46.120 --> 01:37:48.070
emigrated to the Salt Lake Valley

01:37:48.070 --> 01:37:49.570
from their homes in Illinois,

01:37:49.570 --> 01:37:53.680
beginning in 1847, known as the Mormon Exodus.

01:37:53.680 --> 01:37:57.250
Hundreds of thousands of emigrators used the Oregon Trail,

01:37:57.250 --> 01:38:00.070
a 2,000 mile route from Independence, Missouri

01:38:00.070 --> 01:38:02.260
to Oregon City, Oregon.

01:38:02.260 --> 01:38:04.270
Land speculators would sell cheap plots

01:38:04.270 --> 01:38:06.790
with promises of unbounded opportunity,

01:38:06.790 --> 01:38:09.490
inspiring thousands to make the journey.

01:38:09.490 --> 01:38:12.340
In the winter of 1846 to '47,

01:38:12.340 --> 01:38:15.160
members of the infamous Donner party were traveling

01:38:15.160 --> 01:38:17.980
by wagon train west on the Oregon trail,

01:38:17.980 --> 01:38:21.220
but became snowbound in the Sierra Nevada mountains.

01:38:21.220 --> 01:38:23.110
The party members were forced to resort

01:38:23.110 --> 01:38:25.420
to cannibalism to survive.

01:38:25.420 --> 01:38:27.700
The overland journey was so risky

01:38:27.700 --> 01:38:30.520
and difficult that some westward immigrants opted

01:38:30.520 --> 01:38:32.470
for the six-month route by sea

01:38:32.470 --> 01:38:36.430
around Cape Horn at the tip of South America instead.

01:38:36.430 --> 01:38:39.820
In 1848, gold was discovered in the foothills

01:38:39.820 --> 01:38:42.850
of the Sierra Nevada mountains in California,

01:38:42.850 --> 01:38:45.640
which had the same year become part of the US

01:38:45.640 --> 01:38:48.640
as a consequence of the Mexican-American War.

01:38:48.640 --> 01:38:50.980
Once word got out about the gold,

01:38:50.980 --> 01:38:53.770
men from near and far sought their fortunes

01:38:53.770 --> 01:38:55.780
in the Sierra Nevada foothills

01:38:55.780 --> 01:38:58.570
in what became known as the Gold Rush.

01:38:58.570 --> 01:39:02.590
In 1849, San Francisco's population skyrocketed

01:39:02.590 --> 01:39:06.310
from 812 to 20,000 people

01:39:06.310 --> 01:39:07.930
with those prospectors arriving

01:39:07.930 --> 01:39:11.920
that year becoming known collectively as the Forty-Niners.

01:39:11.920 --> 01:39:15.880
The prices for land, goods and services skyrocketed.

01:39:15.880 --> 01:39:18.040
People stood to make more money selling those goods

01:39:18.040 --> 01:39:20.110
and services to prospectors then

01:39:20.110 --> 01:39:22.360
from actually mining for gold.

01:39:22.360 --> 01:39:25.360
Because men outnumbered women in these towns greatly,

01:39:25.360 --> 01:39:27.790
traditional women's work like washing clothes

01:39:27.790 --> 01:39:30.160
and cooking became highly in demand

01:39:30.160 --> 01:39:32.440
and therefore highly profitable.

01:39:32.440 --> 01:39:35.920
Nevertheless, actual gold was certainly found.

01:39:35.920 --> 01:39:40.510
The rush produced on average 76 tons of gold per year,

01:39:40.510 --> 01:39:42.670
and by the end of the 1850s,

01:39:42.670 --> 01:39:46.420
it was estimated that $550 million worth

01:39:46.420 --> 01:39:47.860
of gold had been mined,

01:39:47.860 --> 01:39:52.390
worth about $187 billion in today's dollars.

01:39:52.390 --> 01:39:55.360
The thousands who had moved West needed fast mail service

01:39:55.360 --> 01:39:57.310
for letters and news from the East.

01:39:57.310 --> 01:39:58.810
While several male carriers

01:39:58.810 --> 01:40:00.790
over the Rocky Mountains existed,

01:40:00.790 --> 01:40:03.280
the most famous was the Pony Express.

01:40:03.280 --> 01:40:06.490
Founded in 1860, the service used relays

01:40:06.490 --> 01:40:09.880
of horse mounted riders riding at breakneck speed day

01:40:09.880 --> 01:40:12.310
and night to carry mail between Missouri

01:40:12.310 --> 01:40:15.880
and California, which it could do in about 10 days.

01:40:15.880 --> 01:40:17.800
It only operated for 18 months

01:40:17.800 --> 01:40:20.320
before the first transcontinental telegraph

01:40:20.320 --> 01:40:22.870
was established in 1861,

01:40:22.870 --> 01:40:26.020
but it was vital for connecting the new state of California

01:40:26.020 --> 01:40:27.640
with the rest of the US.

01:40:27.640 --> 01:40:29.950
As Americans began to settle west,

01:40:29.950 --> 01:40:33.220
more conflicts with the existing Native American tribes led

01:40:33.220 --> 01:40:36.280
to further violence, and the United States military

01:40:36.280 --> 01:40:38.380
became nearly permanently quartered

01:40:38.380 --> 01:40:40.810
in various forts across the Midwest

01:40:40.810 --> 01:40:42.430
and along the West Coast.

01:40:42.430 --> 01:40:45.220
The Texas territory in the American Southwest

01:40:45.220 --> 01:40:48.280
had been ceded to Spain in the 1810s,

01:40:48.280 --> 01:40:52.480
but following the Mexican War of Independence in 1821

01:40:52.480 --> 01:40:55.150
and the official formation of the Mexican Republic

01:40:55.150 --> 01:40:59.080
just three years later, the territory became part of Mexico.

01:40:59.080 --> 01:41:01.390
Texas was far away from the center

01:41:01.390 --> 01:41:03.640
of the Mexican Government in Saltillo

01:41:03.640 --> 01:41:06.250
and had fewer than 4,000 people living

01:41:06.250 --> 01:41:08.320
across the vast territory.

01:41:08.320 --> 01:41:10.600
Looking to increase immigration to the state

01:41:10.600 --> 01:41:12.490
and hoping the subsequent rise

01:41:12.490 --> 01:41:15.340
in population would deter Indian raids,

01:41:15.340 --> 01:41:17.710
the Mexican Government offered cheap land

01:41:17.710 --> 01:41:20.410
and considerable financial benefits for those

01:41:20.410 --> 01:41:22.720
who would take residence in the state.

01:41:22.720 --> 01:41:26.050
Many of those who immigrated came from the American South

01:41:26.050 --> 01:41:27.610
and brought with them the culture

01:41:27.610 --> 01:41:31.300
and mentality of the region, including slavery.

01:41:31.300 --> 01:41:34.840
In 1829, Mexico abolished slavery

01:41:34.840 --> 01:41:37.930
and after the Anglo citizens nearly revolted,

01:41:37.930 --> 01:41:41.230
the Mexican president also banned any further immigration

01:41:41.230 --> 01:41:44.620
to Texas by citizens of the United States.

01:41:44.620 --> 01:41:47.950
In Texas, the Anglo citizens ignored the laws

01:41:47.950 --> 01:41:51.880
and rapidly began to outnumber the Mexican-born population

01:41:51.880 --> 01:41:52.840
in the state.

01:41:52.840 --> 01:41:54.760
When in 1834,

01:41:54.760 --> 01:41:58.180
Antonio Lopez de Santa Anna led a successful coup

01:41:58.180 --> 01:41:59.710
of the Mexican Government,

01:41:59.710 --> 01:42:01.720
the Texans were initially pleased

01:42:01.720 --> 01:42:04.660
as Santa Anna quickly undid many of the acts

01:42:04.660 --> 01:42:06.610
and laws of his predecessors.

01:42:06.610 --> 01:42:09.310
However, Santa Anna went much further

01:42:09.310 --> 01:42:11.860
and disbanded the political bodies of each

01:42:11.860 --> 01:42:15.280
of the Mexican states, imposing a dictatorship

01:42:15.280 --> 01:42:16.330
over the country.

01:42:16.330 --> 01:42:19.600
In 1835, with support from both the Anglos

01:42:19.600 --> 01:42:23.110
and Tejanos populations, the Texans rebelled,

01:42:23.110 --> 01:42:25.870
looking to secure independence from Mexico.

01:42:25.870 --> 01:42:28.450
In late February, 1836,

01:42:28.450 --> 01:42:31.540
The most famous battle of the Texas Revolution began

01:42:31.540 --> 01:42:34.180
with the siege of the Alamo Mission.

01:42:34.180 --> 01:42:36.730
Defended by fewer than 300 Texans,

01:42:36.730 --> 01:42:38.590
the walls of the Mission had been turned

01:42:38.590 --> 01:42:40.270
into a makeshift fort.

01:42:40.270 --> 01:42:44.230
Its defenders included Colonel William Travis, James Bowie,

01:42:44.230 --> 01:42:48.640
and former US congressman and folk legend, Davy Crockett.

01:42:48.640 --> 01:42:50.980
The Texans were surrounded on all sides

01:42:50.980 --> 01:42:54.580
and besieged for 13 days by Santa Anna's army

01:42:54.580 --> 01:42:58.930
before the final night attack on March 6th, 1836.

01:42:58.930 --> 01:43:00.400
The battle was brutal

01:43:00.400 --> 01:43:03.850
and Santa Anna ordered for there to be no prisoners taken.

01:43:03.850 --> 01:43:05.680
The handful of prisoners who managed

01:43:05.680 --> 01:43:09.130
to survive the massacre were executed as well.

01:43:09.130 --> 01:43:12.100
The battle of the Alamo became a rallying cry

01:43:12.100 --> 01:43:15.310
for the Texans still fighting and fueled the Texas army

01:43:15.310 --> 01:43:16.810
in the weeks which followed.

01:43:16.810 --> 01:43:18.460
A little more than a month later,

01:43:18.460 --> 01:43:20.890
the Texas Revolution ended in victory

01:43:20.890 --> 01:43:24.670
for the people of Texas after the Battle of San Jacinto

01:43:24.670 --> 01:43:27.130
in April, 1836.

01:43:27.130 --> 01:43:29.740
The Texas Revolution lasted less than a year

01:43:29.740 --> 01:43:32.530
and saw the creation of the Republic of Texas.

01:43:32.530 --> 01:43:35.620
Naturally, the predominantly American population

01:43:35.620 --> 01:43:37.900
immediately began petitioning the government

01:43:37.900 --> 01:43:38.890
of the United States

01:43:38.890 --> 01:43:42.340
to annex the new republic and add it to the growing union.

01:43:42.340 --> 01:43:44.680
Despite fierce arguments over the admittance

01:43:44.680 --> 01:43:47.620
of what would undeniably be another slave state

01:43:47.620 --> 01:43:50.050
into the Union, it took less than a decade

01:43:50.050 --> 01:43:53.110
before Texas was annexed by the United States.

01:43:53.110 --> 01:43:56.140
The annexation of Texas sparked yet another conflict

01:43:56.140 --> 01:43:58.930
with Mexico in 1846.

01:43:58.930 --> 01:44:02.020
Because the borders of the Republic of Texas were undefined

01:44:02.020 --> 01:44:03.610
and disputed by Mexico,

01:44:03.610 --> 01:44:05.980
when the United States annexed Texas,

01:44:05.980 --> 01:44:07.810
Mexico claimed that the United States

01:44:07.810 --> 01:44:09.790
was taking Mexican land.

01:44:09.790 --> 01:44:12.580
President James K. Polk attempted to negotiate

01:44:12.580 --> 01:44:14.050
with the Mexican Government,

01:44:14.050 --> 01:44:16.390
offering to pay for the disputed territory

01:44:16.390 --> 01:44:18.280
in addition to the California,

01:44:18.280 --> 01:44:21.370
New Mexico and Arizona territories.

01:44:21.370 --> 01:44:24.310
However, the Mexican Government refused.

01:44:24.310 --> 01:44:26.320
In response, Polk sent troops

01:44:26.320 --> 01:44:28.480
to occupy the disputed territory,

01:44:28.480 --> 01:44:32.470
causing Mexican forces to attack the small American force.

01:44:32.470 --> 01:44:35.140
Polk used the affair to convince Congress

01:44:35.140 --> 01:44:37.570
to declare war on Mexico.

01:44:37.570 --> 01:44:39.160
Mexico's army was equipped

01:44:39.160 --> 01:44:43.150
with surplus flintlock firearms from the Napoleonic era,

01:44:43.150 --> 01:44:44.830
while the United States was armed

01:44:44.830 --> 01:44:47.170
with far more modern weaponry.

01:44:47.170 --> 01:44:49.330
Disorganized, under-supplied,

01:44:49.330 --> 01:44:51.400
and facing internal political strife

01:44:51.400 --> 01:44:53.320
at every level of management,

01:44:53.320 --> 01:44:55.930
the Mexican forces were little to no match

01:44:55.930 --> 01:44:57.790
for the American Army and Navy,

01:44:57.790 --> 01:45:00.640
who made quick work conquering vast sections

01:45:00.640 --> 01:45:03.070
of Mexico and its territories.

01:45:03.070 --> 01:45:05.620
When the Mexican Government finally collapsed,

01:45:05.620 --> 01:45:08.800
they were forced to surrender large swaths of territory

01:45:08.800 --> 01:45:13.060
to the United States, including California and New Mexico,

01:45:13.060 --> 01:45:15.820
in addition to suffering the indignity of having

01:45:15.820 --> 01:45:19.390
to recognize the sovereignty of the Republic of Texas

01:45:19.390 --> 01:45:23.290
and its subsequent annexation in 1845.

01:45:23.290 --> 01:45:28.060
Lasting from April, 1846, to February, 1848,

01:45:28.060 --> 01:45:31.630
the Mexican-American War proved to be a one-sided one

01:45:31.630 --> 01:45:35.560
and clearly displayed America's ambitions to secure control

01:45:35.560 --> 01:45:37.630
of the North American continent.

01:45:37.630 --> 01:45:39.580
There were many dissidents to the concept

01:45:39.580 --> 01:45:43.150
of manifest destiny, especially within the Whig party,

01:45:43.150 --> 01:45:45.100
the successors of the Federalists,

01:45:45.100 --> 01:45:47.620
including, by the mid 19th century,

01:45:47.620 --> 01:45:51.310
a young Illinois politician named Abraham Lincoln.

01:45:51.310 --> 01:45:55.390
In 1844, Manifest Destiny took center stage

01:45:55.390 --> 01:45:58.630
as territorial disputes with Great Britain over Oregon

01:45:58.630 --> 01:46:00.790
and the ongoing tensions with Mexico

01:46:00.790 --> 01:46:04.870
over the Texas territory split political parties further.

01:46:04.870 --> 01:46:07.750
As Western territories grew in population

01:46:07.750 --> 01:46:10.660
and were being considered for admission to the Union,

01:46:10.660 --> 01:46:12.190
whether these areas would allow

01:46:12.190 --> 01:46:16.090
or ban slavery became a crucial question.

01:46:16.090 --> 01:46:18.730
The fragile balance of power in Congress

01:46:18.730 --> 01:46:22.393
between slave states and free states was at risk.

01:46:23.519 --> 01:46:26.102
(tense music)

01:46:27.280 --> 01:46:31.900
Since the first African slaves arrived in Virginia in 1619,

01:46:31.900 --> 01:46:34.420
the institution of slavery had grown more

01:46:34.420 --> 01:46:36.040
and more ingrained in the culture

01:46:36.040 --> 01:46:40.300
and economy of the United States, particularly in the South.

01:46:40.300 --> 01:46:42.520
While the United States government had abolished

01:46:42.520 --> 01:46:44.650
the slave trade in 1808,

01:46:44.650 --> 01:46:46.210
it had introduced a form

01:46:46.210 --> 01:46:48.700
of chattel slavery within its borders,

01:46:48.700 --> 01:46:53.080
ensuring generations of African-Americans remained working.

01:46:53.080 --> 01:46:55.570
While there had been a few slave rebellions

01:46:55.570 --> 01:46:59.080
across the United States in the early 19th century,

01:46:59.080 --> 01:47:02.500
including Nat Turner's 1831 Rebellion,

01:47:02.500 --> 01:47:03.940
none had succeeded.

01:47:03.940 --> 01:47:05.740
Through the early 19th century,

01:47:05.740 --> 01:47:08.560
some slaves attempted to escape and fled north,

01:47:08.560 --> 01:47:11.860
hoping to find sanctuary in the pro-abolition states

01:47:11.860 --> 01:47:14.230
of the Northeast, or in Canada.

01:47:14.230 --> 01:47:16.990
They traveled north on a series of secret routes

01:47:16.990 --> 01:47:20.620
to known abolitionist locations and safe houses.

01:47:20.620 --> 01:47:22.750
Known as the Underground Railroad,

01:47:22.750 --> 01:47:25.030
the pathway north was dangerous

01:47:25.030 --> 01:47:27.910
and those brave enough to flee bondage were aided

01:47:27.910 --> 01:47:31.630
by fellow escaped slaves, freed men and women,

01:47:31.630 --> 01:47:34.300
and anti-slavery sympathizers.

01:47:34.300 --> 01:47:37.180
One such individual was Harriet Tubman.

01:47:37.180 --> 01:47:40.960
Tubman had escaped slavery herself in 1849

01:47:40.960 --> 01:47:42.340
and spent many years

01:47:42.340 --> 01:47:45.940
after aiding more than 70 slaves escaping slavery

01:47:45.940 --> 01:47:46.870
in the South.

01:47:46.870 --> 01:47:49.150
As the issue of slavery pressed closer

01:47:49.150 --> 01:47:51.070
and closer to a breaking point,

01:47:51.070 --> 01:47:54.280
so too the did the tension within the federal government.

01:47:54.280 --> 01:47:58.390
In 1854, South Carolina Congressman Preston Brooks

01:47:58.390 --> 01:48:02.140
caned Massachusetts Senator Charles Sumner on the floor

01:48:02.140 --> 01:48:03.010
of the Senate.

01:48:03.010 --> 01:48:06.010
Pro-slavery sympathizers from around the country

01:48:06.010 --> 01:48:09.100
sent Brooks new canes congratulating him.

01:48:09.100 --> 01:48:12.010
Abolitionists saw the public attack as the embodiment

01:48:12.010 --> 01:48:15.100
of the control the South seemed to have over the country.

01:48:15.100 --> 01:48:18.220
Could they simply do whatever they wanted and expect nothing

01:48:18.220 --> 01:48:20.050
but compromise in return?

01:48:20.050 --> 01:48:23.680
The polarization of the country was made perfectly clear

01:48:23.680 --> 01:48:25.360
as a result of the incident.

01:48:25.360 --> 01:48:27.340
It had taken years of agreements

01:48:27.340 --> 01:48:29.980
and compromises to come to this stalemate.

01:48:29.980 --> 01:48:32.950
In 1820, the Missouri Compromise declared

01:48:32.950 --> 01:48:35.470
that Missouri would be a new slave state

01:48:35.470 --> 01:48:37.480
and Maine is a new free state,

01:48:37.480 --> 01:48:39.700
and that slavery would be prohibited north

01:48:39.700 --> 01:48:41.470
of the southern boundary of Missouri

01:48:41.470 --> 01:48:44.140
in the rest of the Louisiana Purchase.

01:48:44.140 --> 01:48:46.900
The fragile balance was preserved.

01:48:46.900 --> 01:48:50.110
Texas joined in 1844 as a slave state,

01:48:50.110 --> 01:48:54.190
and Oregon was admitted in 1846 as a free state.

01:48:54.190 --> 01:48:57.550
When the US won more than one million square miles

01:48:57.550 --> 01:48:59.170
of territory from Mexico

01:48:59.170 --> 01:49:03.250
as a result of the Mexican-American War in 1848,

01:49:03.250 --> 01:49:06.430
volatile debate occurred over whether the new territories

01:49:06.430 --> 01:49:07.900
would allow slavery.

01:49:07.900 --> 01:49:11.770
The US gained all of present day, California, Texas,

01:49:11.770 --> 01:49:16.240
Colorado, Arizona, New Mexico, Nevada, and Utah

01:49:16.240 --> 01:49:17.920
as a result of that fight.

01:49:17.920 --> 01:49:19.630
The resulting agreements said

01:49:19.630 --> 01:49:22.930
that California would be a free state and the slave trade,

01:49:22.930 --> 01:49:27.040
but not slavery would be abolished in Washington, DC.

01:49:27.040 --> 01:49:30.250
But a new fugitive slave act would enable Southerners

01:49:30.250 --> 01:49:32.260
to reclaim runaway slaves

01:49:32.260 --> 01:49:35.170
who had escaped across borders to free states.

01:49:35.170 --> 01:49:37.840
The agreement allowed the rest of the areas to determine

01:49:37.840 --> 01:49:40.660
for themselves whether to to allow slavery.

01:49:40.660 --> 01:49:43.450
In 1854, two new states,

01:49:43.450 --> 01:49:45.460
Kansas and Nebraska were set

01:49:45.460 --> 01:49:48.670
to be established in the Louisiana Purchase area,

01:49:48.670 --> 01:49:50.620
but Southern legislators objected

01:49:50.620 --> 01:49:53.740
because according to the terms of the Missouri Compromise,

01:49:53.740 --> 01:49:55.510
both states would be free.

01:49:55.510 --> 01:49:58.810
A new compromise called for popular sovereignty

01:49:58.810 --> 01:50:02.080
or once again, allowing the settlers of the territories

01:50:02.080 --> 01:50:04.600
to determine the question for themselves.

01:50:04.600 --> 01:50:05.860
The battle for Kansas

01:50:05.860 --> 01:50:09.550
and Nebraska came to embody the soul of the nation.

01:50:09.550 --> 01:50:11.380
People flooded to the territories

01:50:11.380 --> 01:50:13.090
and tried to influence the vote,

01:50:13.090 --> 01:50:14.980
many of them voting illegally.

01:50:14.980 --> 01:50:18.100
Soon Kansas spiraled into civil war,

01:50:18.100 --> 01:50:20.200
a conflict that killed hundreds

01:50:20.200 --> 01:50:23.320
and which became known as Bleeding Kansas.

01:50:23.320 --> 01:50:25.840
Among those who had joined in the violence was one

01:50:25.840 --> 01:50:28.030
of the most notorious freedom fighters

01:50:28.030 --> 01:50:30.940
in American history, John Brown.

01:50:30.940 --> 01:50:32.920
Brown was a radical preacher

01:50:32.920 --> 01:50:35.200
and a staunch abolitionist.

01:50:35.200 --> 01:50:37.060
He had, on multiple occasions,

01:50:37.060 --> 01:50:39.850
attempted to incite an armed slave rebellion,

01:50:39.850 --> 01:50:43.450
and in Kansas, ramped up the violence to such an extent

01:50:43.450 --> 01:50:46.750
that he and his followers hacked five Kansan slave owners

01:50:46.750 --> 01:50:49.030
to death with broadswords.

01:50:49.030 --> 01:50:52.000
Brown then began planning a raid on Harpers Ferry

01:50:52.000 --> 01:50:55.120
in Virginia, hoping to once again inspire

01:50:55.120 --> 01:50:56.920
the enslaved peoples of the South

01:50:56.920 --> 01:50:59.350
to rise up against their oppressors.

01:50:59.350 --> 01:51:01.180
He planned on capturing the armory

01:51:01.180 --> 01:51:03.670
and arsenal in Harpers Ferry in addition

01:51:03.670 --> 01:51:07.000
to the rifle factory in order to arm his rebellion.

01:51:07.000 --> 01:51:10.540
Brown's raid commenced in October, 1859,

01:51:10.540 --> 01:51:13.900
and was swiftly put down by the United States Army.

01:51:13.900 --> 01:51:18.280
The US forces, led by a young colonel named Robert E. Lee,

01:51:18.280 --> 01:51:21.670
quickly surrounded the engine house Brown's men had occupied

01:51:21.670 --> 01:51:24.010
and after Brown refused to surrender,

01:51:24.010 --> 01:51:25.840
took the building by force.

01:51:25.840 --> 01:51:28.360
Brown was tried and executed for treason

01:51:28.360 --> 01:51:30.850
by the State of Virginia, and in so doing,

01:51:30.850 --> 01:51:34.630
became a martyr for anti-slave forces around the country.

01:51:34.630 --> 01:51:36.520
Brown's raid on Harpers Ferry was

01:51:36.520 --> 01:51:38.650
a defining moment for the country.

01:51:38.650 --> 01:51:40.510
It seemed now inevitable

01:51:40.510 --> 01:51:42.700
that there would be some great conflict

01:51:42.700 --> 01:51:44.800
to decide the fate of the nation.

01:51:44.800 --> 01:51:48.730
The election of 1860 was the final straw for the South.

01:51:48.730 --> 01:51:51.850
Republican presidential candidate, Abraham Lincoln,

01:51:51.850 --> 01:51:54.550
ran on a platform of liberal policies,

01:51:54.550 --> 01:51:56.380
which included raising tariffs,

01:51:56.380 --> 01:51:59.920
infrastructure improvements, and expanding the railroads.

01:51:59.920 --> 01:52:01.660
While Lincoln was an abolitionist

01:52:01.660 --> 01:52:03.940
and vehemently opposed slavery,

01:52:03.940 --> 01:52:05.350
he understood that the issue

01:52:05.350 --> 01:52:08.020
would inevitably tear the country apart

01:52:08.020 --> 01:52:11.440
and had initially promised to do everything in his power

01:52:11.440 --> 01:52:14.260
to keep the South from breaking away from the Union.

01:52:14.260 --> 01:52:16.240
Lincoln's election to the presidency,

01:52:16.240 --> 01:52:18.940
however, was enough for some Southern States

01:52:18.940 --> 01:52:20.020
to make the break.

01:52:20.020 --> 01:52:23.800
In December, 1860, South Carolina led the charge

01:52:23.800 --> 01:52:26.020
and seceded from the United States.

01:52:26.020 --> 01:52:28.360
Other Southern States quickly followed

01:52:28.360 --> 01:52:30.790
and sitting President James Buchanan faced

01:52:30.790 --> 01:52:32.680
a growing disaster.

01:52:32.680 --> 01:52:34.300
As Southern States seceded,

01:52:34.300 --> 01:52:36.370
they began to confiscate federal forts

01:52:36.370 --> 01:52:39.580
and arsenals which belonged to the United States Military.

01:52:39.580 --> 01:52:42.940
One such location was Fort Sumter in South Carolina.

01:52:42.940 --> 01:52:44.890
President Buchanan had been unwilling

01:52:44.890 --> 01:52:46.600
to resupply the garrison,

01:52:46.600 --> 01:52:48.430
and when Lincoln took office,

01:52:48.430 --> 01:52:51.220
he faced a near impossible decision.

01:52:51.220 --> 01:52:54.100
Lincoln, unwilling to surrender an American fort

01:52:54.100 --> 01:52:57.040
to the rebels or recognized their authority,

01:52:57.040 --> 01:52:59.740
sent a letter to the governor of South Carolina,

01:52:59.740 --> 01:53:02.080
informing him that a ship carrying food,

01:53:02.080 --> 01:53:05.710
but no ammunition would attempt to resupply the fort.

01:53:05.710 --> 01:53:08.200
This allowed Lincoln in the satisfaction of knowing

01:53:08.200 --> 01:53:10.510
that if the South fired on the fort,

01:53:10.510 --> 01:53:13.360
they would be the aggressor in any conflict,

01:53:13.360 --> 01:53:15.880
and if they did not, he would've made strides

01:53:15.880 --> 01:53:19.660
in negotiating with the rebels, as well as holding the fort.

01:53:19.660 --> 01:53:21.160
It was not to be.

01:53:21.160 --> 01:53:22.450
On the 9th of April,

01:53:22.450 --> 01:53:24.580
Confederate President Jefferson Davis

01:53:24.580 --> 01:53:27.370
ordered General P.T.G. Beauregard

01:53:27.370 --> 01:53:30.193
to take the fort before the supplies would arrive.

01:53:32.709 --> 01:53:35.916
(suspenseful music)

01:53:35.916 --> 01:53:38.350
On April 12th, 1861,

01:53:38.350 --> 01:53:40.720
the standoff finally erupted when Beauregard

01:53:40.720 --> 01:53:43.600
at last opened fire on Fort Sumter.

01:53:43.600 --> 01:53:46.330
The bombardment lasted 34 hours

01:53:46.330 --> 01:53:49.420
with more than 4,000 shells fired.

01:53:49.420 --> 01:53:51.790
Despite the ferocity of the bombardment,

01:53:51.790 --> 01:53:55.390
not a single union soldier was killed during the action.

01:53:55.390 --> 01:53:59.080
At 2:30 PM on April 13th, 1861,

01:53:59.080 --> 01:54:01.810
they surrendered the fort under agreeable terms

01:54:01.810 --> 01:54:03.940
and marched from the fort carrying the flag

01:54:03.940 --> 01:54:05.590
which had endured the battle.

01:54:05.590 --> 01:54:07.900
For Lincoln, the loss of Fort Sumter was

01:54:07.900 --> 01:54:09.970
a kind of symbolic victory.

01:54:09.970 --> 01:54:12.130
While losing the fort was not ideal,

01:54:12.130 --> 01:54:15.640
the public in the North rallied behind him and the Union.

01:54:15.640 --> 01:54:18.190
States like New Jersey and Delaware which had been,

01:54:18.190 --> 01:54:21.250
for a time, on the fence regarding secession,

01:54:21.250 --> 01:54:24.160
threw their support wholeheartedly toward the Union.

01:54:24.160 --> 01:54:26.950
Lincoln used the momentum carried by the battle to call

01:54:26.950 --> 01:54:29.620
for 75,000 volunteers

01:54:29.620 --> 01:54:31.930
willing to help restore order in the South

01:54:31.930 --> 01:54:34.810
and return these secessionist states to the Union.

01:54:34.810 --> 01:54:36.580
The North answered the call,

01:54:36.580 --> 01:54:39.610
and in days, the rinks were beginning to fill.

01:54:39.610 --> 01:54:42.010
In Ohio, so many men volunteered

01:54:42.010 --> 01:54:45.250
that they could have met the full 75,000 volunteers

01:54:45.250 --> 01:54:46.420
on their own.

01:54:46.420 --> 01:54:49.150
In the South, the victory at Fort Sumter did less

01:54:49.150 --> 01:54:50.950
to inspire a call to arms

01:54:50.950 --> 01:54:54.160
than did Lincoln's call for volunteers.

01:54:54.160 --> 01:54:57.880
The call for 75,000 volunteers triggered the secession

01:54:57.880 --> 01:55:02.590
of four additional states, Virginia, Tennessee, Arkansas,

01:55:02.590 --> 01:55:03.940
and North Carolina.

01:55:03.940 --> 01:55:06.550
To the South, it was clear that Lincoln planned

01:55:06.550 --> 01:55:08.050
to use the federal government

01:55:08.050 --> 01:55:10.990
to coerce them back into the Union by blood.

01:55:10.990 --> 01:55:13.240
In the North, it was clear that the South

01:55:13.240 --> 01:55:14.950
had violated the Constitution

01:55:14.950 --> 01:55:17.500
by seceding and it was within the power

01:55:17.500 --> 01:55:20.530
of the federal government to take back the states.

01:55:20.530 --> 01:55:22.330
Again, the question of the power

01:55:22.330 --> 01:55:24.820
of the government created great consternation

01:55:24.820 --> 01:55:27.640
and powerful opinions from both sides.

01:55:27.640 --> 01:55:29.950
Amidst it all remained the question at the heart

01:55:29.950 --> 01:55:31.870
of the war, slavery.

01:55:31.870 --> 01:55:34.360
It was clear now to the leaders of the rebellion

01:55:34.360 --> 01:55:37.510
that if Lincoln had the power to raise an army of volunteers

01:55:37.510 --> 01:55:39.580
to return the states to the Union,

01:55:39.580 --> 01:55:40.750
he could use that power

01:55:40.750 --> 01:55:44.230
to end slavery in the United States for good.

01:55:44.230 --> 01:55:47.560
If the Confederacy did not achieve victory early on,

01:55:47.560 --> 01:55:50.500
there was no chance of success for them in the long run.

01:55:50.500 --> 01:55:53.020
A protracted and costly war may wear

01:55:53.020 --> 01:55:54.670
down the North eventually,

01:55:54.670 --> 01:55:56.590
but the South did not have the means

01:55:56.590 --> 01:55:58.360
to conduct such a conflict,

01:55:58.360 --> 01:56:00.820
nor would they survive if they did.

01:56:00.820 --> 01:56:04.660
General Winfield Scott, the veteran of the war of 1812,

01:56:04.660 --> 01:56:06.490
and the Mexican-American War,

01:56:06.490 --> 01:56:10.210
was given command of Union forces at the onset of the war.

01:56:10.210 --> 01:56:12.460
Scott was an excellent tactician,

01:56:12.460 --> 01:56:15.820
although his experience on the battlefield was outdated,

01:56:15.820 --> 01:56:19.150
he implemented a full-scale naval blockade of the South,

01:56:19.150 --> 01:56:21.160
known as the Anaconda Plan,

01:56:21.160 --> 01:56:23.500
which he hoped would help hasten the end of the war

01:56:23.500 --> 01:56:24.700
by choking the South

01:56:24.700 --> 01:56:27.700
of the many resources it would need to run the war.

01:56:27.700 --> 01:56:29.830
However, goods were still making their way

01:56:29.830 --> 01:56:31.930
into the South through Texas.

01:56:31.930 --> 01:56:33.520
The Union had a clear view

01:56:33.520 --> 01:56:36.310
of their strategic goals from this point forward.

01:56:36.310 --> 01:56:39.550
In the East, defeat the Confederate Army in the field,

01:56:39.550 --> 01:56:42.850
capture major coastal cities along the East Coast,

01:56:42.850 --> 01:56:45.250
and capture the new confederate capital

01:56:45.250 --> 01:56:46.900
in Richmond, Virginia.

01:56:46.900 --> 01:56:49.540
In the West, capture major cities and forts

01:56:49.540 --> 01:56:52.780
along the Mississippi River and cut off Texas

01:56:52.780 --> 01:56:54.460
from the rest of the South.

01:56:54.460 --> 01:56:58.060
For the South, the path to success was on the battlefield.

01:56:58.060 --> 01:57:00.850
There was no way in which the South could match the North

01:57:00.850 --> 01:57:04.390
in terms of industry, manpower, or naval power.

01:57:04.390 --> 01:57:07.030
Aid could come in the form of help from Europe,

01:57:07.030 --> 01:57:10.690
but France and England had abolished slavery decades prior

01:57:10.690 --> 01:57:12.760
and would never meaningfully commit

01:57:12.760 --> 01:57:14.650
to the South during the conflict.

01:57:14.650 --> 01:57:16.930
This meant that the Confederates needed swift

01:57:16.930 --> 01:57:19.600
and decisive victories against the Union,

01:57:19.600 --> 01:57:21.730
possibly on Northern soil.

01:57:21.730 --> 01:57:23.890
If the cost of war was too high,

01:57:23.890 --> 01:57:26.890
the peace Democrats and more moderate Republicans

01:57:26.890 --> 01:57:29.890
in Congress might pull the Union out of the war.

01:57:29.890 --> 01:57:31.990
In the Eastern theater of the war,

01:57:31.990 --> 01:57:35.230
early Confederate successes kept the rebellion alive

01:57:35.230 --> 01:57:38.590
as a revolving door of Union high commanders continued

01:57:38.590 --> 01:57:40.720
to plague the federal forces.

01:57:40.720 --> 01:57:44.050
Confederate General Robert E. Lee, who had declined command

01:57:44.050 --> 01:57:46.750
of Union forces at the war's outbreak in favor

01:57:46.750 --> 01:57:48.970
of supporting his home state of Virginia,

01:57:48.970 --> 01:57:50.710
emerged as the tactical

01:57:50.710 --> 01:57:53.500
and logistical genius behind the survival

01:57:53.500 --> 01:57:56.230
of the Confederate Army of Northern Virginia.

01:57:56.230 --> 01:57:58.900
Lee kept the cause of the Confederacy alive

01:57:58.900 --> 01:58:00.190
as long as his army was

01:58:00.190 --> 01:58:02.410
in the field and responded effectively

01:58:02.410 --> 01:58:04.780
and swiftly to the often cumbersome

01:58:04.780 --> 01:58:07.660
and uncertain Union forces he opposed.

01:58:07.660 --> 01:58:11.380
In the West, Union General Ulysses S. Grant emerged

01:58:11.380 --> 01:58:14.050
as the best chance for the North's success.

01:58:14.050 --> 01:58:15.490
Grant waged a series

01:58:15.490 --> 01:58:18.730
of incredible campaigns against his opponents in the West

01:58:18.730 --> 01:58:21.700
and managed to take control of the Mississippi River,

01:58:21.700 --> 01:58:23.440
putting a wedge between Texas

01:58:23.440 --> 01:58:25.360
and the other Southern States.

01:58:25.360 --> 01:58:28.420
Grant's greatest victory in the West came with the siege

01:58:28.420 --> 01:58:31.930
of Vicksburg ending in July, 1863.

01:58:31.930 --> 01:58:35.140
At the same time, General Lee had invaded Pennsylvania

01:58:35.140 --> 01:58:37.750
in the East with the intention of breaking the spirit

01:58:37.750 --> 01:58:40.750
of the North and forcing Lincoln to surrender.

01:58:40.750 --> 01:58:44.440
Instead, he was soundly defeated at the Battle of Gettysburg

01:58:44.440 --> 01:58:46.660
by Union General George Meade.

01:58:46.660 --> 01:58:48.610
Between Lee's defeated Gettysburg

01:58:48.610 --> 01:58:50.680
and Grants victory at Vicksburg,

01:58:50.680 --> 01:58:53.230
the high tide of the Confederacy was over.

01:58:53.230 --> 01:58:56.320
In 1862, after the Battle of Antietam,

01:58:56.320 --> 01:58:59.590
Lincoln issued the Emancipation Proclamation,

01:58:59.590 --> 01:59:02.470
claiming that slavery was abolished within those parts

01:59:02.470 --> 01:59:05.290
of the country, which had rebelled against the Union

01:59:05.290 --> 01:59:06.790
and allowed the Union Army

01:59:06.790 --> 01:59:09.310
to take on any slaves found in the South

01:59:09.310 --> 01:59:10.720
and bring them north.

01:59:10.720 --> 01:59:13.480
Lincoln in the War Department authorized the raising

01:59:13.480 --> 01:59:14.650
of Black troops,

01:59:14.650 --> 01:59:17.620
known as Colored Troops during the Civil War.

01:59:17.620 --> 01:59:19.630
While the war had to begun for Lincoln

01:59:19.630 --> 01:59:23.080
as a means to reunite the country, as it progressed,

01:59:23.080 --> 01:59:25.300
he struck at the heart of the conflict

01:59:25.300 --> 01:59:27.610
and shifted the war goals beyond simply

01:59:27.610 --> 01:59:29.530
a return to the status quo.

01:59:29.530 --> 01:59:31.690
Lincoln believed slavery could not

01:59:31.690 --> 01:59:34.510
and would no longer exist within the borders

01:59:34.510 --> 01:59:36.130
of the United States

01:59:36.130 --> 01:59:39.010
and organized his party to begin working on amendments

01:59:39.010 --> 01:59:41.560
to the Constitution to make it so.

01:59:41.560 --> 01:59:45.040
Grant was given command of the entire Union Army

01:59:45.040 --> 01:59:48.220
and was moved to command the Eastern Theater of the war.

01:59:48.220 --> 01:59:50.890
He left General William Tecumseh Sherman

01:59:50.890 --> 01:59:52.747
in command of the Western Theater,

01:59:52.747 --> 01:59:56.530
and the two began to prosecute total war against the South.

01:59:56.530 --> 01:59:58.960
Grant threw his army repeatedly at Lee,

01:59:58.960 --> 02:00:01.660
forcing engagement after engagement.

02:00:01.660 --> 02:00:03.940
While Lee did win several battles,

02:00:03.940 --> 02:00:06.730
they were battles he could not afford to fight.

02:00:06.730 --> 02:00:09.700
And even when Grand lost, he moved swiftly,

02:00:09.700 --> 02:00:11.350
unlike his predecessors,

02:00:11.350 --> 02:00:13.750
and immediately got back into the fray.

02:00:13.750 --> 02:00:15.940
In the West, Sherman moved south,

02:00:15.940 --> 02:00:18.550
cutting through the South toward Atlanta, Georgia,

02:00:18.550 --> 02:00:21.850
leaving a path of devastation in his wake.

02:00:21.850 --> 02:00:24.970
Atlanta was burned as Confederate forces fled

02:00:24.970 --> 02:00:26.470
before Sherman's army,

02:00:26.470 --> 02:00:29.110
unable to stop the Union juggernaut.

02:00:29.110 --> 02:00:33.520
Sherman marched his armies to Savannah by Christmas of 1864

02:00:33.520 --> 02:00:35.350
and presented the captured city

02:00:35.350 --> 02:00:37.780
to President Lincoln as a gift.

02:00:37.780 --> 02:00:41.620
In spring 1865, Lee was finally defeated

02:00:41.620 --> 02:00:44.380
for the last time at Appomattox Court House

02:00:44.380 --> 02:00:48.250
and surrendered to Grant on April 9th, 1865.

02:00:48.250 --> 02:00:50.800
Sherman continued to chase the Confederate forces

02:00:50.800 --> 02:00:52.270
in the Carolinas North

02:00:52.270 --> 02:00:55.300
until they too surrendered shortly thereafter.

02:00:55.300 --> 02:00:58.600
After four years and 600,000 lives lost,

02:00:58.600 --> 02:01:01.690
the Civil War was at last over.

02:01:01.690 --> 02:01:02.770
Before it had ended,

02:01:02.770 --> 02:01:05.440
Lincoln had successfully managed to convince Congress

02:01:05.440 --> 02:01:08.380
to pass the Thirteenth Amendment to the Constitution

02:01:08.380 --> 02:01:13.030
in January, 1865, officially abolishing slavery

02:01:13.030 --> 02:01:14.800
in the United States.

02:01:14.800 --> 02:01:16.870
Lincoln advocated for peace

02:01:16.870 --> 02:01:18.850
and hoped that the reconstruction period

02:01:18.850 --> 02:01:22.540
that would inevitably follow would be guided, not by malice,

02:01:22.540 --> 02:01:24.640
but by a sense of unity.

02:01:24.640 --> 02:01:26.260
The country was optimistic

02:01:26.260 --> 02:01:28.480
that Lincoln would be the one to lead them.

02:01:28.480 --> 02:01:29.980
It was not to be.

02:01:29.980 --> 02:01:33.670
Abraham Lincoln, the 16th president of the United States,

02:01:33.670 --> 02:01:36.280
was assassinated by John Wilkes Booth,

02:01:36.280 --> 02:01:38.440
a radical Southern supporter,

02:01:38.440 --> 02:01:41.023
and died on the morning of April 15th, 1865.

02:01:42.790 --> 02:01:44.200
Booth was hunted down

02:01:44.200 --> 02:01:45.940
and killed during the manhunt,

02:01:45.940 --> 02:01:48.130
while his co-conspirators were rounded up

02:01:48.130 --> 02:01:50.080
ad executed for treason.

02:01:50.080 --> 02:01:52.780
The country mourned the loss of their leader

02:01:52.780 --> 02:01:55.570
and the fate of reconstruction was left in the hands

02:01:55.570 --> 02:01:58.690
of Lincoln's Vice President Andrew Johnson.

02:01:58.690 --> 02:02:00.550
Reconstruction began immediately

02:02:00.550 --> 02:02:02.380
after the end of the Civil War

02:02:02.380 --> 02:02:06.280
and the South was separated into five military districts.

02:02:06.280 --> 02:02:08.980
These districts were occupied by US troops

02:02:08.980 --> 02:02:10.960
in order to help reestablish law

02:02:10.960 --> 02:02:12.820
and order in the region as well

02:02:12.820 --> 02:02:15.460
as enforce the new laws of reconstruction.

02:02:15.460 --> 02:02:17.290
Over the course of five years,

02:02:17.290 --> 02:02:19.060
the Congress successfully passed

02:02:19.060 --> 02:02:21.790
an additional two constitutional amendments

02:02:21.790 --> 02:02:23.080
to secure the rights

02:02:23.080 --> 02:02:26.740
of the now free Black citizens of the United States.

02:02:26.740 --> 02:02:29.050
The first, the Fourteenth Amendment,

02:02:29.050 --> 02:02:32.020
granted the right of citizenship to all those born

02:02:32.020 --> 02:02:33.730
within the United States,

02:02:33.730 --> 02:02:35.905
and granted those citizens the right

02:02:35.905 --> 02:02:38.290
of equal protection under the law.

02:02:38.290 --> 02:02:40.570
The second, the Fifteenth Amendment,

02:02:40.570 --> 02:02:44.140
guaranteed citizens the right to vote, regardless of race,

02:02:44.140 --> 02:02:47.620
color, or previous condition of servitude.

02:02:47.620 --> 02:02:50.500
The resentment of many individuals in both North

02:02:50.500 --> 02:02:53.830
and South grew as the US Government expanded the rights

02:02:53.830 --> 02:02:56.650
and liberties of Black Americans to match those

02:02:56.650 --> 02:02:58.180
of white Americans.

02:02:58.180 --> 02:03:00.460
Especially in regions deeply affected

02:03:00.460 --> 02:03:02.350
by the Civil War in the South,

02:03:02.350 --> 02:03:04.720
groups of white supremacists rose up

02:03:04.720 --> 02:03:07.360
and formed several hate organizations such

02:03:07.360 --> 02:03:08.920
as the Ku Klux Klan,

02:03:08.920 --> 02:03:12.460
or the KKK, which targeted Black Americans

02:03:12.460 --> 02:03:15.610
and other individuals who favored reconstruction.

02:03:15.610 --> 02:03:18.460
In 1868, Ulysses S. Grant,

02:03:18.460 --> 02:03:22.030
hero of the Civil War, was elected the 18th president

02:03:22.030 --> 02:03:26.470
of the United States and took office in March, 1869.

02:03:26.470 --> 02:03:29.230
Grant committed much of his early years as president

02:03:29.230 --> 02:03:32.170
to Lincoln's original goals of reconstruction,

02:03:32.170 --> 02:03:35.260
signing numerous acts ensuring naturalization

02:03:35.260 --> 02:03:37.570
and equal rights of Black citizens.

02:03:37.570 --> 02:03:38.830
To enforce these acts

02:03:38.830 --> 02:03:41.110
and the new constitutional amendments,

02:03:41.110 --> 02:03:43.300
he created the Justice Department

02:03:43.300 --> 02:03:47.440
and wielded the US Military to stamp out the KKK

02:03:47.440 --> 02:03:50.470
and other white supremacist organizations.

02:03:50.470 --> 02:03:53.080
Sadly, Grant's presidency was wrought

02:03:53.080 --> 02:03:55.000
with political turmoil from both

02:03:55.000 --> 02:03:57.550
within his own party and without.

02:03:57.550 --> 02:03:59.230
The newly reformed governments

02:03:59.230 --> 02:04:01.270
of these Southern States lashed out

02:04:01.270 --> 02:04:03.040
at the reconstruction laws

02:04:03.040 --> 02:04:06.340
and continuously caused issues during elections.

02:04:06.340 --> 02:04:09.010
Grant found his hands tied as his second term came

02:04:09.010 --> 02:04:11.620
to an end and the country began its return

02:04:11.620 --> 02:04:14.770
to stalemate and compromise as the economic

02:04:14.770 --> 02:04:17.410
and business interests of both parties began

02:04:17.410 --> 02:04:20.743
to usurp the social crises of reconstruction.

02:04:22.488 --> 02:04:26.170
(suspenseful music)

02:04:26.170 --> 02:04:28.360
With the end of the American Civil War

02:04:28.360 --> 02:04:31.390
and the question of slavery at last resolved,

02:04:31.390 --> 02:04:34.000
many people within the United States continued

02:04:34.000 --> 02:04:36.670
the exodus out West in the footsteps

02:04:36.670 --> 02:04:39.700
of the early 19th century pioneers.

02:04:39.700 --> 02:04:41.020
With the territories along

02:04:41.020 --> 02:04:43.390
the West Coast fairly well established

02:04:43.390 --> 02:04:46.510
and a growing number of cities dotting the Midwest,

02:04:46.510 --> 02:04:49.210
moving away from the chaos of the East Coast

02:04:49.210 --> 02:04:51.730
and the memory of the war was appealing.

02:04:51.730 --> 02:04:54.520
Access to the West had only grown over the course

02:04:54.520 --> 02:04:57.490
of the mid 19th century with the introduction

02:04:57.490 --> 02:04:59.590
of the transcontinental railroad.

02:04:59.590 --> 02:05:02.560
From 1863 to 1869,

02:05:02.560 --> 02:05:05.980
a transcontinental railroad was built to connect the Eastern

02:05:05.980 --> 02:05:08.140
and Western coasts of the US.

02:05:08.140 --> 02:05:11.950
The very first steam train had debuted in 1830,

02:05:11.950 --> 02:05:16.950
and by 1850, more than 9,000 miles of track had been laid.

02:05:17.020 --> 02:05:20.380
In 1860, it was decided that the mountain pass

02:05:20.380 --> 02:05:23.410
where the Donner Party had been trapped was an ideal place

02:05:23.410 --> 02:05:24.970
for a railroad to cut through

02:05:24.970 --> 02:05:27.130
the Sierra Nevada mountains.

02:05:27.130 --> 02:05:29.140
When President Abraham Lincoln signed

02:05:29.140 --> 02:05:31.150
the Pacific Railroad Act into law

02:05:31.150 --> 02:05:34.480
in 1862, construction commenced.

02:05:34.480 --> 02:05:36.640
Though railroad workers suffered attacks

02:05:36.640 --> 02:05:38.950
from members of the Sioux, Arapaho,

02:05:38.950 --> 02:05:42.190
and Cheyenne tribes as they progressed across the land.

02:05:42.190 --> 02:05:43.780
Wherever the railroad went,

02:05:43.780 --> 02:05:46.540
ramshackle settlements of the sort immortalized

02:05:46.540 --> 02:05:49.630
and Wild West culture were soon to follow.

02:05:49.630 --> 02:05:52.960
These places were hotbeds for drinking, gambling,

02:05:52.960 --> 02:05:55.540
prostitution, and violence.

02:05:55.540 --> 02:05:58.600
When construction of the transcontinental railroad finished

02:05:58.600 --> 02:06:02.530
at Promontory Summit, north of the Great Salt Lake in Utah,

02:06:02.530 --> 02:06:03.910
a final spike made

02:06:03.910 --> 02:06:08.440
of 17.6 karat gold was ceremoniously driven into the ground

02:06:08.440 --> 02:06:11.530
before a crowd of workers and dignitaries.

02:06:11.530 --> 02:06:13.210
With the railroad's completion,

02:06:13.210 --> 02:06:16.420
the travel time for making the 3,000 mile journey

02:06:16.420 --> 02:06:19.390
across the United States was cut from months

02:06:19.390 --> 02:06:21.280
to under a week.

02:06:21.280 --> 02:06:24.340
This made the economic export of Western resources

02:06:24.340 --> 02:06:26.320
to Eastern markets easier

02:06:26.320 --> 02:06:29.020
and increased the speed of westward expansion.

02:06:29.020 --> 02:06:32.170
As settlers entered newly accessible territories,

02:06:32.170 --> 02:06:34.810
conflicts with Native Americans increased.

02:06:34.810 --> 02:06:36.670
During this time, the exploits,

02:06:36.670 --> 02:06:38.650
both real and exaggerated,

02:06:38.650 --> 02:06:42.910
of notorious outlaws gained perpetrators infamy at the time

02:06:42.910 --> 02:06:45.160
and an enduring legacy today.

02:06:45.160 --> 02:06:48.730
Wyatt Earp, former Marshall of Dodge City, Kansas,

02:06:48.730 --> 02:06:52.840
moved to Tombstone, Arizona territory in 1879

02:06:52.840 --> 02:06:54.670
with several of his brothers in search

02:06:54.670 --> 02:06:56.740
of riches from this silver boom.

02:06:56.740 --> 02:06:58.990
While there, the Earps ran into a gang

02:06:58.990 --> 02:07:03.220
of outlaws called The Cowboys, led by Ike Clanton.

02:07:03.220 --> 02:07:05.980
The Earps all had law enforcement backgrounds

02:07:05.980 --> 02:07:09.670
with Virgil Earp acting as both town marshal for Tombstone

02:07:09.670 --> 02:07:12.250
and as a deputy US marshal.

02:07:12.250 --> 02:07:15.700
They teamed up with the temporary policeman, Doc Holiday.

02:07:15.700 --> 02:07:19.240
The lawman had a longstanding feud with the Clanton gang.

02:07:19.240 --> 02:07:22.210
But things came to a head when Virgil made the decision

02:07:22.210 --> 02:07:24.070
to enforce a city ordinance,

02:07:24.070 --> 02:07:26.530
prohibiting carrying weapons in town,

02:07:26.530 --> 02:07:30.160
which meant disarming the gun-toting Cowboys.

02:07:30.160 --> 02:07:33.850
This intervention led to the shootout at the O.K. Corral,

02:07:33.850 --> 02:07:38.050
a 30-second gunfight that nevertheless became symbolic

02:07:38.050 --> 02:07:40.420
of the Old West, a time when the frontier

02:07:40.420 --> 02:07:42.880
was virtually lawless as a consequence

02:07:42.880 --> 02:07:45.400
of lawman being spread incredibly thin

02:07:45.400 --> 02:07:47.353
over vast territories.

02:07:48.829 --> 02:07:52.300
(ominous music)

02:07:52.300 --> 02:07:54.040
The beginning of the Gilded Age,

02:07:54.040 --> 02:07:57.280
a period characterized as much by wealth and abundance

02:07:57.280 --> 02:08:01.420
as by poverty and corruption was in fact a notable ending.

02:08:01.420 --> 02:08:05.380
The year 1877 marked the end of reconstruction

02:08:05.380 --> 02:08:08.170
and therefore an end to one of the greatest periods

02:08:08.170 --> 02:08:11.230
of civil rights reform in the country's history.

02:08:11.230 --> 02:08:12.970
Efforts by the federal government

02:08:12.970 --> 02:08:15.880
to help protect the rights given to African Americans

02:08:15.880 --> 02:08:18.610
after the end of the Civil War were abandoned

02:08:18.610 --> 02:08:20.800
as a result of a compromise struck

02:08:20.800 --> 02:08:24.070
to settle the contested 1876 election

02:08:24.070 --> 02:08:27.460
between Rutherford B. Hayes and Samuel Tilden.

02:08:27.460 --> 02:08:31.210
Hayes, a North Republican, was granted the presidency

02:08:31.210 --> 02:08:33.280
and reconstruction was ended.

02:08:33.280 --> 02:08:35.710
Federal troops were withdrawn from the South,

02:08:35.710 --> 02:08:39.100
no longer interfering to protect African American civil

02:08:39.100 --> 02:08:40.750
and political rights.

02:08:40.750 --> 02:08:43.570
The systemic violence, disenfranchisement,

02:08:43.570 --> 02:08:45.850
and oppression that followed would persist

02:08:45.850 --> 02:08:50.050
for more than a century and come to be called Jim Crow,

02:08:50.050 --> 02:08:52.720
as the federal government gave up on its promise

02:08:52.720 --> 02:08:56.260
to give free Black men the rights of citizens in the South.

02:08:56.260 --> 02:09:00.190
Sharecropping and low-wage work, such as domestic servitude

02:09:00.190 --> 02:09:02.620
were some of the only options available

02:09:02.620 --> 02:09:04.450
to freed people in the South.

02:09:04.450 --> 02:09:07.030
But depending on who you were, what you looked like,

02:09:07.030 --> 02:09:08.680
and where in the country you were,

02:09:08.680 --> 02:09:13.390
economic opportunity could abound in Gilded Age America.

02:09:13.390 --> 02:09:16.000
Cheap land and relatively high wages compared

02:09:16.000 --> 02:09:17.890
to other parts of the world drew

02:09:17.890 --> 02:09:20.050
in immigrants by the millions.

02:09:20.050 --> 02:09:23.320
Between 1877 and 1900,

02:09:23.320 --> 02:09:27.160
approximately 7.3 million people immigrated

02:09:27.160 --> 02:09:28.960
into the United States.

02:09:28.960 --> 02:09:33.130
Prior to 1880, most came from Western Europe and China,

02:09:33.130 --> 02:09:35.140
but closer to the turn of the century,

02:09:35.140 --> 02:09:38.410
more immigrants came from Southern and Eastern Europe.

02:09:38.410 --> 02:09:40.240
They settled in every area

02:09:40.240 --> 02:09:42.580
of the country in large numbers except

02:09:42.580 --> 02:09:45.220
for the economically devastated South.

02:09:45.220 --> 02:09:47.230
But their appearance triggered political

02:09:47.230 --> 02:09:49.300
and social backlash from Americans

02:09:49.300 --> 02:09:51.820
who felt their white Protestant country

02:09:51.820 --> 02:09:53.260
was being threatened.

02:09:53.260 --> 02:09:56.140
Movements to resist certain types of immigrants,

02:09:56.140 --> 02:09:59.920
including Catholics, Jews, and Chinese gained momentum.

02:09:59.920 --> 02:10:02.560
In the West, sentiments against Chinese workers

02:10:02.560 --> 02:10:04.480
were particularly hostile

02:10:04.480 --> 02:10:06.250
and mobs were known to gather

02:10:06.250 --> 02:10:08.650
and attack Chinese people living in areas

02:10:08.650 --> 02:10:11.800
of Wyoming and Washington, driving them out.

02:10:11.800 --> 02:10:14.050
Congress restricted Chinese immigration

02:10:14.050 --> 02:10:17.020
to the US, beginning in 1892,

02:10:17.020 --> 02:10:19.030
continuing to uphold the policy

02:10:19.030 --> 02:10:23.590
until a permanent exclusion policy was enacted in 1902.

02:10:23.590 --> 02:10:27.280
Fear of minority groups festered among white Americans

02:10:27.280 --> 02:10:29.410
after the reconstruction period

02:10:29.410 --> 02:10:31.780
and was only further fueled by the influx

02:10:31.780 --> 02:10:35.560
of immigration, leading to anti-democratic efforts

02:10:35.560 --> 02:10:38.050
to restrict certain groups from voting.

02:10:38.050 --> 02:10:40.270
As immigrants flooded into the country,

02:10:40.270 --> 02:10:41.800
many of them went west.

02:10:41.800 --> 02:10:46.030
As a result of the Homestead and Railroad Acts of 1862,

02:10:46.030 --> 02:10:49.030
the federal government had handed most of the lands owned

02:10:49.030 --> 02:10:52.360
by the Native Americans over to railroad corporations

02:10:52.360 --> 02:10:55.240
and white farmers, including immigrants.

02:10:55.240 --> 02:10:59.050
The Homestead Act did not require American citizenship

02:10:59.050 --> 02:11:02.290
and the railroads sold land grants at low prices.

02:11:02.290 --> 02:11:05.530
Even going so far as to advertise in Europe.

02:11:05.530 --> 02:11:07.510
Advances in technology such

02:11:07.510 --> 02:11:09.550
as improved plow designs,

02:11:09.550 --> 02:11:11.980
meant just one family could officially farm

02:11:11.980 --> 02:11:14.500
a large area of land without need

02:11:14.500 --> 02:11:17.050
for intensive effort, or hired labor.

02:11:17.050 --> 02:11:18.910
But not all farmers were happy.

02:11:18.910 --> 02:11:22.510
Increasingly political movements like populism were drawing

02:11:22.510 --> 02:11:25.450
in hard-pressed wheat farmers of the Midwest

02:11:25.450 --> 02:11:28.000
and resentful white cotton farmers in the South

02:11:28.000 --> 02:11:30.130
who were fed up with wealthy elites,

02:11:30.130 --> 02:11:33.400
monopolistic corporate interests, and gold.

02:11:33.400 --> 02:11:36.580
Nevertheless, farming became so efficient

02:11:36.580 --> 02:11:38.860
that the country was producing more food

02:11:38.860 --> 02:11:42.820
than it could consume, so the excess was exported.

02:11:42.820 --> 02:11:45.760
This was all made possible by the expansion of railroads

02:11:45.760 --> 02:11:48.970
that had occurred in the 1850s and '60s,

02:11:48.970 --> 02:11:51.730
for they made previously inaccessible land

02:11:51.730 --> 02:11:55.270
much more feasible and profitable to work.

02:11:55.270 --> 02:11:58.210
Between 1865 and 1898,

02:11:58.210 --> 02:12:02.410
America's output of wheat increased by 256%,

02:12:02.410 --> 02:12:04.870
corn by 222%,

02:12:04.870 --> 02:12:07.060
coal by 800%,

02:12:07.060 --> 02:12:11.530
and the miles of railway track by 567%.

02:12:11.530 --> 02:12:14.410
The nation's economy revolved around the railroads,

02:12:14.410 --> 02:12:17.560
which trucked commodities like wheat, cattle, silver,

02:12:17.560 --> 02:12:19.540
and timber from place to place.

02:12:19.540 --> 02:12:24.010
The first transcontinental railroad opened in 1869

02:12:24.010 --> 02:12:27.100
and railroads were a rapidly expanding area

02:12:27.100 --> 02:12:28.390
of the new economy.

02:12:28.390 --> 02:12:33.190
By 1890, nearly 800,000 people worked for a railroad.

02:12:33.190 --> 02:12:35.500
However, railway work was poorly paid

02:12:35.500 --> 02:12:37.180
and often dangerous.

02:12:37.180 --> 02:12:39.610
Even as wages were rising and quality of living

02:12:39.610 --> 02:12:42.550
for skilled workers in America was outpacing that

02:12:42.550 --> 02:12:43.870
for those in England,

02:12:43.870 --> 02:12:47.080
mechanization was steadily replacing those skilled workers

02:12:47.080 --> 02:12:49.780
with unskilled ones who could be paid less.

02:12:49.780 --> 02:12:52.480
The distribution of wealth in the Gilded Age America

02:12:52.480 --> 02:12:54.220
was highly unequal

02:12:54.220 --> 02:12:56.200
with the top 10% owning more

02:12:56.200 --> 02:12:58.510
than 3/4 of the nation's wealth.

02:12:58.510 --> 02:13:01.600
This disparity, along with the poor working conditions

02:13:01.600 --> 02:13:04.930
that affected the everyday lives of wage workers

02:13:04.930 --> 02:13:08.920
inspired a number of vicious worker strikes.

02:13:08.920 --> 02:13:13.390
The Great Railroad Strike of 1877 lasted 52 days

02:13:13.390 --> 02:13:16.060
before it had to be put down by federal troops

02:13:16.060 --> 02:13:17.440
and the National Guard,

02:13:17.440 --> 02:13:21.490
but only after the fighting had resulted in over 100 deaths

02:13:21.490 --> 02:13:25.510
and workers having burned several railroad cars and engines.

02:13:25.510 --> 02:13:29.770
Another big railroad strike occurred in 1886 involving more

02:13:29.770 --> 02:13:33.160
than 200,000 labor union workers.

02:13:33.160 --> 02:13:37.750
On May 4th, 1886, a gathering at Haymarket Square in Chicago

02:13:37.750 --> 02:13:41.920
to protest police brutality against striking workers turned

02:13:41.920 --> 02:13:43.810
into a riot when someone threw

02:13:43.810 --> 02:13:47.740
a bomb at police officers trying to disperse the crowd.

02:13:47.740 --> 02:13:50.710
In the ensuing chaos, seven police officers

02:13:50.710 --> 02:13:52.540
and one protestor died.

02:13:52.540 --> 02:13:54.190
Searching for those responsible,

02:13:54.190 --> 02:13:57.400
police in Chicago and elsewhere rounded up radicals,

02:13:57.400 --> 02:14:00.550
labor organizers and anti-capitalist,

02:14:00.550 --> 02:14:02.590
selecting eight men who were tried

02:14:02.590 --> 02:14:05.410
and convicted for the events at Haymarket Square.

02:14:05.410 --> 02:14:07.690
Though some found the trial's evidence to be weak

02:14:07.690 --> 02:14:09.250
and saw the convicted men,

02:14:09.250 --> 02:14:12.730
most of whom were given the death sentence as martyrs.

02:14:12.730 --> 02:14:14.950
For many others, the takeaway from this event

02:14:14.950 --> 02:14:17.560
was heightened anti-labor sentiment.

02:14:17.560 --> 02:14:21.280
Nevertheless, efforts to improve labor rights continued.

02:14:21.280 --> 02:14:25.000
In the Pullman Strike of 1894, widespread striking

02:14:25.000 --> 02:14:27.670
and boycotting severely disrupted rail traffic

02:14:27.670 --> 02:14:28.750
in the Midwest.

02:14:28.750 --> 02:14:31.060
The strike occurred in response to pay cuts

02:14:31.060 --> 02:14:33.850
that the Pullman Palace Railroad Car Company made

02:14:33.850 --> 02:14:36.610
to its workers' already low wages.

02:14:36.610 --> 02:14:39.940
The company did not, however, correspondingly reduce rents

02:14:39.940 --> 02:14:41.860
and other costs in its company's town

02:14:41.860 --> 02:14:44.980
of Pullman, Illinois near Chicago where the majority

02:14:44.980 --> 02:14:47.260
of its workers lived in company housing.

02:14:47.260 --> 02:14:49.360
Workers and their families were starving,

02:14:49.360 --> 02:14:52.930
but the company's president refused to make any changes

02:14:52.930 --> 02:14:55.810
and ordered those that complained to be fired.

02:14:55.810 --> 02:14:57.760
The workers decided to strike.

02:14:57.760 --> 02:15:00.790
Some of the workers belonged to the American Railway Union

02:15:00.790 --> 02:15:03.790
and union delegates found a way to support the strike.

02:15:03.790 --> 02:15:05.830
ARU members across the country

02:15:05.830 --> 02:15:07.660
would boycott the Pullman Company,

02:15:07.660 --> 02:15:10.660
refusing to hitch Pullman-made cars to trains

02:15:10.660 --> 02:15:14.110
and unhitching any Pullman cars already attached.

02:15:14.110 --> 02:15:17.380
The strategy masterminded by ARU president

02:15:17.380 --> 02:15:21.100
and future US Presidential Candidate Eugene V. Debs

02:15:21.100 --> 02:15:25.930
soon had 125,000 workers on 29 railroads

02:15:25.930 --> 02:15:28.960
quitting work rather than handle Pullman cars.

02:15:28.960 --> 02:15:30.790
Some estimates say the number was closer

02:15:30.790 --> 02:15:34.660
to 250,000 workers across 27 states.

02:15:34.660 --> 02:15:37.600
Though the strike was successfully holding up trains,

02:15:37.600 --> 02:15:39.160
workers were still angry,

02:15:39.160 --> 02:15:41.530
and in addition, they set fire to engines

02:15:41.530 --> 02:15:43.780
and engaged in various riots.

02:15:43.780 --> 02:15:47.110
President Grover Cleveland sent federal troops to Chicago

02:15:47.110 --> 02:15:50.260
to quell the violence and obtain the court injunction,

02:15:50.260 --> 02:15:52.990
which said the ARU could no longer communicate

02:15:52.990 --> 02:15:54.520
with any of its members,

02:15:54.520 --> 02:15:57.430
nor do anything to stop its members from working.

02:15:57.430 --> 02:16:00.040
Violence erupted between these striking workers

02:16:00.040 --> 02:16:01.360
and the federal troops,

02:16:01.360 --> 02:16:04.570
culminating July 6th, 1874

02:16:04.570 --> 02:16:07.990
when more than 6,000 rioters destroyed hundreds

02:16:07.990 --> 02:16:11.560
of rail cars in the South Chicago Panhandle yards.

02:16:11.560 --> 02:16:13.330
The strike only finally came

02:16:13.330 --> 02:16:16.960
to an end when the railroad started hiring non-union workers

02:16:16.960 --> 02:16:18.640
to replace those it lost.

02:16:18.640 --> 02:16:20.830
The train started moving again.

02:16:20.830 --> 02:16:23.290
The ordeal had cost the railroads millions

02:16:23.290 --> 02:16:26.440
of dollars in lost revenue and destroyed property,

02:16:26.440 --> 02:16:30.490
and the strikers had lost more than $1 million in wages.

02:16:30.490 --> 02:16:33.940
The Pullman Company was forced to divest its company town,

02:16:33.940 --> 02:16:35.980
which became part of Chicago,

02:16:35.980 --> 02:16:38.980
after the federal government conducted an inquiry

02:16:38.980 --> 02:16:40.480
and called the company's actions

02:16:40.480 --> 02:16:42.730
in the town un-American.

02:16:42.730 --> 02:16:44.500
In the aftermath of the strike,

02:16:44.500 --> 02:16:47.680
in an effort to placate still angry workers,

02:16:47.680 --> 02:16:50.920
the Cleveland Administration designated the first Monday

02:16:50.920 --> 02:16:53.200
in September as a Labor Day,

02:16:53.200 --> 02:16:56.350
but public sentiment had been stirred against the strikers

02:16:56.350 --> 02:16:58.780
who were largely immigrant workers.

02:16:58.780 --> 02:17:01.390
The influx of immigrant workers took advantage

02:17:01.390 --> 02:17:02.380
of the growing number

02:17:02.380 --> 02:17:05.080
of industrial jobs available in cities,

02:17:05.080 --> 02:17:07.810
but these jobs tended to be exploitative

02:17:07.810 --> 02:17:09.280
and low-paying as well,

02:17:09.280 --> 02:17:13.810
even as the country's GDP became the greatest in the world.

02:17:13.810 --> 02:17:17.950
Wealthy Gilded Age moguls such as John D. Rockefeller,

02:17:17.950 --> 02:17:20.830
Andrew Carnegie, Cornelius Vanderbilt,

02:17:20.830 --> 02:17:24.400
and J.P. Morgan were known for their philanthropy,

02:17:24.400 --> 02:17:27.640
but their critics also labeled them robber barons

02:17:27.640 --> 02:17:29.500
for building their empires on the backs

02:17:29.500 --> 02:17:32.350
of an exploited working class using tactics

02:17:32.350 --> 02:17:35.350
like intimidation, union-busting, fraud,

02:17:35.350 --> 02:17:38.530
and monopolies to gain an edge on their competition.

02:17:38.530 --> 02:17:41.950
Muckrakers, or journalists who exposed corruption

02:17:41.950 --> 02:17:44.560
among the elite, helped draw public attention

02:17:44.560 --> 02:17:45.760
to these issues.

02:17:45.760 --> 02:17:49.720
In 1906, Upton Sinclair published "The Jungle,"

02:17:49.720 --> 02:17:52.750
his famous account of the grizzly, dangerous,

02:17:52.750 --> 02:17:56.650
and unsanitary conditions in the meat packing industry,

02:17:56.650 --> 02:18:00.340
which resulted in public outcry and legislation.

02:18:00.340 --> 02:18:02.980
Ida Tarbell wrote a 19-part series

02:18:02.980 --> 02:18:06.490
for McClure Magazine in 1902 about Rockefeller,

02:18:06.490 --> 02:18:09.610
resulting in his Standard Oil company being broken up

02:18:09.610 --> 02:18:11.050
for being a monopoly.

02:18:11.050 --> 02:18:13.150
Meanwhile, as the rich got richer,

02:18:13.150 --> 02:18:15.880
the cities were filling with tenements and slums

02:18:15.880 --> 02:18:17.740
as their populations grew.

02:18:17.740 --> 02:18:21.280
Another muckraker, the Photographer Jacob Riis,

02:18:21.280 --> 02:18:24.040
became famous in 1890 when he published

02:18:24.040 --> 02:18:27.070
a book called "How The Other Half Lives,"

02:18:27.070 --> 02:18:28.570
depicting his photographs

02:18:28.570 --> 02:18:31.840
of New York City slums, which prompted city officials

02:18:31.840 --> 02:18:34.120
to try to improve the conditions there.

02:18:34.120 --> 02:18:37.974
When the Great Blizzard of 1888 dropped between 40

02:18:37.974 --> 02:18:40.780
to 50 inches of snow on the New York area,

02:18:40.780 --> 02:18:44.620
more than 200 people died in New York City alone.

02:18:44.620 --> 02:18:48.700
Most found buried in snow drifts along city sidewalks.

02:18:48.700 --> 02:18:51.580
But in contrast to the extreme poverty,

02:18:51.580 --> 02:18:55.420
technological marvels like new bridges, trolley lines,

02:18:55.420 --> 02:18:59.740
subways, elevators, and skyscrapers were bringing the cities

02:18:59.740 --> 02:19:01.810
into the industrial age.

02:19:01.810 --> 02:19:06.277
Thomas Edison invented a long-lasting light bulb in 1879

02:19:06.277 --> 02:19:08.350
and the Pearl Street Power Station

02:19:08.350 --> 02:19:10.720
was bringing electric light to a small number

02:19:10.720 --> 02:19:12.940
of customers in New York City.

02:19:12.940 --> 02:19:14.890
By the light of the electric light bulb,

02:19:14.890 --> 02:19:18.400
people read newspaper accounts of the Kentucky Meat shower,

02:19:18.400 --> 02:19:22.600
a mysterious event that occurred March 6th, 1876.

02:19:22.600 --> 02:19:25.360
Residents of Olympia Springs, Kentucky were shocked

02:19:25.360 --> 02:19:28.780
to find large chunks of meat falling from the sky,

02:19:28.780 --> 02:19:30.700
which was never fully explained,

02:19:30.700 --> 02:19:32.860
despite attempts to investigate it.

02:19:32.860 --> 02:19:34.840
Though the favored local explanation

02:19:34.840 --> 02:19:36.790
was that it was a vulture vomit.

02:19:36.790 --> 02:19:38.740
Construction on the Brooklyn Bridge,

02:19:38.740 --> 02:19:41.050
which connects the city's boroughs of Manhattan

02:19:41.050 --> 02:19:45.010
and Brooklyn over the East River began in 1869.

02:19:45.010 --> 02:19:46.930
When it opened in 1883,

02:19:46.930 --> 02:19:49.960
it was the longest suspension bridge in the world.

02:19:49.960 --> 02:19:51.340
It was an architectural

02:19:51.340 --> 02:19:53.860
and engineering accomplishment masterminded

02:19:53.860 --> 02:19:57.460
by John Augustus Roebling, who had developed his own method

02:19:57.460 --> 02:19:59.530
for weaving wire cables.

02:19:59.530 --> 02:20:01.630
After an onsite accident killed him

02:20:01.630 --> 02:20:03.250
at the beginning of the project,

02:20:03.250 --> 02:20:05.350
his son, Washington Roebling took

02:20:05.350 --> 02:20:07.120
over management of the project.

02:20:07.120 --> 02:20:10.450
At least 20 workers were killed during construction

02:20:10.450 --> 02:20:13.300
and many more were used to construct the foundations

02:20:13.300 --> 02:20:14.650
of the bridge towers.

02:20:14.650 --> 02:20:18.130
Workers toiled inside the caisson underwater

02:20:18.130 --> 02:20:21.100
at nearly double the normal atmospheric pressure

02:20:21.100 --> 02:20:22.900
and when they returned to the surface,

02:20:22.900 --> 02:20:26.680
had symptoms of what was then called caisson disease,

02:20:26.680 --> 02:20:29.380
but today would be known as the bends.

02:20:29.380 --> 02:20:31.690
When decompression occurs too quickly,

02:20:31.690 --> 02:20:34.300
bubbles of nitrogen form in the bloodstream

02:20:34.300 --> 02:20:37.270
and can result in sharp pains, slurred speech,

02:20:37.270 --> 02:20:40.630
muscular paralysis, vomiting, and cramps.

02:20:40.630 --> 02:20:43.840
Washington Roebling too suffered from the caisson sickness

02:20:43.840 --> 02:20:45.100
and became bedridden,

02:20:45.100 --> 02:20:48.280
though his wife, Emily Warren Roebling stepped into serve

02:20:48.280 --> 02:20:52.060
as a liaison between her husband and the construction team.

02:20:52.060 --> 02:20:54.670
When the bridge was finished, she was the first person

02:20:54.670 --> 02:20:57.520
to cross it by carriage, carrying a rooster

02:20:57.520 --> 02:20:59.140
as a symbol of victory.

02:20:59.140 --> 02:21:03.070
The Gilded Age was a time of enormous economic swings

02:21:03.070 --> 02:21:04.990
with the United States experiencing

02:21:04.990 --> 02:21:07.210
unprecedented economic growth,

02:21:07.210 --> 02:21:10.180
but also marred by economic downturns

02:21:10.180 --> 02:21:12.250
that sent prices crashing.

02:21:12.250 --> 02:21:15.640
In what became known as the Panic of 1893,

02:21:15.640 --> 02:21:17.950
problems with international investments,

02:21:17.950 --> 02:21:19.990
including failed land speculation

02:21:19.990 --> 02:21:21.970
in South Africa and Australia,

02:21:21.970 --> 02:21:25.030
and a railroad bubble caused by the railroads,

02:21:25.030 --> 02:21:28.480
over-building and vastly outpacing demand led people

02:21:28.480 --> 02:21:31.450
to make a run on banks, withdrawing their money.

02:21:31.450 --> 02:21:33.130
A series of banks failed

02:21:33.130 --> 02:21:35.140
and many companies went bankrupt,

02:21:35.140 --> 02:21:39.040
including the Northern Pacific and Union Pacific Railways.

02:21:39.040 --> 02:21:42.130
This led to a huge spike in unemployment.

02:21:42.130 --> 02:21:44.500
Many people also lost their life savings

02:21:44.500 --> 02:21:45.970
in the bank collapses,

02:21:45.970 --> 02:21:48.610
numerous farms had to cease operations

02:21:48.610 --> 02:21:50.410
and stock prices declined.

02:21:50.410 --> 02:21:54.190
People faced starvation, turning to any work they could find

02:21:54.190 --> 02:21:55.690
to help feed their families.

02:21:55.690 --> 02:21:58.750
President Grover Cleveland was blamed for the crisis

02:21:58.750 --> 02:22:00.760
and his administration had taken heat

02:22:00.760 --> 02:22:03.490
for the way it put down the Pullman strikes,

02:22:03.490 --> 02:22:06.340
so his Democratic Party suffered big losses

02:22:06.340 --> 02:22:08.950
during the elections of 1894.

02:22:08.950 --> 02:22:12.310
In the next presidential election in 1896,

02:22:12.310 --> 02:22:15.820
the Democratic candidate, William Jennings Bryan was backed

02:22:15.820 --> 02:22:17.920
by the populist People's Party,

02:22:17.920 --> 02:22:19.000
but he failed to beat

02:22:19.000 --> 02:22:21.760
the Republican candidate, William McKinley.

02:22:21.760 --> 02:22:24.940
By the end of the Gilded Age, many people had become fed up

02:22:24.940 --> 02:22:28.510
with extreme wealth inequality, abusive tycoons,

02:22:28.510 --> 02:22:30.130
and widespread poverty,

02:22:30.130 --> 02:22:33.400
and were ready to usher in a new era of reform.

02:22:33.400 --> 02:22:35.950
When after McKinley was assassinated,

02:22:35.950 --> 02:22:39.670
President Theodore Roosevelt took office in 1901.

02:22:41.522 --> 02:22:44.105
(tense music)

02:22:45.335 --> 02:22:47.080
By the end of the 19th century,

02:22:47.080 --> 02:22:49.180
the United States seemed to have achieved

02:22:49.180 --> 02:22:50.950
its manifest destiny.

02:22:50.950 --> 02:22:53.980
The country now stretched from one ocean to the other.

02:22:53.980 --> 02:22:57.370
It had survived a horrific and bloody civil war

02:22:57.370 --> 02:23:00.460
and stood on the precipice of a new century.

02:23:00.460 --> 02:23:03.340
Now looking to expand its political, social,

02:23:03.340 --> 02:23:05.650
and economic resources outside

02:23:05.650 --> 02:23:07.540
of the North American continent,

02:23:07.540 --> 02:23:08.890
the United States began

02:23:08.890 --> 02:23:10.390
to extend its influence

02:23:10.390 --> 02:23:13.120
on neighboring islands and territories.

02:23:13.120 --> 02:23:15.730
The first was the Hawaiian Kingdom.

02:23:15.730 --> 02:23:18.190
Located 2,400 miles

02:23:18.190 --> 02:23:22.510
or roughly 3,900 kilometers from the US mainland,

02:23:22.510 --> 02:23:24.340
the Hawaiian islands had been ruled

02:23:24.340 --> 02:23:26.050
by the Kamehameha Dynasty

02:23:26.050 --> 02:23:28.240
since the late 1700s.

02:23:28.240 --> 02:23:32.050
In 1846, under the presidency of John Tyler,

02:23:32.050 --> 02:23:34.690
the United States had recognized the independence

02:23:34.690 --> 02:23:36.190
of the Hawaiian Kingdom

02:23:36.190 --> 02:23:38.470
and opened trade with the island nation.

02:23:38.470 --> 02:23:42.370
Enterprising Americans also secured vast sugar plantations

02:23:42.370 --> 02:23:45.220
on the island and American-born immigrants began

02:23:45.220 --> 02:23:46.780
to flood to Hawaii.

02:23:46.780 --> 02:23:49.120
The United States and the Kingdom of Hawaii

02:23:49.120 --> 02:23:52.180
had frequent disagreements over the sugar trade.

02:23:52.180 --> 02:23:53.770
And while the Hawaiians appealed

02:23:53.770 --> 02:23:55.960
for relief from the US government,

02:23:55.960 --> 02:23:57.760
it was frequently ignored.

02:23:57.760 --> 02:24:01.540
As the presence of US natives began to overtake the island,

02:24:01.540 --> 02:24:04.690
so too did the presence of the US Military.

02:24:04.690 --> 02:24:06.970
On January, 1887,

02:24:06.970 --> 02:24:09.250
the US began leasing Pearl Harbor

02:24:09.250 --> 02:24:12.520
from the Kingdom of Hawaii, giving US-born Hawaiians

02:24:12.520 --> 02:24:14.380
the confidence to begin plotting

02:24:14.380 --> 02:24:17.110
against the Hawaiian natives and the government.

02:24:17.110 --> 02:24:20.170
In July, 1887, they launched a rebellion

02:24:20.170 --> 02:24:23.020
and forced the king to agree to what has become known

02:24:23.020 --> 02:24:26.470
as the Bayonet Constitution, which stripped the king of many

02:24:26.470 --> 02:24:28.510
of his powers and gave more power

02:24:28.510 --> 02:24:31.180
to the foreign white plantation owners.

02:24:31.180 --> 02:24:35.200
In 1891, the Hawaiian King Kalakaua passed away,

02:24:35.200 --> 02:24:37.900
leaving the throne, an unsteady government,

02:24:37.900 --> 02:24:40.120
and an economically crippled Hawaii

02:24:40.120 --> 02:24:42.550
to his sister, Liliuokalani.

02:24:42.550 --> 02:24:45.940
Queen Liliuokalani immediately began work trying

02:24:45.940 --> 02:24:49.360
to undo the damage done by the Bayonet Constitution

02:24:49.360 --> 02:24:53.500
and by 1893 was preparing to organize a rewriting

02:24:53.500 --> 02:24:54.970
of the Hawaiian Government.

02:24:54.970 --> 02:24:57.940
In direct contrast, the Committee of Safety,

02:24:57.940 --> 02:25:00.010
a political council of white US

02:25:00.010 --> 02:25:02.110
and European-born landowners,

02:25:02.110 --> 02:25:06.580
began raising forces to once again overthrow the government.

02:25:06.580 --> 02:25:08.980
Both sides quickly mobilized troops

02:25:08.980 --> 02:25:11.890
and the Committee of Safety declared the Queen deposed

02:25:11.890 --> 02:25:15.670
and established a Provincial Republic of Hawaii led

02:25:15.670 --> 02:25:17.440
by Sanford B. Dole.

02:25:17.440 --> 02:25:19.660
The US Navy responded to a request

02:25:19.660 --> 02:25:22.060
for aid from the new provincial republic

02:25:22.060 --> 02:25:23.740
and arrived to keep the peace,

02:25:23.740 --> 02:25:27.100
naturally in favor of the American-born rebels.

02:25:27.100 --> 02:25:29.320
The queen was placed under house arrest

02:25:29.320 --> 02:25:31.390
and never attempted to fight back,

02:25:31.390 --> 02:25:34.330
hoping to avoid any unnecessary bloodshed.

02:25:34.330 --> 02:25:37.840
In Washington, President Grover Cleveland reacted with shock

02:25:37.840 --> 02:25:40.570
and horror and condemned the provincial republic

02:25:40.570 --> 02:25:43.510
as an illegal coup which did not have the support

02:25:43.510 --> 02:25:44.980
of the US Government.

02:25:44.980 --> 02:25:47.890
Despite this, and several inquiries into the events

02:25:47.890 --> 02:25:50.410
which had caused the coup, the Republic of Hawaii

02:25:50.410 --> 02:25:54.220
was officially declared legitimate in 1894.

02:25:54.220 --> 02:25:57.130
Queen Liliuokalani made clear her opposition

02:25:57.130 --> 02:25:59.650
to the unlawful coup for the rest of her life,

02:25:59.650 --> 02:26:01.570
but maintained that her decision not

02:26:01.570 --> 02:26:04.933
to fight the US-backed rebels would save lives.

02:26:05.953 --> 02:26:09.460
(suspenseful music)

02:26:09.460 --> 02:26:12.940
In February, 1895 on the island of Cuba,

02:26:12.940 --> 02:26:14.800
rebels were fighting for independence

02:26:14.800 --> 02:26:16.660
from Spain's colonial rule.

02:26:16.660 --> 02:26:18.700
Graphic portrayals of Spain's efforts

02:26:18.700 --> 02:26:22.450
to quell the rebellion were shared by several US newspapers

02:26:22.450 --> 02:26:25.840
and among the American public, support for the rebels grew.

02:26:25.840 --> 02:26:27.940
The fighting also created economic

02:26:27.940 --> 02:26:32.110
and political instability in an area very close to the US,

02:26:32.110 --> 02:26:34.270
which concerned some Americans.

02:26:34.270 --> 02:26:37.960
In April, 1895, Spain announced an armistice

02:26:37.960 --> 02:26:39.460
and instituted a program

02:26:39.460 --> 02:26:42.460
to give Cubans limited powers of self-government.

02:26:42.460 --> 02:26:45.190
However, the US had long been interested

02:26:45.190 --> 02:26:47.020
in ridding the Western Hemisphere

02:26:47.020 --> 02:26:49.330
of European colonial powers.

02:26:49.330 --> 02:26:52.780
The US saw its opportunity when an American battleship,

02:26:52.780 --> 02:26:56.170
the USS Maine, mysteriously sank while stationed

02:26:56.170 --> 02:27:00.520
in the Havana Harbor on February 15th, 1891,

02:27:00.520 --> 02:27:03.400
killing 268 members of the crew.

02:27:03.400 --> 02:27:06.580
Using "Remember the Maine" as a call to action,

02:27:06.580 --> 02:27:09.520
pro-war propagandists drummed up public support

02:27:09.520 --> 02:27:10.570
for the conflict,

02:27:10.570 --> 02:27:13.030
blaming Spain for the sinking of the Maine.

02:27:13.030 --> 02:27:16.750
The US quickly issued resolutions that declared Cuba's right

02:27:16.750 --> 02:27:19.390
to independence and demanded the withdrawal

02:27:19.390 --> 02:27:21.070
of Spain's armed forces

02:27:21.070 --> 02:27:23.260
and authorized President William McKinley

02:27:23.260 --> 02:27:26.830
to use force to ensure the withdrawal occurred.

02:27:26.830 --> 02:27:31.450
The US also stated it had no intention to annex Cuba itself.

02:27:31.450 --> 02:27:34.630
The Spanish Government rejected the American's ultimatum

02:27:34.630 --> 02:27:38.080
and immediately severed diplomatic relations with the US.

02:27:38.080 --> 02:27:40.330
McKinley responded with a naval blockade

02:27:40.330 --> 02:27:43.930
of Cuba on April 22nd, 1898,

02:27:43.930 --> 02:27:48.930
and issued a call for 125,000 military volunteers.

02:27:48.970 --> 02:27:52.690
First US forces attacked the Spanish naval squadron anchored

02:27:52.690 --> 02:27:56.020
in Manila Bay in the Spanish colony of the Philippines.

02:27:56.020 --> 02:27:59.050
The fleet was destroyed in just two hours

02:27:59.050 --> 02:28:01.840
and Commodore George Dewey even paused the battle

02:28:01.840 --> 02:28:05.380
of Manila Bay to order his crew a second breakfast.

02:28:05.380 --> 02:28:08.050
Fewer than 10 Americans were lost in this battle,

02:28:08.050 --> 02:28:10.960
while the Spanish lost almost 400.

02:28:10.960 --> 02:28:13.090
Next, American forces zeroed in

02:28:13.090 --> 02:28:14.920
on the Spanish Caribbean Fleet

02:28:14.920 --> 02:28:17.070
under general William Shafter,

02:28:17.070 --> 02:28:20.650
an army which included future President Theodore Roosevelt

02:28:20.650 --> 02:28:23.950
and his first volunteer cavalry, the Rough Riders,

02:28:23.950 --> 02:28:27.280
advanced on land toward the city of Santiago.

02:28:27.280 --> 02:28:29.380
The Rough Riders were instrumental

02:28:29.380 --> 02:28:31.270
in the Battle of San Juan Hill

02:28:31.270 --> 02:28:32.890
in which they captured the hill

02:28:32.890 --> 02:28:35.230
and used it as a strategic place from which

02:28:35.230 --> 02:28:39.190
to attack the Spanish military stronghold in Santiago.

02:28:39.190 --> 02:28:41.680
The US Army drove the Spanish Navy out

02:28:41.680 --> 02:28:43.150
of Santiago's port

02:28:43.150 --> 02:28:45.700
by approaching the city from multiple points.

02:28:45.700 --> 02:28:47.500
Then the US Navy proceeded

02:28:47.500 --> 02:28:50.890
to destroy Spain's ships on July 3rd allowing

02:28:50.890 --> 02:28:53.440
for a relatively safe siege on the city.

02:28:53.440 --> 02:28:56.260
A cease fire was signed August 12th.

02:28:56.260 --> 02:29:00.190
The US Military's force had so dwarfed Spain's power

02:29:00.190 --> 02:29:03.400
that future Secretary of State John Hay described

02:29:03.400 --> 02:29:06.700
the conflict as a splendid little war.

02:29:06.700 --> 02:29:09.250
The Treaty of Paris officially ending the war

02:29:09.250 --> 02:29:12.250
was signed December 10th, 1898.

02:29:12.250 --> 02:29:14.800
In it, Spain renounced its claims to Cuba,

02:29:14.800 --> 02:29:17.920
ceded Guam and Puerto Rico to the United States,

02:29:17.920 --> 02:29:20.650
and transferred the Philippines to the United States

02:29:20.650 --> 02:29:21.943
for $20 million.

02:29:22.780 --> 02:29:26.890
However, Filipinos were not happier under American control,

02:29:26.890 --> 02:29:31.690
and the Philippine -American War began in February of 1899

02:29:31.690 --> 02:29:34.420
and lasted until 1902.

02:29:34.420 --> 02:29:37.750
10 times more US troops died suppressing revolts

02:29:37.750 --> 02:29:40.600
in the Philippines than in defeating Spain.

02:29:40.600 --> 02:29:43.030
The McKinley Administration also used

02:29:43.030 --> 02:29:45.490
the Spanish American-War as a pretext

02:29:45.490 --> 02:29:47.980
to annex the independent State of Hawaii.

02:29:47.980 --> 02:29:50.950
The US emerged from the war a world power

02:29:50.950 --> 02:29:54.400
with a new stake in international politics.

02:29:54.400 --> 02:29:56.170
This would soon lead the US

02:29:56.170 --> 02:29:59.440
to play a determining role in the affairs of Europe

02:29:59.440 --> 02:30:01.273
and the rest of the globe.

02:30:02.758 --> 02:30:05.920
(tense music)

02:30:05.920 --> 02:30:08.260
Spurred to action by the suffering caused

02:30:08.260 --> 02:30:10.810
by recessions in the late 1890s,

02:30:10.810 --> 02:30:13.570
the turn of the 20th century was characterized

02:30:13.570 --> 02:30:15.880
by a desire for change.

02:30:15.880 --> 02:30:18.250
Many people were tired of the tight alliances

02:30:18.250 --> 02:30:21.160
between powerful Gilded Age politicians

02:30:21.160 --> 02:30:23.800
and businessmen, as well as the problems caused

02:30:23.800 --> 02:30:25.600
by rapid industrialization

02:30:25.600 --> 02:30:28.510
and urbanization like the growth of slums,

02:30:28.510 --> 02:30:32.410
widespread pollution and increased exploitation of labor.

02:30:32.410 --> 02:30:34.930
With Former Vice President Theodore Roosevelt

02:30:34.930 --> 02:30:37.030
newly established in the head office

02:30:37.030 --> 02:30:39.910
after president William McKinley was assassinated,

02:30:39.910 --> 02:30:41.260
the progressives were set

02:30:41.260 --> 02:30:43.630
to transform the American landscape

02:30:43.630 --> 02:30:45.880
into something far more modern.

02:30:45.880 --> 02:30:48.970
Roosevelt who at 43 was the youngest president

02:30:48.970 --> 02:30:52.570
in the nation's history, came into office in 1901

02:30:52.570 --> 02:30:54.910
with enthusiasm for the public good.

02:30:54.910 --> 02:30:56.710
Unlike presidents before him,

02:30:56.710 --> 02:31:00.220
he wielded the Sherman Antitrust Act to breakup monopolies,

02:31:00.220 --> 02:31:03.340
including the railroad owned by J.P. Morgan.

02:31:03.340 --> 02:31:05.260
The company, Northern Securities,

02:31:05.260 --> 02:31:07.630
controlled almost all railroad shipping

02:31:07.630 --> 02:31:09.280
across the Northern US

02:31:09.280 --> 02:31:12.250
and in 1902, Roosevelt went on the offense

02:31:12.250 --> 02:31:14.380
and took the matter to the Supreme Court,

02:31:14.380 --> 02:31:16.390
which sided with Roosevelt.

02:31:16.390 --> 02:31:18.010
And whereas the former president,

02:31:18.010 --> 02:31:20.140
Grover Cleveland had sent federal troops

02:31:20.140 --> 02:31:23.200
to quell a railroad strike in the 1880s,

02:31:23.200 --> 02:31:24.490
when Roosevelt was faced

02:31:24.490 --> 02:31:28.240
with a large-scale coal miner strike in 1902,

02:31:28.240 --> 02:31:31.810
he sent representatives to serve as a neutral mediator.

02:31:31.810 --> 02:31:35.320
Roosevelt easily won reelection in 1904,

02:31:35.320 --> 02:31:39.490
campaigning on his square deal platform of trust-busting,

02:31:39.490 --> 02:31:43.180
conserving natural resources, and protecting the consumer.

02:31:43.180 --> 02:31:44.710
Like in the Gilded Age,

02:31:44.710 --> 02:31:47.470
immigrants from Southern and Eastern Europe were continuing

02:31:47.470 --> 02:31:49.720
to arrive in the US in large numbers

02:31:49.720 --> 02:31:51.550
during the progressive age.

02:31:51.550 --> 02:31:56.080
Between 1900 and the outbreak of war in Europe in 1914,

02:31:56.080 --> 02:31:59.230
more than 13 million immigrants arrived.

02:31:59.230 --> 02:32:00.880
This meant the issues of slums

02:32:00.880 --> 02:32:02.710
and tenements that were so prevalent

02:32:02.710 --> 02:32:05.350
during the Gilded Age were only growing.

02:32:05.350 --> 02:32:08.050
The progressives, who were mostly middle-class,

02:32:08.050 --> 02:32:11.050
white social reformers saw the urban poor

02:32:11.050 --> 02:32:12.940
as a social concern.

02:32:12.940 --> 02:32:15.460
As early as 1889, reformers,

02:32:15.460 --> 02:32:18.370
Jane Addams and Ellen Gates Starr opened Hull House

02:32:18.370 --> 02:32:21.280
in Chicago, one of the first social settlements

02:32:21.280 --> 02:32:22.630
in North America.

02:32:22.630 --> 02:32:24.580
It provided social services,

02:32:24.580 --> 02:32:26.440
including early child education

02:32:26.440 --> 02:32:29.260
and adult education to poor immigrants.

02:32:29.260 --> 02:32:31.780
Progressive activists each had certain issues

02:32:31.780 --> 02:32:33.970
they felt were more important to address,

02:32:33.970 --> 02:32:36.610
so reform movements were a patchwork of efforts

02:32:36.610 --> 02:32:39.550
that covered a wide swath of social ills.

02:32:39.550 --> 02:32:42.370
Some progressive reformers sought to expand the powers

02:32:42.370 --> 02:32:43.570
of government to reign

02:32:43.570 --> 02:32:46.090
in the negative aspects of capitalism.

02:32:46.090 --> 02:32:49.630
Companies could no longer simply operate unregulated

02:32:49.630 --> 02:32:52.690
with the advent of state factory inspectors

02:32:52.690 --> 02:32:55.060
and public health bureaus, which were tasked

02:32:55.060 --> 02:32:57.880
with minimizing unsafe working conditions,

02:32:57.880 --> 02:33:00.490
stopping poisoned food from being sold

02:33:00.490 --> 02:33:03.310
and tamping down on contagious diseases.

02:33:03.310 --> 02:33:05.980
One event that prompted greater corporate regulation

02:33:05.980 --> 02:33:09.250
was the Great Molasses Flood of 1919,

02:33:09.250 --> 02:33:10.660
which occurred in Boston when

02:33:10.660 --> 02:33:15.400
a tank containing 2.3 million gallons of molasses exploded

02:33:15.400 --> 02:33:17.770
and sent a wave of the sticky molasses

02:33:17.770 --> 02:33:19.330
through the streets of the city.

02:33:19.330 --> 02:33:22.990
The wave was said to move at up to 35 miles per hour

02:33:22.990 --> 02:33:25.720
and be up to 25 feet tall.

02:33:25.720 --> 02:33:29.560
21 people died and more than 150 were injured,

02:33:29.560 --> 02:33:32.020
and an area of several blocks was flooded up

02:33:32.020 --> 02:33:33.550
to two to three feet.

02:33:33.550 --> 02:33:36.130
The tank was used by the purity distilling company

02:33:36.130 --> 02:33:38.350
to store molasses before it was taken

02:33:38.350 --> 02:33:39.970
by pipeline to be fermented

02:33:39.970 --> 02:33:43.660
to produce ethanol, an ingredient in alcoholic beverages

02:33:43.660 --> 02:33:46.270
and a key component in munitions.

02:33:46.270 --> 02:33:48.580
Though the company claimed the tank was blown up

02:33:48.580 --> 02:33:52.360
by anarchists, a class action lawsuit was brought on behalf

02:33:52.360 --> 02:33:55.000
of the victims and a court-appointed auditor found

02:33:55.000 --> 02:33:56.890
the company was responsible.

02:33:56.890 --> 02:33:59.530
It was one of the first class action lawsuits

02:33:59.530 --> 02:34:02.500
in Massachusetts and provided cash payments

02:34:02.500 --> 02:34:04.450
to the families of victims.

02:34:04.450 --> 02:34:06.970
Progressive reformers sought to clean up big business

02:34:06.970 --> 02:34:09.580
and the government in a variety of ways,

02:34:09.580 --> 02:34:11.800
including through the adoption of more amendments

02:34:11.800 --> 02:34:13.150
to the Constitution.

02:34:13.150 --> 02:34:15.970
The Sixteenth Amendment, which made it legal to graduate

02:34:15.970 --> 02:34:20.560
the income tax based on a person's income was added in 1909

02:34:20.560 --> 02:34:22.450
and the Seventeenth Amendment attempted

02:34:22.450 --> 02:34:23.860
to make elections more fair

02:34:23.860 --> 02:34:27.280
by instituting the direct election of senators rather than

02:34:27.280 --> 02:34:29.680
by state legislatures, which could be controlled

02:34:29.680 --> 02:34:32.980
by political bosses in 1913.

02:34:32.980 --> 02:34:34.600
Other political reforms thought

02:34:34.600 --> 02:34:36.790
to give citizens more direct control

02:34:36.790 --> 02:34:38.080
over their governments

02:34:38.080 --> 02:34:41.140
by instituting the initiative and the referendum,

02:34:41.140 --> 02:34:44.020
which let citizens put proposed laws on a ballot

02:34:44.020 --> 02:34:46.690
without needing support from their legislators.

02:34:46.690 --> 02:34:47.980
Reformers also sought

02:34:47.980 --> 02:34:50.590
to streamline government via the short ballot,

02:34:50.590 --> 02:34:53.110
which was intended to increase government accountability

02:34:53.110 --> 02:34:56.230
and clarity and public utility commissions sought

02:34:56.230 --> 02:34:58.390
to stabilize the pricing of city gas

02:34:58.390 --> 02:34:59.800
and water supplies,

02:34:59.800 --> 02:35:03.460
street car fairs and railroad shipping while zoning boards

02:35:03.460 --> 02:35:06.610
and city planning commissions sought to clean up slums,

02:35:06.610 --> 02:35:08.650
improve polluted water supplies,

02:35:08.650 --> 02:35:11.560
and bring order to chaotic land markets.

02:35:11.560 --> 02:35:13.870
Other reformers focused on preventing the spread

02:35:13.870 --> 02:35:17.170
of venereal diseases, stopping prostitution,

02:35:17.170 --> 02:35:20.380
and taking other measures for public health and morality.

02:35:20.380 --> 02:35:23.530
Among these, the Woman's Christian Temperance Union,

02:35:23.530 --> 02:35:25.270
the Anti-Saloon League,

02:35:25.270 --> 02:35:29.260
and the Young Men's Christian Association, YMCA,

02:35:29.260 --> 02:35:33.520
led efforts to promote temperance or abstaining from alcohol

02:35:33.520 --> 02:35:35.980
and discouraging premarital sex.

02:35:35.980 --> 02:35:38.620
Temperance and prohibition were causes taken up

02:35:38.620 --> 02:35:41.830
by a great number of progressive reformers

02:35:41.830 --> 02:35:45.190
who saw alcohol as an evil that spawned a variety

02:35:45.190 --> 02:35:48.580
of other issues like domestic violence and poverty.

02:35:48.580 --> 02:35:51.340
These activists known as The Dries

02:35:51.340 --> 02:35:52.360
helped set the stage

02:35:52.360 --> 02:35:55.630
for various states to pass legislation banning the sale,

02:35:55.630 --> 02:35:58.660
possession or transport of alcohol.

02:35:58.660 --> 02:36:01.750
In 1907, Georgia and Alabama were the first states

02:36:01.750 --> 02:36:05.140
to go dry, followed by Oklahoma, Mississippi,

02:36:05.140 --> 02:36:07.450
North Carolina, and Tennessee.

02:36:07.450 --> 02:36:11.470
By 1917, 2/3 of the states had some form

02:36:11.470 --> 02:36:12.820
of prohibition laws

02:36:12.820 --> 02:36:14.080
and roughly three quarters

02:36:14.080 --> 02:36:16.750
of the population lived in dry areas.

02:36:16.750 --> 02:36:18.760
With the passage of the Eighteenth Amendment

02:36:18.760 --> 02:36:21.130
to the Constitution in 1919,

02:36:21.130 --> 02:36:25.000
which kicked off the era of alcohol prohibition in the US,

02:36:25.000 --> 02:36:27.700
this patchwork was given federal support.

02:36:27.700 --> 02:36:30.130
Not all reform projects were undertaken

02:36:30.130 --> 02:36:31.900
by middle-class white people.

02:36:31.900 --> 02:36:34.900
The progressive era also saw Black communities

02:36:34.900 --> 02:36:37.930
in the segregated South take up reform projects

02:36:37.930 --> 02:36:39.430
like improving schools,

02:36:39.430 --> 02:36:41.950
seeking out larger shares of state budgets,

02:36:41.950 --> 02:36:44.980
engaging in legal action to secure equal rights,

02:36:44.980 --> 02:36:46.810
and environmental efforts.

02:36:46.810 --> 02:36:48.250
At the same time, however,

02:36:48.250 --> 02:36:51.280
the country was deep in a period known as the nadir

02:36:51.280 --> 02:36:53.650
of race relations, which brought some

02:36:53.650 --> 02:36:57.550
of the worst racial violence and racist policies into being.

02:36:57.550 --> 02:37:01.150
During this time, African Americans lost access to many

02:37:01.150 --> 02:37:03.160
of the rights improvements they had gained

02:37:03.160 --> 02:37:05.260
during the reconstruction period.

02:37:05.260 --> 02:37:07.810
Violence, lynchings, segregation,

02:37:07.810 --> 02:37:11.830
and legalized racial discrimination all proliferated.

02:37:11.830 --> 02:37:15.010
In reaction, African Americans began increasingly

02:37:15.010 --> 02:37:18.910
to move north in a period known as the Great Migration.

02:37:18.910 --> 02:37:21.850
Many of those who migrated moved to northern cities such

02:37:21.850 --> 02:37:25.510
as New York, Chicago, Cleveland, and Philadelphia.

02:37:25.510 --> 02:37:29.080
They still faced serious hostility as well as segregation

02:37:29.080 --> 02:37:30.640
and widespread racism.

02:37:30.640 --> 02:37:32.200
In the Midwest and West,

02:37:32.200 --> 02:37:35.320
many places were known as sundown towns,

02:37:35.320 --> 02:37:37.090
which promised African Americans

02:37:37.090 --> 02:37:38.500
that they would face violence

02:37:38.500 --> 02:37:40.690
if they remained there overnight.

02:37:40.690 --> 02:37:44.740
When President Woodrow Wilson was voted into office in 1912,

02:37:44.740 --> 02:37:46.600
he made new efforts to segregate

02:37:46.600 --> 02:37:48.910
the federal government's facilities.

02:37:48.910 --> 02:37:52.240
The 1915 film "Birth of a Nation" celebrated

02:37:52.240 --> 02:37:54.460
the original Ku Klux Klan

02:37:54.460 --> 02:37:55.660
and is credited

02:37:55.660 --> 02:37:59.440
with bringing the Klan back into power in the 1920s,

02:37:59.440 --> 02:38:02.980
more power in fact than it had ever had before.

02:38:02.980 --> 02:38:07.210
By 1924, the Klan had four million members

02:38:07.210 --> 02:38:09.460
and significant influence over the governments

02:38:09.460 --> 02:38:11.950
of several Southern and Western States.

02:38:11.950 --> 02:38:15.580
Mob violence against African Americans was widespread.

02:38:15.580 --> 02:38:17.860
Three dozen cities across the US

02:38:17.860 --> 02:38:22.120
saw white supremacist violence in the summer of 1919,

02:38:22.120 --> 02:38:24.580
which became known as the Red Summer.

02:38:24.580 --> 02:38:28.690
White mobs murdered at least 43 Black men that year,

02:38:28.690 --> 02:38:31.450
but a report delivered to President Wilson indicated

02:38:31.450 --> 02:38:33.910
that the states were unwilling to take any action

02:38:33.910 --> 02:38:35.890
to prosecute the murders.

02:38:35.890 --> 02:38:37.480
Many former Black soldiers

02:38:37.480 --> 02:38:40.930
who had returned from deployment in World War I were angered

02:38:40.930 --> 02:38:43.120
and frustrated by these conditions

02:38:43.120 --> 02:38:45.010
after having fought for their country.

02:38:45.010 --> 02:38:47.290
From a progressive reform perspective,

02:38:47.290 --> 02:38:49.570
many people felt that race relation problems

02:38:49.570 --> 02:38:51.550
actually stemmed from a society

02:38:51.550 --> 02:38:53.230
that was being integrated

02:38:53.230 --> 02:38:56.470
and reformers fought for increased segregation.

02:38:56.470 --> 02:38:59.230
Between 1895 and 1910,

02:38:59.230 --> 02:39:02.380
progressives in Southern States helped deny Black people

02:39:02.380 --> 02:39:06.610
the right to vote by popularizing the Grandfather Clause,

02:39:06.610 --> 02:39:09.280
which restricted voting rights to men who were allowed

02:39:09.280 --> 02:39:11.950
to vote or whose male ancestors were allowed

02:39:11.950 --> 02:39:14.650
to vote before 1867.

02:39:14.650 --> 02:39:16.810
This disenfranchised Black voters

02:39:16.810 --> 02:39:18.430
because the Fifteenth Amendment,

02:39:18.430 --> 02:39:20.260
which provided them the right to vote,

02:39:20.260 --> 02:39:23.080
was not passed until 1870.

02:39:23.080 --> 02:39:24.430
The Supreme Court declared

02:39:24.430 --> 02:39:28.420
the Grandfather Clause unconstitutional in 1915,

02:39:28.420 --> 02:39:29.920
but its use persisted.

02:39:29.920 --> 02:39:33.490
It was not until the Voting Rights Act of 1965

02:39:33.490 --> 02:39:36.340
that the Fifteenth Amendment was enforceable.

02:39:36.340 --> 02:39:38.890
As the Black vote was being forced out,

02:39:38.890 --> 02:39:41.950
voting power for white women was on its way in.

02:39:41.950 --> 02:39:45.070
Organizations like the Woman's Christian Temperance Union

02:39:45.070 --> 02:39:47.140
advocated for women suffrage,

02:39:47.140 --> 02:39:49.780
while they worked on other issues like prohibition.

02:39:49.780 --> 02:39:52.300
In addition to sexist attitudes at the time,

02:39:52.300 --> 02:39:54.100
some opposed female suffrage

02:39:54.100 --> 02:39:56.710
because they feared the women's vote would tip the scales

02:39:56.710 --> 02:40:00.610
on issues they were against, such as eliminating child labor

02:40:00.610 --> 02:40:02.410
and prohibiting alcohol,

02:40:02.410 --> 02:40:05.950
and increase the share of socialists in the voting pool.

02:40:05.950 --> 02:40:10.270
In 1916, Alice Paul formed the National Women's Party,

02:40:10.270 --> 02:40:12.130
which was focused on getting women the right

02:40:12.130 --> 02:40:13.510
to vote nationally.

02:40:13.510 --> 02:40:17.650
When the US entered World War I in 1917 to replace the men

02:40:17.650 --> 02:40:20.380
who left to fight, women moved into workplaces

02:40:20.380 --> 02:40:22.810
that traditionally were closed to them.

02:40:22.810 --> 02:40:24.250
The Nineteenth Amendment,

02:40:24.250 --> 02:40:27.430
which prohibited discrimination in voting on the basis

02:40:27.430 --> 02:40:31.630
of sex was adopted on August 18th, 1920.

02:40:31.630 --> 02:40:35.470
The US sought to be a world leader in other areas.

02:40:35.470 --> 02:40:38.170
The quest for an explorer to reach the North Pole,

02:40:38.170 --> 02:40:40.660
considered the last unexplored area,

02:40:40.660 --> 02:40:42.100
of the Northern Hemisphere,

02:40:42.100 --> 02:40:44.500
inspired competition between British,

02:40:44.500 --> 02:40:47.080
Norwegian and American teams.

02:40:47.080 --> 02:40:49.030
Numerous journeys were attempted.

02:40:49.030 --> 02:40:52.360
In 1909, the New York Times announced that explorer

02:40:52.360 --> 02:40:55.210
and former US Navy Commander Robert Peary

02:40:55.210 --> 02:40:57.730
had successfully reached the North Pole,

02:40:57.730 --> 02:40:59.410
but his victory was marred

02:40:59.410 --> 02:41:02.410
by another American Explorer Frederick Cook,

02:41:02.410 --> 02:41:05.350
who claimed he had visited the Pole a year earlier.

02:41:05.350 --> 02:41:08.530
The competing claims drew significant controversy

02:41:08.530 --> 02:41:11.320
with people unsure of who to credit with the victory.

02:41:11.320 --> 02:41:12.940
Newspapers polled their readers

02:41:12.940 --> 02:41:16.000
on which explorer they thought had been victorious.

02:41:16.000 --> 02:41:17.950
In January, 1911,

02:41:17.950 --> 02:41:19.900
Peary appeared before a subcommittee

02:41:19.900 --> 02:41:21.460
of the House of Representatives

02:41:21.460 --> 02:41:24.820
to defend his claim, which narrowly voted for Peary

02:41:24.820 --> 02:41:27.130
to receive recognition for the feat.

02:41:27.130 --> 02:41:29.770
The Bill of Recognition that was signed into law

02:41:29.770 --> 02:41:31.570
by President William Howard Taft,

02:41:31.570 --> 02:41:33.670
however, did not credit Peary

02:41:33.670 --> 02:41:36.280
with the North Pole's discovery,

02:41:36.280 --> 02:41:38.500
but rather more generally lauded him

02:41:38.500 --> 02:41:40.960
for his Arctic exploration.

02:41:40.960 --> 02:41:43.180
The question remains today whether Cook

02:41:43.180 --> 02:41:45.610
or Peary ever made it to the Pole.

02:41:45.610 --> 02:41:49.000
In 1904, the US took over efforts from the French

02:41:49.000 --> 02:41:51.190
to build a canal that connected the Atlantic

02:41:51.190 --> 02:41:52.600
and Pacific oceans.

02:41:52.600 --> 02:41:55.000
Through a 50 mile stretch of Panama.

02:41:55.000 --> 02:41:57.580
The idea of a Panama Canal dated back

02:41:57.580 --> 02:41:59.080
to the earliest explorers

02:41:59.080 --> 02:42:02.740
of the Americans, who realized it would be a useful shortcut

02:42:02.740 --> 02:42:04.660
between Europe and Eastern Asia.

02:42:04.660 --> 02:42:06.940
Under direction from President Roosevelt,

02:42:06.940 --> 02:42:10.030
the US fought back mosquito-born illnesses

02:42:10.030 --> 02:42:13.570
stubbornly excavated through the local mountain range

02:42:13.570 --> 02:42:15.430
and devised a system of locks

02:42:15.430 --> 02:42:19.390
and dams that would move boats across uneven water levels.

02:42:19.390 --> 02:42:23.680
The canal officially opened on August 15th, 1914,

02:42:23.680 --> 02:42:27.970
and at the time was the most expensive project in US history

02:42:27.970 --> 02:42:32.970
costing the US government around $375 million at the time.

02:42:33.460 --> 02:42:35.920
Added to its cost is the human toll.

02:42:35.920 --> 02:42:38.890
Thousands of workers died during its construction,

02:42:38.890 --> 02:42:41.170
but good records were not kept.

02:42:41.170 --> 02:42:44.290
At least 5,600 workers were listed

02:42:44.290 --> 02:42:48.700
as having been killed between 1904 and 1913,

02:42:48.700 --> 02:42:52.030
but this is thought to be a significant under-count.

02:42:52.030 --> 02:42:54.220
The construction of the Panama Canal proved

02:42:54.220 --> 02:42:55.690
to be a critical boost

02:42:55.690 --> 02:42:58.150
to global trade routes for the 20th century.

02:42:58.150 --> 02:43:01.000
It would later be recognized as one of the marvels

02:43:01.000 --> 02:43:02.440
of the modern world.

02:43:02.440 --> 02:43:04.330
It was one of the progressive era's

02:43:04.330 --> 02:43:07.333
most notable technological achievements.

02:43:08.511 --> 02:43:12.250
(suspenseful music)

02:43:12.250 --> 02:43:15.100
As European countries took sides in the conflict

02:43:15.100 --> 02:43:19.120
between Austria, Hungary and Serbia in 1914,

02:43:19.120 --> 02:43:22.000
President Woodrow Wilson declared the United States

02:43:22.000 --> 02:43:23.590
was going to remain neutral in

02:43:23.590 --> 02:43:26.530
what was then being called the Great War.

02:43:26.530 --> 02:43:29.290
However, after a German submarine sank

02:43:29.290 --> 02:43:33.160
the British ocean liner Lusitania in 1915,

02:43:33.160 --> 02:43:35.320
killing over 1,000 people,

02:43:35.320 --> 02:43:38.380
including 128 Americans,

02:43:38.380 --> 02:43:41.980
public opinion on US involvement began to change.

02:43:41.980 --> 02:43:45.490
In 1917, the British intercepted a coded message

02:43:45.490 --> 02:43:48.310
from German Foreign Minister Arthur Zimmermann

02:43:48.310 --> 02:43:50.770
to the German Minister in Mexico proposing

02:43:50.770 --> 02:43:52.690
an alliance between the countries

02:43:52.690 --> 02:43:55.720
to take back Mexican territory if the US were

02:43:55.720 --> 02:43:58.930
to enter the war on the side of the allies.

02:43:58.930 --> 02:44:01.630
Public outcry against this plan as well

02:44:01.630 --> 02:44:04.330
as against the ongoing German submarine attacks

02:44:04.330 --> 02:44:08.080
on non-military vessels led Wilson to ask Congress

02:44:08.080 --> 02:44:10.540
to declare war on Germany.

02:44:10.540 --> 02:44:14.020
Congress agreed on April 6th, 1917,

02:44:14.020 --> 02:44:16.810
and soon passed the Selective Service Act,

02:44:16.810 --> 02:44:20.560
instituting the first draft since the Civil War,

02:44:20.560 --> 02:44:23.080
leading about 2.8 million men

02:44:23.080 --> 02:44:25.600
to be drafted alongside another 2 million

02:44:25.600 --> 02:44:27.970
who joined the military voluntarily.

02:44:27.970 --> 02:44:29.650
German Americans were required

02:44:29.650 --> 02:44:31.750
to register themselves with the government

02:44:31.750 --> 02:44:34.870
and thousands were arrested and interrogated.

02:44:34.870 --> 02:44:37.060
Some were in interned for the duration

02:44:37.060 --> 02:44:38.890
of the war in two prisoners

02:44:38.890 --> 02:44:42.130
of war camps located in Georgia and Utah.

02:44:42.130 --> 02:44:45.100
At first, the home front was relatively unprepared

02:44:45.100 --> 02:44:46.600
to support the war effort.

02:44:46.600 --> 02:44:47.920
The entire economy

02:44:47.920 --> 02:44:51.640
and US population needed to help keep the money, soldiers,

02:44:51.640 --> 02:44:54.220
food, supplies and munitions flowing.

02:44:54.220 --> 02:44:57.100
The federal government created many new agencies

02:44:57.100 --> 02:44:59.920
to help the economy pivot to support the war effort,

02:44:59.920 --> 02:45:01.750
and to produce propaganda.

02:45:01.750 --> 02:45:04.090
A week after declaring war on Germany,

02:45:04.090 --> 02:45:07.150
Wilson established the Committee on Public Information,

02:45:07.150 --> 02:45:10.660
A bureau dedicated to creating pro-war propaganda.

02:45:10.660 --> 02:45:14.620
Using photographs, movies, rallies, scripted speeches,

02:45:14.620 --> 02:45:16.780
press reports, and public meetings,

02:45:16.780 --> 02:45:19.930
the CPI fostered American patriotism

02:45:19.930 --> 02:45:22.450
and stoked anti-German sentiment.

02:45:22.450 --> 02:45:25.930
With the passage of the Espionage Act of 1917

02:45:25.930 --> 02:45:28.600
and the Sedition Act of 1918,

02:45:28.600 --> 02:45:30.130
criticism of the government

02:45:30.130 --> 02:45:33.280
or the war effort was essentially outlawed.

02:45:33.280 --> 02:45:35.950
A particular focus was put on children

02:45:35.950 --> 02:45:38.950
and youth organizations who were expected

02:45:38.950 --> 02:45:40.510
to teach patriotism

02:45:40.510 --> 02:45:42.850
and to help encourage support for the war.

02:45:42.850 --> 02:45:46.000
The US Food Administration instructed the American public

02:45:46.000 --> 02:45:47.830
to economize their food budgets

02:45:47.830 --> 02:45:48.880
and grow what were known

02:45:48.880 --> 02:45:52.030
as victory gardens in their backyards

02:45:52.030 --> 02:45:53.500
to feed their families.

02:45:53.500 --> 02:45:56.320
A constitutional amendment applied an income tax

02:45:56.320 --> 02:45:59.410
to high earners and businesses faced other new taxes

02:45:59.410 --> 02:46:02.950
on their excess profits, which all helped fund the war.

02:46:02.950 --> 02:46:06.730
Most new funding, however, came from the sale of war bonds.

02:46:06.730 --> 02:46:09.910
Many women began working in traditionally male professions

02:46:09.910 --> 02:46:11.200
to assist the war effort,

02:46:11.200 --> 02:46:14.350
such as on assembly lines making munitions.

02:46:14.350 --> 02:46:17.230
Others worked for the military as support personnel

02:46:17.230 --> 02:46:20.140
or nurses stateside and overseas.

02:46:20.140 --> 02:46:23.530
The Army Signal Corps employed female switchboard operators

02:46:23.530 --> 02:46:26.230
to help with communication along the Western Front.

02:46:26.230 --> 02:46:28.930
These women were highly trained and bilingual

02:46:28.930 --> 02:46:30.700
in English and French.

02:46:30.700 --> 02:46:33.460
But because the war department forbade women except

02:46:33.460 --> 02:46:37.900
as nurses in hospitals, they were hired only reluctantly.

02:46:37.900 --> 02:46:39.820
Ultimately, women were accepted in order

02:46:39.820 --> 02:46:41.860
to free up more men for the Front.

02:46:41.860 --> 02:46:43.900
American men who went to fight in France

02:46:43.900 --> 02:46:45.850
were enthusiastically greeted

02:46:45.850 --> 02:46:48.370
by the worn down allied troops.

02:46:48.370 --> 02:46:52.150
The first elements of the American expeditionary forces,

02:46:52.150 --> 02:46:55.000
under the command of General John J. Pershing,

02:46:55.000 --> 02:46:58.150
arrived in France in June, 1917.

02:46:58.150 --> 02:47:01.390
By early 1918, US forces were arriving

02:47:01.390 --> 02:47:03.610
at a rate of 10,000 a day,

02:47:03.610 --> 02:47:06.550
which had a significant impact on the ally's ability

02:47:06.550 --> 02:47:09.700
to push back the German's powerful spring offensive.

02:47:09.700 --> 02:47:11.830
While American commanders initially

02:47:11.830 --> 02:47:15.220
were using flawed tactics that others had already abandoned,

02:47:15.220 --> 02:47:17.890
resulting in attacks with high casualty rates,

02:47:17.890 --> 02:47:20.200
the infusion of US troops contributed

02:47:20.200 --> 02:47:23.800
to the ally's strategic position and improved morale.

02:47:23.800 --> 02:47:28.000
During the 100 Days Offensive by the allies in 1918,

02:47:28.000 --> 02:47:31.570
American forces launched the Meuse-Argonne Offensive.

02:47:31.570 --> 02:47:35.860
Over 47 days, 1.2 million American troops drove

02:47:35.860 --> 02:47:38.170
the Germans back 40 miles.

02:47:38.170 --> 02:47:41.800
More than 26,000 American soldiers died.

02:47:41.800 --> 02:47:44.920
The 100 Days Offensive helped the allies win the war,

02:47:44.920 --> 02:47:49.450
which was officially declared won on November 11th, 1918.

02:47:49.450 --> 02:47:52.090
Overall, in less than six months of fighting,

02:47:52.090 --> 02:47:56.380
the US suffered 53,402 battle deaths

02:47:56.380 --> 02:47:59.710
and another 63,114 people died

02:47:59.710 --> 02:48:01.930
from accidents and disease.

02:48:01.930 --> 02:48:04.480
The US promptly ended wartime contracts

02:48:04.480 --> 02:48:05.770
and brought troops home,

02:48:05.770 --> 02:48:08.080
but the US at the time lacked programs

02:48:08.080 --> 02:48:10.780
to help veterans readjust to civilian life.

02:48:10.780 --> 02:48:14.200
In January, 1919, the US joined the other allies

02:48:14.200 --> 02:48:16.210
in Paris to negotiate peace.

02:48:16.210 --> 02:48:19.210
President Wilson brought a list of 14 points,

02:48:19.210 --> 02:48:21.520
some of which ended up in the final agreement,

02:48:21.520 --> 02:48:24.610
including the creation of a League of Nations,

02:48:24.610 --> 02:48:28.750
the first worldwide intergovernmental organization dedicated

02:48:28.750 --> 02:48:30.790
to maintaining world peace.

02:48:30.790 --> 02:48:34.840
The Treaty of Versailles was signed on June 28th, 1919,

02:48:34.840 --> 02:48:37.540
but the US never ratified the treaty,

02:48:37.540 --> 02:48:40.630
and instead made a separate peace treaty with Germany.

02:48:40.630 --> 02:48:43.210
Wilson, a Democrat, had refused to bring

02:48:43.210 --> 02:48:45.970
any leading Republicans to the peace talks

02:48:45.970 --> 02:48:48.550
as he sought peace without victory.

02:48:48.550 --> 02:48:52.390
Republicans controlled the Senate after the election of 1918

02:48:52.390 --> 02:48:55.870
and were outraged that Wilson refused to discuss the war,

02:48:55.870 --> 02:48:59.410
as they wanted Germany's unconditional surrender.

02:48:59.410 --> 02:49:01.390
Because the Senators were divided,

02:49:01.390 --> 02:49:04.960
Democrats supporting Wilson against the Irreconcilables

02:49:04.960 --> 02:49:06.097
or the Republicans

02:49:06.097 --> 02:49:09.040
and some Democrats who were against the treaty,

02:49:09.040 --> 02:49:10.570
it proved impossible

02:49:10.570 --> 02:49:13.900
to obtain the 2/3 majority needed to pass.

02:49:13.900 --> 02:49:16.630
The Democrats who opposed the treaty represented those

02:49:16.630 --> 02:49:19.810
among the American public, mostly Irish Catholics

02:49:19.810 --> 02:49:22.590
and German Americans who were intensely opposed

02:49:22.590 --> 02:49:25.780
to the treaty because they thought it favored the British.

02:49:25.780 --> 02:49:28.390
On November 19th, 1919,

02:49:28.390 --> 02:49:30.490
for the first time in its history,

02:49:30.490 --> 02:49:32.980
the Senate rejected a peace treaty.

02:49:32.980 --> 02:49:35.740
Under Wilson's successor, Warren G. Harding,

02:49:35.740 --> 02:49:40.740
the US-German Peace Treaty was signed August 25th, 1921.

02:49:40.930 --> 02:49:44.620
The treaty allowed for American-German cooperation not under

02:49:44.620 --> 02:49:46.753
the purview of the League of Nations.

02:49:47.896 --> 02:49:51.730
(suspenseful music)

02:49:51.730 --> 02:49:53.230
After the First World War,

02:49:53.230 --> 02:49:55.750
the US entered a time of post-war recovery.

02:49:55.750 --> 02:49:58.720
The economy boomed, construction took off,

02:49:58.720 --> 02:50:00.910
and consumer goods like automobiles

02:50:00.910 --> 02:50:03.760
and electricity became far more accessible.

02:50:03.760 --> 02:50:06.520
The decade was a time of bold innovation

02:50:06.520 --> 02:50:10.240
and experimentation as well as significant backlash

02:50:10.240 --> 02:50:11.440
to these things from people

02:50:11.440 --> 02:50:12.790
who didn't like the direction

02:50:12.790 --> 02:50:15.160
the country's culture seemed to be taking.

02:50:15.160 --> 02:50:19.690
This tumultuous time became known as the Roaring Twenties.

02:50:19.690 --> 02:50:24.690
For the first time ever, in the 1920s, more Americans- 51%-

02:50:25.150 --> 02:50:28.810
lived in cities than in villages or on farms.

02:50:28.810 --> 02:50:31.060
New norms, which were the product of trends

02:50:31.060 --> 02:50:34.570
that had been building for decades transformed city life,

02:50:34.570 --> 02:50:36.280
particularly for women.

02:50:36.280 --> 02:50:38.888
At the start of the decade between 1/4

02:50:38.888 --> 02:50:42.070
and 1/3 of unmarried urban women workers lived alone

02:50:42.070 --> 02:50:43.300
in private apartments

02:50:43.300 --> 02:50:46.540
or boarding houses rather than at home with their parents

02:50:46.540 --> 02:50:48.820
according to old Victorian culture.

02:50:48.820 --> 02:50:53.170
These new women visited public amusements like dance halls,

02:50:53.170 --> 02:50:55.390
amusement parks, and movie theaters,

02:50:55.390 --> 02:50:57.880
which drew in young people going on dates.

02:50:57.880 --> 02:51:01.120
A structure that was replacing the old courting culture.

02:51:01.120 --> 02:51:03.220
People now had time for such things.

02:51:03.220 --> 02:51:05.680
As factories and shops mechanized,

02:51:05.680 --> 02:51:08.890
the urban blue collar worker was spending less time working.

02:51:08.890 --> 02:51:13.040
The average work week fell from 55.9 hours in 1900

02:51:13.040 --> 02:51:16.960
to 44.2 In 1929.

02:51:16.960 --> 02:51:20.440
While blue collar wages rose by 25%,

02:51:20.440 --> 02:51:24.310
many Americans had extra money to spend in the 1920s due

02:51:24.310 --> 02:51:27.310
to rising incomes and easily available credit,

02:51:27.310 --> 02:51:30.400
and it was becoming increasingly socially acceptable

02:51:30.400 --> 02:51:33.070
to spend money on consumer goods

02:51:33.070 --> 02:51:35.890
and accumulate debt on those goods even

02:51:35.890 --> 02:51:38.230
if they were not absolute necessities.

02:51:38.230 --> 02:51:42.128
The nation's total wealth more than doubled between 1920

02:51:42.128 --> 02:51:45.130
and 1929, people bought tickets to the movies

02:51:45.130 --> 02:51:48.940
to see stars like Charlie Chaplin and Rudolph Valentino.

02:51:48.940 --> 02:51:50.530
By the mid 1920s,

02:51:50.530 --> 02:51:54.280
movie theaters were selling 50 million tickets each week,

02:51:54.280 --> 02:51:58.120
a sum equal to roughly half the US population.

02:51:58.120 --> 02:51:59.980
They bought ready-to-wear fashion,

02:51:59.980 --> 02:52:01.600
which was being mass produced

02:52:01.600 --> 02:52:03.940
and therefore becoming more affordable.

02:52:03.940 --> 02:52:05.290
They bought radios.

02:52:05.290 --> 02:52:07.690
In the first ever live radio transmission

02:52:07.690 --> 02:52:09.498
to the public, radio station,

02:52:09.498 --> 02:52:12.460
KDKA in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania broadcast

02:52:12.460 --> 02:52:16.708
the presidential election results on November 2nd, 1920.

02:52:16.708 --> 02:52:18.280
By the end of the 1920s,

02:52:18.280 --> 02:52:21.940
there were radios in more than 12 million households.

02:52:21.940 --> 02:52:24.510
In 1912, an estimated 16%

02:52:24.510 --> 02:52:27.130
of American households had electricity.

02:52:27.130 --> 02:52:30.850
By the mid 1920s, more than 60% did.

02:52:30.850 --> 02:52:33.190
Appliances that required electricity

02:52:33.190 --> 02:52:34.720
like the washing machine,

02:52:34.720 --> 02:52:38.560
the freezer and the vacuum cleaner were popular purchases

02:52:38.560 --> 02:52:40.180
and people bought automobiles,

02:52:40.180 --> 02:52:41.980
which were an affordable luxury.

02:52:41.980 --> 02:52:46.300
The Ford Model T cost $260 in 1924,

02:52:46.300 --> 02:52:49.870
which translates to just about $4,000 today.

02:52:49.870 --> 02:52:52.330
But even as some people were experiencing wealth

02:52:52.330 --> 02:52:55.720
and prosperity, others were struggling to get by.

02:52:55.720 --> 02:52:57.730
Extreme wealth inequality,

02:52:57.730 --> 02:52:59.350
which had troubled the progressives

02:52:59.350 --> 02:53:02.230
and defined the Gilded Age persisted.

02:53:02.230 --> 02:53:06.130
The income of the top 0.1% of families equaled the income

02:53:06.130 --> 02:53:09.100
of the bottom 42% during the '20s

02:53:09.100 --> 02:53:11.680
and over 40% of Americans got by

02:53:11.680 --> 02:53:14.680
on less than $1,500 each year,

02:53:14.680 --> 02:53:17.140
or the poverty line at the time.

02:53:17.140 --> 02:53:18.370
Most people living outside

02:53:18.370 --> 02:53:20.860
of cities did not experience the prosperity

02:53:20.860 --> 02:53:22.450
of the Roaring Twenties.

02:53:22.450 --> 02:53:26.110
Farm prices hit rock bottom in the aftermath of World War I.

02:53:26.110 --> 02:53:28.810
The proliferation of cars meant people were more able

02:53:28.810 --> 02:53:30.610
to travel wherever they wanted

02:53:30.610 --> 02:53:33.460
and many of the young people of the day wanted to go out

02:53:33.460 --> 02:53:35.380
and dance at jazz clubs.

02:53:35.380 --> 02:53:38.170
Jazz music was brought north by Black artists

02:53:38.170 --> 02:53:41.290
who had come from New Orleans where the form originated.

02:53:41.290 --> 02:53:44.080
Chicago became the art form's new center

02:53:44.080 --> 02:53:47.560
with the city boasting more than 100 jazz clubs.

02:53:47.560 --> 02:53:49.870
Whites and Blacks began mixing socially

02:53:49.870 --> 02:53:53.560
for the first time in the Black &amp; Tan Clubs of Chicago.

02:53:53.560 --> 02:53:55.457
Poet Langston Hughes wrote that,

02:53:55.457 --> 02:53:57.430
"Midnight was like day,"

02:53:57.430 --> 02:54:00.250
referring to the city's music-filled nightlife.

02:54:00.250 --> 02:54:02.680
Musicians such as Louis Armstrong,

02:54:02.680 --> 02:54:05.680
Jelly Roll Morton and Ethel Waters drew crowds

02:54:05.680 --> 02:54:07.660
to dance halls and people danced

02:54:07.660 --> 02:54:10.510
in new African American inspired styles.

02:54:10.510 --> 02:54:13.330
The Charleston, the cakewalk, the turkey trot,

02:54:13.330 --> 02:54:16.900
and the flea hop were all popular dances of the time.

02:54:16.900 --> 02:54:19.840
Some major dance clubs at the time were the Cotton Club

02:54:19.840 --> 02:54:23.020
in Harlem, New York where Duke Ellington's band played,

02:54:23.020 --> 02:54:25.480
and the Grand Terrace Cafe in Chicago

02:54:25.480 --> 02:54:27.460
where Earl Hines' band played.

02:54:27.460 --> 02:54:30.700
Later, the center of jazz music moved to New York City

02:54:30.700 --> 02:54:34.120
where the Harlem Renaissance was in full swing,

02:54:34.120 --> 02:54:37.720
but because jazz music was pioneered by African Americans

02:54:37.720 --> 02:54:41.020
and represented a departure from traditionally white forms

02:54:41.020 --> 02:54:44.200
of music, significant backlash built in response

02:54:44.200 --> 02:54:46.360
to jazz's rising popularity.

02:54:46.360 --> 02:54:49.900
People decreed for the supposed moral disasters

02:54:49.900 --> 02:54:52.510
it created, its roots in Black culture,

02:54:52.510 --> 02:54:55.300
and some termed it the devil's music.

02:54:55.300 --> 02:54:56.980
By the end of the 1920s,

02:54:56.980 --> 02:55:00.670
at least 60 communities across the nation had banned jazz

02:55:00.670 --> 02:55:02.800
from being played in public dance halls.

02:55:02.800 --> 02:55:04.840
Radio stations carried jazz tunes

02:55:04.840 --> 02:55:06.700
to listeners across the nation

02:55:06.700 --> 02:55:10.270
and 100 million jazz phonograph records were sold

02:55:10.270 --> 02:55:12.850
in 1927 alone.

02:55:12.850 --> 02:55:14.320
But because of discrimination

02:55:14.320 --> 02:55:17.590
and racism, these were mainly recordings of white bands

02:55:17.590 --> 02:55:19.810
that sounded similar to the Black musicians

02:55:19.810 --> 02:55:21.460
who pioneered the genre.

02:55:21.460 --> 02:55:24.280
Thomas Edison, the inventor of the phonograph,

02:55:24.280 --> 02:55:26.710
ridiculed jazz music saying

02:55:26.710 --> 02:55:28.900
it sounded better played backwards.

02:55:28.900 --> 02:55:30.340
And Shaw Faulkner,

02:55:30.340 --> 02:55:33.370
president of the General Federation of Women's Clubs,

02:55:33.370 --> 02:55:35.830
a powerful alliance of women, social,

02:55:35.830 --> 02:55:37.210
and reform groups that launched

02:55:37.210 --> 02:55:40.450
a crusade against jazz in 1921,

02:55:40.450 --> 02:55:43.630
once said that jazz was originally the accompaniment

02:55:43.630 --> 02:55:47.710
of the voodoo dance, stimulating half crazed barbarians

02:55:47.710 --> 02:55:49.750
to the vilest of deeds.

02:55:49.750 --> 02:55:52.630
The increasing visibility of Black culture and jazz

02:55:52.630 --> 02:55:55.660
and blues music, as well as the appearance of millions

02:55:55.660 --> 02:55:57.460
of African Americans who moved north

02:55:57.460 --> 02:55:59.140
during the Great Migration

02:55:59.140 --> 02:56:02.200
inspired significant racist backlash.

02:56:02.200 --> 02:56:06.310
Millions of people joined the Ku Klux Klan in the 1920s,

02:56:06.310 --> 02:56:10.420
raising its membership to five million by 1925.

02:56:10.420 --> 02:56:13.360
By mid decade, the group was in control of the governments

02:56:13.360 --> 02:56:17.440
of Indiana, Texas, Oklahoma, and Colorado,

02:56:17.440 --> 02:56:20.710
and was enormously powerful in several other states,

02:56:20.710 --> 02:56:23.050
including California and Georgia.

02:56:23.050 --> 02:56:26.200
The fundamentalist, conservative paramilitary group

02:56:26.200 --> 02:56:28.930
initiated white supremacist violence

02:56:28.930 --> 02:56:32.050
and also targeted Jews, Catholics, Asians,

02:56:32.050 --> 02:56:34.690
and the so-called new women.

02:56:34.690 --> 02:56:36.430
One of the worst instances

02:56:36.430 --> 02:56:40.840
of violence was the Tulsa race massacre in 1921 when

02:56:40.840 --> 02:56:43.390
a mob burned the Black neighborhood of Greenwood

02:56:43.390 --> 02:56:47.440
in Tulsa, Oklahoma to the ground killing dozens.

02:56:47.440 --> 02:56:52.090
The KKK only grew in power in Oklahoma after the incident.

02:56:52.090 --> 02:56:54.880
In general, the '20s were a time characterized

02:56:54.880 --> 02:56:58.180
by nativism and anti-immigrant feelings.

02:56:58.180 --> 02:57:01.150
A red scare in which people attempted to hunt,

02:57:01.150 --> 02:57:05.333
expose, and prosecute communists occurred from 1919 to 1920

02:57:06.370 --> 02:57:10.480
and the Klan-backed National Origins Act of 1924

02:57:10.480 --> 02:57:13.360
severely restricted immigration from Eastern Europe

02:57:13.360 --> 02:57:15.550
and Asia, while favoring immigrants

02:57:15.550 --> 02:57:17.950
from Northern Europe and Great Britain.

02:57:17.950 --> 02:57:21.010
The federal prohibition of alcohol in 1920,

02:57:21.010 --> 02:57:22.690
which banned the production and sale

02:57:22.690 --> 02:57:26.470
of alcoholic beverages nationwide was as much inspired

02:57:26.470 --> 02:57:29.710
by reformers wishing to cure the country's ills of poverty

02:57:29.710 --> 02:57:31.480
and violence as by those

02:57:31.480 --> 02:57:33.640
who were against the growing population

02:57:33.640 --> 02:57:36.400
of urban-dwelling immigrants in the US.

02:57:36.400 --> 02:57:39.580
Anti-German sentiment after World War I inspired

02:57:39.580 --> 02:57:41.560
the nickname Kaiser Brew

02:57:41.560 --> 02:57:43.990
for the Beer made in German breweries.

02:57:43.990 --> 02:57:45.850
Beer, as well as wine, whiskey,

02:57:45.850 --> 02:57:48.820
and gin were all banned under the statute,

02:57:48.820 --> 02:57:51.580
but enforcement proved nearly impossible

02:57:51.580 --> 02:57:53.230
for the federal government.

02:57:53.230 --> 02:57:57.010
Smuggling and bootlegging were widespread and speakeasies,

02:57:57.010 --> 02:58:00.070
or secret clubs that served illegal alcohol,

02:58:00.070 --> 02:58:01.510
popped up in cities.

02:58:01.510 --> 02:58:06.510
In 1927, there were an estimated 30,000 illegal speakeasies,

02:58:07.330 --> 02:58:10.990
twice the number of legal bars before prohibition.

02:58:10.990 --> 02:58:13.810
Federal agents conducted raids on these establishments,

02:58:13.810 --> 02:58:15.310
looking for lawbreakers,

02:58:15.310 --> 02:58:17.830
but prosecuting the cases proved tricky.

02:58:17.830 --> 02:58:19.960
In New York, 7,000 arrests

02:58:19.960 --> 02:58:24.220
for liquor law violations resulted in 17 convictions.

02:58:24.220 --> 02:58:26.740
Organized crimes such as mafia groups

02:58:26.740 --> 02:58:28.690
and gangs worked a profitable

02:58:28.690 --> 02:58:31.300
and violent black market for alcohol,

02:58:31.300 --> 02:58:33.370
which flourished as consumer demand

02:58:33.370 --> 02:58:36.340
went unmet via legitimate means.

02:58:36.340 --> 02:58:38.440
These organizations operated in part

02:58:38.440 --> 02:58:42.010
by bribing police officers and federal investigators.

02:58:42.010 --> 02:58:45.326
Al Capone Chicago organization reportedly took

02:58:45.326 --> 02:58:49.180
in $60 million in 1927

02:58:49.180 --> 02:58:52.150
and had half the city's police on its payroll.

02:58:52.150 --> 02:58:54.910
John D. Rockefeller, who did not drink,

02:58:54.910 --> 02:58:56.950
observed in 1932 that

02:58:56.950 --> 02:59:00.940
because of prohibition, drinking has generally increased,

02:59:00.940 --> 02:59:03.550
the speakeasy has replaced the saloon,

02:59:03.550 --> 02:59:06.610
and a vast army of lawbreakers has been recruited

02:59:06.610 --> 02:59:09.370
and financed on a colossal scale.

02:59:09.370 --> 02:59:11.530
While that may have been true anecdotally,

02:59:11.530 --> 02:59:13.900
other reports suggest that nationwide,

02:59:13.900 --> 02:59:16.720
drinking actually decreased during prohibition.

02:59:16.720 --> 02:59:18.280
According to statistics,

02:59:18.280 --> 02:59:20.260
drinking-related deaths from cirrhosis

02:59:20.260 --> 02:59:24.820
of the liver in men fell between 1911 and 1929.

02:59:24.820 --> 02:59:26.380
Further, it has been found

02:59:26.380 --> 02:59:29.380
that alcohol consumption levels did not rebound

02:59:29.380 --> 02:59:33.163
to their pre-prohibition levels until the 1960s.

02:59:34.506 --> 02:59:37.720
(suspenseful music)

02:59:37.720 --> 02:59:40.240
All good times must come to an end,

02:59:40.240 --> 02:59:41.980
decreased consumer demand,

02:59:41.980 --> 02:59:44.680
you can only buy so many cars and radios,

02:59:44.680 --> 02:59:46.840
and mounting consumer debt coupled

02:59:46.840 --> 02:59:49.300
with overconfidence in buying stocks,

02:59:49.300 --> 02:59:51.640
meant stock was highly overvalued.

02:59:51.640 --> 02:59:54.640
On what would become known as Black Thursday,

02:59:54.640 --> 02:59:57.520
October 24th, 1929,

02:59:57.520 --> 02:59:59.650
the stock market crashed,

02:59:59.650 --> 03:00:04.650
triggering the worst economic downturn in American history.

03:00:04.750 --> 03:00:07.120
The Great Depression, which marked the end

03:00:07.120 --> 03:00:11.170
of the over-consumptive, freewheeling roaring '20s.

03:00:11.170 --> 03:00:14.380
Millions of stock shares ended up being worthless

03:00:14.380 --> 03:00:16.540
and consumer confidence vanished.

03:00:16.540 --> 03:00:19.870
The resulting decrease in consumer spending caused factories

03:00:19.870 --> 03:00:22.660
to slow production, laying off workers.

03:00:22.660 --> 03:00:25.750
By 1930, four million Americans looking

03:00:25.750 --> 03:00:27.460
for work could not find it,

03:00:27.460 --> 03:00:30.940
and by 1931, that number was six million.

03:00:30.940 --> 03:00:33.820
Many Americans with debt were unable to pay it off

03:00:33.820 --> 03:00:35.860
and had their homes foreclosed upon.

03:00:35.860 --> 03:00:37.840
Homelessness became more common.

03:00:37.840 --> 03:00:40.360
The construction of the Empire State Building,

03:00:40.360 --> 03:00:42.580
which would be the first building in the world

03:00:42.580 --> 03:00:44.770
to have more than 100 floors,

03:00:44.770 --> 03:00:46.900
had broken ground only a few weeks

03:00:46.900 --> 03:00:48.700
before the stock market crash.

03:00:48.700 --> 03:00:50.830
Many tall buildings were being planned

03:00:50.830 --> 03:00:53.560
and constructed during the late 1920s,

03:00:53.560 --> 03:00:56.860
a facet of the optimism inherent to the period.

03:00:56.860 --> 03:00:58.630
This race into the sky

03:00:58.630 --> 03:01:01.000
included five other proposed buildings,

03:01:01.000 --> 03:01:04.592
but only the Empire State Building would make it due

03:01:04.592 --> 03:01:06.250
to the crash of 1929.

03:01:06.250 --> 03:01:08.827
The project was completed in just one year

03:01:08.827 --> 03:01:12.490
and 45 days, a record setting speed.

03:01:12.490 --> 03:01:14.410
But because of the Great Depression,

03:01:14.410 --> 03:01:17.350
there was virtually no demand for office space,

03:01:17.350 --> 03:01:21.100
and the building sat mostly empty until the 1940s.

03:01:21.100 --> 03:01:24.310
In addition to the economic woes, in 1930,

03:01:24.310 --> 03:01:27.760
severe drought swept from Texas to Nebraska,

03:01:27.760 --> 03:01:29.350
bringing with it high winds

03:01:29.350 --> 03:01:32.740
and dust that killed people, livestock and crops.

03:01:32.740 --> 03:01:35.470
This became known as the Dust Bowl,

03:01:35.470 --> 03:01:37.420
and it inspired many more people

03:01:37.420 --> 03:01:39.010
to migrate from the plains

03:01:39.010 --> 03:01:41.020
to the cities in search of work.

03:01:41.020 --> 03:01:43.540
From 1930 to 1933,

03:01:43.540 --> 03:01:47.650
the economic crisis only continued to get worse as thousands

03:01:47.650 --> 03:01:49.540
of banks were forced to close.

03:01:49.540 --> 03:01:52.540
President Herbert Hoover tried supporting the failing banks,

03:01:52.540 --> 03:01:54.250
but Hoover was a Republican

03:01:54.250 --> 03:01:56.890
who believed the government should not directly intervene

03:01:56.890 --> 03:02:00.310
in the economy or provide economic relief.

03:02:00.310 --> 03:02:02.230
In 1932 with close

03:02:02.230 --> 03:02:06.250
to 15 million people unemployed nationwide,

03:02:06.250 --> 03:02:08.590
voters overwhelmingly elected

03:02:08.590 --> 03:02:12.910
Democrat Franklin D. Roosevelt, who took immediate action.

03:02:12.910 --> 03:02:15.490
During his first 100 days in office,

03:02:15.490 --> 03:02:18.880
the Roosevelt Administration passed legislation to reform

03:02:18.880 --> 03:02:22.150
and reopen banks, stabilize industrial,

03:02:22.150 --> 03:02:25.510
and agricultural production, and create jobs.

03:02:25.510 --> 03:02:30.510
The unemployment rate in 1935 was at a staggering 20%,

03:02:30.700 --> 03:02:32.830
so via executive order,

03:02:32.830 --> 03:02:35.770
Roosevelt created a permanent jobs program called

03:02:35.770 --> 03:02:38.350
the Works Progress Administration.

03:02:38.350 --> 03:02:40.930
From 1935 to 1943,

03:02:40.930 --> 03:02:44.920
the WPA employed 8.5 million people,

03:02:44.920 --> 03:02:47.200
building schools, hospitals, roads,

03:02:47.200 --> 03:02:50.470
and other public works, as well as in arts projects,

03:02:50.470 --> 03:02:53.680
employing tens of thousands of actors, musicians,

03:02:53.680 --> 03:02:55.510
writers, and other artists.

03:02:55.510 --> 03:02:57.850
At its height in late 1938,

03:02:57.850 --> 03:03:02.830
more than 3.3 million Americans worked for the WPA.

03:03:02.830 --> 03:03:05.860
They built more than 4,000 new school buildings,

03:03:05.860 --> 03:03:08.590
erected 130 new hospitals,

03:03:08.590 --> 03:03:11.980
laid roughly 9,000 miles of storm drains

03:03:11.980 --> 03:03:15.760
and sewer lines, built 29,000 new bridges,

03:03:15.760 --> 03:03:18.610
constructed 150 new air fields,

03:03:18.610 --> 03:03:22.390
paved or repaired 280,000 miles of road,

03:03:22.390 --> 03:03:26.140
and planted 24 million trees to alleviate loss

03:03:26.140 --> 03:03:28.150
of topsoil during the Dust Bowl.

03:03:28.150 --> 03:03:29.950
Among the most famous projects built

03:03:29.950 --> 03:03:33.790
by the WPA are the Hoover Dam on the Colorado River,

03:03:33.790 --> 03:03:35.680
New York City's Lincoln Tunnel,

03:03:35.680 --> 03:03:37.960
the LaGuardia Airport in Queens,

03:03:37.960 --> 03:03:42.490
and the iconic red San Francisco-Oakland Bay Bridge.

03:03:42.490 --> 03:03:45.160
New Deal funds were also used for the construction

03:03:45.160 --> 03:03:47.290
of Mount Rushmore in South Dakota.

03:03:47.290 --> 03:03:50.590
US Presidents George Washington, Thomas Jefferson,

03:03:50.590 --> 03:03:53.710
Theodore Roosevelt, and Abraham Lincoln into the side

03:03:53.710 --> 03:03:58.090
of the mountain were carved by a total of about 400 artists.

03:03:58.090 --> 03:04:00.340
Tools were forged by blacksmiths

03:04:00.340 --> 03:04:03.340
and tramway operators shuttled people and equipment to

03:04:03.340 --> 03:04:05.770
and from the base of the remote mountain.

03:04:05.770 --> 03:04:08.353
The project cost nearly $1 million,

03:04:09.190 --> 03:04:12.670
about 85% of which was from federal funds.

03:04:12.670 --> 03:04:15.970
The WPA was criticized for the project's slowness

03:04:15.970 --> 03:04:18.790
and inefficiencies, but it was celebrated

03:04:18.790 --> 03:04:20.680
for the employment it offered millions

03:04:20.680 --> 03:04:23.200
of people suffering during the depression.

03:04:23.200 --> 03:04:26.080
Other notable New Deal programs included the creation

03:04:26.080 --> 03:04:28.420
of the Social Security Administration

03:04:28.420 --> 03:04:31.060
to protect older Americans financially,

03:04:31.060 --> 03:04:34.330
the Agricultural Adjustment Act to help farmers get out

03:04:34.330 --> 03:04:37.270
of debt, and the US Housing Authority was created

03:04:37.270 --> 03:04:38.950
to address homelessness.

03:04:38.950 --> 03:04:40.960
The National Labor Relations Act

03:04:40.960 --> 03:04:44.530
was passed to protect labor organizing in 1935

03:04:44.530 --> 03:04:48.910
and the Fair Labor Standards Act of 1938 set maximum hours

03:04:48.910 --> 03:04:51.190
and minimum wages for most workers.

03:04:51.190 --> 03:04:54.580
But not everyone was a fan of Roosevelt's reforms

03:04:54.580 --> 03:04:55.930
with conservative opponents

03:04:55.930 --> 03:04:58.240
calling them government overreach.

03:04:58.240 --> 03:05:00.850
After the elections of 1938,

03:05:00.850 --> 03:05:04.000
New Deal policies became more difficult to enact

03:05:04.000 --> 03:05:06.670
because the new Congress was less liberal

03:05:06.670 --> 03:05:08.620
and less supportive of spending.

03:05:08.620 --> 03:05:10.840
The election of these new conservative members

03:05:10.840 --> 03:05:12.490
of the Congress was largely due

03:05:12.490 --> 03:05:13.930
to a dip in public opinion

03:05:13.930 --> 03:05:16.060
towards the Roosevelt Administration

03:05:16.060 --> 03:05:20.890
during the economic recession of 1937 to 1938.

03:05:20.890 --> 03:05:22.960
With Roosevelt claiming responsibility

03:05:22.960 --> 03:05:25.600
for the previous economic improvements,

03:05:25.600 --> 03:05:27.640
people blamed him for the backslide.

03:05:27.640 --> 03:05:30.430
Nevertheless, the New Deal's popularity helped

03:05:30.430 --> 03:05:33.070
the Democratic Party remain the majority party

03:05:33.070 --> 03:05:36.643
in national politics into the 1960s.

03:05:38.095 --> 03:05:40.678
(tense music)

03:05:41.620 --> 03:05:45.910
When the Second World War kicked off in Europe in fall 1939,

03:05:45.910 --> 03:05:48.250
the vast majority of Americans were still

03:05:48.250 --> 03:05:49.840
in favor of isolation.

03:05:49.840 --> 03:05:52.660
President Roosevelt, however, realized the importance

03:05:52.660 --> 03:05:53.800
of ensuring that Britain

03:05:53.800 --> 03:05:57.340
and France had every chance of success in the conflict.

03:05:57.340 --> 03:06:00.730
When France fell completely in June, 1940,

03:06:00.730 --> 03:06:03.940
Roosevelt began implementing a Lend-Lease program

03:06:03.940 --> 03:06:06.190
with the British, sending war material

03:06:06.190 --> 03:06:09.160
and humanitarian supplies on American ships.

03:06:09.160 --> 03:06:14.160
On December 7th, 1941, the Japanese fleet at last appeared

03:06:14.590 --> 03:06:16.900
and struck at the American Naval base

03:06:16.900 --> 03:06:18.760
in Pearl Harbor, Hawaii.

03:06:18.760 --> 03:06:20.770
The attack did serious damage

03:06:20.770 --> 03:06:23.380
to the fleet, destroying three battleships,

03:06:23.380 --> 03:06:25.510
and damaging several other vessels.

03:06:25.510 --> 03:06:28.000
However, the Japanese were unsuccessful

03:06:28.000 --> 03:06:31.150
in destroying the American aircraft carriers.

03:06:31.150 --> 03:06:34.390
The attack shocked and appalled Americans.

03:06:34.390 --> 03:06:36.520
Japan had hoped the attack would cripple

03:06:36.520 --> 03:06:39.010
the American Pacific fleet and allow them

03:06:39.010 --> 03:06:41.920
to swiftly take control of the Pacific Theater.

03:06:41.920 --> 03:06:46.120
Instead, the Americans recovered with nearly inhuman speed

03:06:46.120 --> 03:06:47.980
and in less than six months,

03:06:47.980 --> 03:06:51.550
struck a devastating blow against the Japanese Navy

03:06:51.550 --> 03:06:53.110
at the Battle of Midway..

03:06:53.110 --> 03:06:55.840
The American victory at Midway opened the Pacific

03:06:55.840 --> 03:06:57.160
to the US fleet

03:06:57.160 --> 03:07:00.160
and allowed for US ground troops to be safely shuttled

03:07:00.160 --> 03:07:02.260
to Japanese-held islands.

03:07:02.260 --> 03:07:05.950
In Europe, following the general declaration of war on Japan

03:07:05.950 --> 03:07:08.200
after Pearl Harbor, Adolf Hitler,

03:07:08.200 --> 03:07:09.940
the leader of Nazi Germany,

03:07:09.940 --> 03:07:12.370
declared war on the United States,

03:07:12.370 --> 03:07:14.470
joining his Axis ally.

03:07:14.470 --> 03:07:17.440
The United States, now a part of the Allied Powers,

03:07:17.440 --> 03:07:19.810
was eager to help Britain regain control

03:07:19.810 --> 03:07:21.370
of the European Theater.

03:07:21.370 --> 03:07:23.590
The War Department began planning a series

03:07:23.590 --> 03:07:26.650
of military operations to retake North Africa

03:07:26.650 --> 03:07:28.810
and Europe from fascist control,

03:07:28.810 --> 03:07:32.170
whilst simultaneously planned for a prolonged invasion

03:07:32.170 --> 03:07:35.950
of the dozens of islands in the Pacific to aid Australia

03:07:35.950 --> 03:07:38.200
and the Philippines from Japan.

03:07:38.200 --> 03:07:40.870
The United States was again at war

03:07:40.870 --> 03:07:43.840
and this time facing enemies on two separate fronts

03:07:43.840 --> 03:07:45.250
on a global scale.

03:07:45.250 --> 03:07:49.540
The entire country mobilized, with millions of men enlisting

03:07:49.540 --> 03:07:52.510
to serve, and the millions left on the home front adapting

03:07:52.510 --> 03:07:54.040
to produce war material

03:07:54.040 --> 03:07:56.500
and other goods to support the war effort.

03:07:56.500 --> 03:07:58.960
Sadly, the fear and xenophobia

03:07:58.960 --> 03:08:00.970
towards Asian Americans caused

03:08:00.970 --> 03:08:04.060
by the Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor led Roosevelt

03:08:04.060 --> 03:08:07.780
to issue Executive Order 9066,

03:08:07.780 --> 03:08:10.960
ordering the internment of any and all citizens

03:08:10.960 --> 03:08:14.320
who posed a national security threat to the country.

03:08:14.320 --> 03:08:15.820
With much of the West Coast

03:08:15.820 --> 03:08:18.670
of the United States divided into military districts

03:08:18.670 --> 03:08:21.550
for the prosecution of an overseas war,

03:08:21.550 --> 03:08:25.570
over 120,000 Japanese Americans,

03:08:25.570 --> 03:08:28.870
more than 2/3 of them born in the United States,

03:08:28.870 --> 03:08:30.580
were removed from their homes

03:08:30.580 --> 03:08:32.860
and settled into camps further inland

03:08:32.860 --> 03:08:37.090
and away from US Military operations along the West Coast.

03:08:37.090 --> 03:08:38.800
Roosevelt's administration,

03:08:38.800 --> 03:08:40.750
as well as the Army High Command,

03:08:40.750 --> 03:08:42.640
immediately realized the importance

03:08:42.640 --> 03:08:45.400
of liberating Europe as soon as possible.

03:08:45.400 --> 03:08:47.800
The early victory against the Japanese Navy

03:08:47.800 --> 03:08:50.560
at Midway gave the US Armed forces a chance

03:08:50.560 --> 03:08:53.410
to reassess their strategy in the Pacific while planning

03:08:53.410 --> 03:08:55.180
for operations in Europe.

03:08:55.180 --> 03:08:57.760
After some debate, North Africa was chosen

03:08:57.760 --> 03:09:00.040
as the first landing site for US troops

03:09:00.040 --> 03:09:03.010
to begin the liberation of the allies in Europe.

03:09:03.010 --> 03:09:07.450
In fall 1942, the Allies launched Operation Torch

03:09:07.450 --> 03:09:10.000
to strike a quick and decisive blow against

03:09:10.000 --> 03:09:12.760
the Axis-controlled North African coast.

03:09:12.760 --> 03:09:16.390
The assault was a massive multinational operation involving

03:09:16.390 --> 03:09:20.380
the United States, the United Kingdom, India, Canada,

03:09:20.380 --> 03:09:24.190
the Netherlands, free France, and Australian forces.

03:09:24.190 --> 03:09:27.130
Over the course of a week, the Allied Powers fought

03:09:27.130 --> 03:09:30.430
for control of major ports along the African coast

03:09:30.430 --> 03:09:32.710
and were successful in occupying much

03:09:32.710 --> 03:09:34.600
of Morocco and Algiers.

03:09:34.600 --> 03:09:38.200
Operation Torch was the first step in an Allied advance,

03:09:38.200 --> 03:09:41.770
which would gradually take control over all of North Africa

03:09:41.770 --> 03:09:44.920
and move on to Italy by the fall of 1943.

03:09:44.920 --> 03:09:47.230
In the Pacific, US forces embarked on

03:09:47.230 --> 03:09:49.480
what was known as an island hopping

03:09:49.480 --> 03:09:51.550
or leapfrogging campaign.

03:09:51.550 --> 03:09:52.690
Utilizing the strength

03:09:52.690 --> 03:09:55.510
and speed of the US Navy, the Americans were able

03:09:55.510 --> 03:09:57.490
to quickly deploy US marines

03:09:57.490 --> 03:09:59.050
and army forces on the hundreds

03:09:59.050 --> 03:10:01.330
of islands under Japanese control.

03:10:01.330 --> 03:10:02.950
across the South Pacific.

03:10:02.950 --> 03:10:04.450
The strategy worked well,

03:10:04.450 --> 03:10:07.630
keeping the Japanese forces under constant threat of attack

03:10:07.630 --> 03:10:10.510
and slowly choking their ability to reinforce

03:10:10.510 --> 03:10:12.490
and supply important islands.

03:10:12.490 --> 03:10:14.770
The Japanese were often forced to take shelter

03:10:14.770 --> 03:10:17.740
and fight for every square inch of ground without hope

03:10:17.740 --> 03:10:19.570
of reprieve or escape.

03:10:19.570 --> 03:10:23.740
Over the course of two years, beginning in the fall of 1942,

03:10:23.740 --> 03:10:28.090
the US Armed Forces fought brutal campaigns at Guadalcanal,

03:10:28.090 --> 03:10:33.070
Saipan, Peleliu, Iwo Jima, and Okinawa, and many others.

03:10:33.070 --> 03:10:34.960
In Europe with the fall of Italy,

03:10:34.960 --> 03:10:37.180
the US and the allies turned their attention

03:10:37.180 --> 03:10:39.820
to liberating France from Nazi control.

03:10:39.820 --> 03:10:41.950
On the other side of the European continent,

03:10:41.950 --> 03:10:44.590
the Soviet Union had at long last repulsed

03:10:44.590 --> 03:10:46.630
the German invasion of their homeland,

03:10:46.630 --> 03:10:49.930
and were steadily pushing the Nazis back toward Germany.

03:10:49.930 --> 03:10:51.610
Seizing on the opportunity,

03:10:51.610 --> 03:10:53.620
American and British strategists planned

03:10:53.620 --> 03:10:57.700
for an audacious amphibious assault on the Normandy beaches

03:10:57.700 --> 03:10:59.350
in the North of France.

03:10:59.350 --> 03:11:02.740
Under the direction of General Dwight D. Eisenhower,

03:11:02.740 --> 03:11:05.920
the Allied Forces launched Operation Neptune,

03:11:05.920 --> 03:11:10.387
more popularly known as D-Day, on June 6th, 1944.

03:11:11.740 --> 03:11:14.260
Like Operation Torch in North Africa,

03:11:14.260 --> 03:11:17.050
D-Day was a multinational assault

03:11:17.050 --> 03:11:19.390
and included most of the allied powers

03:11:19.390 --> 03:11:22.810
with significant contributions from American, British,

03:11:22.810 --> 03:11:26.290
Canadian, Australian, and French forces.

03:11:26.290 --> 03:11:29.320
Undoubtedly one of the most well-known moments

03:11:29.320 --> 03:11:32.890
of the Second World War, D-Day represented the pinnacle

03:11:32.890 --> 03:11:34.780
of Allied cooperation

03:11:34.780 --> 03:11:37.810
and marked the beginning of the end for Hitler's Germany

03:11:37.810 --> 03:11:39.430
and the Axis powers.

03:11:39.430 --> 03:11:42.370
It did not take long for the German occupation of France

03:11:42.370 --> 03:11:43.690
to collapse under the weight

03:11:43.690 --> 03:11:46.510
of the Allied Liberation following D-Day.

03:11:46.510 --> 03:11:48.640
By the winter of 1944,

03:11:48.640 --> 03:11:51.370
Allied forces had pushed the Nazi troops to the border

03:11:51.370 --> 03:11:54.520
of France and Germany and prepared for winter engagements

03:11:54.520 --> 03:11:56.320
through the Ardennes Forest.

03:11:56.320 --> 03:11:59.020
As the Soviets continued their relentless assault

03:11:59.020 --> 03:12:03.520
in the East, Hitler diverted critical military assets west,

03:12:03.520 --> 03:12:06.220
hoping to take the Allies by surprise.

03:12:06.220 --> 03:12:09.610
In December, 1944, German forces launched

03:12:09.610 --> 03:12:11.410
what would be their final offensive

03:12:11.410 --> 03:12:13.540
of the war through the Ardennes.

03:12:13.540 --> 03:12:16.030
The assault was initially successful,

03:12:16.030 --> 03:12:18.010
pushing Allied forces back.

03:12:18.010 --> 03:12:22.120
Fortunately, Allied Air superiority slowed the Nazi advance

03:12:22.120 --> 03:12:24.070
and grounded to a halt.

03:12:24.070 --> 03:12:26.140
When the offensive finally ended,

03:12:26.140 --> 03:12:29.020
the Germans had successfully nearly encircled

03:12:29.020 --> 03:12:32.920
a large pocket of US troops and dug in for the winter.

03:12:32.920 --> 03:12:35.890
In what would become known as the Battle of the Bulge,

03:12:35.890 --> 03:12:39.760
American forces endured relentless artillery bombardments,

03:12:39.760 --> 03:12:43.570
surprise attacks, and unforgiving weather conditions,

03:12:43.570 --> 03:12:45.220
but never gave up.

03:12:45.220 --> 03:12:46.780
When German forces demanded

03:12:46.780 --> 03:12:48.670
the American troops to surrender,

03:12:48.670 --> 03:12:50.860
their commanding officer allegedly replied

03:12:50.860 --> 03:12:53.530
with a single phrase, "Nuts."

03:12:53.530 --> 03:12:54.790
When spring came,

03:12:54.790 --> 03:12:57.370
so too did the Allied air support,

03:12:57.370 --> 03:12:59.470
and Germans were quickly pushed away

03:12:59.470 --> 03:13:01.120
and the pocket was relieved.

03:13:01.120 --> 03:13:03.340
With their resources exhausted,

03:13:03.340 --> 03:13:05.680
their troops surrendering in droves,

03:13:05.680 --> 03:13:09.400
and Allied forces pushing in from both east and west,

03:13:09.400 --> 03:13:11.980
Germany was at last close to surrender.

03:13:11.980 --> 03:13:14.350
It would take a few more months of fierce fighting

03:13:14.350 --> 03:13:16.930
until the Soviet troops reached Berlin.

03:13:16.930 --> 03:13:18.700
Hitler committed suicide

03:13:18.700 --> 03:13:21.760
and the pre-Nazi German government was restored

03:13:21.760 --> 03:13:25.030
as the war in Europe at last came to an end.

03:13:25.030 --> 03:13:29.260
In the Pacific, island after island fell to the US advance.

03:13:29.260 --> 03:13:33.400
By the spring of 1945, the US was preparing for an invasion

03:13:33.400 --> 03:13:35.650
of the Japanese home islands,

03:13:35.650 --> 03:13:37.840
a prospect that was not relished

03:13:37.840 --> 03:13:40.300
by the military or government alike.

03:13:40.300 --> 03:13:42.340
In April, 1945,

03:13:42.340 --> 03:13:45.580
President Franklin D. Roosevelt died suddenly,

03:13:45.580 --> 03:13:48.970
leaving the office to his Vice President Harry Truman.

03:13:48.970 --> 03:13:50.800
Truman was immediately informed

03:13:50.800 --> 03:13:53.650
of a top secret program which had been experimenting

03:13:53.650 --> 03:13:56.260
with the creation of an atomic weapon called

03:13:56.260 --> 03:13:58.060
the Manhattan Project.

03:13:58.060 --> 03:14:00.700
Led by Physicist Robert Oppenheimer,

03:14:00.700 --> 03:14:03.790
the project had brought together leading scientific minds

03:14:03.790 --> 03:14:05.470
from across the United States

03:14:05.470 --> 03:14:08.860
and beyond to develop an atomic weapon capable

03:14:08.860 --> 03:14:10.360
of ending the war.

03:14:10.360 --> 03:14:12.730
When Truman inherited the presidency,

03:14:12.730 --> 03:14:15.820
he inherited the decision to use the bomb.

03:14:15.820 --> 03:14:19.030
Faced with a Japanese Government unwilling to surrender

03:14:19.030 --> 03:14:22.210
and what would likely be an incredibly costly series

03:14:22.210 --> 03:14:23.860
of ground invasions,

03:14:23.860 --> 03:14:25.960
Truman green lit the use of the bombs

03:14:25.960 --> 03:14:28.930
as a way to avoid massive casualties.

03:14:28.930 --> 03:14:33.340
At 08:15 AM on August 6th, 1945,

03:14:33.340 --> 03:14:35.830
the United States dropped Little Boy,

03:14:35.830 --> 03:14:40.210
an enriched uranium bomb on the Japanese city of Hiroshima.

03:14:40.210 --> 03:14:43.180
It exploded roughly a mile above the city with the force

03:14:43.180 --> 03:14:46.330
of 15 kilotons of TNT.

03:14:46.330 --> 03:14:49.780
The initial blast destroyed everything within a mile

03:14:49.780 --> 03:14:51.460
of the bomb's detonation,

03:14:51.460 --> 03:14:52.630
with the exception of

03:14:52.630 --> 03:14:55.870
a few earthquake-resistant concrete structures.

03:14:55.870 --> 03:15:00.130
The 1,200 foot or 370 meter fireball produced

03:15:00.130 --> 03:15:04.090
by the explosion gave off a blinding flash of light

03:15:04.090 --> 03:15:07.060
and reached temperatures of 6,000 Celsius

03:15:07.060 --> 03:15:10.600
or 10,830 degrees Fahrenheit,

03:15:10.600 --> 03:15:13.210
the same as the surface of the sun.

03:15:13.210 --> 03:15:14.710
Individuals near the center

03:15:14.710 --> 03:15:17.680
of the blast were instantly vaporized,

03:15:17.680 --> 03:15:19.450
leaving behind only their shadows

03:15:19.450 --> 03:15:21.280
on the bleached white stone.

03:15:21.280 --> 03:15:23.590
The fireball reached roughly two miles

03:15:23.590 --> 03:15:26.230
or 3.2 kilometers in diameter,

03:15:26.230 --> 03:15:28.960
consuming everything in its path.

03:15:28.960 --> 03:15:32.530
The devastation caused by the bombing caused roughly 60%

03:15:32.530 --> 03:15:35.560
of the casualties with the remaining losses attributed

03:15:35.560 --> 03:15:37.030
to injury sustained

03:15:37.030 --> 03:15:40.510
and to the radiation, which spread from the explosion site.

03:15:40.510 --> 03:15:44.500
Roughly 80,000 to 140,000 civilians

03:15:44.500 --> 03:15:46.960
and military personnel were killed

03:15:46.960 --> 03:15:48.820
as a result of the bombing.

03:15:48.820 --> 03:15:52.240
As word of the full extent of the damage began to spread,

03:15:52.240 --> 03:15:56.350
the US Government again entreated the Japanese to surrender,

03:15:56.350 --> 03:15:59.170
threatening to drop yet another atomic weapon

03:15:59.170 --> 03:16:00.520
if they did not.

03:16:00.520 --> 03:16:03.100
Again, the Japanese Government refused

03:16:03.100 --> 03:16:05.740
and a second atomic bomb was dropped on the city

03:16:05.740 --> 03:16:08.440
of Nagasaki on August 9th.

03:16:08.440 --> 03:16:11.200
Fat Man, a plutonium bomb was dropped

03:16:11.200 --> 03:16:15.070
at 11:01 AM over Nagasaki's Industrial Valley

03:16:15.070 --> 03:16:19.240
and detonated 47 seconds later at 11:02.

03:16:19.240 --> 03:16:22.780
Fat Man exploded with the force of 21 Kilotons

03:16:22.780 --> 03:16:26.080
of TNT, 40% more than Little Boy had.

03:16:26.080 --> 03:16:28.120
However, due to weather conditions,

03:16:28.120 --> 03:16:30.790
the bombardiers had dropped the bomb further away

03:16:30.790 --> 03:16:33.850
from their intended target, causing much of the explosion

03:16:33.850 --> 03:16:36.400
to be contained by the mountains surrounding

03:16:36.400 --> 03:16:37.990
the industrial district.

03:16:37.990 --> 03:16:39.880
Like the bombing of Hiroshima,

03:16:39.880 --> 03:16:43.300
the blast and subsequent fireball consumed everything

03:16:43.300 --> 03:16:47.500
within the blast zone and caused the majority of casualties.

03:16:47.500 --> 03:16:51.160
Between 60,000 and 80,000 people were killed

03:16:51.160 --> 03:16:52.780
as a result of the bombing

03:16:52.780 --> 03:16:55.030
with hundreds of thousands wounded.

03:16:55.030 --> 03:16:57.130
In total, the bombings of Hiroshima

03:16:57.130 --> 03:17:00.417
and Nagasaki took the lives of an estimated 129,000

03:17:02.057 --> 03:17:05.500
to 226,000 individuals,

03:17:05.500 --> 03:17:08.440
the vast majority of whom were civilians.

03:17:08.440 --> 03:17:11.080
On August 10th, the Japanese Government signaled

03:17:11.080 --> 03:17:12.670
their willingness to surrender

03:17:12.670 --> 03:17:15.280
if their government could remain intact.

03:17:15.280 --> 03:17:18.130
The United States answered that the terms would be discussed

03:17:18.130 --> 03:17:20.740
after the Japanese formally surrendered.

03:17:20.740 --> 03:17:23.680
A brief military coup was attempted on the evening

03:17:23.680 --> 03:17:26.680
of August 14th by factions within the government

03:17:26.680 --> 03:17:28.960
who wished to fight to the bitter end.

03:17:28.960 --> 03:17:32.680
However, it was quickly put down by the Japanese Government.

03:17:32.680 --> 03:17:35.620
The following morning, the emperor of Japan issued

03:17:35.620 --> 03:17:37.960
a formal statement of surrender.

03:17:37.960 --> 03:17:41.290
The Second World War had finally come to an end.

03:17:41.290 --> 03:17:43.450
More than 16 million men

03:17:43.450 --> 03:17:46.360
and women served in the US Armed Forces over the course

03:17:46.360 --> 03:17:51.280
of the war and some 420,000 Americans had given their lives

03:17:51.280 --> 03:17:53.380
to help liberate the free world.

03:17:53.380 --> 03:17:56.380
In doing so, the United States had left its position

03:17:56.380 --> 03:18:01.240
on isolation behind and entered a new age of globalism.

03:18:01.240 --> 03:18:04.060
The United States was now a world power

03:18:04.060 --> 03:18:06.070
and held much of the responsibility

03:18:06.070 --> 03:18:08.860
of what would come next in its hands.

03:18:08.860 --> 03:18:11.020
While their alliance with the Soviet Union

03:18:11.020 --> 03:18:13.420
during the war had been one of necessity,

03:18:13.420 --> 03:18:15.400
relations had deteriorated even

03:18:15.400 --> 03:18:17.530
before the war had come to an end.

03:18:17.530 --> 03:18:20.770
Worse, with the unleashing of atomic weaponry,

03:18:20.770 --> 03:18:24.010
the United States had unwittingly brought on a new age

03:18:24.010 --> 03:18:26.410
of warfare and technology,

03:18:26.410 --> 03:18:29.563
one that would define the decades to follow.

03:18:30.751 --> 03:18:33.334
(tense music)

03:18:34.270 --> 03:18:36.760
Despite fighting together against Nazi Germany

03:18:36.760 --> 03:18:39.730
in World War II, the US and the Soviet Union

03:18:39.730 --> 03:18:41.950
were never truly friendly.

03:18:41.950 --> 03:18:44.830
The US was wary of the Soviet's communist system

03:18:44.830 --> 03:18:47.110
of government and the atrocities committed

03:18:47.110 --> 03:18:48.910
by leader Joseph Stalin.

03:18:48.910 --> 03:18:51.370
While the Soviets were angry that the US wanted

03:18:51.370 --> 03:18:52.870
to keep them from being a leader

03:18:52.870 --> 03:18:54.790
in the international community.

03:18:54.790 --> 03:18:57.610
While these grievances were fiercely held,

03:18:57.610 --> 03:19:00.850
the conflict that became the Cold War never developed

03:19:00.850 --> 03:19:04.270
into violence because of the threat of atomic weapons.

03:19:04.270 --> 03:19:07.810
The US adopted a policy known as Containment,

03:19:07.810 --> 03:19:09.910
which referred to stopping Russia's attempts

03:19:09.910 --> 03:19:13.210
to expand their reach and influence throughout the world.

03:19:13.210 --> 03:19:15.370
This strategy provided the rationale

03:19:15.370 --> 03:19:18.850
for never before seen arms build up in the US.

03:19:18.850 --> 03:19:21.040
The end of World War II had been hastened

03:19:21.040 --> 03:19:24.460
by atomic bombs dropped on Japanese cities Hiroshima

03:19:24.460 --> 03:19:28.870
and Nagasaki in 1945, demonstrating the US' power

03:19:28.870 --> 03:19:31.270
with a new class of weapons.

03:19:31.270 --> 03:19:34.240
By 1949, the Soviet Union had tested

03:19:34.240 --> 03:19:37.570
its first nuclear weapon, heating up the rivalry.

03:19:37.570 --> 03:19:41.290
They were racing to develop even more powerful weapons,

03:19:41.290 --> 03:19:42.850
the hydrogen bomb.

03:19:42.850 --> 03:19:44.710
In late 1952,

03:19:44.710 --> 03:19:48.130
the US detonated a hydrogen bomb in the Marshall Islands

03:19:48.130 --> 03:19:51.400
as a test, resulting in an explosion hundreds

03:19:51.400 --> 03:19:54.820
of times more powerful than the bombs dropped in Japan.

03:19:54.820 --> 03:19:56.680
The Soviet Union followed suit

03:19:56.680 --> 03:20:00.430
with its own test in Kazakhstan in 1955.

03:20:00.430 --> 03:20:03.730
These tests resulted in devastating health effects

03:20:03.730 --> 03:20:06.670
for nearby residents in both locations.

03:20:06.670 --> 03:20:10.900
Nevertheless, testing only ramped up in 1958,

03:20:10.900 --> 03:20:13.300
during which the US, the Soviets,

03:20:13.300 --> 03:20:15.520
and the United Kingdom detonated more

03:20:15.520 --> 03:20:17.800
than 100 bombs worldwide.

03:20:17.800 --> 03:20:19.900
Following this, the three countries

03:20:19.900 --> 03:20:22.030
voluntarily paused testing.

03:20:22.030 --> 03:20:26.080
The Cold War affected American life in a variety of ways.

03:20:26.080 --> 03:20:29.080
Fears of nuclear warfare inspired drills

03:20:29.080 --> 03:20:30.640
in schools and people

03:20:30.640 --> 03:20:33.310
to build bomb shelters in their backyards.

03:20:33.310 --> 03:20:35.350
Perhaps most destructively,

03:20:35.350 --> 03:20:38.860
fears of communist sympathy within the US inspired

03:20:38.860 --> 03:20:40.030
the government to form the

03:20:40.030 --> 03:20:44.590
House Un-American Activities Committee in 1947,

03:20:44.590 --> 03:20:47.290
which was tasked with carrying out investigations

03:20:47.290 --> 03:20:49.360
of suspected communists.

03:20:49.360 --> 03:20:52.510
Thousands of federal employees were investigated,

03:20:52.510 --> 03:20:55.960
many were fired, and some were even prosecuted.

03:20:55.960 --> 03:20:58.990
Liberal college professors lost their jobs,

03:20:58.990 --> 03:21:01.810
were forced to testify against colleagues,

03:21:01.810 --> 03:21:05.230
and others forced to take loyalty oaths.

03:21:05.230 --> 03:21:08.410
In Hollywood, hundreds of people were investigated

03:21:08.410 --> 03:21:12.280
and more than 500 movie industry professionals lost

03:21:12.280 --> 03:21:15.100
their jobs for having liberal beliefs.

03:21:15.100 --> 03:21:18.970
Many of these blacklisted writers, directors, actors,

03:21:18.970 --> 03:21:23.470
and others were unable to work again for more than a decade.

03:21:23.470 --> 03:21:26.800
This period became known as the Red Scare

03:21:26.800 --> 03:21:30.070
and is also referred to as McCarthyism

03:21:30.070 --> 03:21:32.440
after Senator Joseph McCarthy,

03:21:32.440 --> 03:21:36.820
a vehemently anti-communist politician who led the efforts.

03:21:36.820 --> 03:21:38.020
Another key symbol

03:21:38.020 --> 03:21:40.660
of the Cold War was the Berlin Wall,

03:21:40.660 --> 03:21:44.530
built in 1961 between the communist East German

03:21:44.530 --> 03:21:47.590
and capitalist West German parts of the city.

03:21:47.590 --> 03:21:50.200
Though the communist government claimed its purpose was

03:21:50.200 --> 03:21:54.730
to keep the so-called Western fascists out of East Germany,

03:21:54.730 --> 03:21:56.200
the wall really functioned

03:21:56.200 --> 03:21:59.470
to stop mass defections from east to west.

03:21:59.470 --> 03:22:02.230
It was also a solution to the Berlin crisis

03:22:02.230 --> 03:22:04.990
of 1958 when Khrushchev demanded

03:22:04.990 --> 03:22:08.050
the Allies give up West Berlin, which they had taken

03:22:08.050 --> 03:22:11.350
after World War II ended in 1945.

03:22:11.350 --> 03:22:12.550
Tensions were high

03:22:12.550 --> 03:22:15.850
between the Westerners and Soviet-backed Easterners

03:22:15.850 --> 03:22:18.370
even after the wall was constructed.

03:22:18.370 --> 03:22:22.450
West Berlin grew prosperous in great contrast to the poverty

03:22:22.450 --> 03:22:25.090
of the surrounding East German territory.

03:22:25.090 --> 03:22:27.070
The wall between them soon became

03:22:27.070 --> 03:22:30.400
an iconic image of the Cold War in Europe.

03:22:30.400 --> 03:22:32.920
The impact of the Cold War on daily life

03:22:32.920 --> 03:22:36.610
was particularly felt during the nearly two-week conflict

03:22:36.610 --> 03:22:40.360
that came to be known as the Cuban Missile Crisis,

03:22:40.360 --> 03:22:43.660
when many Americans thought the world was on the brink

03:22:43.660 --> 03:22:46.120
of an all-out nuclear war.

03:22:46.120 --> 03:22:48.940
The country's standoff nearly tipped into conflict

03:22:48.940 --> 03:22:52.630
in October, 1962 when US spy planes

03:22:52.630 --> 03:22:56.230
discovered secret Soviet missile bases being constructed

03:22:56.230 --> 03:23:00.040
in Cuba just 90 miles from US shores.

03:23:00.040 --> 03:23:03.040
Just a year earlier in 1961,

03:23:03.040 --> 03:23:06.850
the US had mounted the disastrous Bay of Pigs invasion

03:23:06.850 --> 03:23:08.590
to try to depose Cuba's

03:23:08.590 --> 03:23:11.680
Soviet-sympathetic leader Fidel Castro.

03:23:11.680 --> 03:23:13.990
During the 13-day standoff,

03:23:13.990 --> 03:23:17.200
US president John F. Kennedy ordered a naval blockade

03:23:17.200 --> 03:23:20.410
of Cuba and publicly announced the US was ready

03:23:20.410 --> 03:23:23.560
to use military force to neutralize the threat,

03:23:23.560 --> 03:23:25.180
but the crisis was resolved

03:23:25.180 --> 03:23:27.670
when Soviet leader Nikita Khrushchev offered

03:23:27.670 --> 03:23:29.770
to remove the missiles in exchange

03:23:29.770 --> 03:23:32.350
for the US vowing not to invade Cuba

03:23:32.350 --> 03:23:33.460
and removing missiles

03:23:33.460 --> 03:23:36.760
it had secretly placed in Turkey to target Russia.

03:23:36.760 --> 03:23:39.043
The event sobered both the USSR and the US.

03:23:41.353 --> 03:23:44.530
In the following year, a direct hotline was installed

03:23:44.530 --> 03:23:46.660
between Washington and Moscow

03:23:46.660 --> 03:23:49.420
to help diffuse similar situations.

03:23:49.420 --> 03:23:52.360
The two countries, along with the United Kingdom,

03:23:52.360 --> 03:23:54.850
signed a treaty in 1963,

03:23:54.850 --> 03:23:58.090
agreeing to ban several types of nuclear testing.

03:23:58.090 --> 03:24:01.420
The Cold War's anti-communist agenda led the US

03:24:01.420 --> 03:24:04.390
to various other conflicts abroad in its attempts

03:24:04.390 --> 03:24:08.410
to support democratic governments and depose communist ones.

03:24:08.410 --> 03:24:10.150
In June, 1950,

03:24:10.150 --> 03:24:12.820
the Soviet-backed North Korean People's Army

03:24:12.820 --> 03:24:15.430
invaded pro-Western South Korea.

03:24:15.430 --> 03:24:17.290
Many American officials feared

03:24:17.290 --> 03:24:20.290
that this was the first step in a communist campaign

03:24:20.290 --> 03:24:23.860
to take over the world, and that intervening was their duty

03:24:23.860 --> 03:24:25.690
in a fight of good versus evil,

03:24:25.690 --> 03:24:28.960
US President Harry Truman sent troops to Korea,

03:24:28.960 --> 03:24:32.110
but fighting stalled and casualties mounted in a stalemate

03:24:32.110 --> 03:24:34.240
of skirmishes across the border.

03:24:34.240 --> 03:24:36.880
Nearly five million people died.

03:24:36.880 --> 03:24:38.860
More than half of them civilians,

03:24:38.860 --> 03:24:41.890
which is a civilian casualty rate worse than those

03:24:41.890 --> 03:24:45.160
of World War II or the later Vietnam War.

03:24:45.160 --> 03:24:48.130
About 40,000 Americans died in action

03:24:48.130 --> 03:24:50.170
and 100,000 were wounded.

03:24:50.170 --> 03:24:53.020
After more than two years of negotiations,

03:24:53.020 --> 03:24:58.020
the adversary signed an armistice on July 27th, 1953.

03:24:58.150 --> 03:25:01.240
Then when the French colonial regime in Vietnam fell

03:25:01.240 --> 03:25:03.610
to communists in 1954,

03:25:03.610 --> 03:25:05.920
President Dwight D. Eisenhower called

03:25:05.920 --> 03:25:09.640
for American intervention under the Domino Theory,

03:25:09.640 --> 03:25:11.950
which held that allowing a communist government

03:25:11.950 --> 03:25:14.410
to keep power in one nation would lead

03:25:14.410 --> 03:25:17.470
to communist takeovers in neighboring nations

03:25:17.470 --> 03:25:21.190
with each falling to communism like a row of dominoes.

03:25:21.190 --> 03:25:22.870
However, what was intended

03:25:22.870 --> 03:25:26.650
as a brief military venture spiraled into a bloody,

03:25:26.650 --> 03:25:31.600
unpopular and unsuccessful 10 year-conflict in Vietnam.

03:25:31.600 --> 03:25:34.300
While remaining staunchly anti-communist,

03:25:34.300 --> 03:25:37.090
upon taking office in 1969,

03:25:37.090 --> 03:25:40.090
US President Richard Nixon immediately tried

03:25:40.090 --> 03:25:42.730
to soften US relations with the Soviets

03:25:42.730 --> 03:25:45.880
and dial back the Cold War via diplomacy.

03:25:45.880 --> 03:25:49.750
In 1972, the US and the Soviet Union agreed

03:25:49.750 --> 03:25:53.290
to limit the number of nuclear missiles in their arsenals,

03:25:53.290 --> 03:25:55.450
but the conflict revved up again

03:25:55.450 --> 03:25:57.790
under President Ronald Reagan who wanted

03:25:57.790 --> 03:25:59.950
to provide financial and military aid

03:25:59.950 --> 03:26:01.480
to those fighting communism

03:26:01.480 --> 03:26:05.170
around the world, particularly in Central America.

03:26:05.170 --> 03:26:07.210
The Cold War only came to an end

03:26:07.210 --> 03:26:10.330
with the Soviet Unions' unraveling under the leadership

03:26:10.330 --> 03:26:14.170
of Mikhail Gorbachev, whose government reforms caused power

03:26:14.170 --> 03:26:16.180
to shift in the communist block.

03:26:16.180 --> 03:26:17.770
Communist regimes began

03:26:17.770 --> 03:26:19.630
to collapse in Eastern Europe

03:26:19.630 --> 03:26:22.210
under the waning Soviet influence

03:26:22.210 --> 03:26:25.150
and democratic governments rose in East Germany,

03:26:25.150 --> 03:26:27.850
Poland, Hungary, and Czechoslovakia.

03:26:27.850 --> 03:26:32.110
Then West and East Germany were reunified in 1989.

03:26:32.110 --> 03:26:36.550
The Soviet Union itself collapsed in 1991,

03:26:36.550 --> 03:26:39.433
bringing the Cold War to a close.

03:26:41.541 --> 03:26:44.860
(tense music)

03:26:44.860 --> 03:26:47.590
While the Declaration of Independence may have declared

03:26:47.590 --> 03:26:50.230
that all men are created equal,

03:26:50.230 --> 03:26:52.060
the institution of slavery

03:26:52.060 --> 03:26:55.540
and persistence of bigotry throughout American history

03:26:55.540 --> 03:26:58.630
meant African-Americans faced an uphill battle

03:26:58.630 --> 03:27:02.200
to make that declaration of equality feel true.

03:27:02.200 --> 03:27:06.040
Despite slavery being abolished in 1865

03:27:06.040 --> 03:27:07.810
and the addition of the Fourteenth

03:27:07.810 --> 03:27:10.720
and Fifteenth amendments to the Constitution

03:27:10.720 --> 03:27:13.660
in 1868 and 1870,

03:27:13.660 --> 03:27:16.540
which strengthened the legal rights of freed slaves,

03:27:16.540 --> 03:27:19.120
the fact that slavery had been the law of the land

03:27:19.120 --> 03:27:23.050
for nearly 100 years cast a long shadow.

03:27:23.050 --> 03:27:27.550
Legalized segregation policies as well as everyday racism

03:27:27.550 --> 03:27:30.430
and bigotry meant that in many places,

03:27:30.430 --> 03:27:32.710
Black people and white people were not allowed

03:27:32.710 --> 03:27:37.090
to occupy the same public spaces such as buses, restrooms,

03:27:37.090 --> 03:27:39.640
hospitals, prisons, and schools.

03:27:39.640 --> 03:27:41.320
At the turn of the century,

03:27:41.320 --> 03:27:44.320
conservative Democrats in the South passed policies

03:27:44.320 --> 03:27:47.260
that disenfranchised African Americans further

03:27:47.260 --> 03:27:49.450
through various social, economic,

03:27:49.450 --> 03:27:53.650
and political means such as being prevented from voting.

03:27:53.650 --> 03:27:55.930
Sometimes through violent means.

03:27:55.930 --> 03:27:59.470
These practices were further entrenched in 1896

03:27:59.470 --> 03:28:03.340
by the Supreme Court in the case of Plessy versus Ferguson,

03:28:03.340 --> 03:28:07.000
in which the court ruled against a Black man, Homer Plessy,

03:28:07.000 --> 03:28:09.370
who was protesting his arrest for refusing

03:28:09.370 --> 03:28:10.300
to give up his seat

03:28:10.300 --> 03:28:12.970
to a white man on a train in New Orleans,

03:28:12.970 --> 03:28:15.917
which was required by Louisiana state law.

03:28:15.917 --> 03:28:19.210
"If one race be inferior to the other socially,

03:28:19.210 --> 03:28:22.030
the Constitution of the United States cannot put them

03:28:22.030 --> 03:28:23.500
upon the same plane,"

03:28:23.500 --> 03:28:25.900
the court wrote in its decision.

03:28:25.900 --> 03:28:28.060
The court continued to apply this logic

03:28:28.060 --> 03:28:30.580
to its decisions on matters of segregation

03:28:30.580 --> 03:28:32.110
in the years that followed,

03:28:32.110 --> 03:28:35.440
upholding laws that established different rules for Blacks

03:28:35.440 --> 03:28:39.220
and whites, laws, which were known as Jim Crow,

03:28:39.220 --> 03:28:41.830
a derisive term for a Black man.

03:28:41.830 --> 03:28:44.770
Not all of segregation was attributable to laws,

03:28:44.770 --> 03:28:47.380
however, discriminatory customs such

03:28:47.380 --> 03:28:50.020
as barring Black people from certain jobs,

03:28:50.020 --> 03:28:54.070
housing developments or stores were also commonplace.

03:28:54.070 --> 03:28:55.390
Throughout these years,

03:28:55.390 --> 03:28:58.000
groups fought to desegregate the South

03:28:58.000 --> 03:29:00.820
and end disenfranchising practices.

03:29:00.820 --> 03:29:03.700
In 1950, fed up with overcrowded,

03:29:03.700 --> 03:29:06.490
poorly funded inferior schools the

03:29:06.490 --> 03:29:09.910
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People,

03:29:09.910 --> 03:29:11.530
which had put in decades

03:29:11.530 --> 03:29:14.980
of work fighting racial segregation in education,

03:29:14.980 --> 03:29:17.710
put together its most compelling legal case

03:29:17.710 --> 03:29:21.160
against racial segregation in public schools.

03:29:21.160 --> 03:29:23.920
Brown versus Board of Education.

03:29:23.920 --> 03:29:27.670
Brown v. Board was actually a grouping of five cases

03:29:27.670 --> 03:29:31.030
that all challenged the claim that it was constitutional

03:29:31.030 --> 03:29:34.750
for public schools to be racially segregated by law.

03:29:34.750 --> 03:29:37.810
The effort was led by lawyer Thurgood Marshall,

03:29:37.810 --> 03:29:40.690
who argued that separate educational facilities

03:29:40.690 --> 03:29:42.700
were inherently unequal.

03:29:42.700 --> 03:29:47.050
In 1954, the Supreme Court ruled unanimously in agreement

03:29:47.050 --> 03:29:51.280
with Marshall, legally ending racial segregation in schools

03:29:51.280 --> 03:29:54.940
and overruling the doctrine established by Plessy.

03:29:54.940 --> 03:29:58.660
While this was a big victory for civil rights advocates,

03:29:58.660 --> 03:30:01.840
in reality, it did little to end school segregation

03:30:01.840 --> 03:30:04.750
right away due to resistance from racist whites

03:30:04.750 --> 03:30:06.340
who didn't want their children to go

03:30:06.340 --> 03:30:08.110
to school with Black children.

03:30:08.110 --> 03:30:10.570
Meanwhile, resistance was also mounting

03:30:10.570 --> 03:30:13.900
against segregated seating on public transportation,

03:30:13.900 --> 03:30:17.650
a fight brought to prominence by the actions of Rosa Parks,

03:30:17.650 --> 03:30:21.010
an African-American seamstress and civil rights activist

03:30:21.010 --> 03:30:23.530
in 1955 when she refused

03:30:23.530 --> 03:30:25.810
to give up her seat in the colored section

03:30:25.810 --> 03:30:29.350
of a Montgomery, Alabama bus to a white man.

03:30:29.350 --> 03:30:31.450
Parks was arrested and fined,

03:30:31.450 --> 03:30:33.880
but her actions inspired local Black leaders

03:30:33.880 --> 03:30:36.640
to organize the Montgomery Bus Boycott,

03:30:36.640 --> 03:30:40.780
led by a young Reverend Martin Luther King, Jr.

03:30:40.780 --> 03:30:44.740
During the boycott, 40,000 African Americans

03:30:44.740 --> 03:30:48.700
who made up the majority of the city bus's riders refused

03:30:48.700 --> 03:30:50.320
to ride the buses in protest

03:30:50.320 --> 03:30:51.610
of how they were treated.

03:30:51.610 --> 03:30:54.400
Initially, their demands were simply for courtesy,

03:30:54.400 --> 03:30:56.350
the hiring of Black drivers and

03:30:56.350 --> 03:30:59.590
a first come first seated policy with whites entering

03:30:59.590 --> 03:31:01.180
from the bus's front doors

03:31:01.180 --> 03:31:04.420
and Blacks from the rear doors as was custom.

03:31:04.420 --> 03:31:06.760
However, over the course of the protest,

03:31:06.760 --> 03:31:09.790
which lasted over a year, the goals changed to having

03:31:09.790 --> 03:31:13.360
the segregated seating policy totally abolished.

03:31:13.360 --> 03:31:17.650
On June 5th, 1956, a Montgomery Federal court ruled

03:31:17.650 --> 03:31:20.680
that any law requiring racially segregated seating

03:31:20.680 --> 03:31:24.640
on buses violated the Constitution's Fourteenth Amendment

03:31:24.640 --> 03:31:27.850
and the Supreme Court upheld the lower court's decision

03:31:27.850 --> 03:31:29.380
after the city appealed.

03:31:29.380 --> 03:31:34.360
The city's buses were integrated December 21st, 1956,

03:31:34.360 --> 03:31:35.920
and the boycott ended.

03:31:35.920 --> 03:31:37.960
It had lasted more than a year

03:31:37.960 --> 03:31:41.680
and is regarded as the first large-scale demonstration

03:31:41.680 --> 03:31:44.860
against racial segregation in the US.

03:31:44.860 --> 03:31:47.710
Civil rights advocates were obtaining victories,

03:31:47.710 --> 03:31:50.980
but the road towards equality was a difficult one.

03:31:50.980 --> 03:31:52.870
The buses may have been integrated,

03:31:52.870 --> 03:31:55.210
but the bus stops remained segregated

03:31:55.210 --> 03:31:56.440
and the new laws were met

03:31:56.440 --> 03:31:59.350
with significant resistance and violence.

03:31:59.350 --> 03:32:02.290
In one instance, snipers shot into a bus

03:32:02.290 --> 03:32:03.730
and shattered both legs

03:32:03.730 --> 03:32:06.430
of a pregnant African American writer.

03:32:06.430 --> 03:32:10.930
In January, 1957, four Black churches as well as the homes

03:32:10.930 --> 03:32:12.790
of several prominent Black leaders

03:32:12.790 --> 03:32:15.640
in the Montgomery area were bombed.

03:32:15.640 --> 03:32:18.820
In 1956, a group of Southern senators

03:32:18.820 --> 03:32:22.150
and congressmen signed the Southern Manifesto,

03:32:22.150 --> 03:32:25.150
which declared they would resist racial integration

03:32:25.150 --> 03:32:27.940
by all lawful means.

03:32:27.940 --> 03:32:30.340
After the decision in Brown v. Board,

03:32:30.340 --> 03:32:32.260
state and local officials and a number

03:32:32.260 --> 03:32:35.020
of Southern States resisted school integration

03:32:35.020 --> 03:32:37.510
and members of the public fought back as well.

03:32:37.510 --> 03:32:40.000
When nine African American students attempted

03:32:40.000 --> 03:32:43.180
to attend Central High School in Little Rock, Arkansas,

03:32:43.180 --> 03:32:45.400
in September, 1957,

03:32:45.400 --> 03:32:48.130
Arkansas Governor Orval Faubus ordered

03:32:48.130 --> 03:32:49.750
the state's National Guard

03:32:49.750 --> 03:32:52.150
to block their path on the first day

03:32:52.150 --> 03:32:54.400
of school, September 2nd.

03:32:54.400 --> 03:32:55.510
Two days later,

03:32:55.510 --> 03:32:58.210
a belligerent mob appeared in addition

03:32:58.210 --> 03:33:00.460
to the National Guard, again,

03:33:00.460 --> 03:33:03.550
preventing the nine students from attending class.

03:33:03.550 --> 03:33:06.400
By the end of the month, September 23rd,

03:33:06.400 --> 03:33:09.550
the nine were being escorted by Little Rock Police

03:33:09.550 --> 03:33:11.200
and attempting to enter the school

03:33:11.200 --> 03:33:14.740
through a side door when another angry mob appeared

03:33:14.740 --> 03:33:17.560
and tried to rush into the school after them.

03:33:17.560 --> 03:33:19.360
Fearing for the students' lives,

03:33:19.360 --> 03:33:21.040
officials sent them home.

03:33:21.040 --> 03:33:24.310
In response, president Dwight Eisenhower federalized

03:33:24.310 --> 03:33:27.850
the National Guard and sent US Army Troops to the scene

03:33:27.850 --> 03:33:31.300
to personally guard the students who were finally able

03:33:31.300 --> 03:33:33.610
to start attending regular classes.

03:33:33.610 --> 03:33:36.790
Though they still had to endure threats and harassment.

03:33:36.790 --> 03:33:39.790
Nonviolent protests against segregation such

03:33:39.790 --> 03:33:42.160
as sit-ins at whites only lunch counters

03:33:42.160 --> 03:33:46.330
and the 1961 Freedom Rides were signature methods used

03:33:46.330 --> 03:33:49.450
by civil rights activists protesting segregation

03:33:49.450 --> 03:33:51.640
in public spaces throughout the South.

03:33:51.640 --> 03:33:54.850
These demonstrations only increased during the presidency

03:33:54.850 --> 03:33:57.040
of John F. Kennedy when hundreds

03:33:57.040 --> 03:33:59.740
of demonstrations erupted across the nation,

03:33:59.740 --> 03:34:03.250
drawing national and international news coverage

03:34:03.250 --> 03:34:05.890
as well as backlash and violence.

03:34:05.890 --> 03:34:08.740
The Freedom Riders who were interracial members

03:34:08.740 --> 03:34:12.340
of the student activist group, Congress for Racial Equality,

03:34:12.340 --> 03:34:14.890
CORE, met significant opposition

03:34:14.890 --> 03:34:17.920
when they challenged segregation on interstate buses

03:34:17.920 --> 03:34:21.310
and bus terminals by riding from Washington, DC

03:34:21.310 --> 03:34:23.230
to Jackson, Mississippi.

03:34:23.230 --> 03:34:27.100
Though a federal ruling in 1946 had already declared

03:34:27.100 --> 03:34:30.370
that segregation in interstate transport was illegal,

03:34:30.370 --> 03:34:33.550
they faced resistance and arrests in Virginia

03:34:33.550 --> 03:34:36.250
and violent beatings in South Carolina

03:34:36.250 --> 03:34:40.210
and were met by a violent mob of over 100 people,

03:34:40.210 --> 03:34:42.970
including hostile members of the local police

03:34:42.970 --> 03:34:45.370
and members of the Ku Klux Klan

03:34:45.370 --> 03:34:47.620
when they reached Anniston, Alabama.

03:34:47.620 --> 03:34:50.320
The violence that occurred there prompted organizers

03:34:50.320 --> 03:34:51.460
to end the ride,

03:34:51.460 --> 03:34:54.130
though efforts continued on a smaller scale.

03:34:54.130 --> 03:34:57.100
The media attention garnered by these efforts as well

03:34:57.100 --> 03:34:59.830
as Dr. King serving as spokesman for the rides

03:34:59.830 --> 03:35:01.990
as they rose to national prominence,

03:35:01.990 --> 03:35:03.970
prompted the Kennedy Administration

03:35:03.970 --> 03:35:07.720
to take action, directing the Interstate Commerce Commission

03:35:07.720 --> 03:35:12.100
to ban segregation in all buses and facilities it oversaw.

03:35:12.100 --> 03:35:16.150
The ruling took effect November 1st, 1961.

03:35:16.150 --> 03:35:19.030
Though King did not take part in the rides himself,

03:35:19.030 --> 03:35:21.280
the rides are credited with showing him

03:35:21.280 --> 03:35:23.260
and others involved in the campaign

03:35:23.260 --> 03:35:26.920
that nonviolent peaceful protest against the violence

03:35:26.920 --> 03:35:28.090
of white Southerners

03:35:28.090 --> 03:35:31.510
could garner significant national media attention,

03:35:31.510 --> 03:35:35.590
attract sympathy for the cause, and force federal action.

03:35:35.590 --> 03:35:37.747
In the spring of 1963,

03:35:37.747 --> 03:35:40.300
the Southern Christian Leadership Conference led

03:35:40.300 --> 03:35:43.420
by Dr. King, launched a large-scale campaign

03:35:43.420 --> 03:35:47.470
of sit-ins, meetings, boycotts of segregated stores,

03:35:47.470 --> 03:35:49.630
and marches in Birmingham, Alabama

03:35:49.630 --> 03:35:51.670
to protest segregation there

03:35:51.670 --> 03:35:54.190
in partnership with the local activist group,

03:35:54.190 --> 03:35:58.600
the Alabama Christian Movement for Human Rights, ACMHR.

03:35:58.600 --> 03:36:00.820
Activists registered people to vote,

03:36:00.820 --> 03:36:03.370
listened to speeches by King about the philosophy

03:36:03.370 --> 03:36:05.980
of nonviolence in staged sit-ins.

03:36:05.980 --> 03:36:09.730
The boycotts of local businesses were particularly effective

03:36:09.730 --> 03:36:11.230
as they were taking place right

03:36:11.230 --> 03:36:15.100
before Easter, the second busiest shopping time of the year.

03:36:15.100 --> 03:36:18.640
Hundreds were arrested filling the local jails.

03:36:18.640 --> 03:36:19.870
After about a week,

03:36:19.870 --> 03:36:22.390
the city government obtained a state court order

03:36:22.390 --> 03:36:24.790
that said the protests must stop,

03:36:24.790 --> 03:36:27.520
but the activists decided to defy it.

03:36:27.520 --> 03:36:29.410
The efforts continued on May 2nd

03:36:29.410 --> 03:36:32.890
when more than 1,000 African American students marched

03:36:32.890 --> 03:36:34.510
in Downtown Birmingham

03:36:34.510 --> 03:36:37.690
in what became known as the Children's Crusade.

03:36:37.690 --> 03:36:41.230
Hundreds more were arrested, overcrowding the jails.

03:36:41.230 --> 03:36:43.450
The City's Commissioner of Public Safety,

03:36:43.450 --> 03:36:46.720
Eugene Bull O'Connor authorized the use

03:36:46.720 --> 03:36:50.830
of high-pressure hoses against children protestors.

03:36:50.830 --> 03:36:53.680
And when adults watching reacted by throwing rocks

03:36:53.680 --> 03:36:56.080
and bottles at those wielding the hoses,

03:36:56.080 --> 03:36:59.200
Connor ordered the use of police dogs against them.

03:36:59.200 --> 03:37:00.790
Images of the violence

03:37:00.790 --> 03:37:04.630
triggered outrage nationally and internationally.

03:37:04.630 --> 03:37:07.330
Under pressure, the White House sent a facilitator

03:37:07.330 --> 03:37:10.540
to help speed negotiations between protest leaders

03:37:10.540 --> 03:37:13.150
and members of Birmingham's business community

03:37:13.150 --> 03:37:16.150
who were weakening under the sustained boycott.

03:37:16.150 --> 03:37:19.000
On May 8th, the group struck a compromise.

03:37:19.000 --> 03:37:21.460
Street protests would end immediately

03:37:21.460 --> 03:37:23.650
and signs proclaiming whites only

03:37:23.650 --> 03:37:25.600
and Blacks only on restrooms

03:37:25.600 --> 03:37:27.670
and drinking fountains would be removed.

03:37:27.670 --> 03:37:31.120
The Birmingham Truce also called for the release

03:37:31.120 --> 03:37:33.280
of jailed protesters on bond,

03:37:33.280 --> 03:37:35.560
a plan to desegregate lunch counters,

03:37:35.560 --> 03:37:37.900
and the hiring of more African Americans

03:37:37.900 --> 03:37:39.490
for jobs around the city.

03:37:39.490 --> 03:37:42.460
It was not everything the protestors had hoped to achieve,

03:37:42.460 --> 03:37:45.850
but rather a partial success that proved divisive

03:37:45.850 --> 03:37:47.920
among activists who thought the protestors

03:37:47.920 --> 03:37:50.740
should have held out until all their goals were met.

03:37:50.740 --> 03:37:53.290
The city was slowly desegregated in the months

03:37:53.290 --> 03:37:54.580
that followed the truce,

03:37:54.580 --> 03:37:57.910
but the campaign was not a huge local success.

03:37:57.910 --> 03:38:00.340
Rather its significance was in the amount

03:38:00.340 --> 03:38:02.800
of national and international attention

03:38:02.800 --> 03:38:05.110
it drew to the civil rights cause.

03:38:05.110 --> 03:38:07.930
It also led King's reputation as a leader

03:38:07.930 --> 03:38:09.880
to grow exponentially.

03:38:09.880 --> 03:38:11.350
On August 28th,

03:38:11.350 --> 03:38:14.350
King delivered his "I Have a Dream" speech

03:38:14.350 --> 03:38:17.380
at the March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom,

03:38:17.380 --> 03:38:19.630
which was organized in the nation's capital

03:38:19.630 --> 03:38:23.770
to advocate for African American civil and economic rights.

03:38:23.770 --> 03:38:27.580
It is estimated that 250,000 people attended,

03:38:27.580 --> 03:38:30.670
making the assembly, which was planned in cooperation

03:38:30.670 --> 03:38:33.640
with DC Police, a logistical feat.

03:38:33.640 --> 03:38:35.350
The march sought to address the fact

03:38:35.350 --> 03:38:38.980
that many jobs were entirely closed to Black applicants

03:38:38.980 --> 03:38:41.860
and those that were open to them often paid poorly

03:38:41.860 --> 03:38:44.320
or offered little upward mobility.

03:38:44.320 --> 03:38:48.100
The year 1963 was the centennial anniversary

03:38:48.100 --> 03:38:50.410
of the Emancipation Proclamation,

03:38:50.410 --> 03:38:52.900
the declaration of the end of slavery,

03:38:52.900 --> 03:38:54.730
and organizers of the march wished

03:38:54.730 --> 03:38:57.760
to emphasize that change was long overdue.

03:38:57.760 --> 03:39:00.430
The march brought together many different activists

03:39:00.430 --> 03:39:03.100
and organizers, but it was King's speech

03:39:03.100 --> 03:39:05.650
at the Lincoln Memorial that was memorialized

03:39:05.650 --> 03:39:07.780
as a masterpiece of rhetoric

03:39:07.780 --> 03:39:10.210
as it called for an end to racism.

03:39:10.210 --> 03:39:12.130
The march and the speech are credited

03:39:12.130 --> 03:39:14.470
with inspiring the federal government to act

03:39:14.470 --> 03:39:18.520
on civil rights through the Civil Rights Act of 1964,

03:39:18.520 --> 03:39:21.820
which outlawed discrimination based on race, color,

03:39:21.820 --> 03:39:26.560
religion, sex, or national origin in public accommodations,

03:39:26.560 --> 03:39:28.930
public education and employment,

03:39:28.930 --> 03:39:31.930
and the Voting Rights Act of 1965,

03:39:31.930 --> 03:39:34.900
which prohibited racial discrimination in voting.

03:39:34.900 --> 03:39:37.120
These were the two most important pieces

03:39:37.120 --> 03:39:38.650
of civil rights legislation

03:39:38.650 --> 03:39:41.530
to be passed since the reconstruction period,

03:39:41.530 --> 03:39:45.073
and brought many of the Jim Crow policies to an end.

03:39:46.855 --> 03:39:49.780
(tense music)

03:39:49.780 --> 03:39:52.060
No conflict was more representative

03:39:52.060 --> 03:39:54.280
of the US' Cold War commitment

03:39:54.280 --> 03:39:56.410
to getting involved in elective fights

03:39:56.410 --> 03:39:58.210
with communist governments,

03:39:58.210 --> 03:40:03.010
even under unfavorable circumstances, than the Vietnam War.

03:40:03.010 --> 03:40:06.340
Led by the strongly anti-communist politician,

03:40:06.340 --> 03:40:08.680
Ngo Dinh Diem, who was nevertheless

03:40:08.680 --> 03:40:12.040
a repressive dictator who called for the arrest and torture

03:40:12.040 --> 03:40:14.560
of suspected communist sympathizers,

03:40:14.560 --> 03:40:18.010
the South Vietnamese fought the communist North Vietnamese

03:40:18.010 --> 03:40:19.690
for control of the country.

03:40:19.690 --> 03:40:23.230
In 1964 under President Lyndon Johnson,

03:40:23.230 --> 03:40:27.250
the US began regular air raids of North Vietnamese targets,

03:40:27.250 --> 03:40:29.140
dropping bombs in a program known

03:40:29.140 --> 03:40:31.270
as Operation Rolling Thunder.

03:40:31.270 --> 03:40:34.360
Between 1964 to 1973,

03:40:34.360 --> 03:40:38.170
the US also secretly dropped more than two million tons

03:40:38.170 --> 03:40:40.837
of bombs on North Vietnamese supply lines

03:40:40.837 --> 03:40:42.520
and neighboring Laos,

03:40:42.520 --> 03:40:45.520
despite the country being neutral in the conflict.

03:40:45.520 --> 03:40:49.330
In 1965, Johnson called for a significant increase

03:40:49.330 --> 03:40:51.940
in American troops deployed to Vietnam.

03:40:51.940 --> 03:40:54.063
By June, 1965,

03:40:54.063 --> 03:40:57.640
82,000 combat troops were stationed in Vietnam.

03:40:57.640 --> 03:41:01.060
At the end of July, 100,000 troops were sent

03:41:01.060 --> 03:41:04.840
and another 100,000 were sent in 1966.

03:41:04.840 --> 03:41:07.420
South Korea, Thailand, Australia,

03:41:07.420 --> 03:41:09.730
and New Zealand also sent troops,

03:41:09.730 --> 03:41:11.440
but in much smaller numbers.

03:41:11.440 --> 03:41:14.890
North Vietnam was aided by China and the Soviet Union.

03:41:14.890 --> 03:41:16.990
By November, 1967,

03:41:16.990 --> 03:41:19.090
the number of American troops in Vietnam

03:41:19.090 --> 03:41:21.610
was approaching 500,000,

03:41:21.610 --> 03:41:24.940
but support for the unsuccessful war was waning.

03:41:24.940 --> 03:41:28.930
A strong anti-war movement in the US spawned protests

03:41:28.930 --> 03:41:30.280
against the draft,

03:41:30.280 --> 03:41:32.500
the large number of civilian casualties

03:41:32.500 --> 03:41:35.380
the war was generating, and against the US's support

03:41:35.380 --> 03:41:38.470
for the corrupt Southern Vietnamese dictatorship.

03:41:38.470 --> 03:41:42.250
Many troops stationed in Vietnam were also low on morale

03:41:42.250 --> 03:41:45.280
with many turning to drugs, initiating mutinies,

03:41:45.280 --> 03:41:48.010
and developing post-traumatic stress disorder.

03:41:48.010 --> 03:41:51.220
Between 1966 and 1973,

03:41:51.220 --> 03:41:55.750
more than 503,000 US military personnel deserted,

03:41:55.750 --> 03:41:58.930
and another 500,000 dodged the draft.

03:41:58.930 --> 03:42:01.720
Nevertheless, when President Nixon took office,

03:42:01.720 --> 03:42:04.510
he announced that he believed a silent majority

03:42:04.510 --> 03:42:06.790
of Americans supported the war.

03:42:06.790 --> 03:42:09.820
Over the next few years, the death toll grew,

03:42:09.820 --> 03:42:13.930
including the more than 400 unarmed civilian US troops

03:42:13.930 --> 03:42:17.470
killed in the village of Mai Lai in 1968.

03:42:17.470 --> 03:42:19.510
Peace talks were unsuccessful.

03:42:19.510 --> 03:42:23.110
Anti-war sentiment in the US only increased.

03:42:23.110 --> 03:42:26.020
Over 250,000 people gathered

03:42:26.020 --> 03:42:29.200
to demonstrate against the war in Washington DC

03:42:29.200 --> 03:42:32.230
on November 15th, 1969.

03:42:32.230 --> 03:42:35.380
Nixon ended the draft in 1972 moving

03:42:35.380 --> 03:42:37.300
to an all volunteer army,

03:42:37.300 --> 03:42:41.680
but in 1971, the leaked Pentagon papers had revealed results

03:42:41.680 --> 03:42:43.630
of a secret DOD study

03:42:43.630 --> 03:42:47.170
that showed Nixon's Administration had escalated conflict

03:42:47.170 --> 03:42:50.860
in Vietnam, further eroding public support for the war.

03:42:50.860 --> 03:42:53.857
In January, 1973, the United States

03:42:53.857 --> 03:42:57.040
and North Vietnam ended open hostilities,

03:42:57.040 --> 03:42:58.630
though conflict between North

03:42:58.630 --> 03:43:02.590
and South Vietnam continued until 1975.

03:43:02.590 --> 03:43:05.950
When the North took over the Southern city of Saigon,

03:43:05.950 --> 03:43:08.200
the US's effort had failed,

03:43:08.200 --> 03:43:11.500
and the 20-year war took an enormous toll.

03:43:11.500 --> 03:43:14.830
An estimated 2 million Vietnamese were killed,

03:43:14.830 --> 03:43:16.450
while 3 million were wounded

03:43:16.450 --> 03:43:19.450
and another 12 million became refugees.

03:43:19.450 --> 03:43:22.660
About 58,000 Americans were killed.

03:43:22.660 --> 03:43:26.140
Many anti-war Americans lost trust in their government,

03:43:26.140 --> 03:43:28.480
while others who may have been pro-war

03:43:28.480 --> 03:43:30.490
no longer felt invincible.

03:43:30.490 --> 03:43:33.130
The conflict bitterly divided the US

03:43:33.130 --> 03:43:37.099
and its impact would be felt for many years.

03:43:37.099 --> 03:43:40.780
(suspenseful music)

03:43:40.780 --> 03:43:44.350
Following the end of World War II in 1946,

03:43:44.350 --> 03:43:47.920
tensions rose between the capitalistic United States

03:43:47.920 --> 03:43:50.080
and the communist Soviet Union,

03:43:50.080 --> 03:43:52.720
each country wished to prove its economic system

03:43:52.720 --> 03:43:54.160
to be better than the other,

03:43:54.160 --> 03:43:56.230
and to show the world they had the key

03:43:56.230 --> 03:43:58.270
to political superiority.

03:43:58.270 --> 03:43:59.380
Both countries sought

03:43:59.380 --> 03:44:02.080
to demonstrate their technological superiority

03:44:02.080 --> 03:44:06.310
by being the first nation to put a human being into space,

03:44:06.310 --> 03:44:09.490
which at the time was an as yet undone feat

03:44:09.490 --> 03:44:12.670
that each knew was only a few years away.

03:44:12.670 --> 03:44:15.790
Both countries had developed intercontinental missiles,

03:44:15.790 --> 03:44:18.400
which provided critical electronic technology

03:44:18.400 --> 03:44:22.030
and rocketry that could boost small payloads into orbit.

03:44:22.030 --> 03:44:25.900
The competition began on August 2nd, 1955.

03:44:25.900 --> 03:44:29.950
When first the US, then the USSR announced they intended

03:44:29.950 --> 03:44:32.380
to launch artificial satellites.

03:44:32.380 --> 03:44:36.247
Two years later, on October 4th, 1957,

03:44:36.247 --> 03:44:39.220
the USSR was the first to launch its satellite,

03:44:39.220 --> 03:44:40.690
the Sputnik 1,

03:44:40.690 --> 03:44:44.380
which was the first Earth-orbiting satellite in history.

03:44:44.380 --> 03:44:47.290
They followed up with the Sputnik 2 the next month

03:44:47.290 --> 03:44:50.890
and this time the satellite carried a dog named Laika

03:44:50.890 --> 03:44:54.520
who became the first living organism to enter orbit.

03:44:54.520 --> 03:44:59.080
It was not until the following January 31st, 1958

03:44:59.080 --> 03:45:01.420
that the US entered the race by launching

03:45:01.420 --> 03:45:04.510
and reaching orbit with the satellite Explorer 1.

03:45:04.510 --> 03:45:07.420
Later that year, the US created NASA,

03:45:07.420 --> 03:45:10.600
the National Aeronautics and Space Administration,

03:45:10.600 --> 03:45:13.570
an independent agency within the federal government

03:45:13.570 --> 03:45:16.540
that is responsible for the civil space program,

03:45:16.540 --> 03:45:19.690
aeronautics programs and space research.

03:45:19.690 --> 03:45:23.080
On December 18th, 1958, the US launched

03:45:23.080 --> 03:45:26.950
the world's first communication satellite known as SCORE.

03:45:26.950 --> 03:45:30.010
It earned international attention when it broadcasted

03:45:30.010 --> 03:45:32.200
a prerecorded Christmas message

03:45:32.200 --> 03:45:35.110
from US President Dwight D. Eisenhower.

03:45:35.110 --> 03:45:36.700
It was the first instance

03:45:36.700 --> 03:45:40.090
of a human voice being broadcast from space.

03:45:40.090 --> 03:45:44.110
In August, 1959, the US launched Explorer VI,

03:45:44.110 --> 03:45:46.450
the world's first weather satellite.

03:45:46.450 --> 03:45:49.660
It took the first picture of the Earth from space.

03:45:49.660 --> 03:45:53.080
In September, the USSR launched Luna-2,

03:45:53.080 --> 03:45:56.110
which became the first spacecraft to reach the surface,

03:45:56.110 --> 03:45:58.660
of the moon, but these unmanned missions

03:45:58.660 --> 03:46:00.310
were just the beginning.

03:46:00.310 --> 03:46:03.970
In August, 1960, the USSR's Sputnik 5

03:46:03.970 --> 03:46:06.790
was the first spacecraft to return its contents.

03:46:06.790 --> 03:46:09.040
Two dogs, Belka and Strelka,

03:46:09.040 --> 03:46:12.940
and some plants, alive after being in space.

03:46:12.940 --> 03:46:15.790
The US matches this achievement the following year,

03:46:15.790 --> 03:46:18.310
returning Ham, a chimpanzee,

03:46:18.310 --> 03:46:19.870
alive from space.

03:46:19.870 --> 03:46:21.310
While the first five years

03:46:21.310 --> 03:46:25.090
of the space race demonstrated mostly matched capability,

03:46:25.090 --> 03:46:30.040
the USSR took a marked lead on April 12th, 1961,

03:46:30.040 --> 03:46:32.890
when Cosmonaut Yuri Gagarin traveling aboard

03:46:32.890 --> 03:46:37.660
the Vostok 1 became the first human being to reach space.

03:46:37.660 --> 03:46:40.120
Gagarin made a single orbit around the Earth,

03:46:40.120 --> 03:46:42.880
which took just under two hours to complete.

03:46:42.880 --> 03:46:44.950
This milestone sent the competition

03:46:44.950 --> 03:46:47.710
into a new decade with increased vigor.

03:46:47.710 --> 03:46:50.020
In September, 1962,

03:46:50.020 --> 03:46:52.210
US president John F. Kennedy announced

03:46:52.210 --> 03:46:54.940
that the US would land people on the moon

03:46:54.940 --> 03:46:56.920
and return them safely to Earth

03:46:56.920 --> 03:46:58.990
before the end of the decade.

03:46:58.990 --> 03:47:02.297
This speech is largely remembered for his declaration,

03:47:02.297 --> 03:47:04.510
"We choose to go to the moon."

03:47:04.510 --> 03:47:07.180
More and more people, both members of the government

03:47:07.180 --> 03:47:10.030
and members of private industry became involved

03:47:10.030 --> 03:47:11.650
in the US Space Race,

03:47:11.650 --> 03:47:14.320
reflecting the intensity of the competition

03:47:14.320 --> 03:47:18.197
with numbers growing from 36,000 people involved in 1960

03:47:19.097 --> 03:47:22.420
to 377,000 By 1965.

03:47:23.470 --> 03:47:25.390
In May, 1961,

03:47:25.390 --> 03:47:27.520
the US launched Alan Shepherd aboard

03:47:27.520 --> 03:47:29.410
the Mercury-Redstone 3.

03:47:29.410 --> 03:47:31.570
And while Shepherd became the first American

03:47:31.570 --> 03:47:34.720
to visit space, he was not able to enter orbit.

03:47:34.720 --> 03:47:37.720
The flight lasted only about 15 minutes.

03:47:37.720 --> 03:47:38.950
In the following years,

03:47:38.950 --> 03:47:41.620
the Soviet Union replicated its victories,

03:47:41.620 --> 03:47:44.950
sending the first woman to space in 1963.

03:47:44.950 --> 03:47:47.290
Valentina Terra Tereshkova orbited the Earth

03:47:47.290 --> 03:47:49.600
for three days aboard Vostok 6

03:47:49.600 --> 03:47:51.670
and pioneering the first spacewalk

03:47:51.670 --> 03:47:54.610
when Cosmonaut Alexei Leonov left his spacecraft

03:47:54.610 --> 03:47:57.400
for 12 minutes In 1965,

03:47:57.400 --> 03:48:01.300
while the USSR took a clear lead in manned missions,

03:48:01.300 --> 03:48:03.400
the US secured another achievement

03:48:03.400 --> 03:48:05.020
with its satellite program.

03:48:05.020 --> 03:48:07.720
On July 14th, 1965,

03:48:07.720 --> 03:48:10.540
the American satellite Mariner 4 was the first

03:48:10.540 --> 03:48:13.720
to voyage to Mars and take closeup images

03:48:13.720 --> 03:48:15.340
of the planet's surface.

03:48:15.340 --> 03:48:19.120
The US did not give up on manned missions despite tragedy.

03:48:19.120 --> 03:48:23.440
In January, 1967, three American astronauts died

03:48:23.440 --> 03:48:25.570
when a fire broke out inside their capsule

03:48:25.570 --> 03:48:27.520
while it was still on the launchpad.

03:48:27.520 --> 03:48:28.900
At the end of the following year,

03:48:28.900 --> 03:48:32.140
however, the US spacecraft Apollo 8 became

03:48:32.140 --> 03:48:34.720
the first manned craft to reach the moon,

03:48:34.720 --> 03:48:37.240
orbit it, and then return to the Earth.

03:48:37.240 --> 03:48:39.670
This victory showed the US it was time

03:48:39.670 --> 03:48:43.210
to move full speed ahead on missions to the moon.

03:48:43.210 --> 03:48:46.360
The next year, in July, 1969,

03:48:46.360 --> 03:48:49.570
Neil Armstrong and Buzz Aldrin became the first men

03:48:49.570 --> 03:48:51.430
to walk on the moon.

03:48:51.430 --> 03:48:54.640
The televised landing by Apollo 11 was broadcast

03:48:54.640 --> 03:48:58.480
around the world, securing for the US what people saw

03:48:58.480 --> 03:49:01.150
as victory in the space race.

03:49:01.150 --> 03:49:03.250
The Soviet Union transferred its focus

03:49:03.250 --> 03:49:07.690
to building a space station, which it completed in 1971.

03:49:07.690 --> 03:49:11.800
In 1972, the US and the Soviet Union negotiated

03:49:11.800 --> 03:49:14.650
a warming of relations, which paved the way

03:49:14.650 --> 03:49:17.620
for cooperation in the realm of space travel.

03:49:17.620 --> 03:49:21.010
In 1975, the first joint space mission

03:49:21.010 --> 03:49:22.900
between the two countries occurred.

03:49:22.900 --> 03:49:26.080
Separately, the Apollo and Soyuz spacecrafts traveled

03:49:26.080 --> 03:49:28.330
into orbit and docked in space

03:49:28.330 --> 03:49:30.910
where their two commanders shook hands.

03:49:30.910 --> 03:49:34.240
This was a symbolic end to the space race.

03:49:34.240 --> 03:49:36.700
After it occurred, the two countries engaged

03:49:36.700 --> 03:49:38.350
in future missions together,

03:49:38.350 --> 03:49:41.800
like the Shuttle-Mir program in 1993.

03:49:41.800 --> 03:49:44.230
The space race had broader implications

03:49:44.230 --> 03:49:46.330
for the world beyond just the development

03:49:46.330 --> 03:49:48.190
of space flight technology.

03:49:48.190 --> 03:49:51.580
The race to send humans to space resulted in the development

03:49:51.580 --> 03:49:54.160
of other widely used technology,

03:49:54.160 --> 03:49:56.860
including communication and weather satellites,

03:49:56.860 --> 03:49:57.970
which are used today

03:49:57.970 --> 03:50:00.790
for things like broadband and GPS.

03:50:00.790 --> 03:50:03.430
The imaging technology used in CAT scans

03:50:03.430 --> 03:50:06.070
was initially developed during the space race

03:50:06.070 --> 03:50:08.050
for deep space photography.

03:50:08.050 --> 03:50:11.980
NASA also made innovations in shock absorbent material,

03:50:11.980 --> 03:50:15.610
which became useful for developing better artificial limbs

03:50:15.610 --> 03:50:18.760
and wireless headsets were first developed for astronauts

03:50:18.760 --> 03:50:20.413
to use in space.

03:50:21.493 --> 03:50:24.790
(suspenseful music)

03:50:24.790 --> 03:50:27.190
In response to the catastrophes brought on

03:50:27.190 --> 03:50:30.820
by totalitarian ideologies in the 20th century,

03:50:30.820 --> 03:50:32.740
a new school of thought began

03:50:32.740 --> 03:50:36.220
in the 1970s known as postmodernism.

03:50:36.220 --> 03:50:39.280
Postmodernism was deeply skeptical of the claim

03:50:39.280 --> 03:50:42.310
that there was any kind of universal truth.

03:50:42.310 --> 03:50:46.270
Instead, focusing on relative truths and morals.

03:50:46.270 --> 03:50:49.840
The postmodernist period coincided with a cultural shift

03:50:49.840 --> 03:50:52.870
that occurred as the baby boomers came of age.

03:50:52.870 --> 03:50:56.650
During the 1970s, these young people continued movements

03:50:56.650 --> 03:50:59.500
that had begun in the 1960s demonstrating

03:50:59.500 --> 03:51:01.810
against the policies in schools of thought

03:51:01.810 --> 03:51:03.610
of the previous age.

03:51:03.610 --> 03:51:07.000
Thousands of students marched against the Vietnam War

03:51:07.000 --> 03:51:10.330
and the draft, as well as against the manufacturer

03:51:10.330 --> 03:51:12.550
of napalm, Dow Chemical.

03:51:12.550 --> 03:51:16.360
Not all campus anti-war protests were peaceful.

03:51:16.360 --> 03:51:18.100
Some turned violent,

03:51:18.100 --> 03:51:22.750
including the May, 1970 incident at Kent State University

03:51:22.750 --> 03:51:26.860
in Ohio, in which 13 students were shot by members

03:51:26.860 --> 03:51:28.420
of the National Guard.

03:51:28.420 --> 03:51:30.880
During this time, people also protested

03:51:30.880 --> 03:51:34.630
against discrimination against women, racial segregation,

03:51:34.630 --> 03:51:36.130
and other issues.

03:51:36.130 --> 03:51:40.653
The very first Earth Day was observed on April 22nd, 1970.

03:51:41.500 --> 03:51:45.100
Television and radio were ubiquitous with such shows

03:51:45.100 --> 03:51:48.040
as "All in the Family," "Saturday Night Live,"

03:51:48.040 --> 03:51:50.080
and "Wheel of Fortune" premiering.

03:51:50.080 --> 03:51:51.790
This decade also saw the launch

03:51:51.790 --> 03:51:55.060
of the first successful home video game system,

03:51:55.060 --> 03:51:57.100
the Atari 2600,

03:51:57.100 --> 03:52:00.340
and the founding of tech companies Apple and Microsoft.

03:52:00.340 --> 03:52:03.280
At the same time, the US was in a recession

03:52:03.280 --> 03:52:05.560
and gas prices were skyrocketing due

03:52:05.560 --> 03:52:07.510
to the Arab oil embargo,

03:52:07.510 --> 03:52:09.220
which was inflicted on the countries

03:52:09.220 --> 03:52:14.220
who had supported Israel in the 1973 Arab-Israeli War.

03:52:14.230 --> 03:52:16.900
The US also faced political turmoil

03:52:16.900 --> 03:52:19.660
as illegal activities committed in the name

03:52:19.660 --> 03:52:22.680
of reelecting President Richard Nixon came

03:52:22.680 --> 03:52:25.180
to light in the Watergate scandal

03:52:25.180 --> 03:52:28.420
and caused the downfall of Nixon's presidency.

03:52:28.420 --> 03:52:30.910
The legacy of Watergate deeply damaged

03:52:30.910 --> 03:52:33.070
the Republican Party's reputation,

03:52:33.070 --> 03:52:35.440
so Democrat Jimmy Carter was able

03:52:35.440 --> 03:52:38.710
to win the presidency in 1976.

03:52:38.710 --> 03:52:40.870
Carter prioritized calming conflicts

03:52:40.870 --> 03:52:44.380
around the world, signing a nuclear arms reduction treaty

03:52:44.380 --> 03:52:46.990
with the Soviet Union and giving ownership

03:52:46.990 --> 03:52:49.570
of the Panama Canal back to Panama.

03:52:49.570 --> 03:52:53.170
Most notably, he helped broker peace in the Middle East

03:52:53.170 --> 03:52:55.150
where conflict had been ongoing since

03:52:55.150 --> 03:52:58.300
the 1948 Arab-Israeli War.

03:52:58.300 --> 03:53:01.450
But Carter's support for the Shah of Iran who wanted

03:53:01.450 --> 03:53:04.570
to modernize and westernize Iran soon became

03:53:04.570 --> 03:53:06.220
a point of contention.

03:53:06.220 --> 03:53:11.220
By 1979, the Shah had lost popularity and was overthrown

03:53:11.380 --> 03:53:14.440
at which time anti-American sentiment increased

03:53:14.440 --> 03:53:15.460
in the country.

03:53:15.460 --> 03:53:18.550
A group overthrew the US Embassy in Iran

03:53:18.550 --> 03:53:20.980
and 52 American diplomats

03:53:20.980 --> 03:53:25.630
and citizens were held hostage for the next 444 days.

03:53:25.630 --> 03:53:28.600
In the aftermath of this Iran hostage crisis,

03:53:28.600 --> 03:53:31.030
a second energy crisis developed,

03:53:31.030 --> 03:53:33.910
sending gasoline prices soaring again.

03:53:33.910 --> 03:53:36.730
In the presidential election of 1980,

03:53:36.730 --> 03:53:40.060
Ronald Reagan defeated Carter in a landslide.

03:53:40.060 --> 03:53:43.150
In the 1980s, social issues took a back seat

03:53:43.150 --> 03:53:45.160
and personal financial success

03:53:45.160 --> 03:53:47.620
became many people's primary goal.

03:53:47.620 --> 03:53:49.870
The populist conservative movement known

03:53:49.870 --> 03:53:53.080
as the New Right had begun growing in the late '70s

03:53:53.080 --> 03:53:54.910
into the early '80s.

03:53:54.910 --> 03:53:57.940
Reagan advocated for deregulating business,

03:53:57.940 --> 03:53:59.800
reducing government spending,

03:53:59.800 --> 03:54:04.150
and giving tax cuts to both individuals and corporations.

03:54:04.150 --> 03:54:06.670
The tax cut plan was part of a system known

03:54:06.670 --> 03:54:09.250
as supply-side economics

03:54:09.250 --> 03:54:11.740
or the belief that the resulting gains

03:54:11.740 --> 03:54:14.260
for businesses would eventually trickle

03:54:14.260 --> 03:54:15.880
down to everyone.

03:54:15.880 --> 03:54:18.160
Altogether, these economic policies

03:54:18.160 --> 03:54:20.470
were known as Reaganomics.

03:54:20.470 --> 03:54:23.230
In 1982, the United States experienced

03:54:23.230 --> 03:54:27.250
its worst economic downturn since the Great Depression.

03:54:27.250 --> 03:54:29.410
Nine million people were unemployed

03:54:29.410 --> 03:54:31.030
in November of that year.

03:54:31.030 --> 03:54:33.970
Nevertheless, Reaganomics remained popular

03:54:33.970 --> 03:54:36.040
as it made the rich richer.

03:54:36.040 --> 03:54:38.980
Over the 1980s, the average income of families

03:54:38.980 --> 03:54:42.820
in the wealthiest 1% increased significantly

03:54:42.820 --> 03:54:45.040
and at a much greater rate than the income

03:54:45.040 --> 03:54:48.580
of middle-class families, which edged up mildly

03:54:48.580 --> 03:54:52.330
while income for the bottom 40% of families declined.

03:54:52.330 --> 03:54:55.000
Television had entered nearly every household

03:54:55.000 --> 03:54:58.217
and was becoming more varied with shows like "Cheers,"

03:54:58.217 --> 03:55:00.820
"The Simpsons" and the "Cosby Show" premiering.

03:55:00.820 --> 03:55:04.180
Also popular was TV news, which brought new levels

03:55:04.180 --> 03:55:06.790
of attention to crimes like child abduction

03:55:06.790 --> 03:55:08.920
via shows like "60 Minutes."

03:55:08.920 --> 03:55:11.800
People also learned about tragedies around the world,

03:55:11.800 --> 03:55:14.140
such as the famine in Ethiopia.

03:55:14.140 --> 03:55:18.220
The Live Aid Benefit concert on July 13th, 1985

03:55:18.220 --> 03:55:22.090
was watched by about 1.5 billion people

03:55:22.090 --> 03:55:25.540
and raised millions of dollars for famine relief.

03:55:25.540 --> 03:55:27.730
In 1986, viewers could watch

03:55:27.730 --> 03:55:31.210
the local Cleveland, Ohio chapter of the United Way attempt

03:55:31.210 --> 03:55:32.680
to break the world record

03:55:32.680 --> 03:55:35.350
for most balloons released at one time,

03:55:35.350 --> 03:55:36.610
but the event intended

03:55:36.610 --> 03:55:40.480
as a harmless publicity stunt quickly went off the rails.

03:55:40.480 --> 03:55:44.890
A colorful cloud of 1.5 million helium-filled balloons

03:55:44.890 --> 03:55:48.490
was released, but blown by wind and pushed down by rain,

03:55:48.490 --> 03:55:50.680
they caused an airport to shut down

03:55:50.680 --> 03:55:53.710
and impeded the Coast Guard's efforts to find two fishermen

03:55:53.710 --> 03:55:55.270
who needed help nearby.

03:55:55.270 --> 03:55:57.160
The balloons clogged waterways

03:55:57.160 --> 03:55:58.990
and caused traffic accidents

03:55:58.990 --> 03:56:03.430
and came to be seen as a major environmental disaster.

03:56:03.430 --> 03:56:06.010
The US returned to space in 1981

03:56:06.010 --> 03:56:07.960
with the space shuttle Columbia,

03:56:07.960 --> 03:56:11.890
the very first reusable space exploration vehicle.

03:56:11.890 --> 03:56:14.920
The US flew numerous shuttle missions in the '80s,

03:56:14.920 --> 03:56:17.260
though one was marked by tragedy.

03:56:17.260 --> 03:56:20.290
Millions watched live in 1986

03:56:20.290 --> 03:56:23.530
when the space shuttle Challenger exploded seconds

03:56:23.530 --> 03:56:26.650
after takeoff, killing all seven aboard.

03:56:26.650 --> 03:56:28.583
This grounded the space program for two

03:56:28.583 --> 03:56:33.490
and a half years until the Discovery was launched in 1988.

03:56:33.490 --> 03:56:35.830
Reagan's foreign policy was hawkish

03:56:35.830 --> 03:56:38.110
and that he was eager to get the US involved

03:56:38.110 --> 03:56:41.140
in situations abroad where communism threatened

03:56:41.140 --> 03:56:42.280
to take over.

03:56:42.280 --> 03:56:45.430
Under this Reagan doctrine, the US provided financial

03:56:45.430 --> 03:56:48.250
and military assistance to the governments of Grenada,

03:56:48.250 --> 03:56:50.290
El Salvador and Nicaragua.

03:56:50.290 --> 03:56:52.120
However, in 1986,

03:56:52.120 --> 03:56:54.490
it was revealed that the US had sold weapons

03:56:54.490 --> 03:56:58.210
to Iran despite the country being under an arms embargo,

03:56:58.210 --> 03:57:01.540
which was a sanction imposed in retribution for the storming

03:57:01.540 --> 03:57:04.780
of the US embassy in 1979.

03:57:04.780 --> 03:57:08.010
Members of the Reagan Administration sold Iran the arms

03:57:08.010 --> 03:57:11.290
in a bid to illegally divert money from the sales

03:57:11.290 --> 03:57:13.930
to a rebel group known as the Contras

03:57:13.930 --> 03:57:15.370
who were fighting the socialist

03:57:15.370 --> 03:57:18.040
Sandinista Government in Nicaragua.

03:57:18.040 --> 03:57:20.680
It was a scandal for the administration

03:57:20.680 --> 03:57:23.290
and investigations into the issue were impeded

03:57:23.290 --> 03:57:25.330
because of the large number of documents

03:57:25.330 --> 03:57:27.550
that were shredded or without.

03:57:27.550 --> 03:57:30.070
Several administration officials were convicted

03:57:30.070 --> 03:57:33.100
of crimes related to the Iran-Contra scandal,

03:57:33.100 --> 03:57:35.770
but all were vacated or pardoned.

03:57:35.770 --> 03:57:38.830
Another Reagan Administration scandal emerged later

03:57:38.830 --> 03:57:43.830
after review of its response to the 1980s AIDS crisis.

03:57:43.900 --> 03:57:46.540
Though health officials in the US had become aware

03:57:46.540 --> 03:57:49.120
of the AIDS virus in 1981,

03:57:49.120 --> 03:57:52.300
US leaders remained silent over the early days

03:57:52.300 --> 03:57:53.470
of the epidemic.

03:57:53.470 --> 03:57:57.010
Not until 1985 when AIDS had already affected more

03:57:57.010 --> 03:57:59.530
than 7,700 people

03:57:59.530 --> 03:58:03.430
and killed 3,500 did the government allocate funding

03:58:03.430 --> 03:58:05.140
for AIDS research.

03:58:05.140 --> 03:58:07.330
And it was not until 1987

03:58:07.330 --> 03:58:10.930
that the federal government began raising AIDS awareness,

03:58:10.930 --> 03:58:15.930
but by then, about 47,000 Americans already were infected

03:58:16.000 --> 03:58:19.330
with HIV, the virus that causes AIDS.

03:58:19.330 --> 03:58:21.580
The issue had largely been dismissed

03:58:21.580 --> 03:58:22.570
because it was believed

03:58:22.570 --> 03:58:25.870
to only be affecting sexually active gay men,

03:58:25.870 --> 03:58:29.350
but during the 1980s, AIDS emerged as a leading cause

03:58:29.350 --> 03:58:31.750
of death among all young adults.

03:58:31.750 --> 03:58:34.960
By 1990, more than 100,000 people

03:58:34.960 --> 03:58:37.780
in the US had died from AIDS.

03:58:37.780 --> 03:58:40.840
Getting much more federal attention was an epidemic

03:58:40.840 --> 03:58:43.420
of a different kind, drugs.

03:58:43.420 --> 03:58:47.020
Smokeable, solid chunks of crack cocaine were cheap

03:58:47.020 --> 03:58:51.610
and highly available in major US cities in 1985.

03:58:51.610 --> 03:58:54.880
Crack particularly affected low-income communities living

03:58:54.880 --> 03:58:59.170
in cities which included large numbers of African Americans.

03:58:59.170 --> 03:59:02.290
Drug dealers contributed to a significant increase

03:59:02.290 --> 03:59:04.270
in violence in these communities.

03:59:04.270 --> 03:59:08.470
Between 1984 and 1989, the homicide rate

03:59:08.470 --> 03:59:11.380
for young Black men more than doubled

03:59:11.380 --> 03:59:13.810
and Black communities also saw increases

03:59:13.810 --> 03:59:17.110
in fetal death rates, low-birth-weight babies,

03:59:17.110 --> 03:59:21.010
weapons arrests, and the number of children in foster care.

03:59:21.010 --> 03:59:25.150
In 1986, the US Congress passed laws that made penalties

03:59:25.150 --> 03:59:26.980
for the possession or trafficking

03:59:26.980 --> 03:59:30.430
of crack cocaine 100 times more severe than

03:59:30.430 --> 03:59:33.310
for powdered cocaine, which was widely believed

03:59:33.310 --> 03:59:36.220
to be targeting low-income African Americans

03:59:36.220 --> 03:59:38.920
who were more likely to be using cheap crack rather

03:59:38.920 --> 03:59:40.570
than the more expensive powder

03:59:40.570 --> 03:59:43.510
or other drugs like crystal methamphetamine.

03:59:43.510 --> 03:59:46.990
This resulted in harsh social consequences,

03:59:46.990 --> 03:59:49.060
including increased police brutality

03:59:49.060 --> 03:59:51.880
against African Americans and large numbers

03:59:51.880 --> 03:59:55.030
of young Black men imprisoned on drug convictions

03:59:55.030 --> 03:59:58.810
for long sentences, which then caused them to lose access

03:59:58.810 --> 04:00:01.960
to voting, housing, and employment opportunities,

04:00:01.960 --> 04:00:02.980
which in turn led

04:00:02.980 --> 04:00:06.430
to increased violent crime in poor Black communities.

04:00:06.430 --> 04:00:09.777
Though President Nixon began the so-called War on Drugs

04:00:09.777 --> 04:00:13.777
in the 1970s, the federal effort to stop drug use

04:00:13.777 --> 04:00:16.720
and to prosecute users was widely expanded

04:00:16.720 --> 04:00:18.430
under President Reagan.

04:00:18.430 --> 04:00:22.240
Whereas Nixon's programs had repealed minimum sentences

04:00:22.240 --> 04:00:23.890
for marijuana possession

04:00:23.890 --> 04:00:26.860
and set up federal drug treatment programs,

04:00:26.860 --> 04:00:30.250
Reagan's approach was to increase criminalization.

04:00:30.250 --> 04:00:34.720
In 1984, Reagan signed the Comprehensive Crime Control Act,

04:00:34.720 --> 04:00:37.810
which expanded the federal penalties for possession,

04:00:37.810 --> 04:00:40.930
cultivation, or transfer of marijuana,

04:00:40.930 --> 04:00:42.970
established minimum sentences

04:00:42.970 --> 04:00:45.970
and abolished parole for federal prisoners.

04:00:45.970 --> 04:00:49.900
From 1980 to 1984, the Federal Annual Budget

04:00:49.900 --> 04:00:54.310
of the FBI's Drug Enforcement Units went from $8 million

04:00:54.310 --> 04:00:56.380
to 95 million.

04:00:56.380 --> 04:01:00.640
When George H.W. Bush took over the presidency in 1989,

04:01:00.640 --> 04:01:02.590
he continued Reagan's efforts.

04:01:02.590 --> 04:01:05.620
In his very first televised address as president,

04:01:05.620 --> 04:01:07.690
Bush held up a plastic baggie filled

04:01:07.690 --> 04:01:09.610
with white chalky chunks,

04:01:09.610 --> 04:01:12.017
identifying it as crack cocaine.

04:01:12.017 --> 04:01:14.290
"It's as innocent-looking as candy,

04:01:14.290 --> 04:01:18.100
but it's turning our cities into battle zones," he said.

04:01:18.100 --> 04:01:21.730
Drug use was actually in decline by 1989,

04:01:21.730 --> 04:01:25.810
but Bush went on to spend $45 billion mostly

04:01:25.810 --> 04:01:28.720
on drug-related law enforcement which was more than

04:01:28.720 --> 04:01:32.020
the previous four administrations combined.

04:01:32.020 --> 04:01:35.080
Later, it was revealed that the baggie from Bush's speech,

04:01:35.080 --> 04:01:38.590
supposedly confiscated from a drug bust just days prior

04:01:38.590 --> 04:01:40.120
just steps from the White House

04:01:40.120 --> 04:01:42.640
in Lafayette Park had been a setup.

04:01:42.640 --> 04:01:46.300
An undercover federal agent had lured a teenager drug dealer

04:01:46.300 --> 04:01:48.460
to the park before busting him

04:01:48.460 --> 04:01:50.410
to make it seem like the drug trade was

04:01:50.410 --> 04:01:52.360
on the president's doorstep.

04:01:52.360 --> 04:01:56.260
Another major event of Bush's presidency was the Gulf War.

04:01:56.260 --> 04:01:58.390
Under the rule of Saddam Hussein,

04:01:58.390 --> 04:02:00.550
Iraq wanted to nationalize Kuwait

04:02:00.550 --> 04:02:02.830
and take control of its oil fields,

04:02:02.830 --> 04:02:05.440
thereby controlling a significant amount

04:02:05.440 --> 04:02:07.300
of the world's oil supply.

04:02:07.300 --> 04:02:08.350
Because the US

04:02:08.350 --> 04:02:10.570
and other countries wanted to maintain access

04:02:10.570 --> 04:02:12.910
to these fields, they formed a coalition

04:02:12.910 --> 04:02:14.470
to stop the invasion.

04:02:14.470 --> 04:02:17.440
Starting January 16th, 1991,

04:02:17.440 --> 04:02:19.930
an air and ground war was fought with soldiers

04:02:19.930 --> 04:02:22.090
from the US, the UK,

04:02:22.090 --> 04:02:25.570
France, Saudi Arabia, Egypt, and Kuwait.

04:02:25.570 --> 04:02:28.990
The Iraqi army was defeated handily retreating from Kuwait

04:02:28.990 --> 04:02:31.810
just a month later on February 28th.

04:02:31.810 --> 04:02:35.893
The conflict's impacts were felt into the 21st century.

04:02:37.537 --> 04:02:40.204
(mellow music)

04:02:41.650 --> 04:02:44.500
Between 1990 and 1997,

04:02:44.500 --> 04:02:45.790
the percentage of households

04:02:45.790 --> 04:02:48.340
in the United States owning computers increased

04:02:48.340 --> 04:02:51.700
from 15% to 35%.

04:02:51.700 --> 04:02:54.400
This widespread adoption of personal computers

04:02:54.400 --> 04:02:56.770
and the World Wide Web catapulted

04:02:56.770 --> 04:02:59.110
the information technology industry

04:02:59.110 --> 04:03:01.870
into the stratosphere and investors

04:03:01.870 --> 04:03:04.540
and entrepreneurs everywhere were looking for ways

04:03:04.540 --> 04:03:06.130
to get a piece of the pie.

04:03:06.130 --> 04:03:09.730
By 1998, lured by the potential profitability

04:03:09.730 --> 04:03:12.910
of online businesses, low interest rates,

04:03:12.910 --> 04:03:15.340
and the availability of venture capital,

04:03:15.340 --> 04:03:18.610
investors were eager to back nearly any company

04:03:18.610 --> 04:03:20.890
with a .com in its name,

04:03:20.890 --> 04:03:23.860
while ignoring traditional predictors of success.

04:03:23.860 --> 04:03:26.410
That is the ability to turn a profit

04:03:26.410 --> 04:03:28.960
or even a business plan of any kind.

04:03:28.960 --> 04:03:30.460
At the height of the boom,

04:03:30.460 --> 04:03:33.610
even companies that had never made any revenue were able

04:03:33.610 --> 04:03:37.840
to go public by issuing an initial public offering

04:03:37.840 --> 04:03:40.450
or IPO, and raise money.

04:03:40.450 --> 04:03:43.060
On paper, some people became billionaires

04:03:43.060 --> 04:03:45.010
practically overnight.

04:03:45.010 --> 04:03:47.050
The NASDAQ Composite Index,

04:03:47.050 --> 04:03:49.930
one of the most watched stock market metrics,

04:03:49.930 --> 04:03:54.930
rose by 582% from January, 1995

04:03:55.000 --> 04:03:56.860
to March, 2000.

04:03:56.860 --> 04:03:58.930
The situation was risky, however,

04:03:58.930 --> 04:04:01.420
because these companies were highly overvalued due

04:04:01.420 --> 04:04:03.640
to their lack of a plan to turn a profit.

04:04:03.640 --> 04:04:05.980
Analysts were instead focused on their ability

04:04:05.980 --> 04:04:07.930
to attract internet traffic.

04:04:07.930 --> 04:04:11.680
Speculation or the purchase of risky stocks at a low price

04:04:11.680 --> 04:04:14.380
with the expectation that the price will rise enough

04:04:14.380 --> 04:04:15.880
to make a later profit,

04:04:15.880 --> 04:04:19.630
the dotcom speculation bubble was just a house of cards.

04:04:19.630 --> 04:04:22.180
When investment capital began to dry up,

04:04:22.180 --> 04:04:23.920
many of the companies that had caused

04:04:23.920 --> 04:04:26.140
so much excitement went bankrupt,

04:04:26.140 --> 04:04:27.730
and the bubble burst.

04:04:27.730 --> 04:04:32.730
Market panic resulted in massive sell-offs, and by 2002,

04:04:32.890 --> 04:04:36.190
investor losses from the dotcom boom were estimated

04:04:36.190 --> 04:04:39.190
at around $5 trillion.

04:04:39.190 --> 04:04:41.860
The dotcom bubbles bursting is credited with helping

04:04:41.860 --> 04:04:45.160
to trigger an eight-month economic recession starting

04:04:45.160 --> 04:04:46.900
in March, 2001.

04:04:46.900 --> 04:04:49.360
However, the recession is considered one

04:04:49.360 --> 04:04:52.150
of the milder ones in the country's history,

04:04:52.150 --> 04:04:53.680
and not all of the companies

04:04:53.680 --> 04:04:56.530
of the dotcom era succumbed to bankruptcy.

04:04:56.530 --> 04:04:59.470
Some of those that survived became the juggernauts

04:04:59.470 --> 04:05:04.360
we're familiar with today, such as Microsoft, Amazon, eBay,

04:05:04.360 --> 04:05:06.253
Qualcomm, and Cisco.

04:05:08.499 --> 04:05:11.582
(suspenseful music)

04:05:17.590 --> 04:05:19.960
After a record-breaking turnout,

04:05:19.960 --> 04:05:23.770
Barack Obama was the first ever African American to be voted

04:05:23.770 --> 04:05:25.990
to the office of US president,

04:05:25.990 --> 04:05:27.160
winning the popular vote

04:05:27.160 --> 04:05:29.680
by more than 10 million votes,

04:05:29.680 --> 04:05:33.190
and securing a vast majority of electoral votes.

04:05:33.190 --> 04:05:34.990
Obama's message was hope

04:05:34.990 --> 04:05:37.480
and it resonated with the American people.

04:05:37.480 --> 04:05:39.880
As the war of terror raged on,

04:05:39.880 --> 04:05:42.610
economic difficulties on the home front compounded

04:05:42.610 --> 04:05:44.440
the feelings of insecurity.

04:05:44.440 --> 04:05:48.310
In 2008, losses on a rapidly declining housing market

04:05:48.310 --> 04:05:50.860
within the US caused a chain reaction

04:05:50.860 --> 04:05:53.583
of losses across the global financial market,

04:05:53.583 --> 04:05:55.090
causing a massive

04:05:55.090 --> 04:05:58.000
and sustained economic contraction known

04:05:58.000 --> 04:05:59.770
as the Great Recession.

04:05:59.770 --> 04:06:00.880
The recession marked

04:06:00.880 --> 04:06:04.150
the most significant economic downturn in the US

04:06:04.150 --> 04:06:07.420
since the Great Depression of 1929.

04:06:07.420 --> 04:06:09.370
Thousands of Americans could not make

04:06:09.370 --> 04:06:11.770
their loan payments and lost their homes,

04:06:11.770 --> 04:06:13.480
businesses went bankrupt

04:06:13.480 --> 04:06:15.430
and the US government scrambled

04:06:15.430 --> 04:06:17.320
to help alleviate the damage.

04:06:17.320 --> 04:06:19.360
In 2009, under the direction

04:06:19.360 --> 04:06:22.210
of newly elected President Barack Obama,

04:06:22.210 --> 04:06:24.220
the Congress passed a series of acts

04:06:24.220 --> 04:06:27.040
to alleviate the issues caused by the recession

04:06:27.040 --> 04:06:28.390
and to install reforms

04:06:28.390 --> 04:06:31.030
to ensure it could never happen again.

04:06:31.030 --> 04:06:35.440
In 2013, the Afghan Military officially took over control

04:06:35.440 --> 04:06:37.540
of operations in their country,

04:06:37.540 --> 04:06:39.520
and the US announced a timetable

04:06:39.520 --> 04:06:43.090
for a complete US withdrawal by 2016.

04:06:43.090 --> 04:06:45.370
During the election of 2016,

04:06:45.370 --> 04:06:47.410
Republican Nominee Donald Trump

04:06:47.410 --> 04:06:50.290
and Democrat Hillary Clinton faced off in one

04:06:50.290 --> 04:06:54.280
of the ugliest elections the country had ever experienced.

04:06:54.280 --> 04:06:56.710
While Clinton ran on her vast experience

04:06:56.710 --> 04:06:58.420
within the federal government,

04:06:58.420 --> 04:07:02.170
Trump's campaign was unlike any that had been run before.

04:07:02.170 --> 04:07:04.300
Trump appealed to a group of Americans

04:07:04.300 --> 04:07:07.777
who had never felt they'd been marginalized in recent years

04:07:07.777 --> 04:07:10.780
and to people who had distrust in the government.

04:07:10.780 --> 04:07:13.870
Clinton was defeated by Trump who secured the majority

04:07:13.870 --> 04:07:15.490
of electoral votes.

04:07:15.490 --> 04:07:18.460
Almost immediately, suspicion of Russian

04:07:18.460 --> 04:07:20.560
and Chinese involvement in tampering

04:07:20.560 --> 04:07:22.300
with the election arised.

04:07:22.300 --> 04:07:25.780
In 2017, President Donald Trump took office

04:07:25.780 --> 04:07:27.910
and reversed the planned withdrawal

04:07:27.910 --> 04:07:30.460
as an emerging terrorist organization known

04:07:30.460 --> 04:07:34.390
as the Islamic State began operating within Afghanistan.

04:07:34.390 --> 04:07:35.890
Trump authorized the use

04:07:35.890 --> 04:07:38.980
of the US's largest non-nuclear bomb

04:07:38.980 --> 04:07:41.575
in an act which coincided with his decision

04:07:41.575 --> 04:07:45.220
to continue the US's military presence on the ground.

04:07:45.220 --> 04:07:47.710
After another two years of conflict,

04:07:47.710 --> 04:07:52.030
the US and Taliban once again opened peace negotiations

04:07:52.030 --> 04:07:55.000
and after a series of back and forth cancellations,

04:07:55.000 --> 04:07:58.120
an agreement was at last reached in 2020.

04:07:58.120 --> 04:08:02.590
In early 2020, a new type of virus emerged from Wuhan China.

04:08:02.590 --> 04:08:04.630
By mid-March 2020,

04:08:04.630 --> 04:08:08.920
all 50 US states had reported at least one positive case

04:08:08.920 --> 04:08:13.450
of COVID-19 and nearly all of the new infections were caused

04:08:13.450 --> 04:08:14.890
by community spread,

04:08:14.890 --> 04:08:17.830
and not by contracting the disease abroad.

04:08:17.830 --> 04:08:21.040
The COVID-19 pandemic took a heavy toll

04:08:21.040 --> 04:08:25.510
on Americans economically, politically, and psychologically,

04:08:25.510 --> 04:08:28.570
and revealed deep divisions between Americans' views

04:08:28.570 --> 04:08:31.120
of the role of government in a crisis,

04:08:31.120 --> 04:08:34.420
particularly with regard to vaccine mandates.

04:08:34.420 --> 04:08:36.880
In 2020, the nation again faced

04:08:36.880 --> 04:08:39.880
a challenging and incendiary election.

04:08:39.880 --> 04:08:41.680
Incumbent Donald Trump running

04:08:41.680 --> 04:08:43.120
for reelection faced off

04:08:43.120 --> 04:08:45.670
against Former Vice President Joe Biden

04:08:45.670 --> 04:08:47.740
at the height of the pandemic.

04:08:47.740 --> 04:08:51.910
Again, domestic issues of racial injustice, gun control,

04:08:51.910 --> 04:08:53.950
and appointments to the Supreme Court

04:08:53.950 --> 04:08:56.320
were the chief concerns of the race.

04:08:56.320 --> 04:08:59.740
As the ongoing health crisis further divided the parties,

04:08:59.740 --> 04:09:02.110
the psychological and physical toll

04:09:02.110 --> 04:09:05.770
of the pandemic became a centerpiece for both candidates.

04:09:05.770 --> 04:09:07.990
After a contentious election

04:09:07.990 --> 04:09:10.570
during which the counting lasted longer than normal,

04:09:10.570 --> 04:09:13.750
due to early election, and mail-in ballots prompted

04:09:13.750 --> 04:09:15.970
by the COVID-19 pandemic,

04:09:15.970 --> 04:09:18.790
Biden won the presidency, winning the majority

04:09:18.790 --> 04:09:22.060
of electoral votes as well as the popular vote.

04:09:22.060 --> 04:09:24.970
The outcome of the election was immediately contested

04:09:24.970 --> 04:09:28.360
by Trump and the Republicans who made claims of fraud.

04:09:28.360 --> 04:09:31.930
Trump would claim repeatedly that the election was stolen

04:09:31.930 --> 04:09:35.800
and increased distrust in the American electoral process.

04:09:35.800 --> 04:09:38.470
On January 6th, 2021,

04:09:38.470 --> 04:09:41.560
as the US Congress met to certify the election,

04:09:41.560 --> 04:09:43.600
large crowds of Trump supporters led

04:09:43.600 --> 04:09:46.030
by the Proud Boys and Oath Keepers,

04:09:46.030 --> 04:09:49.720
both far-right anti-government extremist organizations

04:09:49.720 --> 04:09:53.080
with ties to white supremacist organizations,

04:09:53.080 --> 04:09:56.320
the groups conspired to take the US Capitol Building

04:09:56.320 --> 04:10:00.070
and force the Congress to certify the election as fraudulent

04:10:00.070 --> 04:10:03.130
and instate Trump as the rightful president.

04:10:03.130 --> 04:10:05.530
On January 6th, the mob outside

04:10:05.530 --> 04:10:07.930
of the Capitol Building breached through security

04:10:07.930 --> 04:10:11.410
and entered the Capitol, forcing the Congress to flee

04:10:11.410 --> 04:10:15.430
and Capitol police to engage with force in some cases.

04:10:15.430 --> 04:10:18.250
When the police had at last cleared the building,

04:10:18.250 --> 04:10:20.620
counting of the electoral votes resumed

04:10:20.620 --> 04:10:24.100
and Vice President Pence proclaimed Biden the winner.

04:10:24.100 --> 04:10:27.130
In 2021, Joe Biden assumed the office

04:10:27.130 --> 04:10:31.090
of the presidency alongside Vice President Kamala Harris,

04:10:31.090 --> 04:10:32.950
the first African American,

04:10:32.950 --> 04:10:35.530
and first woman to hold the office.

04:10:35.530 --> 04:10:37.090
Under President Joe Biden,

04:10:37.090 --> 04:10:39.310
the US military at last began

04:10:39.310 --> 04:10:42.010
its final withdrawal from Afghanistan.

04:10:42.010 --> 04:10:45.550
As it did, the Taliban quickly rushed to fill the gap

04:10:45.550 --> 04:10:48.520
and toppled the fragile Afghan government,

04:10:48.520 --> 04:10:52.600
undoing the work that was done for the last 20 years.

04:10:52.600 --> 04:10:55.000
The following year, 2022,

04:10:55.000 --> 04:10:58.420
the Russian Federation invaded the Republic of Ukraine

04:10:58.420 --> 04:11:01.600
and the United States began funneling aid to the country

04:11:01.600 --> 04:11:04.360
to combat Russia's expansion into the region.

04:11:04.360 --> 04:11:07.420
Today, Biden's Administration continues to push

04:11:07.420 --> 04:11:11.140
for progressive policies, both at home and abroad,

04:11:11.140 --> 04:11:14.530
and still combats the intense political division

04:11:14.530 --> 04:11:15.973
within the country.

04:11:17.684 --> 04:11:20.920
(mellow music)

04:11:20.920 --> 04:11:23.860
As the 2024 election looms,

04:11:23.860 --> 04:11:26.080
the future of the United States seems

04:11:26.080 --> 04:11:27.700
to hang in the balance.

04:11:27.700 --> 04:11:28.630
Since the signing

04:11:28.630 --> 04:11:32.170
of the Declaration of Independence in 1776,

04:11:32.170 --> 04:11:34.450
the nation has endured substantial

04:11:34.450 --> 04:11:38.200
and often violent changes politically, socially,

04:11:38.200 --> 04:11:40.810
and economically, but this is,

04:11:40.810 --> 04:11:43.690
in and of itself, the defining attribute

04:11:43.690 --> 04:11:45.430
of the United States that,

04:11:45.430 --> 04:11:48.070
despite the trials and tribulations,

04:11:48.070 --> 04:11:52.300
she always emerges intact and stronger than before.

04:11:52.300 --> 04:11:53.647
The beauty of the United States

04:11:53.647 --> 04:11:55.930
and its people is their resilience

04:11:55.930 --> 04:11:58.540
and its ability to adapt and change.

04:11:58.540 --> 04:12:01.300
Today, the United States remains a world leader

04:12:01.300 --> 04:12:03.490
to be respected and admired.

04:12:03.490 --> 04:12:07.960
Its population of more than 334 million people is one

04:12:07.960 --> 04:12:10.870
of the most diverse countries in the world.

04:12:10.870 --> 04:12:12.850
Its landscape is painted with some

04:12:12.850 --> 04:12:16.780
of the most magnificent natural features on the planet

04:12:16.780 --> 04:12:19.090
with hundreds of recognized national

04:12:19.090 --> 04:12:22.180
and historical parks, preserves, monuments,

04:12:22.180 --> 04:12:24.940
and sites preserved by the federal government.

04:12:24.940 --> 04:12:26.860
From the humblest beginnings,

04:12:26.860 --> 04:12:29.890
the people of the United States of America have fought for

04:12:29.890 --> 04:12:32.170
what they believed was right and continue

04:12:32.170 --> 04:12:34.030
to do so to this day.

04:12:34.030 --> 04:12:36.040
The indomitable American spirit,

04:12:36.040 --> 04:12:38.680
which characterizes the best of Americans,

04:12:38.680 --> 04:12:41.650
has helped bring the country to new heights in the realm

04:12:41.650 --> 04:12:45.400
of politics, science, business, and culture.

04:12:45.400 --> 04:12:47.470
And while they're far from perfect,

04:12:47.470 --> 04:12:50.680
the American people continue to strive for greatness,

04:12:50.680 --> 04:12:53.080
never ceasing to prove themselves worthy

04:12:53.080 --> 04:12:55.180
of the great experiment started

04:12:55.180 --> 04:12:59.053
by their revolution nearly 250 years ago.

